<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLATLANTIC-VODAFONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC AND VODAFONE NEAR CELLULAR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
 (HLW)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bell Atlantic, the nation's largest local telephone
company, appears close to an agreement to combine its national
wireless operations with the United States wireless assets of
Vodafone Airtouch PLC, the world's largest wireless telephone
company, in a deal that would create a separate company valued at
between $70 billion and $80 billion, said people close to the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   If the two companies are successful in their negotiations, and
there is no guarantee that they will be, an announcement could come
as early as this week. The deal being discussed would give Bell
Atlantic the national cellular footprint that the company has long
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic was prevented from doing that in January when it
lost a bidding war to acquire Airtouch, then the nation's largest
wireless operator.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone Group PLC beat out Bell Atlantic by offering to buy
Airtouch for about $60 billion in stock and cash. The combined
company was then renamed Vodafone Airtouch.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone executives have been very vocal about wanting to expand
the company's cellular reach in the United States, and this deal
would give the company an additional 14 million mobile phone
subscribers to add to the approximately 9.5 million it already has
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Vodafone's business and Bell Atlantic's
wireless business would also allow Vodafone to compete in the
United States against rivals like AT&AMP;T Wireless Services and
Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic was expected to complete its $52.9-billion merger
early next year with GTE, which would then control about a third of
the United States' local phone industry and would have major
Internet and wireless phone units.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Vodafone Airtouch confirmed it was discussing an
alliance with Bell Atlantic. The structure of a deal has begun to
emerge over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the talks said that Bell Atlantic would own
about 55 percent of a newly combined United States wireless company
with Vodafone owning the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from both companies have been working out other
issues over the weekend, including fine-tuning the new company's
value, discussing who would run it, and what executives would be
appointed to the new concern's board.
</P>
<P>
   Although executives have been making progress, according to
people close to the talks, one noted that the negotiations could
fall apart at any time. If talks do dissolve, Vodafone probably
will consider other alternatives in its quest to establish itself
as a dominant player in the U.S. cellular market.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Bell Atlantic decided to disband its Primeco Personal
Communications partnership with Vodafone, which left Vodafone
without cellular service in the Eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Logical options would include the acquisition of a company like
Omnipoint Corp. or the bankrupt Nextwave Telecom Inc., both of
which have operations in the Eastern United States. Omnipoint
agreed to merge with Voicestream Wireless Corp., but that
$3-billion deal has not closed, and it is possible Vodafone could
still make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Vodafone and Bell Atlantic each declined to
comment on reports of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a surprising compromise, albeit a seemingly smart
one, for Ivan Seidenberg, chairman and chief executive of Bell
Atlantic. In interviews last January after his company lost
Airtouch to Vodafone, he was candid about his disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we see this, is this was more of a missed
opportunity,'' Seidenberg said at the time. ``In the longer term,
it is our job to prove that we would have been the best
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, by early summer, executives from Vodafone and Bell
Atlantic had agreed to start talking about some kind of joint
venture in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gent, chief executive of Vodafone, is transforming the
company into a cellular powerhouse both here and abroad. He makes
frequent trips to the United States _ he is here about once a month
_ and has held meetings with Seidenberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
