<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-WELTERWE     09-12 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DELAHOYA-WELTERWEIGHT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELTERWEIGHTS FIGHTERS AN ISLAND OF STABILITY IN DIRTY SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The landscape is littered with outrageous decisions, Mike
Tyson's profanity, sucker punches, low blows, Don King's fractured
metaphors, fractured jaws, fraudulent matches, addled brains,
bruises, blood, pretenders, contenders, convicts, grand juries, FBI
raids and a long-lost piece of Evander Holyfield's ear.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a piece of condemned property. Enter at your own
risk, and be sure to bring along a good criminal attorney. The
fight game is a sport in name and, too often, a felony in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it endures.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of reasons have been offered for boxing's ability to
survive scandals that might have shut down any other business long
ago. If it isn't the world's oldest profession, it is a close
second. It always manages to stick around, regardless of whether it
is illuminated by bright lights or hidden amid dark shadows in back
rooms of low-rent saloons.
</P>
<P>
   For the crowd that hates it, boxing is like a cockroach. The
abolitionists can't do anything to get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   But there might be a secret to the sporting stepchild's
resiliency:
</P>
<P>
   The welterweights.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past century, the curiously named division _ almost at
the midpoint between all the juniors, supers and cruisers _ has
been a place that a badly battered sport comes to renew itself. The
money is still in the heavyweights. So, too, is most of the alleged
corruption. But it is at 147 pounds where boxing has traditionally
rediscovered the drama, grace and courage that so often have been
resources for the novelists and filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's welterweight clash between Oscar De La Hoya and Felix
Trinidad is being called the Fight of the Millennium by the
promoters. It's part hype. But there also some truth in it. The
welterweights always have come to the rescue when boxing seems to
be headed for another demise.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, himself, seems to sense his role. He talks about
leading the attempted restoration of the sport's credibility, lost
in the controversial judging in March for the Lennox
Lewis-Holyfield draw and the infamous Bite Fight in which Tyson
dined on Holyfield's ears. De La Hoya even talks about what will
happen when, and if, he retires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch what happens when I retire from boxing,'' De La Hoya,
the unbeaten World Boxing Council champion (31-0, 25 knockouts),
said 10 days ago from his training camp at Big Bear, Calif. ``It's
not going to be the same, because my fans _ mothers, grandmothers
of kids _ will follow me wherever I go.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks smack of arrogance, and there are more than just a
few who would love to see Trinidad, the unbeaten International
Boxing Federation champ (35-0, 30 KOs) knock De La Hoya off the
pulpit. Nonetheless, his rivals welcome the attention and the money
he has brought to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Sugar, a well-known boxing historian, compares De La Hoya's
role in boxing to that of Tiger Woods in golf. He has generated
interest from people who have been ambivalent or even offended by
prizefighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a person whether they could meet Lennox Lewis or
Oscar, they would say Oscar,'' he said. ``Sometimes fight fans find
him the most recognizable boxer, even more than Evander. For him to
put the heavyweights' biggest names under a bushel basket is a hell
of a marketing job.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, he is boxing's most recognizable name because he is
also its most credible. He is the first boxer in years to attract
endorsements from the hamburger chains and deodorant companies that
had fled the fight game because of repeated scandal. King can sell
a fight, but would you buy a car from him?
</P>
<P>
   In terms of history, De La Hoya's role is not unprecedented.
Sugar Ray Leonard was the last fighter to have his kind of
broad-based appeal and clout. Leonard came along just when the
sport had receded into another one of its declines. An aging,
ailing Muhammad Ali had just lost to Larry Holmes in a bout that
left the public disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   Along came Leonard and a whole generation of welterweights who
would make boxing a credible, popular sport throughout the late
1970s and and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that many parallels are being drawn between
De La Hoya-Trinidad and the classic Leonard-Thomas Hearns
welterweight clash in September 1981. It was a classic, in large
part because of what happened within the ropes. The fighters
switched roles. Leonard, the boxer, became the puncher to beat
Hearns, the acknowledged puncher, in the 14th round.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard went on to fight Marvin Hagler as a middleweight. But
his fame came as a welterweight. He took his nickname, Sugar, from
perhaps the best fighter of all time. Sugar Ray Robinson came along
as a welterweight when boxing was suffering through scandals linked
to the big-city mobs. Fixed fights were suspected and addressed in
front of Senate subcommittees.
</P>
<P>
   The original Sugar Ray won the welterweight title in 1946 before
moving on and up to the middleweights. But it was as a welter that
he established a legacy that continues. An alternative pop group
calls itself Sugar Ray these days.
</P>
<P>
   The pound-for-pound designation, a permanent part of today's
language, was created because of Sugar Ray, who in his days was
better than any champion in any weight class.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sugar Ray Robinson, there was Henry Armstrong, who
defended the welterweight title 18 times _ five in one month _ in
the 1930s. Before Armstrong, there was Barney Ross, who came out of
Chicago's ghettos in the 1920s and was perhaps the best in a
generation of great Jewish fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Ross, whose parents wanted him to become a Hebrew
teacher, defines what the welterweight division has always been.
It's a crossroads. Poor kids from a variety of backgrounds can
fight at 147 pounds. They don't have to be a freak of nature with a
6-foot-5, 220-pound frame. All they need are some smarts, courage,
quick hands and a willingness to fight. In 1938, Ross, the Jewish
kid, lost to Armstrong, a Black kid who was born in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one years later, the crossroad takes on a decidedly Latin
beat. De La Hoya, the Mexican-American from East Los Angeles, meets
Trinidad, a Puerto Rican and a Black man. The cultural
crosscurrents are there as much as they have ever been. There is a
longtime rivalry between Mexican-American and Puerto Rican
fighters. It also pits Los Angeles, home for many of Mexican
descent, and New York, home for a large Puerto Rican community. The
fight itself also is symbolic of the rapid rise of the Latin market
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take that to another level,'' De La Hoya said when
asked about the fight as a symbol of the Latin emergence. ``I
choose to carry that responsibility. I want to make a name for all
of us, for all Latinos across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   He's in the right weight class to do it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
