r s BC-CAR-CART-DEATH-AZR &LR;      09-12 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-DEATH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH KILLS CART ROOKIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ A lively practice session ended tragically
Saturday when rookie Gonzalo Rodriguez was killed following a
vicious head-on crash into a concrete wall at the Honda Grand Prix
of Monterey at Laguna Seca Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a 27-year-old Uruguayan, died of massive head and
neck injuries, according to the Championship Auto Racing Teams
medical director, Dr. Steve Olvey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impression of (witnesses) at the scene was (Rodriguez) was
killed instantly with impact of the wall,'' Olvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who finished 12th in the Aug. 8 Detroit Grand Prix in
his only previous CART start, was approaching the famed Corkscrew
turn on the 2.238-mile road course when his brakes locked, and his
car plowed through a gravel trap without losing speed.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's car then slammed into a tire barrier and the
concrete wall behind it at a speed measured at about 160 mph. The
car then flipped backward about 30 feet into the air, catapulted
over an advertising wall, narrowly missed striking a tree and
landed upside down on a grassy hill.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team owner Roger Penske nor CART officials would
immediately speculate on the cause of the accident, but there was
some speculation that the throttle may have stuck open or
Rodriguez's foot may have mistakenly slipped and pressed the
accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   CART officials impounded the car, and Penske immediately
withdrew the team's other car and driver, Al Unser Jr., from
today's race.
</P>
<P>
   Course workers removed Rodriguez from the wrecked car, and he
was taken by ambulance to Community Hospital of the Monterey
Peninsula, where he was pronounced dead 42 minutes after the
accident at 10:10 a.m. (Arizona time).
</P>
<P>
   ``At our drivers' request, and a request that we absolutely
support, there will be no (second round of qualifying),'' CART
President and Chief Executive Officer Andrew Craig said.
``Obviously, the teams are decimated with the loss of a well-liked
driver.''
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic tribute to Rodriguez, the green flag was displayed
in front of an empty pit lane during the scheduled qualifying
session.
</P>
<P>
   Today's starting grid will be determined by Friday's qualifying
session. Defending champion Bryan Herta will start from the pole
position, and Tony Kanaan will line up outside the front row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible tragedy,'' Michael Andretti said. ``Our hearts
go out to his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Robby Gordon also expressed sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable what happened,'' Gordon said. ``Out of
respect for Gonzalo and his family, the drivers stuck together and
decided to have a moment of silence. It's the least we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   A Toyota Atlantic race went on as scheduled, as did qualifying
in another support series. However, no car returned to the
racetrack until 4{ hours following the crash. Much of the delay was
due to repairing the wall, which was significantly damaged by the
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was the first CART fatality since Jeff Krosnoff was
killed in a race held at Toronto in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Three spectators, however, were killed by debris following a
crash at Michigan Speedway in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Three more spectators were killed by debris following a crash in
a May Indy Racing League event at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Olvey said Rodriguez's crash was the first serious injury since
the series began going to Laguna Seca in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragic day for Laguna Seca Raceway,'' said John
Stornetta, the racetrack's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Until the Atlantic cars returned to the track, an eerie silence
shrouded the garage area and the grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   Fans also seemed to agree with the decision to curtail CART
activities for the remainder of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right decision,'' said Monterey fan Terry Terrana,
whose 5{-year-old son was attending his first race. ``After
something like that, everybody should pay their respects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows fatalities are part of racing, but they're few
and far between. Unfortunately, my son had to be at this race, and
now I have to try and explain to him that people dying at races
doesn't always happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was a regular in the European Formula 3000 circuit,
where he was runner-up in the drivers standings. Rodriguez also is
a three-time Uruguayan Formula Renault champion and was a Formula 3
rookie of the year in 1991. His last win was in a Formula 3000 race
in May at Monaco. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZ     09-12 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS ALIGN TO CREATE SEASON OF A LIFETIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Baseball is governed by the law of gravity and the law
of averages. Over the course of a 162-game season, it has the
uncanny power to bring you down to earth and drop you off right
where you're supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are always exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   As the Diamondbacks continue to chug toward a division title,
there is a prevailing belief that a second-year expansion team is
benefiting largely from a cluster of ``career years'' _ guys who
have somehow escaped baseball's radar and never hit the ground.
Guys who are doing things they'll never do again.
</P>
<P>
   This is a misperception.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, the Diamondbacks are flourishing because of a
confluence of abnormal factors. And all told, it is the
organization that is having a career year. One that will never
happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all interrelated,'' Matt Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   If you look up and down the Diamondbacks' roster, only Luis
Gonzalez is truly having a ``career year,'' the kind of season that
is so far above his normal production that it will never be
duplicated. Entering Saturday's game with the Phillies, Gonzalez
was hitting .339 - a whopping 71 points higher than his career
average. And he's already set personal bests for runs scored (104),
home runs (24), doubles (41) and RBIs (97).
</P>
<P>
   The power numbers offered by Bell (33 home runs, 97 RBIs) are
staggering, and with one more hot streak, he has an outside shot to
join Rogers Hornsby, Davey Johnson and Ryne Sandberg as the only
second basemen in history with 40 or more home runs in one season.
But home runs are up all over baseball, and it's debatable whether
Bell's season fits the criteria of a career year. After all, Bell
hit .310 with 187 hits in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as it's tempting to put the same label on Matt
Williams, Steve Finley and Matt Mantei, it just doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Finley will exceed his career bests in home runs and RBIs, but
he has had better overall seasons. Mantei is dominating in his
second full season as a closer, but it's too early in his career to
know what's normal. And then there's Williams, the MVP candidate,
the one who is constantly lumped in the ``career year'' category by
national observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction? I'm not,'' Williams said. ``I've passed my career
high in RBI, but I've hit more homers, hit for a higher average. I
think that label just comes from the lack of that (production) last
year. ``And probably because it makes good copy.''
</P>
<P>
   A company called Diamond Mind Inc. offers projections based on
where a team should finish given the standard production of its
players. It relies on comprehensive mathematical formulas and
adheres to the theory that the number of above-average seasons will
be balanced by the below-average performances. Which is normally
the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season started, it pegged the Diamondbacks as a
second-place finisher with a record of 83-79. It predicted the
pitching staff would finish fifth in the National League, but
projected the Diamondbacks' offense to end up in the bottom half of
the standings.
</P>
<P>
   So, with only one unquestioned career year, how can you explain
what could be the single greatest one-year turnaround in the long
history of baseball? &QL; 
The loaded gun factor
</P>
<P>
   The top three slots in the Diamondbacks' batting order _ Tony
Womack, Bell and Gonzalez _ have scored a mind-boggling 315 runs
through 141 games. That is more than the any three players on the
Mets, Braves, Reds or Astros.
</P>
<P>
   When on base, Womack's speed has diverted the focus of opposing
pitchers, helping Bell to see a lot of fastballs. Gonzalez's whole
season has been a hitting streak, offering protection to Bell and
RBI opportunities to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I have so many RBI is because they've been on base
all season,'' Williams said. ``Otherwise, I'm just hitting the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   With Williams, the top four players in the lineup have combined
for 405 of 776 runs scored (52 percent) and 357 of 740 RBIs (48
percent). &QL; 
The good season factor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just like the world champion Yankees of last season, the
Diamondbacks have an abundance of players enjoying good seasons and
few who are struggling. That, more than anything, has tipped the
scales in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   The two-catcher tandem of Kelly Stinnett and Damien Miller has
20 home runs and 76 RBIs. The pinch-hitting/platoon tandem of Greg
Colbrunn and Bernard Gilkey has combined for a .297 average, 10
home runs and 48 RBIs. And the one flame-out _ Travis Lee _ has
been replaced by the huge bat of Erubiel Durazo, who has nine home
runs in 105 at-bats. Which, by the way, is a 54-home run pace over
the course of a full season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is because we're a veteran club, and when the game
starts, we know what to do,'' Gonzalez said. ``If we're scuffling
on a particular day, we know how to work a walk. We push each
other. Not verbally, but by example. No one wants to be the weak
link.''
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative productivity has shocked the experts. Entering
Saturday, the Diamondbacks ranked second in the National League in
runs scored, total bases, home runs and RBIs. They rank third in
slugging percentage. And soon they will tie a National League
record by having four players with 100 or more RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has contributed,'' Gonzalez said. ``Even Rob Ryan was
getting big hits for us when he was in the lineup.'' &QL; 
The luck factor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have had an assortment of injuries, and the one
suffered by David Dellucci curtailed what would've been another
career year. But none of their position players has been on the
shelf for an extended period. And even with the mid-season loss of
Todd Stottlemyre, their six starting pitchers entering spring
training have started 141 of 141 games.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of horseshoes, you know the Diamondbacks aren't the
fleetest team in the world. Yet, they rank first in the National
League in fewest amount of double plays.
</P>
<P>
   That's hitting them where they ain't.
</P>
<P>
   They also rank first in grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   That's hitting them when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what it is?'' Gonzalez said. ``Everyone is having a
career year at something.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. So forget the individuals. It's the franchise enjoying
the career year. The kind you'll still be talking about in 50
years. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
