<HEADLINE>
ROBUST AMERICA FINDS ROLE IN CENTURY'S SECOND DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
 2NDTAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Listen again, after the Cold War, to President Clinton as he
justifies the NATO-led offensive against Serbia, the country where
an assassin sparked World War I by killing Austrian Archduke Franz
Ferdinand.
</P>
<P>
   ``By acting now we are upholding our values, protecting our
interests and advancing the cause of peace,'' Clinton said as the
despair of Kosovar refugees was broadcast around the world.
``Ending this tragedy is a moral imperative.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, Army soldiers stationed in 75 countries plied
their trades in the name of international defense. Computer users
clicked themselves around the globe, sending e-mail messages to
foreign friends they had never met. Somewhere, no doubt, a shopper
pondered whether to buy that shirt made in an Asian sweatshop.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke, Ford Motor Co. sealed its deal with Volvo.
Speculation spread that Sprint might merge with Deutsche Telekom.
Hong Kong vied for a Disney theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, America is tethered to the world like no other country.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect that to change in the next century. Just expect the
questions that tethering creates, without the Soviet threat, to be
more complicated than they were in this century.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: Does a ``moral imperative'' exist for returning
peace to East Timor? Will an unstable Russia threaten our national
security or prove to be a minor annoyance? Should we offer
friendship to China if its economy strengthens? Will the euro
compete with the dollar in the same way the yen has? Should we
assist post-colonial African countries struggling to find new
governments?
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Pickering, a political science professor at Kansas State
University and an expert in international relations, adds to that
list: ``What do you do with rogue states like Korea or Iraq?
Terrorism reaching our shores? Some worry about the global trading
system growing more fragile given the threatened trade wars among
the U.S., Japan and Europe. There are questions about growing
ethnic conflicts....
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really at a fluid juncture in history. The main dilemma
right now is what to do with American power.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that, confronted with so many choices, some
Americans are tempted to retreat _ again _ no matter how much power
the country wields. Just as Kansas City long neglected the Liberty
Memorial, the nation's World War I monument and symbol to our entry
into the world, some Americans will no doubt continue to urge
politicians to ignore the rest of the world. They will echo Pat
Buchanan's cry of ``America First'' and ask for protections against
global competition.
</P>
<P>
   Will their pleas yield results? Maybe a few. But it is unlikely
that such isolationist rhetoric can compete with the untamed,
world-embracing will of our cultural, technological, political, and
commercial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, that will accompanied the doughboys as they sang
``Over There'' on their way to the trenches. It accompanied Wilson
as he fought for the country's participation in the League of
Nations. It helped lay the foundations for this, the American
century. Now we must ask: Will it make the next century ours as
well?
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
