<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ROENICK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROENICK SETS HIS SIGHTS ON A STAR  
 HATCHER'S ELBOW PROVIDES INCENTIVE FOR COYOTES CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Forgive and forget? Not hardly. Jeremy Roenick knows
there is some unsettled business between himself and Derian Hatcher
of the Dallas Stars. And when the two lock horns for the first time
this season, expect the sparks to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I'm going to be out there looking for
anything,'' Roenick, the Coyotes' star center, said, ``but if
something comes my way, there's no way in hell I'm going to let it
go by.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: If Roenick sees a chance to knock a few inches off
of the 6-foot-5 Hatcher with a good, hard, clean hit, he's going to
shoot first and answer questions later.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't happen tonight when the Coyotes meet the reigning
Stanley Cup champion Stars at 5 in America West Arena. Roenick is
scheduled to play, but Hatcher is getting the night off after
playing Saturday against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher prematurely ended Roenick's regular season and forced
him to miss the first six games of the Coyotes' seven-game playoff
series against the St. Louis Blues after elbowing Roenick in the
face and shattering his jaw in a mid-April game. Hatcher, the
Stars' captain, was suspended for seven games for the hit, believed
as retaliation for Roenick laying out Dallas center Mike Modano
with a monstrous check in an earlier game in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't forgotten what happened. I'll ``never'' forget what
happened,'' Roenick said. ``It's in the back of my mind, and it'll
never leave my mind. There's no question about that. . . . Do I
want it to go away? No. It gives me a lot of adrenaline, a lot to
look forward to and a lot to psych myself up for.''
</P>
<P>
   The soonest a Roenick-Hatcher rematch could take place would be
Nov. 5 in Phoenix, the first regular-season game between the two
clubs. But every game figures to be an adventure, according to
Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going away. Not for a long time,'' Hitchcock said
Saturday. ``I don't think anything will happen (today), but you
never know. There's bad blood between these two teams, and there
will be for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   If it gets overly rough between Roenick and Hatcher, don't call
the calvary. Roenick said he could take care of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never look for anyone to go out and fight my own battles,''
he said. ``Obviously, you feel good when someone comes to your aid.
That's comraderie. That's what makes you feel like part of a team.
But when it has to be done myself, I'm not afraid to do it. I'm not
afraid of getting beat up. I'm not afraid to take a punch or get
knocked down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher also knocked Roenick out of action four years ago with a
knee-on-knee collision that left JR with a badly bruised tibia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one was a little easier to forget,'' Roenick said.
``That's just the way he plays. He plays with his elbows up and
that big, wide stance. That's what's made him successful. There are
going to be injuries because of it, and I just happened to get
caught twice by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing against him as a hockey player. I think he's a
dynamite hockey player. He's got a Stanley Cup. That says something
for him. Hopefully, he can just find something to put in it now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
