<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-TIMELINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBUST AMERICA FINDS ROLE IN CENTURY'S SECOND DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK WIEBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In second decade of the century, a robust America
finds its world role It's time to sum up. To look at where we are
going by asking where we have been. Confident. At times swaggering.
The world's industrial leader. But not yet its moral leader. That
was America as President Woodrow Wilson prepared to deliver his war
message to Congress on April 2, 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years before Wilson's address, in which he would ask
Congress to declare war against Germany, America snapped its
fingers to the hit song ``I Didn't Raise My Boy to Be a Soldier.''
Less than a year before the address, Democrats bragged that Wilson
had kept America out of the war.
</P>
<P>
   But early in 1917, German U-boats renewed attacks on U.S. ships
in the Atlantic, killing dozens of Americans. The nation, which had
endured the deaths of 128 Americans in the 1915 sinking of the
Lusitania, could no longer sit still.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, Wilson believed, could it act without a moral purpose,
without asserting itself as a world leader. America, he said, must
fight for ``the rights of nations great and small and the privilege
of men everywhere to choose their way of life and obedience.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Wilson would champion U.S. participation in the League of
Nations, an organization he believed would protect the sovereignty
of all who joined it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world,'' he said in his war message, ``must be made safe
for democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words the United States forever changed. No longer
would it limit its foreign affairs to a strictly defensive posture.
Although America would retreat into cozy isolation after World War
I, Wilson's vision would inform the foreign policy of presidents
from Franklin D. Roosevelt to Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And it would spark an ambivalence that follows America into
nearly every conflict it enters. A recent Kansas City Star poll,
for example, found that only 45 percent of respondents ``strongly
agreed'' or ``agreed'' that the United States should serve as the
world's ``policeman.'' Forty-four percent ``somewhat disagreed'' or
``strongly disagreed.''
</P>
<P>
   This ambivalence, however, cannot mask a reality that has marked
America ever since World War I. ``The real lesson from the teens,''
said Jeff Moran, history professor at the University of Kansas,
``is that we must participate in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1910s, America had largely avoided that, wrapping
itself in what Moran called ``this old tradition of American
exceptionalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think of ourselves as a shining city on a hill,''
Moran said, ``that we'll be an example to the rest of the world and
not participate in it.''
</P>
<P>
   America had, to be sure, done its share of participating before
this century's second decade. It had acquired colonies from its
victory in the Spanish-American War, negotiated a peace treaty
between Russia and Japan in 1run e-inch.pgm 905 and flexed its
muscle by sending the Navy on a worldwide tour.
</P>
<P>
   But until Wilson's address, America had never fought on European
soil. No sitting president had ever crossed the Atlantic. America
simply did not meddle in Europe's affairs. For most of this
century's first two decades, America simply shone.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: By 1913 its industrial production outpaced that of all
other countries. The same year, the Ford Motor Co. set up the first
moving assembly line and was soon producing a thousand Model T cars
a day. Cities erected skyscrapers. Tractors tilled farms.
</P>
<P>
   From the turn of the century until World War I, progressives
fought to alleviate the suffering of the poor, to give women the
vote, to give workers a fighting chance against corporate America
and to bring democracy closer to the people (most notably with the
popular election of senators in 1913).
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's take care of life at home,'' much of America seemed to
say at the outset of the Great War. ``Europe can bleed.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as America resisted joining the war, it could not
resist joining the world, or keeping the world at bay.
</P>
<P>
   By 1910 foreign-born residents made up nearly 15 percent of the
population and held close to 24 percent of the country's jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Armory Show of 1913 toured New York, Chicago and Boston with
nearly 1,300 works of modern art, about a third of them foreign and
many of them bewilderingly abstract. Picasso, van Gogh, Matisse and
others shocked mainstream America out of its cultural isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's modernist literature found a new audience in America as
dozens of publishing houses emerged to showcase the likes of James
Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   In 1915, AT&AMP;T technicians made the first trans-Atlantic
radiotelephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the war, sending nearly 2 million soldiers overseas to
fight the Germans. Europe ignited the pens of these
tourist-doughboys, who mailed their impressions not only of the war
but also of France to millions of Americans. Many of them were
farmers who had never traveled more than 50 miles from home. They
wrote about lands teeming with history and aging cathedrals, about
verdant landscapes and trips to the Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't trade any of U.S. for an equal part of France,''
wrote Capt. Harry S. Truman to his sweetheart, Bess Wallace, ``but
if I had to give up being a Missourian I'd be a citizen of France
by second choice.''
</P>
<P>
   To the 200,000 black soldiers who served in Europe, the relative
freedom and respect they encountered meant more than beautiful
vistas and old churches. In France they were exposed to a less
racist society, one that embraced the jazz they played and awarded
some of them the Croix de Guerre for their battlefield
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Negro soldier returning from the front,'' wrote Emmett J.
Scott in his Official History of the American Negro in the World
War, ``bore it grievously that on arriving home he had to ride in
`Jim Crow' cars, and be excluded from the use of public places.''
At war's end, 110,000 of these letter writers lay dead _ more than
half as a result of the Spanish influenza that killed millions
worldwide. Americans _ dubious about the war's accomplishments _
wanted nothing to do with Europe's problems, the League of Nations
or Wilson's dream of moral leadership. For nearly two decades after
Congress rejected the Treaty of Versailles, America would keep to
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Even as America rejected Wilson's dream, the Bolshevik
Revolution of 1917 planted the seeds for its permanent return.
True, World War II and America's entry into the United Nations
breathed new life into that dream. But the fear of Soviet expansion
made it last.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to President Truman _ the World War I hero from Missouri
who said the war messages of Woodrow Wilson stirred him ``heart and
soul'' _ explain why the United States should aid Greece and Turkey
to curb communism: ``I believe that we must assist free peoples to
work out their own destinies in their own way.'' (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
