<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S TURN THE ROCKIES INTO AMERICAN'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' ownership group is extremely concerned with
the possibility that it might be moved to the American League
sometime before the 2002 season, a distinct possibility since the
Diamondbacks agreed to wave veto power on such a move during a
three-year window that starts this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing general partner  &UR; Jerry Colangelo was in
Milwaukee last week and managed to meet up with Commissioner  &UR; Bud
Selig to discuss the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball forced the Diamondbacks and Tampa Bay,
which each joined the league last year, in an eleventh-hour tactic
the night before the franchises were awarded back in the spring of
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a $310 million investment here, while others who
own their clubs may have put in $13 million,'' Colangelo said,
taking a swipe at New York Yankees owner  &UR; George Steinbrenner, who
bought the Yankees in 1973 for $13 million. ``We've completed a new
study that shows 85 percent of our fans want us to remain in the
National League. We're going to live by whatever they decide, we
just want them to know all of the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   All this talk of restructuring centers around the Texas Rangers'
valid argument that they be moved out of the AL West, where they
are the only Central time zone club while the others are all in the
Pacific time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's logical to move, say, Arizona to take Texas' spot,
there is another, far more logical move that could help alleviate
two potential problems. Instead of moving the Diamondbacks to the
AL West, why not consider asking Colorado to switch leagues?
</P>
<P>
   It would help the Diamondbacks remain in the National League,
where they have built some quick rivalries with San Francisco, Los
Angeles and Chicago in a short time. Plus, whatever club or clubs
they meet in the playoffs this season will become instant rivals
for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, moving Colorado to the AL might finally help
that club see what it truly is, an AL-style club that plays in an
AL-style ballpark. The altitude will never decrease in Denver,
meaning the Rockies will be forced to play like they have in their
first seven years, waiting for the long ball to help provide runs.
</P>
<P>
   Why not simply make it official in Colorado? After all, the
Rockies are an AL club disguised within the NL, where they have no
chance to compete as long as the style of play remains more slash
and dash than the hammer-time style they play in the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Expect this item to be brought up when owners meet next week in
Cooperstown. Of course, all this probably makes way too much sense
for baseball's powers that be to see it that way. However, the
Diamondbacks can be moved against their will, the Rockies cannot. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; Sammy Sosa entered the weekend series with 59 home runs. His club,
the Chicago Cubs, had 56 victories before they were set to take on
Houston during the weekend, meaning Sosa could become the first
player ever to hit more home runs than his club has victories. Who
were the closest to achieve this feat? &QL; 
The real world &QL; 
If this kind of thinking is pervasive within the major leagues,
then maybe we are still living in the Dark Ages. New York Yankees
outfielder  &UR; Chad Curtis was asked last week his thoughts about
former outfielder  &UR; Billy Bean coming out of the closet and
admitting his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you polled every player in this room,'' Curtis said, ``they
would tell you they wouldn't want to even have the thought another
guy on the team might be checking them out. You have a lot of guys
in this room who are fairly uncomfortable with the idea of women in
the media coming in here _ even just the notion they're being
looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, we're relieved by Detroit General Manager  &UR; Randy
Smith, who was San Diego's GM at the time Bean played for the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone would've judged him on ability,'' Smith said.
``I don't think of him any differently no matter what his
lifestyle, and people would've judged him for what he was because
people knew him. In today's society, it would've had much less of
an impact than it might've had years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, it's highly unlikely any gay player would come
out during his playing days. The harassment would undoubtedly make
what
 &UR; Jackie Robinson went through in breaking the color barrier seem
like a day at the beach. &QL; 
The bizarre world &QL; 
Those wacky New York Mets have adopted the old Doors tune ``Mojo
Risin'' as their 1999 theme song.  &UR; Patricia Morrison,  &UR; Jim
Morrison's widow, was a special guest of the Mets for their game
against San Francisco last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Morrison is revered as a high priestess in the witch
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a perfect anagram for Jim Morrison,'' Patricia said.
``The song is about Los Angeles, which is kind of ironic. The
California friends of mine are very annoyed at the Dodgers for
letting the song get away. . . . I find all this extremely ironic.
I'm amused, flattered and honored. I think it's really cool. This
is Jim's way of going to baseball games.'' &QL; 
LA's real house of blues &QL; 
``Los Angeles Times'' columnist  &UR; Bill Plaschke put together these
quotes from several Dodgers sources for a recent entertaining
piece. Some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers GM  &UR; Kevin Malone, Feb. 18: ``They can't forget us now,
because they know the Dodgers are back.'' Malone, Aug. 23: ``Yes,
we did inherit some situations that we're still trying to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, March 31: ``This club has really come together under
 &UR; Davey ( &UR; Johnson) and his staff. They've been able to unite the
team and get everyone on the same page.'' Malone, July 24: ``We
have to get everyone on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Sheffield, April 3: ``If everybody just does their jobs
and plays together, we should be all right.'' Sheffield, Aug. 5:
``I know what it takes to win in the playoffs, and this team
doesn't have close to what it takes to even think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, June 29: ``I love Mondy.''  &UR; Raul Mondesi, Aug. 11:
``(Expletive) Davey.'' &QL; 
Ya'll come see us, ya hear? &QL; 
The wife of Seattle Mariners owner  &UR; Hiroboshi Yamauchi, the
Japanese tycoon, visited Seattle for the first time last week.
Mariners chairman  &UR; John Ellis and president  &UR; Chuck Armstrong
escorted the Yamauchi congregation on a tour of new Safeco Field.
She took pictures with Manager  &UR; Lou Piniella and  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Yamauchi, the chairman of Nintendo, bought the Mariners in the
middle of the 1992 season. He has yet to see the Mariners play a
single game. He has also never visited the United States. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
 &UR; Wally Berger of the 1935 Boston Braves hit 34 home runs while his
club won just 38 games. Next up on the list was Hall of Famer
 &UR; Ralph
 &UR; Kiner, who hit 37 home runs in 1952 while the Pittsburgh Pirates
won 42 games. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Honest honey, I've never even noticed that Cindy Crawford
 &UR; is a beautiful woman: ``I don't even let myself think about that. .
. . Our magic number is four, right? Yeah, I don't even think about
it.'' _ Cleveland Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What, this? I brought it in with me: With nine more games
remaining at Tiger Stadium, fans have started taking bits and
pieces of the old park home with them after games. One fan tried to
take a urinal from the stadium last week before he was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (very special edition): Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, may
he finally rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quick pop quiz for 20 points: Over the course of the past five
seasons, only two pitchers have won at least 15 games each season.
One is easy because it's Atlanta's  &UR; Greg Maddux. The other?
 &UR; Charles Nagy of the Cleveland Indians. Surprise!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Forget Joe DiMaggio's whereabouts. Where have you
 &UR; gone, Rickey Henderson?: The American League leader in stolen bases
entering the weekend was Toronto's  &UR; Shannon Stewart, who had a
grand total of 36 steals. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees closer  &UR; Mariano Rivera, who entered the weekend
having converted all 17 save opportunities since July 16, has not
walked the first batter he has faced in any appearance since July
9, 1998. That's a span of 81 consecutive regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   With his club-leading 29 home runs this season,  &UR; Eric
 &UR; Karros is within five of tying  &UR; Steve Garvey for second place on
the all-time list since moving to Los Angeles with 211. Former
third baseman  &UR; Ron Cey tops the LA list with 228 home runs, a
figure that probably will remain since it's doubtful Karros will
return next year.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's  &UR; Cal Ripken grounded into the 323rd double-play of
his career last week, tying the AL record held by  &UR; Carl
 &UR; Yastrzemski. If he hits into five more, he will tie  &UR; Hank Aaron for
the major league record.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday's game between Los Angeles and Florida featured a
starting match-up of Dodgers rookie  &UR; Eric Gagne and  &UR; Ryan
 &UR; Dempster of the Marlins. It was the first time a pair of
Canadian-born pitchers started against each other in a National
League game since St. Louis'  &UR; Reggie Cleveland and  &UR; Ferguson
Jenkins of the Chicago Cubs faced each other on July 28, 1973.
</P>
