<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9000 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WACO-COMMITTEE2TAKES-     09-12 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DANFORTH FACES MONUMENTAL TASK IN WACO INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- WACO-COMMITTEE 2TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY and DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Jack Danforth canceled plans to go fishing this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   To put it mildly, he has work to do. News media from everywhere
want to interview the former U.S. senator from Missouri, and for
now he will happily oblige.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, he is going to clam up and hunker down in what
promises to be an exhausting and tedious investigation into one of
the most contentious episodes in recent American history. Getting
to the truth of the April 19, 1993, tragedy at the Branch Davidian
compound in Waco, Texas, will take time, he says.
</P>
<P>
   How much time? Danforth can only speculate and hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking months rather than years,'' said the man
appointed last week by Attorney General Janet Reno to serve as
special counsel to the Waco probe.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than six years already.
</P>
<P>
   The physical evidence alone _ items plucked from the compound's
ashes, including rifles and grenades and 5-gallon buckets filled
with ammunition rounds _ weighs in at more than 24,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There will be hundreds of interviews to conduct, videotapes to
review and crates upon crates of documents to pore over. In Texas a
wrongful-death lawsuit pending against the U.S. government tells
the Waco tale in no fewer than 25 volumes, each 3 or 4 inches
thick.
</P>
<P>
   And if Danforth has his way _ he insists he will _ the public
will not be tipped to what his staff discovers until the probe is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who talks to the media, who leaks anything, is out,''
said Danforth, snapping his fingers to accentuate the point.
``That's an absolute priority....We'll be looking for good lawyers,
good investigators, confident people, and we need people who will
keep their lips zipped.''
</P>
<P>
   For now the Danforth team numbers three _ himself, U.S. Attorney
Edward L. Dowd and Thomas Schweich, one of Danforth's partners at
the Bryan Cave law firm. The government will pay Danforth and Dowd
$118,000 each annually.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth has 60 days to complete a budget. He said he would
recruit private lawyers and government investigators from agencies
that were not targets of the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Each staffer will be required to disclose financial holdings and
subjected to intense background checks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will be based in St. Louis, the home of
Republican Danforth and Democrat Dowd, who will be the chief
investigator. A specific office site has not been determined, but
Dowd said a ``top security'' facility would be needed to store the
records and evidence in safes.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways ``it's like any other criminal investigation,''
said Dowd, a one-time Kansas Citian who is stepping down as federal
prosecutor to assist Danforth. ``You get the facts, you examine the
law, compare the two, and then you pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as both men know, this is no typical case.
</P>
<P>
   The three big questions they seek to answer are chilling:
</P>
<P>
   Did the government cover up vital information about the FBI's
siege at Waco and the deadly fire that ended it?
</P>
<P>
   Did the military have an improper involvement?
</P>
<P>
   And, as Danforth bluntly puts it: ``Did federal officials kill
people?''
</P>
<P>
   The 42-story One Metropolitan Square, with its buffed offices
and captivating view of the Gateway Arch, is a long way from the
hand-cobbled compound that David Koresh and his religious followers
occupied in the rural outskirts of Waco.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' largest law firm, Bryan Cave, occupies six floors
near the top. Danforth practices law here and, for the moment, the
skyscraper is but the latest in a series of venues that the Waco
incident has traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993 various aspects of the standoff have been scrutinized
by the Texas Rangers; the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms; the Justice Department; criminal courts; civil courts;
documentary film crews; conspiracy peddlers; Internet Web masters;
and at least two congressional committees.
</P>
<P>
   The tides of available information, and misinformation, were
monstrous even before they shifted last month. That is when the FBI
acknowledged that two or three military tear-gas canisters capable
of starting a fire were shot at a concrete bunker hours before the
Branch Davidian compound became engulfed in smoke and flames.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and other authorities said they had no reason to think the
canisters _ which were used on the orders Richard Rogers, FBI
Hostage Rescue Team commander _ contributed to the blaze in which
Koresh and about 80 of his followers died.
</P>
<P>
   But the revelation that combustible projectiles were fired
defied years of sworn statements by federal agents. And Friday, The
Associated Press reported that an FBI lab report _ turned over to
Congress eight months after the tragedy _ was missing a key page
that acknowledged the use of the tear-gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Danforth, 63, was expecting to enjoy autumn weekends
fishing and anticipating the births of five more grandchildren, he
now finds himself wading into an issue where the political
radioactivity jumps off the meter.
</P>
<P>
   And with national elections on the horizon, the heat could
become more intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lot of folks on the Hill who have their political
agendas, then there will be people in the FBI and in the Department
of Justice who have their political agendas,'' said former Kansas
Congressman Jim Slattery, a Democrat. ``I think that Danforth has
the opportunity to really be the honest broker.''
</P>
<P>
   Danforth will have to contend with Congress, where members are
praising him one minute and then embarking on their own search for
the truth about Waco the next.
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform Committee has issued subpoenas, in
all likelihood for many of the same people Danforth will want to
interview. Committee Chairman Dan Burton, an Indiana Republican,
has been an outspoken critic of the Clinton administration and led
an investigation into the 1996 campaign-finance scandal.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois
Republican, has drafted legislation to create a five-member joint
House-Senate commission to look into Waco. He intends to proceed
only if he becomes convinced that the Justice Department is
stymieing Danforth's probe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
