<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WACO-COMMITTEE2NDTAKE     09-12 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DANFORTH FACES MONUMENTAL TASK IN WACO INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- WACO-COMMITTEE 2ND TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY and DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Even in Danforth's old haunt, the Senate, he faces
competition from Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican,
who also plans to weigh in on Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding characteristically deferential, Danforth said: ``I'm
not going to try to tell Congress what to do,'' but privately, he
may be wondering how, with so many cooks trying to stir a simmering
pot, the process will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works poorly,'' said Bill Frenzel, a Republican member of
Congress for 20 years and now a guest scholar at the Brookings
Institution. ``What happens is Congress wants to get people and
they try to cooperate with the independent counsel, but they do
step on each other toes.''
</P>
<P>
   The most notable example is the Iran-contra scandal in the
1980s. Both Congress and independent counsel Lawrence Walsh
investigated the illegal funneling of money and the trading of arms
for hostages, involving Nicaraguan revolutionaries and the Iranian
government.
</P>
<P>
   A court overturned the convictions Walsh won against two of the
key figures, Reagan White House aides Oliver North and John
Poindexter. The court ruled that the immunity granted them to
testify before Congress made it impossible for them to get a fair
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competing investigations where immunity is given can wreck a
prosecution,'' said Michael R. Bromwich, an Iran-contra prosecutor
and one of the trial lawyers in the North case.
</P>
<P>
   Bromwich, a former Justice Department inspector general, said
that everyone would be trying to interview the same witnesses and
that witnesses got tired of talking. The pressure also could force
Danforth into interviewing some witnesses before he was ready,
Bromwich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have competing bodies looking to interview the same
people, you do run into problems,'' he said. ``You need to know
what is being told to the other investigators. There are just a lot
of complications. This is a difficult enough one to master with the
passage of time and the extensive factual record.''
</P>
<P>
   If criminal wrongdoing is found, ``we will prosecute,'' Danforth
pledged.
</P>
<P>
   The special counsel at least will issue a final report to the
attorney general, and the report will be made public. Danforth and
Dowd said they hoped that when their investigation was complete,
Americans would consider the Waco tragedy a ``case closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck Revell expressed hope, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you can get to the bottom of this,'' said the retired FBI
special agent, who oversaw the agency's Dallas office when the
siege occurred. But Revell said he expected the final judgment to
be relatively mundane.
</P>
<P>
   ``A breakdown in communication'' within the FBI, Revell
predicted the special counsel would conclude. ``There will be no
conspiracy, no widespread cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's presuming everyone else had perfect knowledge of
what was happening in Waco, and that's just not how these things
are handled,'' Revell said. ``There were serious problems with the
way things were handled, but those problem had nothing to do with
the Davidians dying at their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the legacy of Waco, there will be accusations that
the fix is in. At least one group already insists as much.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth is ``just another `Washington Club' politician who will
likely compromise justice,'' declares a news release of Judicial
Watch, a right-wing legal group that is suing the government over
Waco. ``The choice of ex-Senator Danforth...is like having the fox
investigate his own hen house massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cox, a spokesman for the Texas Department of Public Safety,
expected as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that no matter how hard we work, people will be
talking about all the possibilities long after I'm here to worry
about it,'' said Cox, who in 1993 was the media's point man when
state investigators fished out evidence from the charred debris.
``We're still talking about the Kennedy assassination and the
grassy knoll, aren't we?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Jack Danforth can give this the funeral it deserves. I'd
like to see the whole thing rest in peace, though I don't think I
ever will.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
