<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV '99 _ THE YOUNG, THE PRETTY AND THE CRUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know you mean well, but you really have to let me grow up.'' &QL; 
That's a line from a new television series this fall. So what? you
say. What precocious teen hasn't uttered the same words to her
parents?
</P>
<P>
   But that's just it _ it's not a teen who says it. It's a grown
woman. A mother herself. A judge, no less.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much sums up the new fall season. Think young,
attractive actors. Then chop a few years off what you're picturing.
Add a couple of levels of beauty, subtract a measure of maturity,
and you've got the idea.
</P>
<P>
   And if the characters aren't young, they act it _ see the above
example, from Judging Amy, a new CBS show that stars Amy Brenne man
as a single mother living with her mom.
</P>
<P>
   Further proof? Check out the title of a new ABC comedy about
three men living together, one of whom recently discovered he was
gay, which understandably fouled up his marriage, another of whom
discov ers he has a teenage daughter: Oh Grow Up.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the title of a show. It's a theme for the season.
</P>
<P>
   You can thank the WB Network for this. Or blame it, if you like.
</P>
<P>
   Shows like Buffy the Vampire Slayer, Felicity and Dawson's Creek
don't necessarily draw viewers in droves (droves defined as many,
many millions of people), but they leave advertisers with their
mouths hanging open, drool pooling at their feet. Advertisers love
young people. Thus, so do network programmers. And that matters
because?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world where there are increased costs and increased com
petition, and where the business is being defined by very specific
demographic groups . . . TV shows are just there so people will
watch the commercials,'' Chris Albrecht, HBO's president for
original pro gramming, told television critics this summer. Of
course, a cable guy would say that.
</P>
<P>
   But he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, there is nothing inherently bad about watch
ing beautiful young people doing wacky things. If there were,
C-SPAN would be a ratings leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's what they call fantasy fulfillment,'' said Paul Feig,
the creator of the season's best new show, Freaks and Geeks.
``That's the mantra that most executives in town have, which is
teens don't want to watch their lives portrayed. They want to see
the fantasy version of their lives. And that is true _ these shows
do really well.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who run networks must think so. Otherwise such
teen-heavy shows as Safe Harbor, Roswell and Popular wouldn't have
found a spot in the fall lineup. And those are just the new WB teen
offerings. At least six other shows on the other networks feature
teens in either lead roles or major sup porting ones: Odd Man Out
on ABC; Freaks and Geeks on NBC; and Get Real, Manchester Prep, The
Bad Land and Malcolm in the Middle on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   But a little variety is nice. Freaks and Geeks happily avoids
fantasy fulfillment, opting instead for a more realistic, if
touchingly hilari ous, look at high school in the early '80s. Feig
just didn't have it in him to do a show about magazine-cover
candidates emoting about their Pent house Forum-grade sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are being written, and I don't think they're
based on anybody's real experience,'' he said earlier this month on
a break from shooting the show. ``That's a harsh statement, and it
might not even be true. But I sincerely can't believe that many
people were that cool at that age. We're not wired that way. I
don't know anybody who's that cool now.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Feig might be. He certainly came up with the coolest
show. And there are a surprising number of good ones this fall
(especially when you consider that in some years, that number is
zero).
</P>
<P>
   This time next year, titles like Freaks and Geeks, Action and
Malcolm in the Middle ought to sound familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, titles like Shasta McNasty, The Bad Land and Jack and
Jill won't sound familiar this time next month. Next week, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes every fall season. Some shows hit. Most miss. Here's
a quick glance at some things to look for over the next few months:
</P>
<P>
   A wide-open Thursday night. For years, NBC has ruled Thursdays
with an iron fist. But last season, with the departure of Seinfeld
and ER's precipitous drop in quality (the whole Mare
Winningham-psycho doc plot was especially embarrass ing), the
Peacock network began to slip. ER, still the most popular show on
television, lost 14 percent of its viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Any scent of blood in the water sends the other networks
circling. CBS ``retooled'' Chicago Hope (translation: bring back
Mandy Pa tinkin, fire most of the cast and hire a bevy of fabulous
babes in its place) and got a commitment from creator David E.
Kelley to be more hands-on this season.
</P>
<P>
   ABC trots out Wasteland to compete with Frasier. Kevin Wil
liamson, who created Dawson's Creek (and wrote the first two Scream
movies), created this young-adult ensemble about beautiful peo ple
hanging around New York trying to find themselves. C'mon, kids,
there's always modeling to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   UPN, doormat to the other net works, is hoping for salvation
with World Wrestling Federation Smack down! So far, so good, but
its numbers will drop when the other networks' new shows premiere.
</P>
<P>
   NBC isn't standing pat. It's add ing new faces to ER (including
a TV doctor from another television era, Alan Alda, for a few
episodes). It's also putting Stark Raving Mad in the primo slot
behind Frasier. It stars a grown-up Doogie Howser, Neil Patrick
Harris, as a book editor. Don't mark your calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting salvo fired across NBC's bow is Action,
Fox's dead-on comedy about a ruthless Hollywood producer. There is
bleeped-out cursing, one of the main characters is a prostitute,
and much is made of, you know, size. As in, size doesn't really
matter (although it apparently does). If this sounds crude, that's
because it is. It's also really funny, which forgives a lot.
</P>
<P>
   All David E. Kelley, all the time. Or so it might seem. The whiz
kid behind the Emmy-winning The Practice and the ever-so-trendy
Ally McBeal will add to his workload this season.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the two previous shows mentioned, Kelley has prom
ised to write a couple of Chicago Hope scripts and to make notes on
others. He's also cutting a half-hour all-comedy version of Ally
McBeal, which will be called Ally. (Perhaps later he will doctor up
an all-drama version called McBeal.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Snoops, Kelley's new ABC show starring Gina Ger
shon and Paula Marshall as high-tech private eyes. It'll air at 8
p.m. on Sundays, leading into The Prac tice. On the seventh day,
Kelley didn't rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Snoops is a nice com panion piece with The Practice,''
Kelley told critics this summer. ``The color palates are different.
This show really is more about the escapism. It's not nearly as
gritty. It's a distortion of private-detective reality. It's more
oriented towards fun and capers and high jinks, and, therefore, I
don't think it'll exhaust the sensibilities of The Practice
viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   It may, however, exhaust the patience of people who like to
watch good TV, if the pilot is any indication. It's looking like a
rare misfire from the most prolific man in television since Dick
Van Patten's character on Eight Is Enough.
</P>
<P>
   In a somewhat related matter, Aaron Sorkin risks spreading him
self thin this season, too.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kelley, Sorkin is a rarity _ he writes most of his scripts
himself (in his case, for the great Sports Night). So if you're
trying to build an audience for a critically ac claimed show, what
do you do? Sign on for another one, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin's The West Wing, on NBC, is a mostly comic look at the
White House of a fictional president, played by Martin Sheen. The
big relief is that the pilot is great. The big question is how long
Sorkin can maintain the quality of both.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question for Sorkin and Kelley both: Don't you guys
ever sleep?
</P>
<P>
   More adult language, more skin, more sex. And that's just on
Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous predictions about the fall season from television
critics.
</P>
<P>
   More immature antics, silly situations and childlike behavior
than you'll find on the first day of the semester at a junior high
school. From kids or from adults?
</P>
<P>
   This fall, from everyone. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
