<HEADLINE>
CONTENDER OR PRETENDER: WHICH CARDINALS TEAM WILL WE SEE TODAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - They're not having an identity crisis, even if
the rest of the football world is driving itself crazy trying to
figure the Cardinals out.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the team that was picked by many to win the NFC East, or
the one that lost three preseason games by an average of 33 points?
</P>
<P>
   ``The team that everybody is writing off is the same one that
people picked to win the division at the start of (training)
camp,'' defensive back J.J. McCleskey said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, the Cardinals, who open the 1999 regular
season today at Philadelphia, put on an Academy Award-winning
performance this summer, these sand-baggers in football cleats.
</P>
<P>
   They are coming off their most turbulent preseason in 11 years
in Arizona, one that ended with a 36-point loss at home to the
Oakland Raiders, their worst preseason defeat in 43 years.
</P>
<P>
   The feeding frenzy started almost as soon as the Raiders game
ended. Those football experts who had been picking the Cardinals to
make the playoffs for the second consecutive year were now changing
their predictions to drop them ahead of only the Eagles in the NFC
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange,'' Eagles linebacker James Darling said. ``Last
year ended on such a high note for them (the Cardinals), and
especially around the league, people thought Arizona would be one
of the teams to beat. We thought they all would come back this year
with their heels clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Training camp began with the Cardinals missing their top tackler
of a year ago (linebacker Jamir Miller), all-time leading receiver
(Larry Centers) and best blocker (Lomas Brown), all gone in free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals took the field against the Raiders, they were
without four offensive starters _ quarterback Jake Plummer (thumb),
left guard Chris Dishman (elbow), right guard Lester Holmes
(lacerated forehead in a car accident in which three players were
injured) and wide receiver Rob Moore (holdout).
</P>
<P>
   Moore signed on Thursday but is expected to see only limited
duty today. Dishman hasn't played in a game since last January.
Holmes has been out for nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Coach Vince Tobin made four starting lineup changes
Monday. Zack Walz, who weighs only 219 pounds, was inserted at
right outside linebacker. Terry Hardy, who has no career catches,
was promoted at tight end. Journeyman Matt Joyce takes over at left
offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little bit of a mystery,'' center Aaron Graham said.
``But, internally, we're as focused as we've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals still have two holdouts _ veteran defensive tackle
Mark Smith and first-round pick L.J. Shelton, the Eastern Michigan
offensive tackle _ and defensive lineman Eric Swann hasn't
recovered from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   How effective Moore will be after only one practice is anybody's
guess.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's holdout made a starter out of top draft pick David
Boston, the Ohio State wide receiver picked eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely will help him out,'' Moore said of Boston. ``Just
knowing the (Eagles') defensive players, things that work and don't
work against them, I need to pass that on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rookie starting in his first NFL game is fullback Joel
Makovicka, a fourth-round pick from Nebraska who won the job in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be a little nervous, but it helps that I played in
front of 80,000 fans in college,'' Makovicka said. ``But all of the
(veterans) have told me that the speed of the game picks up three
or four times from the preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the condition of Plummer's thumb. It improved every
day last week, but he still won't be at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make all the throws,'' Tobin said. ``It's a matter of
if he can make them all consistently through a complete ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   All-pro cornerback Aeneas Williams understands why many fans
have become skeptical about the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what they think of us right now,'' said Williams,
one of two defensive captains. ``Maybe because of all that has
happened, the public is taking a wait-and-see attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt in Williams' mind how the Cardinals will do
today. He gave the team a fiery pep talk after Friday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like what Aeneas said, `We don't care what everyone
in the outside world thinks. We know what we've got,' '' defensive
coordinator Dave McGinnis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
