<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAKE'S THUMB IS BIG SUBJECT FOR VALLEY FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - Hold up your right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Look at it for a moment. (OK, that's long enough.) The thumb is
the Swiss Army knife of body parts. It's as versatile as a utility
infielder.
</P>
<P>
   A thumb can flip a coin. Pop a cork. Pry a lid. Cock a gun. Turn
a page. Hitch a ride. Shoot marbles. Call a runner out.
</P>
<P>
   Without a thumb, how would we eat with chopsticks? Or hold a
glass? Or stroke our chin? Or give the thumbs-up sign?
</P>
<P>
   Without thumbs, what would we twiddle?
</P>
<P>
   The thumb is underrated. We take it for granted. It doesn't get
the attention, or respect, it deserves. Look up ``thumb'' in the
``World'' ``Book'' &UR; encyclopedia. Know what it says?
</P>
<P>
   See ``Hand.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jake Plummer is to be commended. Since being injured in a
preseason game 23 days ago, Plummer has raised public awareness
about the human thumb and its importance, at least as it relates to
the Cardinals season.
</P>
<P>
   It is safe to say the No. 1 question going into today's season
opener is ``How's Jake's thumb?''
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever think about Plummer's thumb, or anybody else's for
that matter, until now?
</P>
<P>
   The thumb on Plummer's throwing hand is the talk of Valley
sports. Fans haven't been this concerned about an athlete's
physical condition since Charles Barkley experienced back problems,
when the Suns were a championship-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   After Barkley collapsed at training camp, the Suns switchboard
lit up with calls from worried fans. Many wrote Sir Charles,
offering help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Charles,'' Barkley said one day, reading aloud a letter
in his hands. ``You are my favorite player. I heard about your back
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley stopped in mid-sentence. ``My back. Everybody wants to
know about my ``bac''k! . . . You wouldn't believe the stuff I get.
I've got every back magazine in the world. Every back book in the
world. Chiropractors. Exercises. ``Everybody'' has a cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles held up a product he received in the mail. ``See this?''
The canister contained a powdered protein supplement. ``Some lady
sent me these milkshakes. For my BACK!''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer hasn't been besieged with home remedies, although you
suspect some exist. Instead, every day since a Tennessee defensive
lineman mistook Jake's right thumb for a slot-machine lever the
Cardinals quarterback has undergone conventional treatment
recommended by team doctors and the training staff.
</P>
<P>
   Ice packs. Heat. Whirlpool baths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultrasound,'' trainer John Omohundro said. ``High voltage
galvanic stimulation'' (Don't try this at home). ``Massage.
Splints. Tape . . .''
</P>
<P>
   What, no faith healer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake might have done that on his own,'' Omohundro said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Plummer is a $30 million investment, and the most
important and popular player on the team, perhaps the Cardinals
should have flown in one of those traveling evangelists who work
miracles on TV.
</P>
<P>
   One night I saw an elderly man flop over on the stage like a
hooked marlin, get up, throw away his crutches and start dancing
the Charleston after one touch of Benny Hinn's electrified hand. It
seems like a good bet that _ with a little faith on Jake's part _
he could be cured of his sore thumb completely.
</P>
<P>
   Are you hee-yulled?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Plummer admitted after Friday's practice. His right
thumb is still tender. He can't throw the ball as hard as he did
before the injury. He isn't, as we say in sports, 100 percent. His
preseason preparation was limited to three series and 10 passes.
</P>
<P>
   To strengthen his grip, Plummer has been squeezing a Nerf ball
and plastic putty.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Plummer keeps a brace on his right hand. The
devise immobilizes the thumb and provides protection. Without the
brace, Omohundro said, Jake risks accidentally tweaking his thumb
by doing something as simple as ``fluffing a pillow'' during the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Jake wore the brace to last week's kickoff luncheon, attended by
about 500 fans. Many were excited to be in Plummer's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people grab your hand,'' Jake said, ``and squeeze it like
a gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Although listed as questionable, Plummer will start against the
Eagles. Will he require a painkiller to play?
</P>
<P>
   Omohundro said he doubts Plummer would take anything stronger
than an Advil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question you have with (stronger) oral medication is `How
clear is a guy thinking?'' Omohundro said. The Cardinals trainer
read the warning label on an imaginary bottle of pain pills. ``When
using this medication do not operate heavy machinery. Do not drive
a car. Do not run into 280-pound linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   A good rule of thumb. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at &QL; 
(602) 444-8635 or by e-mail at &QL; 
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
