<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME THINGS ARE SURE EVEN BEFORE 1ST KICKOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can take these to the full-service bank or nearest ATM this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals first-round pick  &UR; L.J. Shelton, star of the NFL's
newest home video, won't be the league's Offensive Rookie of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   The new book on Saints rookie  &UR; Ricky Williams, ``Dreadlocks to
Ditka,'' will sell more copies in the New Orleans area than  &UR; Boomer
Esiason's &UR; new novel ``Toss,'' but won't be as popular as the
Budweiser bottles sprouting dreadlocks and the T-shirts that say,
``Run Ricky Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Bengals wide receiver  &UR; Carl Pickens won't enjoy life
after retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Miami Dolphins quarterback  &UR; Jim Druckenmiller won't be inviting
San Francisco 49ers General Manager  &UR; Bill Walsh to hear Salsa bands
on Miami's South Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Eagles owner  &UR; Jeff Lurie will win more games in the
Arena League than in the NFL this season.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four years after moving to the Pontiac Silverdome, the
Detroit Lions still will have had more area codes than home playoff
games and playoff victories. &QL; 
America's funniest video
</P>
<P>
   Remember that silly tape Shelton's agent,  &UR; Lamont Smith,
threatened to play if the Cardinals didn't bargain in good faith,
the one that was supposed to show team Vice President  &UR; Bill Bidwill
Jr. saying on draft day that the club would give the Eastern
Michigan offensive tackle a contract filled with ``bells and
whistles''?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out it's a videotape of Shelton's draft-day party, but
the arbitrator didn't let Smith play it at Friday's grievance
hearing because it wasn't made available to the Cardinals earlier
in the discovery process.
</P>
<P>
   You can just imagine how insightful the videotape is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, L.J., pass the spinach dip.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamont, I think we're out of chips.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The beer is outside in the cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, somewhere on the tape is Bidwill's voice, but it's
probably drowned out by Smith's clients singing, ``He's (Smith) a
jolly good fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   How absurd are these negotiations going to get?
</P>
<P>
   Two Valley radio stations are asking the same thing. KGME and
KMVP representatives said Friday that on several occasions,
Shelton's camp talked of revealing the tape on the air.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape? On the radio? &QL; 
Book reviews
</P>
<P>
   Few league rookies have had a book written about them before
they take their first regular-season snap. But Williams, the
Heisman Trophy winner, isn't an ordinary rookie, and most of the
book is about his life leading up to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Esiason, meanwhile, considers himself a bit of a Renaissance
man. So he decided to branch out and write his first novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder . . . machinations . . . and the mob keep the pot
boiling to an explosive climax,'' writes ``Publishers Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason, the former Cardinals quarterback, won't be discussing
all the plot's details on ``Monday Night Football''.
</P>
<P>
   There's the owner's seductive daughter with a thing for rookies
and the corpse of the team's ex-quarterback. &QL; 
About-face
</P>
<P>
   Pickens was so sure he never, ever would play for the Bengals
again that he walked off the field last December singing ``This is
It''.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner  &UR; Mike Brown, refusing to trade Pickens, took him at
his word that Pickens had retired and recently wished him luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he enjoys his golden years,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickens will be in a Bengals uniform for today's season opener
at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is strange, one of the strangest here,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickens, the team's designated franchise player, signed the
one-year tender offer of $3.53 million and will sign a five-year
deal next week that averages about $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person has the right to change his mind,'' said Pickens,
adding that it's ``kind of hard to turn down that money.'' &QL; 
Free at last
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco fans never could forgive quarterback Druckenmiller
for not being  &UR; Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers ignored Walsh's advice and passed on Plummer to draft
Druckenmiller in the first round out of Virginia Tech three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has been wanting to get rid of him since returning to the
49ers last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller left a parting shot on his way to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill just does things sometimes just to hear himself talk,''
Druckenmiller said. &QL; 
Midas touch &QL; 
Lurie, the draftnik and Fantasy Football League fanatic, has been
so successful turning the Eagles from NFC East contenders to 3-13 a
year ago, he is about to expand his football horizons.
</P>
<P>
   He joins the Saints'  &UR; Tom Benson as NFL owners who also will be
running teams in the Arena League.
</P>
<P>
   Two more NFL owners,  &UR; Wayne Weaver of Jacksonville and  &UR; Al
Lerner of Cleveland, are trying to get into Arena Football. &QL; 
News of the weird &QL; 
With the retirement of All-Pro running back  &UR; Barry Sanders, the
Lions are expected to struggle to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Until they make the postseason again, they will continue to get
teased about having had more area codes (three) than home playoff
games (two) and playoff wins (one).
</P>
<P>
   Dog-eat-dog world &QL; 
Pittsburgh Steelers cornerback  &UR; Chad Scott, a third-year pro,
received some advice this week from veterans about playing in
Cleveland for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   They told him that with all the dog bones flying from the
stands, ``keep your helmet on'' while standing on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns-Steelers rivalry has always been one of the league's
best, which is why the NFL scheduled tonight's game in Cleveland
for the expansion team's debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't gonna lie,'' said Browns offensive tackle  &UR; Orlando
Brown, who came into the league with the Browns in 1993 before the
team moved to Baltimore. ``I hate Pittsburgh. I really hate
Pittsburgh. Anything yellow and brown, I hit it. That's how they
brought me up.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Atlanta Falcons offensive tackle  &UR; Ephraim Salaam, whose team plays
the Minnesota Vikings today in a rematch of last year's NFC title
game, thinks few still take the Falcons seriously. ``People still
don't believe we made it to the Super Bowl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, St. Louis Rams Coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil often referred to
today's opponent as the Colts instead of the Ravens. ``They'll
always be Colts to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos have won 24 consecutive games at Mile High
Stadium going into Monday night's game against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Chargers linebacker  &UR; Junior Seau, on the team having a
bye the first week: ``I do think we have control over this. . . .
We've got to win more than five games, I guess, in order to have an
opening (week) game.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Northern Arizona quarterback  &UR; Jeff Lewis, who hoped to be
Carolina's opening-day starter, was demoted to third team after the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Said New England Patriots Coach  &UR; Pete Carroll, who's tired of
people telling him he seems more confident this season, ``You mean
there's no deer in the headlights here?'' &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; THE TOP FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Minnesota &QL; The Vikings are great until playoff time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
2. Denver &QL; Can you say quarterback controversy? Coach Mike Shanahan
keeps denying one exists. &QL; 
 &QL; 
3. Green Bay &QL; General Manager Ron Wolf has given first-year Coach
Ray Rhodes a boatload of talent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. New York Jets &QL; Anything short of a Super Bowl will be a
disappointing season for most Jets fans. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Atlanta &QL; NFC champion still has to prove it's for real. &QL; 
 &UR; THE BOTTOM FIVE &QL; 
 &QL; 
31. Chicago &QL; Quarterback Shane Matthews will not lead the Bears to
the promised land. &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Cleveland &QL; There isn't a running back here good enough to play
for the Rattlers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
29. Philadelphia &QL; Veteran quarterback Doug Pederson could be booed
from his first misfired pass. &QL; 
28. Carolina &QL; Wasn't this franchise in the NFC title game a few
years ago?. &QL; 
27. Detroit &QL; Hope Barry Sanders is enjoying his extended vacation. &QL; 
ON THE RISE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buccaneers: They just missed the playoffs a year ago despite
shaky play at quarterback. So, again, QB Trent Dilfer's development
is the key. But nobody in the league has the Buccaneers' depth on
the defensive line. Their backs, Warrick Dunn and Mike Alstott, are
a terrific combination. Receiver no longer is a weak spot. The
Buccaneers could finish third in the NFC Central and still be one
of the five best teams in the league. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cardinals: They've had an awful off-season and training camp,
which has been well-documented. Two holdouts still remain. Starting
wide receiver Rob Moore, who signed on Thursday, enters the season
having had only one practice. Quarterback Jake Plummer still has a
sore thumb. Defensive tackle Eric Swann remains on the sideline
recovering from knee surgery. If that's not bad enough, the
Cardinals play the second-toughest schedule in the NFC. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Coach Mike Ditka, on Heisman Trophy winner Ricky
Williams returning to practice from an ankle injury: ``He was into
a full limp. . . . What do you want me to say, `He looks like he
needs a wheelchair or something?' He looks fine. I bet you he's 99
percent, and at 99 percent, he's better than most guys at 100
percent.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
ODD-SHAPED BALL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk about an offensive machine, the New York Giants haven't had
an NFL receiving leader since 1935.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't had a rushing leader since 1951.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't had a Pro Bowl receiver since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense has ranked 28th, 29th, 30th, 27th and 29th the
past five seasons.  &QL; 
SHORT SHOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer's new cereal, Jake's Flakes,
should be available in Valley grocery stores by the end of this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Shane Matthews has beaten out first-round pick Cade
McNown for the Bears' starting quarterback job is he enters the
regular season with the league's highest preseason passing rating _
124.1.
</P>
<P>
   Lions running back Greg Hill, on replacing Barry Sanders: ``I
don't think there's any back in the league that could replace
Barry. You could bring back some of the great ones that are in the
Hall of Fame, and I don't think they could replace Barry. There may
be somebody who can take Barry Sanders' place. Does Barry Sanders
have a son?''
</P>
<P>
   Have times changed. Washington Redskins first-round pick Champ
Bailey, instead of singing the Georgia fight song during hazing at
training camp, delivered comedian Chris Rock's ``No Sex in the''
``Champagne Room''.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee center Bruce Matthews is scheduled to start his
league-high 181st consecutive game today against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to St. Louis, the Rams have gotten worse each year.
They've gone 7-9, 6-10, 5-11 and 4-12. Could they go 3-13 this
year?
</P>
<P>
   Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld
can be reached at (602) 444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
