</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-FREDRICKSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREDRICKSON LETS ACTIONS SPEAK FOR HIM  
 HE'S DIFFERENT FROM MILLER, BUT EFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARiz. - Jamir Miller and Rob Fredrickson play the same
position, but any similarities end right there.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is an aggressive force against the run, while Fredrickson
brings more pass coverage to the equation. Miller rarely minces
words. Fredrickson prefers to be seen and not heard.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference? When the NFL kicks off its 1999 season
today, Miller will be helping the Cleveland Browns against
Pittsburgh, and Fredrickson will be in Philadelphia at Miller's
former left-linebacker post for the Cardinals against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   It's that difference that has fans wondering how much the
Cardinals have lost on the field, or in the locker room, in terms
of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to compare individual players,'' Cardinals
Coach Vince Tobin said. ``They all have their different strengths
and weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis added, ``Any time you lose a
player off your team, you lose something. Every player is unique,
and you lose something unique to that player. But to say because a
guy is gone the whole thing collapses, is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue regards two highly competent players. Fredrickson has
started 67 of a possible 74 games in five seasons with Oakland and
Detroit, while Miller started 57 of 74 games in five years with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fredrickson is a guy who has very good cover ability,''
McGinnis said. ``Jamir is bigger. He's a 6-foot-5, 260-pound
linebacker with long arms. He could even be out of position and
still make plays because of his reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamir could cover, but he doesn't cover as well as Rob. Rob
can play the run, but he's not as physical as Jamir.''
</P>
<P>
   Given their diametrically opposed strengths, it figures that
McGinnis has spent long hours adjusting his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to compensate,'' McGinnis said. ``We'll do the
same things. What you do is capitalize on the strengths of the guy
you have. It's not like Jamir was a terrible cover guy, and Rob is
a terrible run player. It's just that their strengths are on the
other sides of the spectrum. As far as quickness goes, they are
close. Rob is extremely quick.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-4, 240, Fredrickson isn't a shrinking violet. He played in
98 percent of Detroit's defensive plays last season before signing
a three-year, $7.9 million contract with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   He started all 16 games for the second straight season last year
and made 116 tackles, had 2{ quarterback sacks, defensed five
passes and had an interception and forced two fumbles. Miller,
playing the final 13 games with his hand in a cast to protect a
dislocated wrist, had 150 tackles, three sacks and defensed seven
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Slight edge to Miller. He was a leader, certainly. But he was a
leader who was a double-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's career in Phoenix was tumultuous. He came to the
Cardinals from UCLA with a reputation for being difficult to
handle. He was suspended for four games in his second season for a
substance abuse violation. To his credit, he noticeably changed his
lifestyle thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   When tackle Eric Swan went down last season with a knee injury,
it was Miller who picked up a large portion of the defensive load.
Yet it was Miller who publicly groused when quarterback Jake
Plummer was given a $29.7 million pact.
</P>
<P>
   It was Miller who angered coaches by demanding to be used more
as a pass rusher before the Cardinals playoff game at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Miller who, after the season, demanded a multi-year
contract calling for $6.5 million a year _ quarterback-type
numbers. He turned down a two-year, $6 million offer from Arizona
to test his marketability, and finally settled for a one-year deal
for $1.3 million in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   He now vows to make every team in the NFL sorry for snubbing
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I was brought in to replace Jamir,'' Fredrickson
said. ``I just signed as a free agent. I don't feel any pressure
about filling his shoes. He's one type of player, and I have a lot
of respect for him. But he's gone. He's in Cleveland. You (media)
have to lay that to rest and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much have the defense down, and I don't feel like a
rookie around here. I feel like an established veteran, which I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he bring leadership to the equation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership doesn't always come from guys who talk a lot,''
McGinnis said. ``It comes from the way guys play or perform. The
real leaders are the guys in the locker room who are respected for
the way they work, the way they prepare, and how available they are
all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that aspect of it, Rob Fredrickson is fine. But he's new.
That's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredrickson, a high school honor student, was his senior class
president, which certainly shows leadership qualities. He also was
a three-time All-Big Ten linebacker at Michigan State, while
earning all-conference academic honors en route to a business
degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can lead by example on and off the field,'' he said. ``We
need vocal leaders, and some people are good vocal leaders. Myself?
That has never been my deal. I've always worked hard and kept my
mouth shut.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
