r s BC-FBN-CARDS-SHAPPELL-AZ     09-12 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SHAPPELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD OPENERS GROWING OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - The Cardinals have shown that, if anything, they
need no help digging a hole. Crisis managers they are. Usually from
opening day on.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the NFL should be flagged for piling on. The Cardinals are
opening on the road for the 12th straight season today. That's a
claim no other NFL team can make. And for the ninth time since
moving to Arizona, they play three of their first four on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder they struggle?
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly the league ships the Cardinals out early to protect
players and fans from the desert heat. Short of getting a new home
with a lid on it, there isn't much they can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a competitive disadvantage,'' said  &UR; Bill Bidwill, the
Cardinals owner. ``The heat is very difficult, and the sun is quite
difficult. We are the only team in the league that can't sell
50-yard line seats because of the sun on the east side (of Sun
Devil Stadium).''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Cardinals' schedule is particularly inequitable.
The league makes them go to Miami next week, where the heat and
humidity could be as unbearable as a September day in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but that game won't be played if there is a hurricane,''
Bidwill said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL doesn't let the Cardinals play at home until Week 3, a
Monday night game with San Francisco. It then sends them to Dallas
in Week 4, where it could be hot and humid.
</P>
<P>
   The league lets Green Bay play at home in potential sub-zero
conditions in Week 17 where the Packers play _ you guessed it _ the
Cardinals, on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Joe Ferreira, senior director of broadcast planning and
scheduling for the NFL, acknowledges that the early games at Miami
and Dallas and the late one at Green Bay are quirks. The Dolphins
play at home only twice before Oct. 24, the Packers play at home
only twice after Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of other situations, Tampa Bay (three of
first five on the road) and Dallas (three of first five on the
road, including today at Washington), where we really try to avoid
playing September day games whenever possible,'' Ferreira said.
``In some places, like Miami, it becomes more complicated because
they are sharing a facility with a baseball team. With Green Bay,
for whatever reason players' and fans' resistance to extreme cold
isn't as severe as their resistence to extreme heat. They seem to
enjoy the cold-weather atmosphere surrounding the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things go into making the schedule to make it work
that sometimes a team gets what its fans perceive as the lesser end
of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals always get it. Let them play an opener at home
once in a while. Even Tampa Bay opens at home today. &QL; 
Late hits &QL; 
Rough week for the radio blow-hards, eh? With KGME and KMVP
arm-wrestling to be first to erroneously report the signing of
 &UR; Rob &UR; Moore, KFYI running with a false rumor that Bidwill had sold
the team, and syndicated blabbermouth  &UR; Jay Mariotti ripping the
Cardinals on their flagship station, KDUS, and then daring ``that
P.R. clown  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Jensen,'' the team's media relations director, to pressure the
station to take Mariotti off the air, is there any doubt why God
created FM?
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; L.J. Shelton goes back into the draft, someone should do an
intervention. He was barely a first-rounder this year (21st
overall), he plays a position that doesn't quickly change games
(offensive line), he's from a small-time college program (Eastern
Michigan) and he's a big guy (6-6, 343) with potential to get
bigger in a bad way while sitting out a year. He would be a
third-round pick next year and lose millions.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm making the call on the kickers, I choose the other guy.
The Cardinals might well be showcasing  &UR; Chris Jacke.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cards don't win today, they are looking at 0-4 with the
New York Giants coming to town. They've lost four straight to the
Giants. &QL; 
Lee Shappell can be reached at by e-mail at lee.shappell(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
