</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-RUTGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas strikes quickly, rolls past Rutgers 38-21
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Texas coach Mack Brown began preparation for the
Longhorns' first road trip of the season by admonishing his team to
forget everything about the previous week's 52-point win over
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   If the Longhorns followed his instructions, Saturday's first
half against Rutgers must have stirred feelings of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   Texas got rolling early, tallying 21 first-quarter points for
the second straight game on its way to a 38-21 win over the Scarlet
Knights before a record sellout crowd of 41,511 at Rutgers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when you're up that much at halftime (28-6), the only
way you can lose the game is by turnovers, blocked kicks or your
defense not playing well,'' Brown said. ``Giving them a halftime
speech when you're leading big is easy. I've had to do it the other
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns (2-1) did not maintain the scoring pace throughout
the game as they did against the Cardinal, but the 21-3 lead at the
end of the first period was enough to spur them to the win. Rutgers
(0-2) would get no closer than 17 points the remainder of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Texas jumped on Stanford 21-7 after the first 15
minutes and went on to a 69-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first quarter, guys ran spectacular routes, caught the
ball real well, and we started mixing the run in,'' UT quarterback
Major Applewhite said. ``The first-half execution was excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``(In the) second half, we kind of fell off a little bit, but it
wasn't so much that we put our team in jeopardy of losing the
ballgame. But we've got to be a four-quarter team, and I think we
played about 3{ today.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite was the offensive catalyst again, completing seven of
eight passes for 97 yards and two touchdowns in the first quarter.
For the game, Applewhite connected on 19 for 32 passes for 244
yards, his 13th consecutive 200-yard passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Split end Ryan Nunez had a career-best day for the Longhorns
with 104 yards on seven receptions.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive week, Texas brought some excitement to
the punting game, and as was the case against Stanford, the
Longhorns had the fun this time. Texas returned a blocked punt for
a touchdown and had another score set up when Rutgers punter
Charlie Titus mishandled a snap, putting Texas in business at the
Scarlet Knights' two-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot play head-to-head with Texas or any team of that
quality and have a punt blocked and have a muff,'' Rutgers coach
Terry Shea said. ``The breakdown was a product of two things. We
had a man shoot one of our gaps, and the snap got back there at a
very average pace. And Texas has too much speed not to take
advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first big play came just 62 seconds into the game. Terrell
Dillon broke free on the left side and blocked Titus' punt
following Rutgers' opening possession.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Jones scooped up the loose ball and raced 11 yards for
the score to give Texas the early lead.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Dillon, who also blocked a punt against Stanford, was the
first man in on Titus after the fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty much my whole job _ running down the field on
special teams,'' Dillon said. ``I figure if I'm going to be out
there I need to give it my all.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers answered that initial score with a field goal on its
next possession to close within 7-3, but Applewhite had not hit the
field yet.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore guided Texas into Scarlet Knights territory in his
first opportunity, but a sack forced Texas to punt. The next two
times the Longhorns had the ball, Applewhite found the end zone in
short order with touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   On first-and-10 from the Rutgers 28, Applewhite avoided a heavy
rush, stepped up through an attempted arm tackle and lofted a
perfect toss to a waiting Mike Jones, who had gotten behind
linebacker Jabari Moore in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Texas went 56 yards in three plays on its next possession.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite found Ryan Nunez on a deep in route for a 23-yard
gain to the Rutgers 23.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite then hit Montrell Flowers on a virtually identical
pattern on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers danced by cornerback Tony Berry and made it into the end
zone with Moore draped around his feet. Kris Stockton's kick put
Texas ahead 21-3 with just more than a minute to play in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns got their struggling running game going to produce
their next score, and the timing could not have been better.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite was in a head-to-head collision with a Rutgers
defender after completing a pass to Hodges Mitchell, who picked up
21 yards on the play. Applewhite was on the ground only a short
time after getting his bell rung.
</P>
<P>
   The running game took over, as it should have. Rutgers'
defensive line averages 260 pounds, while Texas' offensive line
(even without 367-pound Leonard Davis) averages 320 per man.
</P>
<P>
   Though Texas ended with only 141 yards on the ground, after
averaging just 117 in its first two games, the ground game appeared
to make progress.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Brown ripped off 15 yards and on the next play delivered
the biggest block on a Victor Ike 30-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Ike went around the right side and left freshman defensive back
Nate Colon looking dumfounded. Colon stood flat-footed without
getting a hand on Ike as he passed by on the way to his fifth
rushing touchdown of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting better every game,'' said Ike, who had 94 yards
on 17 carries. ``We're a young team with young backs, and we're
still trying to get it together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
