<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9024 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-BAYLOR-UNLV-HNS &LR;      09-12 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-UNLV-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Baylor gift-wraps UNLV's 27-24 victory
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WACO _ Baylor thought last week's one-point loss was heartbreaking,
but few teams ever will suffer a more shocking defeat than befell
the Bears on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada-Las Vegas won the game on the final play with a 101-yard
touchdown return on a fumble recovery by cornerback Kevin Thomas to
give the Rebels a 27-24 victory at Floyd Casey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With a first down at the UNLV eight-yard line, Baylor only
needed to run out the clock to win the game. Instead of quarterback
Jermaine Alfred taking a knee when the ball was snapped with eight
seconds to go, Alfred gave the ball to tailback Darrell Bush for a
handoff up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush broke a couple of tackles and reached the one as he fought
to cross the goal line, but UNLV linebacker Tyler Brickell stripped
the football and Thomas picked it up in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas took off around the left side and raced down the sideline
untouched for the winning TD with no time left on the clock in
front of a stunned crowd of 32,272 in the home opener for Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth consecutive loss for Baylor, dating to last
season, and ruined the home debut for new coach Kevin Steele.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hindsight is 20-20, and I know what the textbook says,''
Steele said. ``It was stupid on my part, and there is no defense
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to create an attitude of toughness, and we made
the decision to try to hammer it in. That was the intent. It was a
one-in-a-million thing for this to happen. But there's still no
justification for it. We played with fire and got burned. I take
full responsibility for it. It was a lesson learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said his staff talked about having Alfred take a knee but
opted to run the ball forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered it strongly,'' Steele said. ``But we were trying
to create an attitude, and I never thought that could happen. I
have no answer for it. The arrows will come from 10 million
directions, and I will stand here and take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush rushed 24 times for 127 yards and one TD, all he
will remember is the horrific final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That young man gave his heart and soul tonight,'' Steele said
of Bush. ``I made a bad judgment call. It was a sad, sad situation
for the entire team, but these players have a lot of character. I
just want to say, if there's any criticism, it comes at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' run officially was listed at 99 yards because Baylor's
statistics computer does not allow triple digits. But Thomas
clearly picked up the ball one yard deep in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   UNLV now finds itself a surprising 2-0 under new coach John
Robinson after going 0-11 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things looked out of control, but we learned a great lesson
tonight about hanging in there,'' Robinson said. ``I think everyone
still is shocked. It's just overwhelming. It was such a hard-fought
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Both starting receivers for the Rebels had a strong showing
Saturday. Len Ware had eight receptions for 83 yards, and Nate
Turner caught five passes for 85 yards and two touchdowns. UNLV
quarterback Jason Vaughan completed 17 of 27 throws for 192 yards,
two TDs and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game had four lead changes in the fourth quarter, but
Bush scored on a 10-yard run to give the Bears the lead at 24-21
with 6:06 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor defense held UNLV and forced the Rebels to punt
before the Bears' offense worked to run out the clock by driving
down the field.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that plan had worked until the seemingly impossible
happened and left Baylor 0-2 after losing on the last play of the
game for the second consecutive week. The Bears lost 30-29 at
Boston College last week when Kyle Atteberry missed an extra-point
attempt in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears led 10-7 at the half, but Baylor failed to score on
three chances inside the UNLV 25, including two inside the 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to put them away (in the first half),'' Steele
said. ``We have to learn how to put the nails in the coffin. When
we get that kind of momentum, we have to make it big.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears wasted two other scoring opportunities in the first
quarter, including a fourth-and-goal situation when Baylor elected
to go for the touchdown. Elijah Burkins took an option pitch to the
left and was tackled inside the one by UNLV safety Quincy Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor defense forced the Rebels to punt from their end
zone, and the Bears took possession at the UNLV 31. Baylor had a
fourth-and-three at the UNLV 24 but elected to go for it rather
than punt because of strong headwind. Alfred's fourth-down pass
fell incomplete, and the Bears again came away empty in UNLV
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears drove to the UNLV nine on their final possession of
the first half, but Atteberry missed a 27-yard field-goal attempt
when his kick bounced off the left upright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
