<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-TEN-WILLIAMS-HNS &LR;      09-12 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Younger Williams strikes first blow in budding rivalry
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ The journey that began on the broken glass-strewn
playgrounds of Compton, Calif., ended Saturday inside the pristine
pay grounds of the National Tennis Center, on the floor of the big,
new stadium named for the late Arthur Ashe, the last person of her
race to claim one of tennis' major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Althea Gibson, Serena Williams' muse, opened doors for Ashe, who
in turn opened doors for Zina Garrison and Lori McNeil. The two
Houston women, latter-day trailblazers, had wonderful moments in
their careers, but they never accomplished what Williams, 17, did
at the expense of fellow teen-ager Martina Hingis, a former U.S.
Open champion and No. 1-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one years after Gibson won her fifth and final major title
in what was then called the U.S. Nationals _ and 24 years after
Ashe's career-capping Wimbledon triumph _ the younger of the two
tennis-playing Williams siblings prevailed 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) in a U.S.
Open final as heroic at the finish as it had been horrible at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   Serena, seeded seventh, prevailed despite 57 unforced errors to
Hingis' 24. Told she had that many, Williams said: ``Wow! Imagine
if I stop making so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she also hammered 36 winners, 29 more than Hingis
managed.
</P>
<P>
   An American is assured of claiming the men's title, too, with
Andre Agassi facing Todd Martin at 3 p.m. CDT today.
</P>
<P>
   The last time American-born participants claimed both U.S. Open
titles in the same fortnight was 1982, when Chris Evert and Jimmy
Connors did the honors.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' win was worth $750,000, an unfathomable sum for the
little girl who took up tennis at her father Richard's behest in a
mean-streets neighborhood better known for violence than serves and
volleys. Still, Hingis' superior resume and higher ranking
notwithstanding, this Williams breakthrough was surprising only in
that Serena beat sister Venus, 15 months Serena's senior, to the
championship punch.
</P>
<P>
   But Venus, who lost to Hingis in the 1997 final, gets an
``assist'' for Serena's triumph, having forced Hingis to battle for
almost two draining hours in a rain-delayed three-set semifinal
that didn't conclude until after dark Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said yesterday,'' Hingis said, ``I've never beat both
(Williamses) in the same tournament. Serena was just better today,
after (what happened) yesterday. It was tough. I was always behind,
always having to be defensive. But I had chances. I just didn't
take them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Serena had played four consecutive three-set matches,
upending defending champion Lindsay Davenport in her semifinal,
only Hingis was fatigued at the outset. The top-seeded Swiss miss
found herself overpowered at every turn until Serena's nerves,
understandable considering the gravity of the occasion, opened a
window of opportunity after Hingis saved two championship points
against her serve in the ninth game of the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Both came on errors off Serena's huge, heavy backhand, the next
super shot in women's tennis. She made a whopping 14 backhand
errors during the last four games of the second set, but survived a
five-deuce struggle at the end to hold and force the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Serena was in her element there, having won each of the six she
has been in this year. Tied at 4, after a cross-court forehand had
floated long to cost her a mini-break, Serena bashed a forehand
return that landed inches inside the baseline to return the favor,
then served out the victory when a desperate Hingis lob sailed
beyond the baseline, followed by an errant defensive backhand.
</P>
<P>
   But Serena was of the opinion it never should have come down to
a tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought for sure I was going to hold my serve (in the 10th
game),'' she said, ``but something went dreadfully wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Serena smacked three balls out and another into the
bottom of the net, losing at love. How would she stop the bleeding?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very upset with myself,'' Serena said. ``It was like,
`Serena, this can't happen. You have to think positive things.'
There comes a time when you just have to stop caving. In the end, I
told myself, `You're going to have to perform.'''
</P>
<P>
   Serena, like Venus, is bigger, stronger and faster than Hingis.
She dictated a vast majority of the points in the match, reducing
Hingis for the first set and a half to virtual spectator status.
But Hingis dragged herself off the ropes, earning verbal applause
from her vanquisher, never mind the occasional bad blood that has
existed between the two families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martina is a great champion,'' Serena said. ``She's a real
fighter. She never gives up.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hingis' final shot landed long, Williams' knees appeared
to buckle and she screamed, ``Oh my God!'' Martina gave Serena a
gentle hug and two pats on the back after their handshake at the
net, then Serena headed to the players' box, where her parents and
Venus waited to embrace her.
</P>
<P>
   She kissed her mother, Oracene, and hugged her father while
Venus looked on with what seemed to be a wistful smile. But Serena
contends Venus won't be jealous and will profit from her
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything,'' she said, ``it's going to motivate her. Venus
was up there supporting me. After I lost my first two match points,
I looked over to not my mom or dad but to Venus. She was pumping me
up. It really helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   As little girls, Serena always wanted to win the U.S. Open,
whereas Venus had targeted Wimbledon. They'll get a chance today to
win the women's doubles title after beating Mary Pierce and Barbara
Schett 7-6 (7-2), 6-3 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess when she wins Wimbledon,'' Serena said, ``she's going
to have the same feeling I had today. She has many, many more
opportunities, and so do I. We'll both be fighting for the next
Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9026 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     09-12 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jose proving his act belongs in The Show
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a clean, pure, hold-your-breath moment when everyone in
the ballpark knows the game will be decided by the next move.
</P>
<P>
   For Jose Lima and the Astros, the moment arrived in the eighth
inning Saturday, with the Astros leading 5-3, one out, one run in,
two runners on base, and Sammy Sosa waiting to bat for the Chicago
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Lima was straining to pin down his 20th victory of an unexpected
season. Sosa was looking for his 60th home run of another historic
summer. More than 52,000 fans, the largest crowd of the Astrodome's
last year, were all but maxed out with tension of this perfect
setting.
</P>
<P>
   On the monitors in the press box, you could see Lima's lips
pursing in a fishlike motion. Then manager Larry Dierker popped out
of the dugout, and the words mouthed by Jose were unmistakable:
``No! No!''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker described himself as ambivalent even as he strolled to
the mound and waved in Jay Powell from the bullpen. He felt Lima's
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going for 20,'' he said, ``you'd like to get a
complete game. My heart is with the starting pitcher. He wants to
go on. You saw how late I went out. I had really mixed feelings. I
believe he probably could have gotten Sosa out. But Sammy has four
home runs off him in the last couple of seasons. If he hits one
here, it puts them ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima left the field, making it clear he did so under duress,
acknowledging the ovation by waving his cap so forcefully it seemed
more a gesture of despair than gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to face him,'' he said, of his fellow Dominican. ``I
wanted to do it (clinch his 20th win) in front of everybody. I'm
the kind of guy who wants to finish what he started.''
</P>
<P>
   The scripted ending Jose craved wasn't to be, but you couldn't
fault the results. Powell struck out Sosa, who tried to check his
swing on a pitch in the dirt _ and said later he thought he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never liked this place,'' said the honest, obliging slugger.
``I mean the Astrodome, not the city. I like Houston fine. But I've
never had any luck here. I'm so happy knowing that tomorrow is my
last game here. When I come back next year, no more Astrodome.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sosa, and a multitude of other frustrated batters, the Dome
walls seem to pulse, a haunting place, as if a product of the pen
of Edgar Allan Poe.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no pitching staff has given Sosa more headaches than
the Astros'. He is 1-for-10 in this series and hitting .125 for the
season with one dinger, off Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're great,'' he said. ``All of them. Lima, Powell, (Billy)
Wagner, they all know how to pitch to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell extended the suspense in the eighth by walking the bases
full before Craig Biggio flagged a line drive to retire the side.
Wagner blew away the Cubs in order in the ninth and it was time,
Lima Time, to celebrate. The Astros have won nine in a row,
feasting on the dogs, as they should.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa was left with 59, but he will do what not even Babe Ruth
achieved, becoming the first player to have back-to-back 60-homer
seasons. Mark McGwire will join him, but Sammy will have the
distinction of getting there first, with a team that vanished in
July.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are the worst team in the National League, and that
might be too narrow a geographic distinction. They are ranked 15th
in hitting and pitching, and to make manager Jim Riggleman's task
even more depressing, his players are old and slow. They had three
straight singles to start the eighth, each advancing one base.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this can detract from the dimension of Lima's
achievement _ the first pitcher in the NL to win 20, the first
Astro to do so since Mike Scott in 1989. Lima predicted in spring
training he would achieve this magic number, and you look at his
history and salute him as a candidate for the psychic hotline. In
parts of three seasons with Detroit, his record was 8-16 and his
lowest ERA was 5.70. Pitching in middle relief for the Astros in
1997, he went 1-6.
</P>
<P>
   When injuries gave him a chance to start a year later, he
blossomed as a 16-game winner, and a candidate for a national
talent search. The Astros never have had a pitcher who could also
sing and dance, who has cut an album of merengue rhythms heard in
the Astros' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Does he show his passion, emotion and energy? Is he volatile?
Yes. When he pleases himself, he does a dance step or two that seem
to be part conga and part the twist. If Lima lacks anything, it is
not confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 20 because I believe in myself,'' he said. ``People get
the wrong impression when they see me do my dance on the mound. I
do not disrespect this game. But I want to have fun and be the best
I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined Scott, J.R. Richard, Joe Niekro and Dierker as the
Astros' only 20-game winners. Asked how he welcomed Jose to the
club, Dierker said, ``He didn't need to be welcomed. He ushered
himself in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
