<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Martin adapts, profits from experience
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Martin calls himself a late bloomer. Saturday,
he also was a late boomer.
</P>
<P>
   The mild-mannered, conservative, gray-about-the-temples Martin,
who always looks as if he should be dressed in a business suit
instead of tennis shorts, is routinely decried for his lack of
``killer instinct,'' for his bloodless, aristocratic style in a
passionate, emotional sport. Martin is the anti-Ricky Martin, a
total stranger to la vida loca.
</P>
<P>
   But, against Cedric Pioline in the U.S. Open semifinals, the
seventh-seeded Martin turned into a thug, a brute and a bully. He
was a Spike or a Biff, most definitely not a Todd.
</P>
<P>
   He took off his tie. He loosened his shirt. He rubbed spit on
his hands. Then he played like a linebacker instead of the
stockbroker he resembles, or the schoolteacher he, no kidding,
might become after tennis.
</P>
<P>
   His coach, Dean Goldfine, concedes Martin needs to be more
``ruthless,'' but that was not a justifiable criticism of him
against the journeyman Frenchman, who might as well have had his
back up against the wall, a blindfold over his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline was out of here in 96 minutes, blown off his feet and
then off the grounds by a 6-4, 6-1, 6-2 score. He isn't sure what,
or who, hit him. All he knows is he was out cold before he had a
chance to raise a finger of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of the mugging are Martin, 29, will play on the
final day of a Grand Slam tournament for only the second time.
Given that this is America's Open and he is an American playing a
fellow American in Andre Agassi, today becomes the biggest day of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasis on ``his.'' One of Martin's assets, as a human being
anyway, always has been his strong sense of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'll still put one foot in front of the other,'' he
said when asked what the championship would mean to him. ``I don't
think it matters a whole lot in the broad scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   So, can Martin win? Can he get past the re-focused,
re-energized, again top-ranked Agassi?
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's able to play that way,'' Pioline said of the way
Martin performed against him, ``yes, I think he has a good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin explains himself thusly in the current issue of Tennis
magazine: ``I think being normal is underrated. The idea that image
is everything (you know who's old slogan) goes against everything I
stand for. Substance is what counts _ not that as a player or a
person I'm always as substantial as I'd like. The truth is, I'm
constantly falling short of who I'd like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people who know him, or his game, would dispute such a
self-effacing attitude, but it's a fact his nine mostly
undistinguished years on the ATP Tour have featured a pattern of
near misses and shortfalls, the best-remembered of which was his
humiliating meltdown of Novotna-ian proportions in the 1996
Wimbledon semifinal vs. MaliVai Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, leading 5-1 in the fifth set and serving for the match,
somehow lost it 10-8. The word ``choke'' barely does justice to the
dreadful particulars of the dreary afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin swears he profited from the painful experience,
saying: ``That match humbled me _ in a good sense. I learned that I
could deal with a terrible situation pretty well. I was surprised I
had the strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin gradually rebuilt his confidence. He changed his life
view. He stopped believing he had to play perfect tennis every time
out to win. By lowering his standards, he wound up raising his
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter had pulled out of
the Open with injuries _ both were in his half of the draw, too _
Martin had concluded he was ready to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations and belief are two different things,'' he said.
``I believed it from the beginning; I just didn't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   He suffered moments of self-doubt early in the tournament, then
found himself down two sets to love against Greg Rusedski in the
fourth round Tuesday night. That by-the-seat-of-his-britches
victory, accomplished despite a stomach virus and the midnight
hour, would prove to be the antithesis of his collapse against
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If we believed the Wimbledon disaster defined Todd as a
competitor, felling Rusedski under such adverse circumstances
clearly re-defined him. And Martin threw us for another loop when
the match ended. Showing uncharacteristic spontaneity and emotion,
he tossed his racket into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he threw Pioline instead.
</P>
<P>
   Martin contends the ``Wimbledon thing'' has been out of his
system for a long time. Just the same, he says it was wonderful to
finish so strong, never lifting his foot off the accelerator
against Pioline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased, more than anything else, with the way I
played the last two games,'' he said. ``I'm not taking a monkey off
my back, which I'm sure some people would write, but it was great
to be in the same situation and do something good with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite a decade ago, when Agassi was the boy phenom and had
achieved a top-three ranking, when Sampras, 19, was winning the
first of his 12 majors here, Martin was a Northwestern University
dropout eternally grateful for having received a wild-card spot in
the draw. The subsequent years have seen him overcome a range of
disabilities, from a weak ``heart'' to, in 1997, a shredded elbow.
In the last 10 months, he says he has played ``the best tennis of
my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, better late than never.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
