</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Cubs-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Lima delivers on his promise
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Before the start of last season, there were some serious whispers
about the Astros releasing Jose Lima, who had just endured one of
the ugliest outings in the history of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the voices in the background are muttering something
totally different. They sound something like: cha-ching, cha-ching,
cha-ching.
</P>
<P>
   Every starting pitcher dreams of winning 20 games in a season,
and in Lima's case, it was almost to the point of obsession. The
dream became a reality Saturday when he reached the milestone in
the Astros' 5-3 victory over the Chicago Cubs before 52,010, the
largest crowd at the Astrodome this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you it was going to be Lima time, and it's Lima time,
baby,'' he said. ``The reason I said that back in spring training
was that I believe in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's safe to say the Astros and the rest of baseball believe
in Lima, too. As an arbitration-eligible player after the season,
20 wins means Lima will be moving into a much higher tax bracket
next season.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he's moving into some elite company among Astros
pitchers. That's a far cry from March 1998, when Lima was ripped by
the Kansas City Royals for nine earned runs in three innings in a
spring training disaster.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the 26-year-old righthander became the fifth
pitcher in franchise history to win 20 games in a season, and the
first since Mike Scott did it in 1989. Coincidentally, Scott will
throw out the ceremonial first pitch before today's series final
against the Cubs, who are in position to become the Astros' 11th
sweep victim of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros extended their season-best winning streak to nine
games and could tie a franchise record with a victory today.
</P>
<P>
   Locked in a tight National League Central Division race with
Cincinnati, the Astros have won 19 of their last 27 games and are
on pace to finish with 99 victories despite using the disabled list
16 times.
</P>
<P>
   Several other players have suffered non-disabling injuries,
including right fielder Derek Bell, who was a late scratch Saturday
because of pulled rib-cage muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still falling off, but we keep winning,'' said
shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, who has six hits in his last nine
at-bats. ``That just shows the character of this team. We've got a
lot of good players on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, but Saturday belonged to just one. After the final out
was recorded, Lima bolted from the dugout to retrieve the ball from
closer Billy Wagner, who tied Doug Jones' franchise record by
notching his 36th save.
</P>
<P>
   As the sixth-largest baseball crowd in Astrodome history rose
and applauded, Lima stood in front of the dugout and blew kisses to
the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was for the fans,'' said Lima, who is one victory shy
of Joe Niekro's club record for wins in a season. ``The fans have
been so great to me. I'm just so thankful that I was traded from
Detroit to Houston (before the 1997 season). That changed my whole
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty wins has a way of putting a pitcher's career in a
different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker, along with Lima, Scott, Niekro
(twice) and J.R. Richard, is part of the select group of Astros
that knows what it takes to win 20 games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you win 20 games is by pitching consistently
month after month,'' Dierker said. ``You can't have a slump. Lima
has had a remarkable season, and he was outstanding today. He
doesn't need to be welcomed into it (the 20-win fraternity); he
ushered himself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima allowed three runs (two earned) and struck out seven
batters in 7 innings. Jay Powell bailed him out of a jam in the
eighth inning, including a huge strikeout against Sammy Sosa, and
Wagner pitched a perfect ninth inning to preserve the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to Jay Powell and Billy Wagner, it's a done
deal,'' said Lima, who offered some resistance to Dierker's
decision to remove him from the game. ``It's `game over.'''
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, the game was over when Cubs
manager Jim Riggleman presented his lineup card to the home-plate
umpire. The Cubs' lineup featured only three established major
leaguers _ Sosa, Mark Grace and Henry Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Lima before the game that the Cubs have a lot of young
guys and that you only really have to worry about Grace, Sammy and
Henry,'' said Astros catcher Tony Eusebio, who was 2-for-3 with a
homer and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys were mostly a bunch of rookies, and if he
(Lima) got anything close, they would swing at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eusebio's RBI single gave the Astros a 1-0 lead in the second
inning, and the Astros led 3-0 after hits by Gutierrez and Ken
Caminiti drove home runs in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs scored an unearned run in the fourth when Grace raced
home on Rodriguez's fielder's-choice grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Euesbio's fourth homer _ a solo shot to right-center _ rebuilt
the Astros' three-run lead in the fourth inning, and the Astros
scored their final run on Ryan Thompson's RBI single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The runs the Cubs scored without the benefit of an error came on
sacrifice flies by Jose Nieves in the seventh inning and Grace in
the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
