<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-FAA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL CALLS FOR PROBE  OF BABBITT IN CASINO DENIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 FAA WRITES OFF $2.5 MILLION OF AMWEST FINE  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration in Washington waived a $2.5
million fine against America West Airlines in July despite
objections from the agency's Phoenix inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   America West, slapped with a $5 million fine last year over
safety and maintenance violations, had not fully complied with an
agreement to fix the problems, according to the FAA inspectors in
Phoenix who oversee the airline. The company was given a year to
improve maintenance on its fleet of 111 aircraft and add safety and
quality assurance staff.
</P>
<P>
   But FAA administrators in Washington, without explanation,
ignored the June recommendations of their own field inspectors, FAA
documents show. On July 14, they waived the remaining half of the
fine against America West.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic obtained copies of the FAA documents last
week after filing a Freedom of Information Act request.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's files show that Phoenix FAA inspectors sought a
six-month extension of the deadline and wanted to use the remaining
$2.5 million fine as leverage to force America West to resolve
remaining problems.
</P>
<P>
   America West paid $2.5 million of the fine in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix FAA office's final progress report, written by
supervi sor Ron Rosenhahn, said that Amer ica West flew aircraft as
late as this spring that it knew did not meet federal maintenance
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The June 23 report outlines a number of unresolved maintenance
problems and lays the blame on the company's top management, saying
safetycontinues to take a back seat to making money at the airline.
</P>
<P>
   The pervasive nature of the problems at America West ``is
centered on senior management's inability, unwillingness, or both,
to decisively and without market-based mitigation, change their
safety cul ture,'' Rosenhahn wrote.
</P>
<P>
   America West spokesman Ste phen Johnson counters that the
airline has the best safety record in the industry over the past 16
years and senior management is commit ted to maintaining that
record.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe-based airline fully complied with the terms of the FAA
agreement and the company dis putes the findings of the Phoenix FAA
inspectors, said Johnson, America West corporate group man ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never operated an airplane that was unairworthy or one that
caused the remotest risk to the safety of any of our passengers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Turk, an FAA spokesman in Washington, reiterated that
agency administrators determined that America West had complied
with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the questions were sub mitted by telephone by The
Arizona Republic, a written statement from the FAA in Washington
did not address the conflict with Phoenix FAA inspectors over
America West's compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the advice of the local FAA inspectors isn't unusual
for the agency, but it is cause for concern, according to Mary
Schiavo, former inspector general of the U.S. De partment of
Transportation, which oversees the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   FAA administrators in Washing ton are cozy with airline manage
ment throughout the industry, said Schiavo, who wrote a 1997 book
critiquing airline safety titled Flying Blind, Flying Safe.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation by the Inspector General's Office during
Schiavo's tenure in the early 1990s showed that the FAA typically
settles for about 10 cents on the dollar for the fines it levies
against airlines, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA had considered a fine of $11 million to $15 million
against America West in 1998, but settled on $5 million to avoid a
protracted legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   Despite maintenance problems cited by the FAA, America West has
never had an airline crash or fatality after more than 6 million
flights since it was founded in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   And the nation's ninth-largest air carrier has made significant
im provements to its organization and improved safety and quality
con trols, Rosenhahn said in his report.
</P>
<P>
   America West has focused on improving its operations since set
tling protracted contract negotiations with mechanics in October
1998 and flight attendants in March. The company blamed some of its
main tenance problems on its labor trou ble. Profits, meanwhile,
hit $108.6 million on record revenue of more than $2 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenhahn also praised the hiring of Gilbert Mook in April as
Amer ica West's chief operating officer. Mook's initial actions
indicate he may be effective in resolving Amer ica West's remaining
deficiencies, Rosenhahn said.
</P>
<P>
   America West says it has in creased its maintenance workforce by
more than 7 percent _ adding about 90 mechanics and 80 manag ers _
to respond to the safety issues raised in the July 1998 settlement
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Under that agreement, America West was fined $5 million, one of
the largest penalties in U.S. com mercial aviation history. The Tem
pe-based carrier paid half of that fine immediately. The remaining
$2.5 million was to be waived if America West complied.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to waive the second half of the fine angered local
inspectors who felt they were under cut by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 5 memo, Rosenhahn wrote that the decision by Washing
ton FAA officials eliminated the agency's leverage in forcing Amer
ica West's compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenhahn declined comment on the dispute when contacted Sept.
3.
</P>
<P>
   The July 1998 settlement agree ment was a compromise to settle
11 cases of aircraft maintenance and operation violations against
America West.
</P>
<P>
   FAA inspectors had cited Amer ica West for operating 17 Airbus
A-320 aircraft on 40,961 flights while significant structural
inspec tions were overdue from August 1996 to November 1997. The
planes flew an additional 815 flights with out inspections after
the airline was notified of the problem, according to the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors also cited the carrier for unsecured webbing in the
cargo hold of airplanes and for flying a Boeing 757 that was
missing one of its elevator actuators, which control the plane's
tail flap for ascent and descent.
</P>
<P>
   Records also show that America West used masking tape rather
than a required part, called an index plate, to conduct tests on a
power control unit of a Boeing 757 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   FAA inspectors tallied 41,276 violations against America West in
which aircraft were not airworthy by federal standards, according
to FAA documents.
</P>
<P>
   To be deemed airworthy by federal standards, an air carrier must
main tain an aircraft according to rigid specifications spelled out
by the manufacturer, must have all required inspections and use
only approved parts and testing procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's complex safety regula tions are intended to protect
the traveling public by requiring surgi cally precise maintenance
proce dures on aircraft and to spot flaws in safety oversight that
could lead to potentially fatal accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Periodic structural inspections of aircraft are required to try
to detect cracks in the fuselage, which can be deadly if a plane's
skin peels back in flight. That's what happened in 1988 when an
Aloha Airlines flight attendant was sucked out of hole in the torn
fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   Improperly installed cargo netting caused a 1987 fatal crash in
Miami when cargo shifted during takeoff and caused the plane's nose
to tilt upward. &QL; 
The settlement agreement required America West to set up strategic
action teams and develop action plans to address its maintenance
and safety problems. That included over sight of outsourced
maintenance, which has been a major point of contention since the
company laid off about 500 maintenance workers in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Other strategic action teams were formed to address such things
as deferred maintenance, the dispatch and flight-tracking systems,
training programs, flight-crew scheduling and proper maintenance
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   America West was also required to create an autonomous quality
assurance department and appoint a vice president of corporate
safety who operates independently of all other departments.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's final progress report in June identifies a number of
issues that still concern the Phoenix in spectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that 95 percent of the topics would have been
properly addressed if it were not for the priorities of (America
West) being shifted elsewhere,'' Rosenhahn said in his report.
</P>
<P>
   That report also documents other America West maintenance and
safety problems, including:
</P>
<P>
   Operation of 12 Boeing 737 aircraft in June even after America
West acknowledged that improperly installed bolts made the planes
non-airworthy by federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Operating an aircraft for four days in April without proper
avionics tests, even after an FAA inspector pointed out the
deficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix FAA's progress re port also says America West's
internal evaluation program has audited only four of the 20 areas
required by the settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And the report said problems remain with the company's quality
assurance oversight of Air Canada, America West's heavy maintenance
contractor in Winnipeg, Manitoba. Inspectors discovered that Air
Can ada had not properly tested avionics systems on an America West
air craft. Avionics are the electronic and computer components that
con trol aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   America West carried passengers on flights in the improperly
tested plane from April 23 to April 27 even after the company was
notified of the problem, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the FAA report discloses that America West operated a
Boeing 737 aircraft from April 6 to April 22 without proper
maintenance records relating to a wing flap transmission.
</P>
<P>
   America West told the FAA that it allowed the aircraft to remain
in service because no replacement part could be found, the FAA
said. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
