u s BC-FBC-HOUSTON-ALABAMA-H     09-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-ALABAMA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
UH makes Alabama's Alexander look great
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JERRY WIZIG &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ If the University of Houston discovered anything
in its 37-10 whipping at the hands of No. 21 Alabama on Saturday,
it was the simple fact defenders can't ground Crimson Tide tailback
Shaun Alexander with an arm tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the difference in the game today,'' said UH coach Kim
Helton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missed tackles killed us all game long,'' added Cougars
linebacker Wayne Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander compiled 167 yards rushing on 27 carries, scoring on
runs of 17 and eight yards after a 25-yard TD pass from quarterback
Andrew Zow. His 192 yards rushing and receiving compared favorably
to the Cougars' net output of 274. Alabama totaled 505 yards, split
tidily between running (275) and passing (230), while averaging 6.8
per play.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of early missed opportunities before a Legion Field
crowd of 81,110, the Cougars saw a competitive 17-10 game
degenerate when the Tide scored three TDs in just over six minutes
spanning the third and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   UH drove 77 yards with the second-half kickoff, rallying within
seven points on Jason McKinley's 16-yard pass to Orlando Iglesias
when the 6-2 Iglesias outleaped 5-11 cornerback Reggie Myles near
the left boundary of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   That 17-10 margin proved to be the high point for the Cougars,
who were seeking their first win over a Top 25 team since defeating
Southern Mississippi in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-yard punt left the Tide just 40 yards to cover, and Zow
found wideout Freddie Milons uncovered for the final 19 yards after
the UH secondary blew its coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being in a two-deep, we were in a no-deep,'' said
Helton.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's eight-yard run then gave the Tide a 30-10 lead,
concluding a series highlighted by Tim Bowens' diving 32-yard
reception.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore tight end Terry Jones, left uncovered for the second
time on a quick screen pass from Zow, ended the scoring on a
39-yard play with 10:28 remaining. A sack of McKinley followed by
Cornelius Griffin's 17-yard return of the resulting fumble gave
Alabama's defense reason to claim credit for that score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was good coming in,'' Helton said of Alexander,
``and we know he's good when we're leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Helton: ``Their players played well, their coaches coached
well, and their officials officiated well.''
</P>
<P>
   Without making any specific criticisms of the latter in the wake
of the 27-point loss, Helton also couldn't help but note, ``We get
to the one-foot line and get a clip called.''
</P>
<P>
   That second-quarter play eventually helped negate an 88-yard
drive by the Cougars that produced nothing when Clark missed a
39-yard field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's 80-yard drive with the opening kickoff finished with
what turned into Zow's 25-yard pass to Alexander coming out of the
backfield on third-and-17. Ryan Pflugner kicked a 26-yard field
goal for a 10-0 lead after the Tide drove 53 yards on its second
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Ketric Sanford's 64-yard kickoff return to the Bama 31 preceded
a second-and-four for UH at the Tide 15, but the Cougars were
forced to settle for Clark's 32-yard field goal and a 10-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias, who caught six passes for 105 yards, had receptions of
39 and 26 yards in the next UH series, which reached the Alabama
six. Mike Green carried a quick pitch to the three (not the
one-foot line) before the clipping penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made a big difference,'' Helton said of the penalty, one of
11 called on his team for a total of 92 yards (Alabama had nine for
92 yards). ``We got close in the second half, but penalties and
their athletic ability wore us down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' Helton emphasized. ``Alabama's athletes and
coaching staff decided this game.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be obvious three plays after UH's aborted series.
Alabama, which often substituted two or three players before each
snap to get various offensive packages on the field, set up with
Jones set out to the left. Redshirt freshman Tyler Watts, who split
time with Zow, fired a quick screen pass to Jones, who broke two
tackles during a 41-yard gain to set up Alexander's 18-yard TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great move at the half by their coaching staff,'' UH safety
Kenny Hill said of the quick screen. ``Alexander showed us his
ability to cut back, and we didn't take the right angles sometimes
in pursuit. So I give him `an all-out good game, Shaun.'''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley's critique: ``We need to make more plays when we get to
the other end of the field. We just didn't take advantage close to
the goal line.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinley was 12-of-25 passing for 169 yards with no
interceptions before Tyson Helton played most of the fourth
quarter. Sanford (12 carries for 49 yards) and Leif Penn (five for
37) accounted for most of the Cougars' 103 net yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Shaun Bohanon, Alexander's roommate, added 95 yards on 12
carries for the Tide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
