<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-CLARK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LONGER GETTING BURNED  
 WIFE, BABY HELP CORNERBACK MATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Like those around him, who make a living putting
out fires, Kareem Clark lives his days to not get burned.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State senior has felt the heat of playing cornerback
in a Division I football program, where only your mistakes are
remembered. Yet just when his career was on the verge of getting
wiped out by a backdraft of hotshot recruits, it was Clark who
emerged as the starting cornerback when the smoke cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I finally realized that I have a family to take care
of and I can't be messing around off the field and on the field,''
he said. ``On the field, I have to take care of business. I think
I've grown up into a productive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark credits his recent marriage and the birth of his daughter,
April, now 5 months old, with providing direction in his life. It
has translated to success on the football field, where he turned
some heads in ASU's opener against Texas Tech and prompted Coach
Bruce Snyder to call him one of that game's ``best tacklers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also thwarted a Red Raiders drive in the first quarter by
intercepting a pass at the ASU 37. He hopes for a similar
performance when the Sun Devils play host to New Mexico State on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kareem has matured,'' cornerback Courtney Jackson
said. ``He has a family now, and he knows he has to take care of
business. He's played well, it's just that people always remember
the bad things about our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   He has come to define what Snyder envisions for his 1999 team: a
group of athletes who have put their lives, on and off the field,
in order.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, whose brother and uncle are firefighters, knows a little
something about heat. Although he started three times last year, it
was more out of necessity than accomplishment. Injuries and a lack
of depth left the Sun Devils scrambling to find healthy
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Although at 5 feet 10 and 186 pounds Clark is one of the team's
smallest corners, he is also one of its fastest players. Yet he
struggled to secure a full-time role, and for that, he blames
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the lack of knowing my position,'' he said. ``I
think I took some things for granted that I shouldn't have. I
wasn't studying hard enough, focusing on the right things at that
time. Now I'm practicing, studying the game more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been (hard). But my father always taught me to keep my
head focused and don't worry about it. He said, `Be ready when you
do get called.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clark was the forgotten man in the off-season. Any talk of
cornerbacks involved a couple of high-profile junior college
transfers, Nijrell Eason and Kenny Williams. Both have shown
promise, but as for most transfers from junior college, the
adjustment to Division I football takes time.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, two of last season's safeties, Christon Rance and
Courtney Palmore, moved to cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Clark, who, like most corners, was sometimes
remembered for things he didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't bother me at all,'' he said. ``It's part of
playing DB. There are going to be games when somebody's going to
beat you deep. What matters is if you can bounce back and play
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is technique. You can be blessed with 4.2 speed,
but if you don't have technique, the guy's going to get open and
catches passes on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Improved technique and commitment have made Clark a better
player. He's also benefiting from an improved defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front line is pressuring the quarterback a lot more, and
that's just making our job easier,'' Clark said. ``Last year, we
didn't have as much pressure, and the quarterback had all day to
throw the ball. That's really hard on us, when the wide receivers
can run over here, over there, across field.''
</P>
<P>
   Said defensive coordinator Phil Snow, ``You can see how much
better they are by how our corners are playing. The quarterback has
less time.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Clark during the football season. His days often start
at 5:15 a.m., because of morning practices, and don't end until
6:30 p.m. His wife, Amber, who is also an ASU student (and former
track athlete), carries much of the load during the fall, and he's
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   Early parenthood has derailed the careers of many athletes, but
Clark calls it a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really great,'' he said. ``My little daughter is
pushing me every day to perform, in the class and on the field.
It's the most exciting thing in the world. God has blessed me with
a beautiful daughter and a lovely wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his peers, Clark dreams of a future in professional
football, but if it doesn't happen, he may pursue a career as a
firefighter or probation officer. He'll have his degree in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he'll keep trying to hold off a group of talented
recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not to my fullest potential yet, but every game I'm
getting better and better and better,'' Clark said. ``That's my No.
1 objective: to improve every game and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   And to cool off some of the Pac-10's best receivers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
