<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-RICE-MICHIGAN-HNS     09-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-MICHIGAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Michigan outmans Rice
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ After suffering six turnovers last week against
Houston, the Rice offense cut that in half Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being victimized by self-inflicted mistakes, Rice
was overmatched against a Michigan defense that did not allow the
Owls to cross midfield until 3:28 remained in the game. Rice was
limited to a field goal for the second time in two weeks, losing
37-3 to the sixth-ranked Wolverines before 110,501 at Michigan
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their superior talent was hard to overcome,'' Rice coach Ken
Hatfield said. ``They deserved to win. They were the better team,
and they proved it today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls (0-2) had 157 total yards, their fewest since gaining
119 yards in a 49-0 loss to BYU in 1996. Rice will play at the
University of Texas this weekend still looking for its first
touchdown, which is atypical for the Owls' triple-option attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts real bad (not to score a touchdown),'' said Rice
offensive tackle Aaron Sandoval. ``It's totally uncharacteristic of
this offense and these coaches and these players. That's first on
our mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatfield said it was hard for the offense to play consistently
because of Michigan's physical supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we called a play and Williams (Josh Williams, the
Wolverines' defensive lineman from Cypress Creek) whipped us at the
point of attack, then we are not going to get on that guy because
Williams is better than him,'' Hatfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, if he did what we asked to do and did the best he could,
then fine. But if he didn't do what he was coached to do, then we
didn't make improvement. While we may have made some improvement,
we didn't have as much success because of the strength of the
Michigan defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines' defense threw the Owls for losses on nine plays,
forcing the Rice defense to spend more time on the field than
normal. The defense gave a good accounting in the first half and
even stopped Michigan twice on fourth down in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense couldn't prevent the Big Ten powerhouse from
scoring when the Wolverines (2-0) obtained good field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense played great and gave us a chance to win,''
Sandoval said. ``One of the things the coaches stress is total team
blocking where all 11 guys perform their assignments on every play.
Until we get better on that, our offense won't be as good as it can
be. We are going to have to work on that this week if we are going
to beat Texas. I have total faith that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice's defense held Michigan off the scoreboard until 2:48
remained in the first quarter, when Jeff Del Verne kicked a 24-yard
field goal. After taking a 10-0 lead on a one-yard plunge by
quarterback Drew Henson early in the second quarter, the Wolverines
tacked on a 38-yard field goal by Del Verne six minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But the massive crowd still was uneasy about the way the game
was going until Henson threw a 14-yard scoring strike to receiver
David Terrell with 1:34 left in the first half for a 20-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of third-quarter touchdowns by Anthony Thomas on runs of
11 and four yards produced a 34-0 Michigan lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines had only 132 of its 356 yards on the ground,
beating Rice through the air and on special teams. The Owls said
they were not going to let the Wolverines beat them with their
running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan prides itself on running the ball, and I thought we
did a heck of a job creating traffic in the backfield,'' Hatfield
said. ``We stopped them twice on fourth-and-one, and that was good.
I've been pleased with our defensive effort the last couple of
games.''
</P>
<P>
   But the offense was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we were just swamped,'' Hatfield said. ``We were
trying to find out the whole game where their weak one was on
defense, and we'd kind of run at him and pick on him. We ain't
found him yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither have the Rice defensive linemen or linebackers found the
Michigan quarterback. Tom Brady, Drew Henson and even third-teamer
Jason Kapsner were able to stand like statues in the Wolverines'
backfield and pick out receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The overall superiority did not go unnoticed by Michigan coach
Lloyd Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, we did a tremendous job against the triple
option,'' Carr said. ``I thought we played hard, although there
wasn't a lot of emotion. The real season starts now. We have a
tremendous schedule ahead of us. We must be ready to play and
minimize our mistakes in order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice quarterback Chad Richardson said he knows the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any stupid plays, any blatant mistakes, which
is good,'' Richardson said. ``We are going to try and take the
positives out of this. We're going to bounce back. There is no way
this can make you worse. They are good and the best you are going
to see. We'll move forward from here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
