<SLUG> BC-GAY-MILITARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESERVIST GAY LAWMAKER TRAINS, WAITS WORD FROM ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Whether Arizona lawmaker Steve May should be kicked
out of the Army Reserve has been a discussion across the country,
with debates on Larry King and morning TV and radio shows.
</P>
<P>
   Strangers talk about whether his openness about his
homosexuality should end his military career, and a special Army
investigator is looking into it.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, dressed in his camouflage work uniform and
combat boots, May stood in the shade of a canopy and taught
military strategies to other reservists. For May and the other 120
reservists, it was business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   And the routine of the day was good, the reservists seemed to
agree, after May was forced into the public view this summer when
Army officials began to investigate him because of reports in the
media in which the state legislator acknowledged he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   The attention continued when May hosted a press conference in
New York last month, calling for an end to the military's ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   May, 27, says he didn't start the issue and worries that the
attention could affect his fellow reservists. ``They've been pulled
into this great national debate on this `don't ask, don't tell'
policy and they didn't ask to be part of it,'' he said. ``We're
doing our best to not allow it to become a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, at a huge parking lot outside Phoenix Municipal
Stadium, the men and women in May's 348th Transportation Company
seemed to ignore the issue altogether. Few mentioned it other than
to tease May about the camera crews following what they saw as a
routine training exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most soldiers are professional. They are concerned about
competence, my performance as a leader,'' May said, taking a break
from serving his company hamburgers at lunch. ``They may not like
me . . . or appreciate or understand my sexual orientation, but
they understand that I have a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A few paused to pat May on the back and say, ``Keep it up,'' or
``We appreciate the courage,'' but for the most part the soldiers
remained silent, choosing not to say anything to the media to
indicate whether or not it's a non-issue for most of them.
</P>
<P>
   May said he doesn't discuss his sexual orientation with his
fellow reservists. ``I guess we have a `don't ask, don't tell'
policy on the weekend drill,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   May's case differs from other cases in the military. His
homosexuality became an issue after his dual careers as state
legislator and military reservist collided when he opposed an
anti-gay rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   Army Reserve officials began investigating May this summer after
learning of statements he made to the media during the 1999
legislative session when he indicated he was gay. At the time he
made the statements, May was not an active reservist.
</P>
<P>
   May initially joined the Navy through an ROTC program and in
college transferred to the Army ROTC program. After graduating from
college, he went into the Army.
</P>
<P>
   He was called back to active duty in February, after the
statements had been reported in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, once you're out of the closet, you can't go back in,''
May said. ``So this is really out of my control. But as a good
soldier, I'll do my duty. I will do my job to the best of my
ability. I'll come down here every month and put on my uniform and
train with the troops. That's all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   May says he clearly made public statements about his sexual
orientation. ``The big issue for the Army is did I violate the
`don't ask, don't tell.' And what do they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's policy says the military shouldn't go out of its way
to find out if a service member is homosexual and that the service
member shouldn't be open about it.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether May's statments, made while he was not on
active reserve, violated the policy.
</P>
<P>
   An Army Reserve investigator interviewed May last month. May
said he may hear from the investigator as soon as today about how
the case is proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Under the policy, the military discharged 1,145 homosexuals in
1998, up from 997 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole conflict has been created because I chose to serve
my country in uniform. I chose to serve my community in the
Legislature and I chose to live my life with integrity,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
