<SLUG> BC-WAL-MART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ARIZONA TOWNS BLOCK WAL-MART SUPERCENTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN CRENO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's plans to build at least 16 huge supercenter stores in
Arizona have transformed the state into the latest battleground in
the retailer's effort to barge into the nation's grocery business.
</P>
<P>
   One supercenter has opened in Show Low in eastern Arizona. Mesa,
Payson, Scottsdale and Surprise are scheduled to get the ``big
box'' stores this year or next.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's move into Arizona is part of a larger push to build
supercenters in Utah, Idaho, Nevada and New Mexico. The company
plans to build 150 of the giant stores this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are controversial in part because of their size: They
are 200,000 square feet or larger _ about twice the size of a
typical Wal-Mart and four times the size of a large supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are different in another important way, too: They
combine a supermarket and all other Wal-Mart merchandise in one
giant store.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Wal-Mart has staked its future on the supercenter.
By the end of the 1980s, the company had loaded the country with
Wal-Mart stores and needed a new way to keep growing, said Sally
Wallick, an analyst at Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave them a tremendous amount of growth potential,'' she
said of Wal-Mart's entry to the grocery business. ``That's what
they were looking for and what they needed.''
</P>
<P>
   But city governments, neighborhood groups and grocery-union
members in Arizona are throwing blockades in front of Wal-Mart's
plans. They're fighting the supercenters, and killing off some of
them, in guerrilla skirmishes around the country and around the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are catching on to what this is and understanding the
impact,'' grocery union spokesman Jim McLaughlin said. ``It's not
just a union issue. It's a community issue. Every city in Arizona
needs to make themselves aware of the impact these stores will
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, opponents were successful in stopping a Wal-Mart
Supercenter from being built in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa City Council is squabbling over a location for a
supercenter there. A Gilbert store is on hold after neighbors
protested, and one in Coolidge was delayed until a dispute over the
store's location, an important archaeological site, is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson is sorting through several proposals for controlling
big-box stores after Councilman Steve Leal proposed what he called
a ``hypothetical'' ban on such stores bigger than 100,000 square
feet. Leal said he offered the 100,000-square-foot figure to the
city staff as a way to open discussions on ways to control the
spread of big stores in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, is winning more
battles than it's losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to count Wal-Mart out. They're very tough,''
analyst Wallick said. ``They'll have done their homework about the
market. They have the staying power to tough it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not the sort of company that will turn tail and leave
because `Gee, we didn't expect this. What a shock.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A supercenter was approved by Yuma voters Tuesday. Wal-Mart
prevailed in a similar vote last year in Payson, and that store
also is under construction and scheduled to open early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Show Low Supercenter opened in April after a legal fight
with a grocery union, the United Food and Commercial Workers Local
99R.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart has encountered opposition in other states, but the
company says that the backlash in Arizona has been stronger than
most. The company is not sure why.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart redefined the notion of the big-box store _ bare-bones
stores that stock a lot of merchandise and sell at low prices _
when it opened its first supercenter in Missouri in 1988. Stores
that were big got bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The supercenter strategy is a familiar one in grocery selling:
convenience. The idea is to cram a store with a variety of services
and low-priced items to persuade time-poor shoppers to buy
everything in one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the American consumer has changed immensely,''
Wal-Mart spokeswoman Daphne Davis said. ``People are pressed for
time. They want convenience. I really think people of all income
levels expect value.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fight for public opinion, Wal-Mart is hammering the
themes of price and competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly think there is plenty of room for our grocery
business,'' Davis said. ``We think it will add a level of
competition to that market. While there is competition, you're
still paying higher prices in Phoenix than in other markets.''
</P>
<P>
   But comparing prices at grocery chains can be difficult. Walt
Heller, director of research at ``Progressive Grocer,'' a trade
magazine based in New York, said there have been no authoritative
studies of grocery prices recently.
</P>
<P>
   He said that's mainly because stores stock thousands of items
whose prices change constantly. Compiling comparative data would be
very difficult, Heller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a massive undertaking,'' he said. ``It changes weekly.
It's like trying to nail Jell-O to the wall or getting cats to
march.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller, though, said Wal-Mart's fixation on cutting prices
generally affects its competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do, just by general knowledge, drive prices down in a
market,'' he said. ``Of course, they ultimately drive all the
little guys out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart is following its usual game plan for growth as it moves
into the West _ build an immense distribution center and ring it
with stores. The company is expanding its Buckeye distribution
center, which ships general merchandise, and has opened another one
in Las Lunas, N.M., to handle grocery deliveries to supercenters in
Arizona and nearby states.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's high-tech supply system is the backbone of its
business. The highly automated ``just in time'' delivery network is
designed to keep excess merchandise from piling up in the
warehouses, letting the company minimize costs by buying goods only
when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart won't specify what a new store or distribution center
costs other than to say, ``Millions.'' It's planning $4.9 billion
in new stores this year, financed mainly by cash generated by its
stores, according to the company's 1999 annual report.
</P>
<P>
   Other supermarket companies are bulking up to take on Wal-Mart's
challenge. Two players in the Valley supermarket scene _ Kroger Co.
and Albertson's Inc. _ recently wrapped up mergers that vastly
enlarged their national reach. Kroger, which owns Fry's and Fred
Meyer, is the biggest grocery chain in Arizona and the country.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the motive for expansion is cost-cutting. Bigger
companies consolidate operations and buy larger amounts of
merchandise, putting them in a position to demand better deals from
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   They need those deals because profit margins in supermarkets are
notoriously low. But Wallick said that doesn't scare Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The company is famous for pinching pennies, she said, buying and
distributing large amounts of goods and getting them to stores
cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from learning the ropes of handling perishables like milk
and vegetables, Wal-Mart already was used to the pressures of a
low-cost, price-conscious operating style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the low margins worried them because I think
they thought they could get the volumes they needed to make a lot
of money,'' Wallick said.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, some supercenters are expansions of regular Wal-Marts.
That lets the company squeeze more from existing assets.
</P>
<P>
   The company rang up sales of $1 billion in 1980. The figure
leaped to $26 billion in 1989 and $137.6 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Stone, an Iowa State University economics professor and
frequent Wal-Mart critic, expects Wal-Mart to soon become the
largest grocer in the United States. He said the company has made
mistakes but didn't become the top retailer in the world by being
dumb. &QL; 
Glen Creno can be reached at (602) 444-7483 or at
glen.creno(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
