<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-FUSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOWED UP IN SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ The drama of a playoff berth showdown
between the Revolution and Miami Fusion deteriorated into a
farcical scene Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. The Fusion earned a point after the
match finished 1-1 in regulation time, but only after a bizarre
scene in the shootout, during which Revolution striker Joe-Max
Moore ended up playing goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Both goals were scored within 74 seconds of the first half, the
first by Welton in the 30th minute before the Revolution's Giovanni
Savarese tied the score by crashing a header off the underside of
the bar.
</P>
<P>
   But in the shootout, the Revolution's fate was sealed when
goalkeeper Jeff Causey was ejected by referee Ricardo Valenzuela
for taking down Welton. Moore then slipped a green jersey over his
No. 9 Revolution shirt, and went into the goal. He was unable to
touch Welton's penalty kick or the next two Fusion shots, and Miami
took a 1-point advantage over the Revolution in the Eastern
Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we were robbed a little bit,'' Revolution captain
Mike Burns said. ``The score was 1-1 and that was not an unfair
result. Both teams were trying to get a point and jockeying for
playoff position. If we had lost the point a little differently, it
would be easier to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel like the ref handed them a point. He could have
given the penalty but not the red card. This was a big game and for
the referee to decide it is frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey entered the match in the 45th minute of a 49-minute
second half, replacing player-coach Walter Zenga. The Revolution
nearly broke the tie as Savarese headed in the rebound of a Moore
shot, but was ruled to be offside on Moore's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution then converted the first two shootout attempts
before Welton and Causey collided. Saul Martinez and Brian Kamler
scored the next two Miami attempts and Garth Lagerway saved two
Revolution shots before Paulo Dos Santos missed wide.
</P>
<P>
   Causey now could be suspended for the Revolution's next game,
against Columbus Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela was not originally scheduled to referee the game, but
MLS officials replaced Rich Grady, whose last visit to Lockhart
Stadium resulted in four ejections. Valenzuela seemed to keep the
match under control, though there were several controversial plays.
But the situation deteriorated in the shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions were raised by Valenzuela's decision, since there
are no FIFA rules to cover the shootout, and since the shootout
takes place after regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The game was chaotic during regulation time. Leonel Alvarez,
returning to the Revolution lineup for the first time in three
games, added poise to the midfield and helped limit Fusion
opportunities. Then, substitutes Dos Santos and Johnny Torres
sparked the team in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had excellent opportunities to break the tie. Welton
slammed a left-footed shot off the bar after outmaneuvering Brian
Dunseth in the final minute of the first half. Nelson Vargas had
two opportunities, stopped by Zenga and Alvarez. Then, Edwin Gorter
and Henry Gutierrez set up Martinez before Dos Santos recovered in
the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Moore failed to convert after finding himself free in the
penalty area twice in the second half, then had a point-blank drive
blocked by Lagerway in the 37th minute. Savarese's follow was
nullified for offside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this would be a tense game,'' Revolution general
manager Brian O'Donovan said. ``I called the league just to make
sure they realized the importance of the game, the intensity of the
game. It should have been treated like a Cup final, and I just
wanted to make sure the referee would understand this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not concerned that we lost in the shootout, but only that
everything deteriorated into farce.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Revolution players were reluctant to talk about the match and
the lockerroom was closed to reporters. ``I am not going to say
anything until Tuesday,'' Zenga said. ``It's better for everyone
that I remain quiet. I've been fined enough already this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
