<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9067 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LA     09-12 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA IS OVERMATCHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ UCLA coach Bob Toledo uses motivational tricks
as judiciously as trick plays. He tried both this weekend, with an
inspirational team meeting Friday and some well-timed shenanigans
Saturday night that made for an entertaining and competitive first
half.
</P>
<P>
   But reality eventually emerged and it wasn't kind to the Bruins.
They simply were not ready for this, at least not as they are
currently composed _ with no proven quarterback and 11 suspended
players. In much of the critical third quarter, for instance, their
defense consisted of one junior, six sophomores and four freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   They were not ready for the crowd and the pressure and the
intensity. And most of all, they were not ready for Ohio State,
which used three second-quarter touchdowns to take control of what
became a 42-20 Buckeyes victory before 93,283 fans at Ohio Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team played hard, but our youth showed up,'' Toledo said.
``We didn't execute a lot of things and our field position was not
very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question not having our full team had an effect.
Our guys were worn down and our youth showed up in a lot of
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The game started well and ended poorly for the No.14 Bruins
(1-1). Then again, so did the Hurricane Bowl and the Rose Bowl. No
doubt, UCLA's defense performed better than it did against Miami or
Wisconsin. But there was no high-octane offense in support. The
running game sputtered and the quarterbacks, Drew Bennett and Cory
Paus, were unimpressive.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the game was remarkably similar to Toledo's debut four
years ago this week _ a 35-20 loss at Tennessee. Then, as now, the
Bruins played with spirit but lacked the experience, depth and
talent to match their opponent quarter after quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, they jumped to a 10-0 lead, then watched it disappear
as the Buckeyes rolled for 177 yards and 21 points in the second
quarter. UCLA's touchdown early in the third simply prolonged the
inevitable, as Ohio State quickly regained command.
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue, turnovers, penalties and missed assignments _ all
traits of a young team _ made UCLA's challenge almost
insurmountable. So did an inconsistent running game. Tailback
DeShaun Foster gained just 51 yards and the Bruins averaged a
meager 3.1 yards per rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just aren't clicking,'' right tackle Brian Polak said.
``I thought we were doing all right, but something kept screwing us
up. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems on the line are no different from the problems at
quarterback or the problems on defense. The Bruins started 13
freshmen and sophomores, and just six of the 44 players on the
two-deep were seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we had a lot of guys missing,'' defensive captain Pete
Holland said. ``But we weren't thinking about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have asked for a better opportunity _ to play a
great team like Ohio State on national TV. It was a chance to test
ourselves against a good opponent. It's very disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The game's fourth play was the strangest. It began with Bennett
throwing to Freddie Mitchell, who was surrounded by three Buckeyes.
The ball went through the hands of safety Percy King, then bounced
off Courtland Bullard and Ahmed Plummer, and finally landed on
Mitchell's back.
</P>
<P>
   It rested there for a split second, then fullback Matt Stanley
snatched it off Mitchell's shoulder pad and raced 55 yards past the
stunned Buckeyes for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how long it took for us to practice that play?''
Toledo quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took a 10-0 lead on their most impressive drive of
the game. The key play was a trick: Bennett handed to Mitchell on a
reverse right, then Mitchell threw back to Bennett on the left
side. He ran 18 yards to set up Chris Griffith's 35-yard field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage vanished in minutes as quarterback Austin Moherman
moved the Buckeyes 81 yards for their first touchdown. Ohio State
switched quarterbacks on the ensuing series, but Steve Bellisari
was as good as Moherman _ if not better _ and directed the Buckeyes
to two touchdowns and a 21-10 lead before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins emerged from the locker room with renewed energy. The
defense held and the offense moved the ball. Several option runs
set up the second trick play: an option reverse to Mitchell, who
scampered 33 yards to Ohio State's 7. On the next play, Foster ran
left into the end zone, and the Bruins were within 21-17.
</P>
<P>
   They would get no closer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
