<HEADER>
A9068 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     09-12 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES' STRUGGLES CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For an organization that talks about its lack of
options, the Dodgers do have a few. It's in their starting
pitchers, and the recent performances of Mike Judd and Eric Gagne
have created some flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   The hotly rumored pitcher to be departing the Dodgers near the
trading deadline was right-hander Ismael Valdes, though the Dodgers
elected to hold on to one of its top young pitchers. And when the
offseason arrives, again expect Valdes' name to be thrown around
endlessly in trade scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the last month of the season has a bearing on his market
value, which will be high, remains to be seen, but he certainly
hasn't helped it lately.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes, who said he isn't fatigued, has allowed 17 runs in his
last three starts, including six runs in five-plus innings of the
Dodgers' 6-2 loss to the Mets at Dodger Stadium on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, all in all, a bad game,'' Valdes said. ``I think
everybody, through the season, struggles, and I guess this is my
time. In the month of September, I have no control of my pitches at
all. I'm behind all the hitters. I struggle with my control all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers catcher Mike Piazza hit his second two-run homer
of the series and went 4 for 4. The four hits tied a career-high.
It was the 18th time he's done it, but he said familiarity with his
one-time battery mate didn't play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I had anything to recall,'' said Piazza, who
continues to receive huge ovations when he bats. ``It's a
flattering reaction. Every time I come up there seems to be some
kind of commotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off an atrocious three-inning, six-run stint against
Florida, Valdes walked five to fall to 0-3 with a 8.40 ERA this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Until the start against the Marlins, Valdes hadn't allowed six
earned runs this season. Now, he's allowed six earned runs in each
of his last two starts, during which he has a 13.50 ERA and has
seen his ERA rise from 3.27 to 3.69.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes (9-14) also took over the team lead in losses. He's lost
three straight and six of his last seven decisions. The Dodgers
lost for the 10th time in the last 11 games Valdes started.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes failed to record an out in the sixth inning, allowing the
first five batters to reach. He was knocked out on consecutive
two-run singles by former Dodger Roger Cedeno and Rey Ordonez as
the Mets turned a tie game into a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ismael's just in a little mini-slump,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``I guess the sixth inning, he gets in a jam and he's
not getting out of it like he can. I guess, his last (three)
starts, he's gotten into trouble and he can't get out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9069 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     09-12 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERG MAKES PRESENCE FELT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The hockey season won't end for nine months, so it's
probably unwise to put too much stock in the events of the opening
game of the exhibition schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, against a Phoenix Coyotes lineup missing all its
stars Saturday night, the Kings provided a few flashes of what
could be in store during the upcoming season, defeating the Coyotes
4-0 before a crowd of 6,531 at the MGM Grand Garden Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Finnish defenseman Aki Berg _ back from a one-year exile due to
a contract dispute _ made an instant impact, with a couple of
crunching checks and a goal 21 seconds into the game with a shot
from the slot off the rebound of winger Marko Tuomainen's shot.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Johnson (shorthanded), Dan Bylsma and Len Barrie (power
play) were the Kings' other goal scorers. Goalie Stephane Fiset
made 19 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We outworked them for a lot of the game,'' captain Rob Blake
said. ``The effort was there. The goaltending was excellent. It's
definitely a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Role model: One player not in the lineup for the Kings was
36-year-old defenseman Garry Galley. Coach Andy Murray said this
week that Galley has been the best defenseman in the Kings'
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us before we came that there would be no nonsense in
camp,'' Galley said. ``I came ready to go. I've been happy with the
day-to-day progress. I'm trying to work hard. I figure if the
oldest guy works as hard as he can, everyone will see that and
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said, ``It's exciting to see a veteran buy into things
like he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Galley has plenty of motivation this season. He's entering the
last year of his contract, and he's coming off a disappointing
season in which he was in and out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frustrating year for me,'' Galley said. ``The great
thing about this game is coming back, and if you're ready to stand
up for yourself, you're all right. I feel I can contribute, and I
want to leave the impression I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Contract talk: Phoenix is without two key players, center Robert
Reichel and goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, both of whom are embroiled
in contract disputes. Reichel has signed with a team in Europe but
could return to Phoenix so long as he doesn't appear in a game for
the team after the start of the NHL regular season. Khabibulin
reportedly is seeking $5million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Kings general manager Dave Taylor reported no progress in
contract negotiations with defenseman Mattias Norstrom or in
efforts to secure a work visa for Finnish defenseman Jere
Karalahti.
</P>
<P>
   Betting line: The Detroit Red Wings are 4-1 favorites to win the
Stanley Cup in the latest odds posted by the MGM Grand sports book.
The Kings are listed at 60-1, and the Mighty Ducks are listed at
30-1. Other Cup favorites are Buffalo (5-1), Colorado (6-1) and
Dallas and Philadelphia (both 7-1). The expansion Atlanta Thrashers
are listed at 300-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 03:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TIMOR-REPERCUSSIONS-E     09-12 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REPERCUSSIONS-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR: NO LONGER AN `INSIGNIFICANT' LOCAL MATTER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 11 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   East Timor does not amount to much: it is a tiny territory of
some 800,000 people coveted by Indonesia, a country of 200 million.
That is why the rest of the world has never been much bothered by
what happened there.
</P>
<P>
   But even tiny places can become significant. If the world fails
the East Timorese again, the consequences will be felt far beyond
the fringes of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The body most immediately concerned is the United Nations. It
could hardly have prevented Indonesia from invading East Timor in
1975, after Portugal, the colonial power, had bolted _ though
America, which knew the invasion was coming and did nothing to stop
it, is far less blameless.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could the U.N. have stopped Indonesia from then annexing the
territory and embarking on a campaign of repression that was to
claim, directly or indirectly, some 200,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, moreover, the U.N. never recognized Indonesian
rule and when, last January, President B.J. Habibie surprisingly
offered the East Timorese a referendum, the U.N. organized it with
admirable efficiency: 98.6 percent of the eligible voters cast
their ballots on Aug. 30, and 78.5 percent of them opted for
independence.
</P>
<P>
   But now the territory is engulfed by violence, most of it
carried out by militias determined to frustrate the voters' clear
desire.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost responsibility for this, as for East Timor's earlier
suffering, is Indonesia's. But the U.N., having agreed to hold the
vote, and on Habibie's timetable, is now so involved that it too
will be guilty of a most terrible breach of trust if the East
Timorese are denied their independence, or gain it only after
another bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, the U.N. is not an autonomous
organization whose boss has at his beck and call the troops needed
to impose law and order in unruly parts of the world. It is the
servant of its members, especially the five countries with
permanent seats on the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Two of these, China and Russia, generally stand up for oppressed
peoples only when it suits their ideological or other interests.
But the three others, America, Britain and France, nowadays
proclaim nobler principles and, over Kosovo at least, have been
prepared to rain down bombs and rockets for them.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of persecution, the East Timorese have surely suffered
more than the Kosovars, and arguably the U.N.'s obligation to them
is more explicit.
</P>
<P>
   So where are the West's principles now? On hold, is the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries, such as Australia and New Zealand, are ready to
provide peacekeepers. Australia well might since it has a
particularly guilty conscience about the East Timorese: though they
fought in the Second World War to help prevent a Japanese invasion
of Australia, the Australians _ ever nervous of their big neighbor
_ shamefully broke western ranks to recognize Indonesia's rule of
the annexed territory.
</P>
<P>
   But even Australia will not send in its forces without
permission from the Indonesian government. That is what must now be
extracted.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to take on the Indonesian army, which is widely
accused of orchestrating the militias. And no one wants to
destabilize the world's fourth-biggest country, especially as it is
struggling to restore its economy and establish democracy.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, outsiders are anxious to help. But they should
do so only if the Indonesian government is sincere in what it says
it is doing _ and, to judge by its actions this week, it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie may well have miscalculated in allowing the referendum:
he may have reckoned that the vote would go Indonesia's way.
Neither he nor anyone in the army should miscalculate again.
</P>
<P>
   They should be left in no doubt now that the world will not
allow Indonesia to hang on to East Timor, as it did in 1975. The
current mess is, after all, a direct consequence of that piece of
misguided realpolitik.
</P>
<P>
   Conceivably, diplomatic pressure alone could still work. It will
have a better chance of doing so if it does not all come from the
West.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's Asian neighbors have a powerful interest in regional
peace. Some of them also say they resent the West's predominance on
the world stage. Why then don't they help to bring a little order
to their own neck of the woods by leaning on the powers-that-be in
Indonesia?
</P>
<P>
   The West, however, must also weigh in, making it plain that,
regardless of Indonesia's parlous economy, it will not lend money
to a country in which militias, with the connivance of the army,
make a bloodstained mockery of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomacy, however, may not be enough. In that case, the U.N. _
meaning the Security Council _ will have to threaten, and be ready
to use, force, even without Indonesia's permission.
</P>
<P>
   If it does not, it is hard to see it being taken seriously in
such circumstances again. Rather it will be treated as an outfit
that merely organizes votes and then scuttles, leaving the local
thugs to seize control (as in Cambodia).
</P>
<P>
   That would hearten despots the world over, and dash the hopes of
millions in countries where the big powers have no direct interest.
Yet the big powers too would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   China, Russia and the West all stand to gain from an orderly
world. If the U.N. collapses in disrepute like the League of
Nations, the prospects of finding international solutions for
international problems _ such as the spread of weapons of mass
destruction _ will simply vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps then those western countries that could not tolerate
mass murder in Kosovo will wonder why they could so readily
tolerate it in ``insignificant'' East Timor. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this TIMELY 950-word article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 0318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 03:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-TIMOR-REPERCUSSIONS-E     09-12 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REPERCUSSIONS-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR: NO LONGER AN `INSIGNIFICANT' LOCAL MATTER  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current
(week beginning 11 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   East Timor does not amount to much: it is a tiny territory of
some 800,000 people coveted by Indonesia, a country of 200 million.
