<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-UNLV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR FUMBLE GIVES UNLV MIRACLE WIN AT WIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When he vowed to resurrect the glory days of
Baylor football, this was not the type of ``Miracle on the
Brazos''that first-year coach Kevin Steele envisioned. But the
Bears fell victim last night to what Steele termed a
``one-in-a-million deal''when Nevada-Las Vegas cornerback Kevin
Thomas returned a fumble 99 yards as time expired to give the
Rebels a stunning, 27-24 victory at Floyd Casey Stadium. Rest
assured, none of the 32,272 in attendance _ or the shell-shocked
Baylor players _ will forget Steele's decision to try to pound in
an extra touchdown against a UNLV defense that was out of timeouts
and trailed, 24-21, when the Bears came to the line of scrimmage
with eight seconds remaining. Instead of having quarterback
Jermaine Alfred kneel with the football, thereby killing the
remaining time, Steele said he opted to ``create an attitude''in
his struggling offense and allowed tailback Darrell Bush to take a
handoff between the tackles. Bush fought his way toward the goal
line, where the ball was stripped by Tyler Brickell and Andre
Hillard. It bounced off the turf and into the arms of Thomas, who
sped untouched down the left sideline as the final seconds ticked
off the clock. Fans and Baylor players fell silent as UNLV players
created a huge dogpile in the south end zone. Most did not move
until the public address announcer confirmed that, yes, the Rebels
(2-0) had won and the Bears (0-2) had lost a second consecutive
heart-breaker to start the Steele era. ``We played with fire and we
got burned,''said Steele, whose team fell in overtme to Boston
College, 30-29, last week. ``We learned a very expensive lesson.
``The million-dollar question is, `Why?' And that falls on my
shoulders. I've got an explanation, but it doesn't hold water after
what we just went through.'' Steele said he was seeking to instill
a killer attitude in an inconsistent offense that previously had
failed twice on pivotal fourth-down plays, both in the first
quarter. Instead, the Bears snatched defeat from the jaws of
victory and authored a result perhaps more stunning than the
initial ``Miracle on the Brazos''_ the Bears' 1974 team that won
its first Southwest Conference championship in 50 years despite
being picked last in most pre-season polls. This time, the
unexpected twist of fate had a more immediate return. In the span
of eight seconds and 99 yards, UNLV hit the lottery. Thomas said he
expected to score as soon as he scooped the ball. ``When I picked
it up, the only thing that went through my mind was, `I hope they
don't call it back,''' said Thomas, who saw nothing but a clear
sideline ahead. ``I knew no one was going to catch me.'' After
Thomas capped his game-winning score by removing his shirt, like
U.S. women's soccer heroine Brandi Chastain, several Baylor players
slumped to the turf in disbelief. Jeff McInerny, UNLV's defensive
coordinator, stood at midfield in the postgame bedlam, shaking his
finger toward the stunned Baylor players. In hindsight, said
Steele, running out the clock would have been the textbook call. It
would have preserved a victory for a team coming off consecutive
2-9 seasons. Instead, Steele made a prophet of UNLV coach John
Robinson. Asked at a Monday news conference to comment on Baylor's
heart-breaking loss to Boston College in its season opener,
Robinson said such an outcome was typical of the Bears. ``When you
play Baylor, it's always a physical game. But they always do
something to screw things up. That's been the history of their
program,'' Robinson said. Steele said Robinson's comment had no
bearing on his decision to go for an in-your-face touchdown in the
final minute. He simply wanted to build confidence in his offense,
a move that Alfred seconded. ``I'd run the same play again,'' said
Alfred, the only Baylor player who took part in postgame
interviews. ``I wanted to put more points on the board. But this is
hard. It's like a shot in the heart.'' Steele said his decision
will be chronicled as ``one of the dumbest things that ever
happened'' in college football. ``The flaming arrows are going to
start coming from every direction,'' Steele said. ``This is
unbelievable ... to lose on a one-in-a-million deal. I can't tell
you how bad I hate this right now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
