<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-RUTGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK APPLEWHITE PACES LONGHORNS OVER RUTGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ With 5:28 remaining in a 38-21 Texas victory
last night, the moment many among a record throng of 41,511 at
Rutgers Stadium had been waiting for finally arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Simms, son of Phil Simms, former local hero,
and orangeclad turncoat, entered the game.
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled, the crowd responded with its most enthusiastic ovation
of the evening _ a triumphant chorus of boos that turned to cheers
when, on his third snap, Simms fumbled the ball, and the Longhorns
were forced to punt.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the evening was not a total wash for the home crowd _
although much of it was a severe trial for the Scarlet Knights
(0-2), thanks to the other Texas quarterback, Major Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   Running the Longhorns' season record to 2-1, Applewhite once
again provided most of the zing in the offense, completing 19 of 32
passes for 244 yards and two touchdowns and keeping Texas on the
march through most of the game despite a ground attack (141 yards)
that remained suspect.
</P>
<P>
   With the Knights closely watching ace receiver Kwame Cavil (6
catches, 42 yards), the key receiver turned out to be Ryan Nunez,
who grabbed 7 balls for 104 yards, as Applewhite recorded his 13th
consecutive performance featuring at least 200 yards and one score.
</P>
<P>
   For the Scarlet Knights, the worst of it was picking up one of
Texas' recent bad habits _ giving the Longhorns 14 points on two
blocked punts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that was important was the `W,''' Texas coach
Mack Brown said. ``Even if it was 14-0 I would still be excited.
This wasn't an ugly win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, the Longhorns opened with three
first-quarter touchdowns, in this instance constructing a 21-3 lead
on a blocked punt and two Applewhite scoring passes.
</P>
<P>
   The first blow came 62 seconds into the game when Terrol Dillon
crashed through to block a punt by Rutgers' Charlie Titus, with
Jeremy Jones picking up the loose ball and running 11 yards for the
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights struck back quickly with an 18-yard run from
Jacki Crooks and a completion by quarterback Mike McMahon, but a
35-yard scoring run by Crooks was wiped out by a holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, McMahon hit L.T. Smith for 40 yards to the 5-yard
line, but a running play lost a yard and two passes fell
incomplete, and Rutgers settled for Steve Barone's 23-yard field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   But with Rutgers bottled up, Texas got the ball at the hosts'
42-yard line after a punt. On the second play thereafter,
Applewhite _ who hit seven of his first eight passes for 97 yards _
evaded the rush and hit tight end Mike Jones for 28 yards and the
score.
</P>
<P>
   On the next drive, the Longhorns required three plays to move 56
yards, with Applewhite hitting Nunez for 23 yards and then Montrell
Flowers for 21 yards and the score.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, Texas launched a 10-play,
83-yard drive climaxed by Victor Ike's 30-yard scoring sprint. A
late field goal by Barone left it 28-6 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns extended it with a Kris Stockton field goal, but
the Knights responded with an 11-play, 85-yard drive to move to
within 31-14 as the fourth quarter opened.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster once again struck the Rutgers kicking game, however.
Attempting to punt from his 15, Titus fumbled the snap and Marcus
Wilkins recovered for the Longhorns at the 2-yard line. Chris
Robertson's one-yard dive with 11:39 left severely wounded the
Knights' comeback plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights nevertheless scored once more, but Brown now felt
safe enough to insert Simms and give the home crowd a lift.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
