<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS YOUTH MOVEMENT SHOWS QUICK RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Mike Heika 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If the battle for open winger spots continues to heat
up, Stars general manager Bob Gainey could look like a genius after
letting go of veteran wingers Pat Verbeek, Dave Reid and Brent
Severyn in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars used a team effort to suffocate the Colorado
Avalanche, 3-0, before an announced crowd of 16,103 last night at
Reunion Arena _ getting strong team defense, consistent goaltending
and a great all-around effort from all four centermen. However, the
real story was the increased intensity of the Stars young wingers
as they battle for what could be two open roster spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making it really hard on us,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``I didn't see a weak player.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the competition to claim a place on the defending
Stanley Cup champions, the wingers continue to push each other to
greater heights. Aaron Gavey came up with a big assist and was one
of the Stars' top defensive forwards. Jamie Wright chipped in an
assist and four hits. Jon Sim was all over the ice, delighting the
crowd and drawing two key penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, they complemented the Stars' team-first system
by forechecking hard, creating turnovers and avoiding positional
mistakes on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to stray from the schedule,'' Wright said.
``Not too many bad things happened out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when Wright and Sim were able to play on a line with center
Mike Modano, who was his usual flawless self. And not when Gavey
was able to get a charge from a scrappy Jamie Langenbrunner and a
hungry Derek Plante.
</P>
<P>
   Those two lines dominated an Avalanche team missing most of its
star players. Peter Forsberg is out with a shoulder injury. Joe
Sakic didn't play. Neither did Sandis Ozolinsh, Claude Lemieux or
Adam Foote. The Stars, meanwhile, took advantage of strong play
from Modano, Jere Lehtinen, Langenbrunner, Derian Hatcher and
Sergei Zubov to help the youngsters. In the end, the Stars outshot
the Avalanche, 31-17 and handed goalies Marty Turco and Manny
Fernandez an easy shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche goalie Philippe Sauve, a 19-year-old who is expected
to return to junior hockey, played well, but was overwhelmed.
Langenbrunner scored at the 3:17 mark of the first period off a
smooth feed from Gavey, who was set up behind the net. Stars
defenseman Richard Jackman added a power play goal in the third
period and Modano finished the scoring, chipping in a rebound off a
Wright shot.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 24, who was a part of the Stars two seasons ago and was
sent to the minors last season, said the trip back to the Michigan
K-Wings served as great inspiration. Gavey, who at 25 is on his
third NHL team after stints with the Tampa Bay Lightning and
Calgary Flames, said he is determined to not give the Stars a
reason to send him back to the minors. And Sim, 21, is defiant in
saying he's not going to let the older players get an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing my game and believing I can play at this
level,'' Sim said.
</P>
<P>
   While the team performance might establish the Stars as a great
deal deeper than the Avalanche _ something that could be crucial
after Colorado lost Theo Fleury, Valeri Kamensky and Sylvain
Lefevbre to free agency _ it really only means a 1-0 start to the
preseason. The Stars today travel to play the Phoenix Coyotes at
America West Arena in a scheduled 7 p.m. start and will get an even
deeper look at the prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, but it's fun,'' Wright said. ``I can feel we're
pushing each other, and that's good. Nobody wants anything handed
to him. It's a lot more self-gratifying when you earn it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 1101EDT &QL; 
