<HEADER>
A9116 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-OKLAHOMA-INDIANA-     09-12 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OKLAHOMA-INDIANA-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEUPEL, SOONERS ROUT INDIANA STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ It mattered little to last night's sellout crowd
of 74,119 that Oklahoma stooped to conquer Division I-AA Indiana
State.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite fitting, actually, in that the 49-0 blowout marked
the head-coaching debut of baby-faced Bob Stoops, who turned 39 on
Thursday. But what did matter to the packed house was that the
Sooners overwhelmed the overmatched Sycamores in a style to which
the rabid OU following hopes once again to become accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   This was all for which an offense-hungry throng had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The execution was really pretty sharp,'' Stoops said.
</P>
<P>
   So was junior-college transfer quarterback Josh Heupel. Already
being touted as the best OU quarterback since all-time
total-offense leader Cale Gundy (1990-93), Heupel led the rout by
throwing Gundy-type figures and a school-record five touchdown
passes before the largest crowd to witness a home opener in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The cool left-hander broke Gundy's game-completion record and
tied his school record of 341 yards passing before retiring after a
33-yard scoring strike to Ryan Daniel with 10:40 left in the game.
OU did not score again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh played really well,'' said tight end Matt Anderson, one
of 13 receivers who caught at least one pass from Heupel.
</P>
<P>
   Heupel's numbers included an OU-record 31 completions in 40
attempts with one interception that Stoops said wasn't his fault.
His other touchdowns went for 19 yards to wide receiver Andre
Woolfolk, six to running back Josh Norman, five to wide receiver
Jarrail Jackson and 11 to wideout Julius McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great atmosphere to come into in your first game,''
said Heupel, who dealt praise to the other members of the offense
as well as he distributed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, give credit to the receivers. They did a great
job. And if the offensive line protects me like they did tonight,
we'll be successful in this offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Heupel's numbers are modest for some programs. But don't confuse
Oklahoma with Brigham Young. And don't confuse the Sycamores with a
Big 12 team. But a start is a start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josh did an excellent job directing the day,'' Stoops said.
``I felt good about \Rthe passing game\S, but believe it or not, it
can be better and should be better. We had a few overthrows and
some drops. We can improve on that, and I believe we will as we go
on. We'll add wrinkles as we go, but what you saw tonight is
typical of what we should be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize we'll meet stronger opponents. \RIndiana State\S
was outmanned. We recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners amassed 507 yards total offense and saw some
productive running by senior running back Michael Thornton, who
accumulated 85 yards on 19 carries and scored OU's second TD on a
10-yard dash up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Three different receivers caught at least five passes, led by
Woolfolk's five for 61 yards. Anderson's five went for 55, and
Jackson had five for 54. Linebackers Rocky Calmus and Torrance
Marshall led a defense that limited the Sycamores' wishbone offense
to 195 yards.
</P>
<P>
   By the half, Heupel and the Sooners had already buried memories
of the offensive-sorry Sooners of past season under former coach
John Blake. OU led 28-0. Heupel had thrown for three touchdowns and
177 yards and engineered 279 yards of total offense _ including a
98-yard scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the '98 Sooners averaged only 16.7 points, 109.9
yards passing and 293 yards total offense per game. All but the
latter figure ranked last in the Big 12. The Sooners were 11th in
total offense.  &LR; tagtop:Mike Jones, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:jonz &LR; star-telegram.com
Quick hits OU scheduled Indiana State as a replacement for Arkansas
State, which had committed to the game before discovering it
already had a contract for the date. ... Former QB Brandon Daniels,
expected to be one of OU's top receivers this year, sat out last
night's game for violating a team rule over the summer. ... LB
Rocky Calmus, who led OU's defensive effort, suffered bruised ribs
just before the half, but returned to play in the third quarter.
... OU's last scored this many points in a 51-10 win in 1995
against North Texas. ... Cale Gundy threw his school-record 341
yards against Texas Tech in '91 and hit his 25 completions against
Virginia in the '91 Gator Bowl.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
