r s BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-12 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TCU, IT MIGHT BE TIME FOR A QUARTERBACK CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ TCU coach Dennis Franchione said he doesn't
know what he will do. He shook his head. He looked away. He'll
watch the films, he said, then figure something out.
</P>
<P>
   His darting eyes, filled with agony, told a different story.
</P>
<P>
   As painful as it's going to be, Franchione has to make a change
at quarterback, and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner the better.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that the Horned Frogs suffered a devastatingly
disappointing 17-7 loss to Northwestern yesterday at Ryan Field. It
was ``how'' they lost.
</P>
<P>
   They were embarrassingly pathetic on offense. Pitiful. And the
main problem _ but not the only one _ is senior quarterback Patrick
Batteaux.
</P>
<P>
   This is a difficult truth for Franchione to swallow. He is
almost fanatically loyal, but if he's as smart as I think he is,
sometime this week he will take a walk with Batteaux and break the
news: freshman Casey Printers will be the Frogs' starting
quarterback in two weeks at Arkansas State.
</P>
<P>
   It is a move that is inevitable if the Frogs are to salvage this
season and, with an extra week to prepare, the timing is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if there's ever a perfect time to break a heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that young man \RBatteaux\S,'' Franchione said softly
after the Frogs fell to 0-2. ``I love what he's done for this
program since he's been here. I mean, he didn't ask to be the
quarterback. He's the guy we won the Sun Bowl with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before anybody gets too critical of Pat Batteaux, they need to
appreciate that he's the first quarterback to win a bowl game in 41
years around here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that we don't appreciate what Batteaux did last year.
But big-time college athletics is, of necessity, a
what-have-you-done-for-me-lately business. Batteaux, putting it as
gently as possible, is simply not good enough as a passer to start
for a major college program.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, against a defense geared to stop the Frogs' option
play and tailback LaDanian Tomlinson, Batteaux completed 10-of-23
passes for 96 yards. This, on the heels of a similar collapse in
the second half last week against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He threw low. He threw high. Time after time he threw behind
receivers. The idea of actually leading a receiver seems to be a
foreign concept to him. With his feet always moving, more often
than not Batteaux has the touch of an inebriated bricklayer.
</P>
<P>
   Printers, who came on in the fourth quarter after Batteaux
fumbled away a pitch inside the 5 with the Frogs trailing 14-7, hit
9-of-13 for 109 yards. The difference, even in such a brief cameo
appearance, was startling.
</P>
<P>
   It says here that the Frogs, despite allowing the Wildcats to
hang around and burn them with three big plays _ including an
87-yard punt return for a touchdown _ would have still pulled this
game out if Franchione had gone to Printers earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick Batteaux didn't \Rfail\S cover the punt, he didn't run
the wrong depth on the pass routes, he didn't miss tackles,''
Franchione insisted. ``Patrick Batteux didn't lose this ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but more importantly, he didn't put his team in a
position to win it either, which is what a quarterback must do in
this offense.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there isn't plenty of blame to go around,
including a hefty share for the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   After easily marching 80 yards in 10 plays, capped by
Tomlinson's 1-yard TD dive, the Frogs all but abandoned their
bread-and-butter option play which was working so well, using it
only sporadically the rest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to keep 'em off balance, tried to mix our
plays,'' Franchione explained. ``In retrospect, you're probably
right. We should have run at 'em a little more, should have stayed
with it a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' offensive approach also demands a lot of Batteaux.
Many of his incomplete passes were on rollouts to his left, forcing
him to throw across his body and on the run, a difficult play for
the best of passers and virtually impossible for those with lesser
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the turnover down there inside the 5 is his fault,''
Franchione said. ``The missed passes and some of the other things
are his fault. But not all the fault today lies with Pat Batteaux.
I'll take a lot more of it than Pat Batteaux.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision Franchione faces regarding his quarterbacks may be
his most important since coming to TCU. But the idea of hurting
Batteaux is almost more than he can bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just kills me in this game for anybody to crucify that
kid,'' Franchione said. ``They don't make them better than that
one. Maybe we can't win with him and we'll have to make that kind
of decision. But I'll take every Pat Batteaux that the good Lord
will ever let me coach.''
</P>
<P>
   When they take that walk sometime this week, that might be a
good way to start the conversation.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
