<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-PORTUGAL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PORTUGAL SUPPORTS FORMER COLONY EAST TIMOR
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ Although Portugal is too poor and powerless
to protect the people of its former colony, East Timor, news
reports of widespread murders by pro-Indonesian militiamen have
stimulated an outpouring of pro-Timorese sentiment among the
Portuguese people.
</P>
<P>
   Handmade posters and ``Peace in Timor'' T-shirts proliferated in
downtown Lisbon after violence exploded in the tiny Indonesian-held
territory.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, a hastily organized benefit concert drew an
estimated 15,000 to 20,000 people. The affair culminated with a
candlelight march that attracted teenagers, families pushing
strollers, troops of Boy Scouts in uniform and elderly couples
marching with their canes and candles.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from sales of concert tickets, which cost about $1.15
each, went to an East Timor relief fund, as did profits from $10
``Peace in Timor'' T-shirts that are being sold all over Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to support the East Timorese because they used to
be a territory that belonged to Portugal. We tried to set them
free,'' said Nuno Carvalho, 52. ``We are not here because of money,
but we are taking a position to press the U.N. to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Carvalho said he had never heard of any of the rock groups that
performed but came anyhow because of his concern over the plight of
the East Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   The concert was ``quite spontaneous,'' Ilena Esteves said as she
handed out flyers outside the concert hall in Lisbon's Park of the
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The city is plastered with handmade posters and computer-printed
flyers with messages such as: ``Timor: U.N. In, Already,'' and
``Don't Let East Timor Become a Giant, Independent Graveyard,'' and
``Timor Is Waiting for Your Help.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, one of the poorest countries in Europe, no longer is
the power it was when it had colonies all over the world. The
Portuguese can do little to help East Timor but plead with the rest
of the world to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   The average taxi driver in Lisbon can explain that Indonesia
took over East Timor 24 years ago when other Portuguese colonies
were gaining their independence. Many taxi drivers, like thousands
of Lisbon residents, are flying white scarves from their cars to
show their solidarity with the East Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture swept Lisbon on Thursday when a local radio station
asked listeners to wear white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been broadcasting just on Timor 24 hours a day since
last Sunday at 7 p.m.,'' said Cristina Lai Men, a journalist at TSF
Radio. The station has mixed news on the situation in East Timor
with Timorese music.
</P>
<P>
   For people like Jose Sousa, an East Timorese who has lived in
Portugal for four years, the response in Lisbon has been
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only here, they know we are suffering. This is the only help
we are getting,'' he said, as he marched around the Park of the
Nations with his wife, pushing their son in stroller.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
