<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELKINS13-COX     09-12 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELKINS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drum hiding body ignored for years
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A suburban Boca Raton man killed himself
Friday after New York police interviewed him about a body found in
an oil drum stored for decades in a house he once owned.
</P>
<P>
   The unraveling of Howard Elkins, of the Crescent Lakes gated
community, started late this summer when Ronald Cohen sold his
split-level home in Jericho, N.Y., for $455,000. Elkins had owned
the home 27 years before. All that separated Cohen from his money
was the disposal of a rusting, 345-pound drum that had been rotting
in an attic crawl space for more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen opened the barrel Sept. 2 and found the mummified body of
a pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning police questioned the 70-year-old Elkins about
what Cohen found.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon Elkins walked to the unoccupied home of a
family friend and shot himself dead, a Palm Beach County sheriff's
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Police don't know if the suicide and drum are related. But a
homicide detective for New York's Nassau County Police Department
had been curious enough to fly to Florida to ask Elkins what he
knew about the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County Police Sgt. Robert Edwards returned to Long Island
on Saturday night. A source in the department's homicide squad said
Edwards was investigating a murder and that Elkins ``hadn't been
eliminated from suspects'' in the developing case. A Palm Beach
County Sheriff's Office log entry confirms Elkins' suicide and
lists him as ``a suspect in a 30-year homicide in Nassau County,
N.Y.''
</P>
<P>
   Police credit the airtight drum for preserving clues decades
after the woman's death. On the day she was found, the unidentified
woman measured 4 feet 9 inches and weighed 59 pounds. She wore a
sweater and skirt over high socks and shoes with a discreet heel.
Jewelry also hints at her life: A locket engraved with the words
``Patrice, Love Uncle Phil,'' and a wedding band bearing the
inscription ``M.H.R. XII-59.'' She was also nine months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The Nassau County police source said detectives have turned over
evidence to a forensic anthropologist, anticipating the scientist
will be able to raise currently undetectable fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the woman's death led detectives to Elkins.
</P>
<P>
   Police in New York determined that the drum was manufactured in
1963 and originally held paint that was discontinued after 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Elkins and his wife Ruth owned the home at 67 Forest Drive in
Jericho, N.Y., from 1957 to 1972. The house had two owners between
1972 and the time Cohen bought it in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Elkins had lived in Hollywood before moving into Crescent
Lakes, which is just north of the Broward County line, in 1997. A
man who answered the door to the family home declined to answer
questions Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Ruth and Howard Elkins walked the 1/3-mile loop
around the community daily. The couple also was regularly invited
to cocktail parties at other homes in the 220-family subdivision of
two- and three-bedroom homes worth about $150,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know him well,'' said Joe Schulman, who lives two
doors down from the Elkins' residence on Royal Crown Terrace East.
``I would wave at him over the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Schulman said he heard that Howard Elkins left home for the last
time about 1:30 Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a wallet on him,'' Schulman said. ``All he had
were his keys, so his wife thought he just went swimming at the
community pool.''
</P>
<P>
   About dusk Schulman joined sheriff's deputies and other
neighbors in a search for Elkins. Howard Elkins' son Steve found
his father, with a shotgun between his legs, about 10 p.m. in the
back seat of a Ford Explorer in the garage of a home on Barrister
Drive in Crescent Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Crescent Lakes resident Robert Froment took computer classes
with Elkins at Loggers' Run Middle School. He described him as a
big man with a gray beard who largely kept to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be really down to do what he did,'' Froment said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
