   ARGENTINA-ECON (Mendoza) _ If economics is the dismal science,
then Domingo Cavallo, the former economy minister who is
universally credited with whipping Argentina's hyperinflation in
the early 1990s, is the dismal third-party presidential candidate.
1000 words. By Clifford Krauss. (This story is TENTATIVE.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Vicente Fox Quesada, a leading
contender for the presidency, is officially chosen as his party's
candidate in a nationwide primary. 800 words. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-BOOM (Houston) _ America is an increasingly comfortable
place for young Latinos, who are coming of age at a time when the
sheer growth of the Hispanic population is easing the pressure to
assimilate and lifting ethnic pride. While that pride has most
recently been fueled by the success of some Latino artists and the
phenomenal media attention that has followed, it finds its real
strength in demographic trends that have Hispanic people surpassing
blacks in about five years as the country's largest minority group.
But what these numbers mean to the country is an open question.
2200 words. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-FAILURES (Chicago) _ Over and over again this summer, the
lights went out in this muscular, make-it-work city. Cities around
the country have faced similar frustrations during this sweltering
summer. In New York City, on one of the hottest days of the year, a
power cable short-circuited, leaving 200,000 homes in the
Washington Heights area powerless for 18 hours, the worst blackout
to hit the City in 22 years. Although the reasons behind the power
failures vary from place to place, they hint at deep-seated
problems at the nation's largest electric power companies.
Utilities that are now the lifeblood of the electronic age are
grappling with deregulation, an aging and long-neglected
infrastructure, new and sometimes confusing transmission systems,
and unprecedented demands for the electricity needed to power a
booming U.S. economy. 2000 words. By Pam Belluck and David Barboza.
(This story is TENTATIVE.)
</P>
<P>
   FALN-RETURN (San Juan, Puerto Rico) _ The nationalists return
home after their release from prison to very small crowds and
indifference, heroes to only a small minority of Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   BUSING-RECOLLECT (Charlotte) _ In the place where school busing
began, and is now ending, some recollections from those who lived
through busing itself and from those who fought for it in the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Health care for the aged is
increasingly seen -- and marketed politically -- as a women's
issue. Three quarters of those over 80 are women, and they are more
likely to be poorer and more dependent on government support. How
this translates into political terms. 1300 words. By Robin Toner.
</P>
