<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NBC-ALONE-690(2TAKES)     09-12 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-ALONE-690(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC STICKS TO SOLO STRATEGY AS ITS MEDIA RIVALS CONSOLIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of Viacom's multimillion-dollar betrothal to CBS,
the media spotlight has swung around to NBC, the last network unwed
to a movie studio and left to stand alone on the crowded,
vertically integrated television dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   But as one executive close to NBC and familiar with its
long-term strategy put it last week: ``Don't cry for NBC. NBC is
not some wallflower that has been left at the altar. NBC is in a
whole different church.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because NBC already has a big, rich parent: General
Electric Co. Far from being jealous of the deal that CBS cut with
Viacom, NBC executives said they looked at that transaction as an
excellent asset match for the companies involved _ but something of
an irrelevance for themselves, because it was simply not a deal
that NBC could ever have made.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, as a unit of GE, still functions on an earnings-per-share
philosophy. The Viacom-CBS deal, like most other big media mergers,
involved the melding of two companies that measure their progress
not on the basis of actual profits but according to a cash-flow
concept known as earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization, or EBITDA (which financiers pronounce EE-bih-da).
</P>
<P>
   For media companies, which tend to subscribe to the philosophy
of spending money in order to make money and are not shy about
borrowing to do so, EBITDA is a generally accepted way to keep
score from financial quarter to financial quarter. The assumption,
loosely put, is that the only payoff that matters is a big one
somewhere in the future. But GE, an industrial powerhouse from the
old school of bookkeeping, aims to make money for its shareholders
each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   So every deal that NBC has considered in the past decade has
been deeply influenced by its status as a GE unit. And no deal that
might dilute earnings could be contemplated. That has meant NBC's
passing up a number of properties it would have liked to acquire,
including the Family Channel, a cable network that NBC coveted as a
potential new distribution outlet for entertainment programs but
that, instead, was snatched up by Fox's owner, News Corp., for $1.9
billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC is very near to closing a deal that, while of much
smaller scale than the Viacom-CBS deal, is of high strategic value
for the network. This week, barring an unforeseen last-minute snag,
NBC should conclude negotiations with Paxson Communications Corp.
to spend just over $400 million for a 32 percent interest in that
company's Paxnet network, a lineup of 73 television stations that
reach about 75 percent of the nation's viewers. The deal is not
expected to dilute NBC's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Viacom-CBS deal, NBC executives, while
declining to discuss their strategy on the record, said they did
not feel pressured by the way the other networks have now all
aligned themselves with big partners that own film studios capable
of producing television programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, they say, do they feel hamstrung by GE's insistence on
earnings protection. ``We know the EBITDA game is not the game we
play,'' a senior NBC executive said. ``It forces us to be more
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   So NBC is sticking to the strategy it has long had in place.
That includes adding to its portfolio of Internet holdings and
distribution outlets for its television programming and,
potentially, creating a spin-off company that would combine all
those assets into a separate company with publicly traded shares of
NBC stock.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, NBC could become an EBITDA-based company _
perhaps with GE still holding a major stake, but off the
corporation's earnings-dependent balance sheet. Then NBC would be
free to ``bulk up'' as one senior executive put it, in a deal with
a studio or a large Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of such a move is still uncertain. But speculation
has centered on an NBC spinoff taking place sometime before the end
of 2000, when GE's chairman, John F. Welch Jr., reaches the
mandatory retirement age of 65. One senior NBC executive said of
the spinoff talk: ``It gets a lot of consideration. But it's not in
the cards in the near term.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An NBC spinoff would undoubtedly be a very attractive initial
public offering, several Wall Street analysts said. NBC remains the
most profitable broadcast network by far and its cable offerings,
especially CNBC, are also powerful earnings generators.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, NBC earns so much _ more than $500 million a year, by
some estimates _ that it has become an asset of enormous value to
GE, providing about 10 percent of the parent corporation's
earnings, according to an NBC executive. That is one reason why,
executives involved in NBC's strategic planning said, GE is in no
way eager to sell off the company _ despite many years of
persistent rumors that GE would love to unload NBC.
</P>
<P>
   But those healthy broadcast profits do depend on NBC's
maintaining its position as the leading network with young adult
viewers, a serious challenge given the cyclical nature of network
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's pressure on NBC, it is to continue to dominate with
the 18- to 49-year-old viewers,'' Christopher Dixon, a media
analyst with Paine Webber. ``But in the next two years, a rising
tide will lift all boats.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the booming advertising market that has
raised revenues at every network. Dixon noted that NBC, despite
seeing its ratings decline by double-digit percentages in the last
television season, nevertheless showed an increase of about $100
million in advance advertising sales for this fall's season,
compared with last season.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon agreed that NBC is already so well-positioned _ as the
leader in broadcast media, a force in cable and an active investor
in the Internet _ that it needs to feel no special concern at being
the only network without a link to a big production studio.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the one aspect of the Viacom-CBS combination that
should give NBC pause is the second broadcast stations that CBS
will gain in six of the country's 10 biggest cities if the deal is
approved by the FCC. ``You've got to respond competitively to
that,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   That is where the Paxson deal would come in. If completed, it
will give NBC more than a second station in six big markets; it
will give the network a full second national distribution outlet
for entertainment programming. NBC has sought such an outlet for
years, looking for a way to re-use entertainment programs it owns,
like the ``Tonight'' show and ``Saturday Night Live,'' and thus
help amortize programming costs.
</P>
<P>
   It was widely believed that NBC opened negotiations with Paxson,
owned by W. Lowell Paxson, following the decision by the FCC last
month to allow companies to own second stations in cities with
multiple television outlets. But in fact, NBC has been chasing
Paxson for more than a year, a senior NBC executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Rogers, president for business development at NBC, spoke
with Paxson several times over the past year and finally won an
exclusive negotiation period to close the deal two weeks ago, this
executive said. That period ends next week. NBC expects to announce
that it has acquired 32 percent of Paxson, with the right to
acquire the rest of the company should the FCC relax restrictions
on the number of stations companies can own nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Even without changes, NBC executives said the Paxson deal would
allow it to add the separate entertainment channel it has long
sought. Unlike Viacom-CBS, which may have to divest itself of an
interest in the UPN network, NBC has no concern about an FCC
regulation that limits network ownership of another network. That
is because Paxnet is not among the six entities that the FCC has
defined as a network.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of the station-ownership rules, though, NBC still wants
the FCC to relax the regulations so that it can complete the full
acquisition of Paxson. And on that front, there is one clear
benefit for NBC from last week's marriage announcement by Viacom
and CBS, which have already begun lobbying the agency to change the
rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 1611EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALTMAN-PROFILE-1100(T     09-12 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTMAN-PROFILE-1100(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S LATEST MEDIA WHIZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger C. Altman wants to make a few things clear.
</P>
<P>
   No, he does not consider himself the newest media investment
guru on the block, despite his role in last week's blockbuster
Viacom-CBS deal.
</P>
<P>
   And no, he is not the Altman who was involved in the Bank of
Credit and Commerce scandal in the early 1990s with the late Clark
M. Clifford. (Although he is the Altman who was involved in a
little something called Whitewater.)
</P>
<P>
   And no, he says with the weary sigh of a man who has a
particularly funny last name and has heard the same jokes his whole
life, he is not to be confused with the guy who is married to
Wonder Woman. ``That used to happen all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So get this straight: Roger C. Altman is the former deputy
treasury secretary whose boutique investment firm, Evercore
Partners, last week served as a principal adviser to CBS Corp. in
its $37.3 billion merger with Viacom Inc. That is the same Evercore
that became owner of The National Enquirer five months ago and
plans to introduce a revamped Enquirer in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But he is not the man for whom he is often mistaken: Robert A.
Altman, the former BCCI chairman and the husband of Linda Carter,
the actress who played the star-spangled superheroine in the 1970s
action series ``Wonder Woman.'' (He is even occasionally confused
with Robert B. Altman, the film director who made ``MASH'' and
``Cookie's Fortune.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to have a sense of humor about it,'' Roger C.
Altman said in an interview in his office, a typical banker's suite
off Park Avenue that features both expensively panoramic views of
Manhattan and enough modern art to clue visitors that the quarters'
inhabitant is not a single-minded financial wonk.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With last week's Viacom-CBS deal, in which Evercore earned an
estimated $10 million fee as the principal adviser to CBS, Altman
sealed his growing reputation as a politically connected player on
the media merger scene. But he points out that his seeming
overnight success has been a quarter-century in the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had been in this business less long than I have
been,'' said Altman, who is 53. ``If you go back to the early '80s,
you'll see that I was in charge of investment banking at Lehman
Brothers. I was on the management committee. I was on the board of
directors. It's not like I started my career four years ago. Sure,
our first deal was Westinghouse acquiring CBS, but that was 25
years after I started.''
</P>
<P>
   For many members of the public, though, Altman arrived on the
scene during President Clinton's first term. In 1993, Altman was
seen as a rising star in Washington. But he was forced to resign
his post as deputy treasury secretary in August 1994 under a cloud
of criticism from both Democrats and Republicans. At the time of
the Whitewater hearings, he was criticized by members of the Senate
Banking Committee for delivering what was later determined to be
inaccurate testimony about the extent of communication between the
White House and the Treasury over the Whitewater affair. Five years
later, it is not clear, even to Altman, whether his forced
resignation left a permanent blemish on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know is the honest answer,'' he said. ``We have had
some good fortune recently, but I do not know the answer to that
question.''
</P>
<P>
   It was after he resigned from the Treasury that Altman _
operating out of borrowed space at a friend's law firm, with no
support staff or relationship with any investment bank _ worked his
existing network of connections to become the lead adviser in 1995
to Westinghouse Electric Corp. in its successful bid to acquire
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, he founded Evercore with Austin Beutner and
another partner, and since then has been involved in a half-dozen
transactions for CBS. (There are now three other partners in the
firm.) Other deals have involved Dow Jones, NBC, Court TV,
Tele-Communications, Time Warner and, notably, American Media,
which publishes The National Enquirer. Beutner mainly runs the
firm's investment operations, while Altman mostly doles out advice.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Altman's ties to Westinghouse-cum-CBS can be traced to the
1980s, when he was vice chairman at Blackstone Group, an investment
firm where he worked with Pepsico. Two Pepsico executives, Michael
H. Jordan and Fredric Reynolds, subsequently moved to Westinghouse,
where as chairman, Jordan called on Altman to help engineer the
acquisition of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jordan resigned last year from CBS (the name that
Westinghouse took on), Reynolds, still CBS' chief financial
officer, remained friendly with Altman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they went to Westinghouse, we were able to work with them
in this new capacity,'' Altman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And fortunately, the relationship encompassed Karmazin more
recently,'' he added, referring to Mel Karmazin, the CBS chief
executive, who is to become president and chief operating officer
of Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Closing the Viacom-CBS deal could take several months as the
Federal Communications Commission vets the terms. The FCC will
examine the overlapping ownership in six cities where CBS and
Viacom both operate television stations; the national market
penetration of the two companies' station holdings, which reach a
total of 41 percent of the population, and Viacom's 50 percent
ownership of another broadcast network, UPN. Unless the FCC alters
or waives its rules, the companies will need to reduce their
station holdings to bring the national penetration to 35 percent or
lower, and Viacom will need to scale back its stake in UPN to less
than one-third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether those issues involve us in any of the steps they might
take, we don't know yet,'' Altman said. ``There are a host of other
tasks, and how many of them we will be involved in I do not know.
Karmazin and Redstone are the main leaders here, not us.'' Sumner
M. Redstone is the chairman of Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds self-effacing, it is. Altman declines the
opportunity to characterize himself as the newest media investment
gunslinger to ride into town. And he says he has no plans to start
up one of those schmoozy media-kingpin conferences _ like the
investment banker Herbert A. Allen Jr.'s annual conference in Sun
Valley, Idaho _ that Ken Auletta is fond of writing about in The
New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, no, no,'' he said, waving the firm's prospectus under a
reporter's nose. ``These are my clients, and as you can see, some
of them are media companies, but certainly not all of them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the list of Evercore clients also includes companies as
varied as Schlumberger, the French nuclear power company Framatome,
General Mills, Kmart and Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Altman raised eyebrows when Evercore, which
both advises and acquires companies, purchased American Media Inc.
Altman _ a close friend of the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton
_ suddenly became an owner of The Enquirer, a notorious tabloid
newspaper that regularly splashed Monica Lewinsky's lipsticked
visage across its front pages.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, that newspaper even featured as its cover story
an article alleging that the first lady has had several love
affairs: ``Hillary's cheating dates as far back as the Clintons'
days in Arkansas,'' the story read in part, ``and it continued even
after they moved into the White House.'' And to think that only
five months ago, Mrs. Clinton attended a small private dinner in
her honor at Altman's Upper East Side home.
</P>
<P>
   But Altman is unfazed by any perceived involvement with The
Enquirer, which has spent $50 million on a new advertising campaign
and redesign that will have its debut two weeks from today. Already
underway is a television campaign that features a trim,
authoritative-sounding woman alluding to the tabloid's new
journalistic standards and describing it as the most popular
newspaper in America.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   American Media also publishes other newspapers and magazines
that are off the radar of most of traditional journalism: The
Weekly World News, the weekly tabloid Star and Country Weekly, a
magazine about the country music industry. ``American Media reaches
an audience of 20 million people each week,'' Beutner, who
shepherded the American Media deal, said. ``We think the ability to
deliver interesting content to that large an audience, and deliver
that large an audience to advertisers, and providers of commerce _
whether through direct-response marketing or e-commerce _ is
compelling. And we think the scale of that business can grow
many-fold over the next several years.''
</P>
<P>
   And while smart-alecks at Manhattan cocktail parties may tease
him about the next alien landing, the fact that Altman now owns The
Enquirer seems to have caused no stir in the investment banking
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it is widely known at all in this world,'' said
Robert D. Hormats, the vice chairman of Goldman Sachs
International. Hormats served with Altman in Washington during the
Carter administration, when Altman was an assistant treasury
secretary and Hormats was deputy U.S. trade representative.
</P>
<P>
   Altman, meanwhile, sees the properties of American Media _ The
National Enquirer (a current headline: ``Teen Bride Living Happily
Ever after With Prince Charming, 74!''), Star (``Fuming Fans Give
Kathie Lee a Big Thumbs Down: Stop Dressing Like a Slut!''), The
Weekly World News (``Bat Boy Found in Cave'') and Country Weekly
(``Dolly Takes Charge!'') _ as an investment, not a journalistic
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think American Media is a good investment, plain and
simple,'' Altman said. ``We are not sitting there working on each
week's copy. We are not involved in the weekly or monthly or, for
that matter, any editorial decision of any kind. I think if you
went around and asked any number of reasonably well-established
buyout firms, they approach it the same way. It is management's job
to manage the company. We are financial guys, and we do not manage
the companies.''
</P>
<P>
   David J. Pecker, the former chief executive officer of
Hachette-Filipacchi Magazines who is now the chief executive of
American Media, confirmed that _ to his surprise _ Altman had taken
a hands-off approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Austin first called me and started talking about the
National Enquirer deal,'' he said of Beutner, ``my immediate
concern was that The Enquirer and Star were going to continue to be
pretty hard-hitting, and I asked him, `What is Roger Altman going
to say?' Because at the time, Hillary Clinton and Monica were on
the cover almost every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Austin said, `I can guarantee you will never have a call
from him,''' Pecker said. ``And I never have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
