<HEADLINE>
WAS IT THE MET? NO, `JUICE' SET MTV'S RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The combination of Manhattan's Metropolitan Opera
House, Brooklyn's Chris Rock and MTV's high-glitter roster of
performers attracted a huge crowd to Lincoln Center Thursday night
for the annual MTV Video Music Awards show. And the show fared well
around the rest of the country: 8.1 million viewers tuned in,
making it by far the most-watched entertainment program in the
history of cable television.
</P>
<P>
   In the 71 million households that receive MTV, of those that had
TV sets turned on that evening, 18 percent were watching the awards
show. The television audience was 37 percent bigger than last year,
when the Video Music Awards show was held in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being at the Met and having Chris Rock as host gave us an
incredible opportunity to really generate buzz,'' Judy McGrath,
president of MTV, said Friday. Conveniently, last week's issue of
Time magazine crowned Rock ``the funniest man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's also the overall juice of the channel right now,''
Ms. McGrath added. ``We went into it driving almost 40 percent more
audience than we had the same time last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That is in prime time. But MTV's overall ratings keep growing,
too. ``Total Request Live,'' its live afternoon show, has increased
ratings 150 percent in its time period, also aided by some New
York-generated buzz: the crowds of young people who gather in Times
Square to watch through the giant plate-glass windows of MTV's
second-floor studio as the host, Carson Daly, interviews the latest
hot singer or celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Similar throngs milled outside police barriers at Lincoln Center
last week for the Video Music Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to go to the Grammys and all the other award shows,''
Ms. McGrath said. ``But we're the people who are there every day in
the music business. We come in there every day and put `Total
Request Live' on, and the musicians and performers know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers of the awards show know they are likely to see some
surprises, too _ anything from a star-spangled breast exposed by
the rapper L'il Kim, to a speech by Adam Horovitz of the Beastie
Boys asking for better security to protect women from assault and
rape at outdoor concerts, to MTV's big coup this year, Paul
McCartney, who joined Madonna in presenting the final award of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to get that magic mix,'' Ms. McGrath said, ``the
funny, the profane, the sentimental and the smart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
