<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCURY-NEWS-VIET-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE PAPER ANGERS ITS COMPETITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (js) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vietnamese-language publishers in Silicon Valley are angry with
The San Jose Mercury News for creating a free Vietnamese weekly
that the publishers say unfairly undermines their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a dozen catch-as-catch-can Vietnamese
newspapers in San Jose, Calif., and surrounding Santa Clara County,
a region with a large Vietnamese population. And these other
Vietnamese-language publications now say they dread the idea of
competing for advertising revenues with a newspaper owned by Knight
Ridder, a company that had $3.1 billion in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took over by storm our community,'' said Tam Nguyen, the
managing editor of the twice weekly Saigon USA. ``That's why we
feel resentful. It's a repression, not a service to our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at The Mercury News, however, see little need for
remorse. ``Our commitment here is to serve the whole of this
community today and in the future,'' said Jay Harris, the publisher
of The Mercury News and the free weekly, Viet Mercury. ``We were
looking at a large part of the county that we're not serving. That
conflicts with our journalistic values, but it's also dumb
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury News introduced the Viet Mercury in January, in what
is generally thought to be the first foray of a major U.S. media
company into producing an ethnic newspaper in a language other than
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   About 25,000 copies of Viet Mercury are distributed free each
Friday to 500 restaurants, medical offices, news racks and other
locations with a high level of Vietnamese patronage around Santa
Clara County. The newspaper was introduced after more than two
years of market research showing that 58 percent of ethnic
Vietnamese newspaper readers preferred to get news in their own
language rather than in English. There are about 110,000
Vietnamese-speaking residents in the Silicon Valley area _ perhaps
as many as 200,000 when including the San Francisco Bay area just
north and east of the valley _ the largest concentration of
Vietnamese residents in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Knight Ridder has a history of experimenting with publishing in
foreign languages. (The first newspaper bought by Herman Ridder, in
1892, was New York's German-language Staats-Zeitung.) The company
began a Spanish-language version of The Miami Herald, El Herald, in
1975, and it was revamped and re-introduced as El Nuevo Herald in
1997. And the Mercury News has published a free Spanish-language
weekly newspaper in San Jose, Nuevo Mundo, since 1996. The Mercury
News maintains a news bureau in Hanoi, and the paper has
occasionally run articles translated into Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   The Viet Mercury is a tabloid, with a single article or topic
dominating the front page _ like last week's cover story about
local school districts trying to get Vietnamese parents more
involved in their children's educations. The paper also carries
dispatches from Houston, Southern California, Paris and other
centers of Vietnamese population, as well as stories by The Mercury
News' reporter in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the coverage is related to Vietnamese topics; the
newspaper also ran articles on the war in Kosovo, for example. The
San Jose-based staff of eight covers the local area, and its
stories are sometimes translated for use in the main paper, and
vice versa, said De Tran, Viet Mercury's editor, who came to the
United States in 1975 at age 12 and was a reporter for The Mercury
News, then The Los Angeles Times and again for The Mercury News
before taking his current job.
</P>
<P>
   In creating Viet Mercury, Tran said, the newspaper has
introduced American media standards of impartiality and fairness
into a culture that has long supported advocacy journalism.
``Vietnam still operates under the Napoleonic Code of law, the
French legal system,'' he said, alluding to the country's status as
a former French colony. ``That means you are guilty until proven
innocent. A lot of the time, Vietnamese newspapers, when they cover
a story, don't use `alleged,' don't use `suspect.' They say, `This
guy did this; this guy did that.' We use words like `suspects,' or
`allegations.'''
</P>
<P>
   The real issue for Tran's competitors is their accusation that
the Viet Mercury is offering cheap advertising in an effort to
drive them out of the market. Executives at one newspaper, Gia
Dinh, estimated the Viet Mercury's operating costs at $300 per
page, while another publisher said Viet Mercury was offering
introductory $45 rates for half-page advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But Harris, Viet Mercury's publisher, while declining to reveal
the paper's advertising rates, said its prices had been higher than
most of the competitors' rates _ even before a recent increase in
Viet Mercury's rates, which he said were now the highest in the
market.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are other sources of resentment. Some of the other
publishers, as well as some readers, take exception to the Viet
Mercury's use of Ho Chi Minh City in referring to Vietnam's
capital, rather than Saigon, as it was known before Communists
seized power in the former South Vietnam in 1975. Many Vietnamese
who fled Communist rule still refuse to use the city's new name.
</P>
<P>
   And feelings within the Vietnamese-language publications were
not soothed by Tran's comments in an interview with the trade
magazine Editor and Publisher last year, in which he said
Vietnamese newspapers ``steal stuff'' to fill their pages. And many
are still stinging from a letter Harris sent to other Vietnamese
publishers that remarked on a large number of copies of Viet
Mercury that he said were being stolen from news racks _ a letter
the publishers construed as an accusation of sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   But Tran said the reception from readers had been good. And
Harris said that while Viet Mercury had not been expected to turn a
profit until several years into its operation, the number of pages
already far exceeds what had been forecast. The Sept. 3 issue, for
example, was 176 pages _ about 80 percent of it advertising. The
original business plan had projected issues of only 48 pages by
this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of their presence in our community, I think it brings
to the people another way to run a newspaper,'' said Thuan Nguyen,
the president of the San Jose Vietnamese Chamber of Commerce. ``It
forced the Vietnamese-owned newspapers to find ways to improve
their product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
