<HEADLINE>
FILMS, PARTIES AND HIGH HOPES IN TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A crimson tapestry of rosebuds, flaring red from
spotlights hidden in the gloom, silhouetted the chattering crowd of
publicists, journalists, filmmakers and actors, or ``talent'' as
they are called, as in ``Has the talent arrived yet?'' or ``Where
do we stand to see the talent?'' Waiters snaked their way through
the room carrying trays of citrusy cocktails on which rose petals
floated.
</P>
<P>
   This midnight post-gala party, thrown by Dreamworks at Monsoon,
an aggressively chic downtown restaurant here, was to celebrate
``American Beauty,'' a scabrous comedy about tormented suburbanites
that has emerged as an early favorite at the 24th Toronto
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, at a more cavernous nightspot called the Courtroom,
Disney was giving an even bigger party to celebrate Lawrence
Kasdan's new ensemble comedy, ``Mumford,'' about a seemingly
guileless small-town psychologist, which was also well received at
the festival. A band played upstairs, a second group performed in a
small room near the front door, and waiters carried platters of
sushi, pizza and shrimp tempura through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day Toronto festival, which opened on Thursday night with
the world premiere of an Atom Egoyan film, ``Felicia's Journey,''
will present 319 films, including 64 world premieres and 107 North
American premieres, before closing on Saturday with ``Onegin,'' the
director Martha Fiennes' adaptation of Pushkin's epic poem,
starring her brother Ralph.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto has emerged in the last decade, and especially over the
last five years, as among the most important and popular stops on
the international festival circuit, both as the premiere launching
pad for the Hollywood studios' award-hopeful prestige films and,
increasingly, as a marketplace for smaller films searching for a
distributor or producers of medium-size films peddling
foreign-release rights.
</P>
<P>
   Piers Handling, the festival's director, said he did not
consider this year's event to be all that different from those of
recent years, with its mix of big-studio releases and comparatively
obscure works from every continent. ``Over the past five years the
festival has built up slowly, bit by bit,'' Handling said. ``The
U.S. film industry looks to Toronto in a very serious way, and an
international group comes as Toronto is showing a lot of films with
foreign rights available.''
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the festival, he said, remains the public
screenings at theaters scattered around the city. A dizzying list
of films is made available to Toronto's appreciative and
sophisticated audience, largely nurtured by the festival. ``What we
are is a very large public festival,'' Handling said. ``Not an
industry confab.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was possible to wander through the lobbies of some of
the city's swanky hotels and spot, say, the Miramax co-chairman
Harvey Weinstein chatting happily at one end of the room while the
actor Ethan Hawke was the center of his own cluster at the other,
and Dick Cook, president of Walt Disney Motion Picture Group, led a
group of executives through the lobby to their waiting cars.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the festival on Tuesday, for instance, have a
choice among 62 programs, including Terence Stamp as a British
tough investigating his daughter's disappearance in ``The Limey,''
from Steven Soderbergh; the Hungarian director Istvan Szabo's new
epic, ``Sunshine''; Woody Allen directing Sean Penn in ``Sweet and
Lowdown,'' about a troubled but trend-setting jazz guitarist; Jim
Jarmusch's ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai,'' about a Brooklyn
hit man; and films from Spain, Japan, Sweden, Italy, Ecuador, the
Philippines, Jamaica, Germany, Brazil, China, Iran, South Korea,
Argentina, India, Belgium, Mexico, Denmark, Senegal, Yugoslavia and
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Toronto is a wonderful place to launch a film,''
Kasdan said as he relaxed at the post-gala party for his film. He
had brought ``The Big Chill'' to Toronto 16 years ago, he said, and
felt that it might also be the perfect spot to introduce
``Mumford.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The audiences here are very sophisticated, and they're not out
to get you like audiences at some other festivals can be,'' Kasdan
said. ``They're open and appreciative. It's all very Canadian.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Toronto festival is spread across so many theaters
in different parts of town, it has no real central focus, like the
Palais des Festivals in Cannes, and since it takes place in an
already large and humming city like Toronto, it does not seem to
take over the town in the way that the Sundance festival does in
Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   It resembles not so much a single event as a concentrated series
of events, something like a fraternity rush week, with films backed
by the big studios or the major independents rolling into town for
their two or three days in the spotlight. A series of screenings,
some open to the public and some only for press and industry types,
is followed by a couple of days of print and television interviews
in hotel suites and fancy restaurants, perhaps a big gala at the
cavernous Roy Thomson Hall downtown and the post-gala party at some
nearby nightspot, festooned with red carpets and velvet ropes to
keep the hoi polloi away from the talent and their limousines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ride With the Devil,'' a Civil War epic from the director Ang
Lee with a young cast including Tobey Maguire and the
singer-songwriter Jewel, had its brief window in the spotlight on
Friday and Saturday before handing off to ``American Beauty'' and
``Mumford'' on Saturday and Sunday, soon to be followed by Lasse
Hallstrom's adaptation of the John Irving novel ``Cider House
Rules'' (with Maguire, again) and Scott Hicks' adaptation of ``Snow
Falling on Cedars'' with Hawke on Sunday and Monday, to be followed
later in the week by Robin Williams in the Holocaust drama ``Jakob
the Liar,'' Meryl Streep in Wes Craven's ``Music of the Heart,''
Susan Sarandon and Natalie Portman in Wayne Wang's adaptation of
the Mona Simpson novel ``Anywhere but Here'' and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Each will gets its hours in the spotlight, its round of
interviews, its gala night.
</P>
<P>
   And all around it, films not chosen for the high-profile galas
but still backed by important studios and distributors will jostle
for their share of the attention. Everyone will be looking for the
unknown, breakout hit, and distributors will hope to unearth,
somewhere in the tangle, next year's ``Blair Witch Project''
waiting to be bought for a song.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the dense, noisy gloom of the ``American Beauty'' party, the
arrival of the stars was announced by the eruption of television
lights near the doorway and the slow, snaking progression through
the crowd to the tables in the back reserved for the talent, the
filmmakers and the studio executives. All others stand and scream
into one another's ears while sneaking glances from side to side.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey smiled and waved and hugged his way across the
room. Chris Cooper, his eyes downcast and gloomy, pushed his way
through, pausing only to acknowledge a handshake of congratulations
from the crowd, his face suddenly erupting into a sweet smile. Only
Annette Bening was absent, on the advice of her doctor, publicists
said, as she is pregnant with her fourth child with her husband,
Warren Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Bentley, a young actor with startling blue eyes capped by
pitch-black eyebrows, who has a juicy role in the film as Spacey's
next-door neighbor, looked almost dazed by all the attention as he
made his way to his seat.
</P>
<P>
   He really had not had a chance to get out in the city at all or
see any other films or take part in any festival activities beyond
promoting ``American Beauty'' and attending its premiere. He has
been a happy prisoner of the marketing monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like fun, though,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
