<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON POST'S OPINION PAGE; CARTOONING BY THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (js) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To judge from his most recent books, Fred Hiatt, soon to be
editorial page editor of The Washington Post, has some strongly
held policy views: Anyone with access to 100 lollipops ought to
share them, and baby talk, used judiciously, can be an effective
means of dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But trying to intuit the future direction of The Post's
editorial pages from the deconstruction of the children's books
``Baby Talk'' (Margaret K. McElderry, 1999) and ``If I Were Queen
of the World'' (McElderry, 1997) probably has limited utility _
though the analysis may help understand Hiatt's views on his three
children.
</P>
<P>
   More relevant to the public debate, probably, are the 1,500 or
more columns and articles Hiatt, 44, has written in 18 years at The
Post as a state reporter (Virginia); Pentagon correspondent;
foreign correspondent (Tokyo and Moscow) and editorial writer _
work that displays a nuanced approach to issues.
</P>
<P>
   The heir to the pages shaped over 25 years by the trenchant and
irreverent intelligence of the late Meg Greenfield knows he will be
a czar of pundits just as readers show signs of pundititis. In this
divisive din, the editorial pages are ``where you can make a lot of
the connections that a general-subject newspaper should,'' Hiatt
said last week, after being named to the post he will assume in the
next few months.
</P>
<P>
   If, he said, cable TV programs and Internet sites ``are
fracturing the issues as well as the audience, ideally our page can
be a place where they can come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greenfield and her deputy and immediate successor, Stephen
S. Rosenfeld, produced a page with often-progressive editorials
facing often-conservative columns, but The Post's views have been
hard to generalize. On some issues it takes predictable stands: for
gun control, campaign finance reform and abortion rights. But it
also allows that school vouchers may do some good for some children
_ a view associated with the political right.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever changes may occur will happen gradually, Hiatt said,
but he is looking for new thoughts and voices. The chance to speak
to The Post's 809,000 readers is, after all, better than 100
lollipops. And Hiatt is all for sharing.
</P>
<P>
   A Cartoonist's Drawing That Drew Questions
</P>
<P>
   The article in The Indianapolis Star on Wednesday focused on a
curious local practice: passing the proceeds of a political
fundraiser in honor of one candidate immediately to another.
</P>
<P>
   But some reporters at The Star, owned by Central Newspapers
Inc., noticed the mention that The Star's cartoonist, Gary Varvel,
had illustrated invitations to the fundraiser, a $250-a-head
birthday party for the Marion County prosecutor Scott Newman. Most
proceeds will go to Sue Anne Gilroy, a Republican candidate for
mayor of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters questioned Varvel's involvement in a letter to
their editors.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's publisher, Dale Duncan, said Friday that he had met
with Varvel's boss, the editorial page editor John H. Lyst, that
morning. ``We're in agreement that it's inappropriate for him to do
some of the things he has been doing,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``You just don't want to be that closely tied into
people or organizations that are routinely covered by the
newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns of the Star staff were not unique. Douglas C.
Clifton, editor of The Cleveland Plain Dealer, said: ``The rules of
cartoonists should be the same as the rules for the political
writer. Would you allow our political writer to write advertising
content for a political candidate? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying he made ``a stupid mistake,'' Varvel said he thought the
sketch was for a birthday party, not a political event. ``My
instincts were down,'' he said. ``I don't make a habit of trying to
get people elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
