<HEADLINE>
INTERLOCKING BRICKS BUILD ON THE IDEA BEHIND LEGOS; NEW INDUCTEES
IN INVENTORS HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ohio)  (rm) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What if building a real house were as easy as snapping together
Legos, those brightly colored plastic bricks that kids use to build
miniature structures?
</P>
<P>
   This is a thought that occurred to Dominic Cerrato, a school
administrator, while he was trying to construct a barn on his farm
in Bloomingdale, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty good at electrical wiring and carpentry, but I
didn't know a thing about masonry,'' Cerrato said. ``I started to
wonder why someone hadn't invented some kind of interlocking wall
system.'' He decided to invent his own interlocking blocks, and he
recently received a patent for what he says is the first truly
mortarless brick.
</P>
<P>
   Cerrato's blocks lock together, just as Lego bricks do. However,
the locking system is different. A standard-size Lego brick has
eight cylinder-like protrusions on the top, while the bottom is
hollowed out so that another block's protrusions can snap in
underneath. Cerrato's blocks rely on a tongue-and-groove
construction similar to that used by carpenters. The blocks slide,
rather than snap, onto each other. Cerrato's bricks are stacked
onto a metal track that has been bolted into a concrete footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can build real structures without being an expert mason.''
Cerrato said. ``With this if you make a mistake, you can just pull
it apart. It's goof-proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerrato acknowledged that perhaps a half dozen companies already
manufacture interlocking blocks. ``But they are hollow blocks,'' he
said. ``While in fact they dry-stack their blocks, you have to go
back and pour the mortar back down inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Cerrato's blocks have no mortar, what prevents them from
toppling over like some Lego tower built by an overly ambitious
7-year-old?
</P>
<P>
   At the wall corners, post-tension steel rods are placed at the
bottom and top to help lock the blocks in place. In addition, each
of Cerrato's blocks has two vertical holes that go all the way
through the brick. When the bricks are stacked, the holes line up
with each other all the way through the wall. Once a wall is built,
steel pins are dropped down the holes, and these pins give the wall
its strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can slide them down from the top, because all the holes
will line up,'' he said. ``More rods, thicker rods make for less
movement in the walls. Fewer rods, smaller rods make for greater
fluidity in the walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer modeling experiments suggest that this fluidity will
make the blocks better able than traditional brick and mortar to
withstand earthquakes, according to Cerrato. ``As the wall begins
to flex slightly, Those pins act as internal backbones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this gain in flexibility means a loss in building height.
Cerrato acknowledges that his blocks are good for a structure no
higher than two stories.
</P>
<P>
   And don't look to Cerrato's blocks for a traditional brick
facade. These are, after all, essentially cinder blocks. But
Cerrato hastens to point out that they can be aesthetically
appealing cinder blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can change the color very easily by putting in different
resins,'' he said. ``We can give it a rough texture or put in bands
or other architectural details.'' The blocks are at
www.cercorp.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cerrato, who received patent 5,899,040, hopes to license his
patent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW INDUCTEES IN HALL OF FAME
</P>
<P>
   This week 10 inventors will be inducted into the National
Inventors Hall of Fame, where they will join the august company of
Thomas Edison and 140 other legendary inventors.
</P>
<P>
   Those to be inducted during a ceremony on Saturday at Inventure
Place, in Akron, Ohio, are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bryan B. Molloy and Klaus K. Schmiegel, who headed the
chemistry team at Eli Lilly &AMP; Company that discovered fluoxetine
hydrochloride, better known as Prozac.
</P>
<P>
   _ James Edward West and Gerhard M. Sessler, who invented the
technology used in nearly 90 percent of all microphones today.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donald L. Campbell, Homer Z. Martin, Eger V. Murphree and
Charles Tyson, who while at Exxon developed a process known as
``fluid cat cracking,'' which revolutionized the petroleum
industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ George de Mestral, the inventor of Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   _ Percy L. Spencer, who invented the microwave oven and whose
work with magnetron tubes during World War II helped lead to the
development of the modern TV camera.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
