<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER'S POWER ERODES FURTHER AS PARTY SUFFERS DEFEATS IN STATE
VOTES
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The political plight of Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
intensified Sunday as his Social Democratic Party was thrown out of
government in the eastern state of Thuringia and suffered severe
setbacks in the Ruhr, Germany's industrial heartland.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary plunge in support for Schroeder, who swept to
power a year ago, was most eloquently symbolized by his party's
failure to win municipal elections in Dortmund. The city is so tied
to the labor movement that it was called ``the capital of the
Social Democratic Party'' by former Chancellor Willy Brandt.
</P>
<P>
   Coming after defeats in the Saarland and in Brandenburg a week
ago, the results Sunday amounted to an unmistakable message that
Schroeder has squandered his wide popularity through what seems to
be a mixture of unfortunate hesitations, unconvincing policy and
serious errors of style.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the chancellor's repeated appearances
in luxury Brioni suits, his penchant for fat Cuban cigars and his
much-publicized August-long vacation in the Italian resort of
Positano have not helped at a time when he is arguing for austerity
as a bitter, but necessary, pill for a state-heavy German economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have a series of party scandals in cities that include
Cologne and Dortmund _ involving insider-trading, tax-fraud and
prostitution _ helped the Social Democrats at a time when they
appear unsure of their message.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is trying to modernize his party with a Tony
Blair-type message of entrepreneurship and personal responsibility,
while struggling to retain traditional Social Democratic support
among state employees and workers. But he has been unable to secure
wide backing and appears to have lost votes in the center and on
the left.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been able to keep his electoral promise to cut
unemployment, still running at over 10 percent nationwide and over
20 percent in many parts of the former East Germany. The powerful
German economy is stalled.
</P>
<P>
   In Thuringia, projections by state television networks based on
preliminary returns indicated that the Christian Democrats were
gaining about 8 percent to take a clear majority, with 50.4 percent
of the vote. As a result, the Christian Democrat state premier,
Bernhard Vogel, will no longer have to govern in a coalition with
Schroeder's party.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats' vote appeared to plunge about 10
percentage points, to 19.7 percent _ less even than the Party of
Democratic Socialism, the former East German Communists, which the
projections indicated took 21.4 percent, 5 percentage points higher
than in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   These projected results suggested that the Party of Democratic
Socialism is consolidating itself as the party of preference for
left-of-center Germans from the former East who are disillusioned
with a decade of German unity.
</P>
<P>
   If this proves to be the case, Schroeder's party could be
confronted with serious difficulties in finding the votes it needs
in the east to win national elections. It has apparently not come
up with a successful strategy for dealing with the former
Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a link in state government and the upper house of
parliament, the defeat in Thuringia further erodes Schroeder's
support in the upper house, or Bundesrat, where he will now have to
negotiate with the Christian Democrats on legislation, including a
bitterly contested budget calling for spending cuts of about $16
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In municipal elections in Dortmund, where the Social Democrats
had won about 60 percent of the vote in every local election since
1952, the Christian Democratic candidate, Volker Geers, took 45.6
percent of the vote, the projections indicated, 3 percentage points
more than his Social Democratic rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Democrats are a spent force in Dortmund,'' Geers
declared, buoyed by widespread disillusionment with high
unemployment and a series of scandals, including one involving the
former Social Democratic mayor, Josef Drabig, who was found in a
car with a prostitute earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Geers still faces a runoff with the Social Democratic
candidate, Gerhard Langemeyer, because a victory with at least 50
percent of the vote is required in such elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats apparently lost the city of Cologne by a
crushing margin and seemed to be losing in other major cities of
North Rhine-Westphalia, including Essen and Dusseldorf. The state
is Germany's largest, with 17 million inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Although Schroeder's ``Red-Green'' coalition does not appear to
be in immediate danger, the government now faces an extremely tough
winter. If the chancellor cannot rally support by the time of state
elections in North Rhine-Westphalia next spring, his hold on power
will begin to appear tenuous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
