<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-835&AMP;AD     09-12 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-REFUGEES-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTMARE STILL NOT OVER FOR EAST TIMOR REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-RDP) 
(lb) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUPANG, Indonesia _ ``Go away, quick. It's very dangerous here.
Go back to your home,'' said a panic-stricken man, as he pushed
visitors into their car and hurried back to his wooden shelter.
</P>
<P>
   For this man and the other dispossessed people of East Timor,
fleeing their homeland has not been enough to escape a campaign of
terror. Burned out of their houses and hunted down by
machete-wielding gangs, they have fled or been forcibly moved by
the tens of thousands to neighboring West Timor _ only to encounter
fresh danger.
</P>
<P>
   As the refugees huddle in makeshift camps, militia men, wearing
bright red bandannas and black T-shirts, roam the grounds
menacingly. They harass aid workers and journalists who try to
visit the camps. And they search for refugees who they believe
voted for independence for East Timor in the recent referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are caught here, the militias will kill them,'' said
one young man, who sat in a ragged encampment next to a football
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Kupang, the capital of West Timor, is not as
desperate as in East Timor, where anti-independence gangs have
killed thousands and destroyed the capital, Dili. But the fear here
is pervasive and paralyzing.
</P>
<P>
   In visits to two large refugee camps on Sunday, it appeared that
the army and police were unwilling or unable to control the gangs,
which effectively run the camps. Although the Indonesian government
is supplying food and water to the refugees, international relief
agencies are reluctant to send staff there.
</P>
<P>
   West Timor is firmly under Indonesian control, unlike the East,
which was seized by Indonesia in 1975. But for President B.J.
Habibie, who has invited peacekeeping troops to restore order in
East Timor, the presence of anti-independence militias in solidly
Indonesian West Timor is a sign that the political turmoil is
spreading to other parts of this far-flung island nation.
</P>
<P>
   For the nearly 100,000 people who have fled or been forced out
of East Timor, the gangs mean that their nightmare has not ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable what they have done to us,'' said Yanto
DaCosta, a hollow-eyed 19-year-old who fled East Timor on Sept. 7
after a militia group set fire to his family's house shortly before
dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Awakened by screams and flames, DaCosta escaped by clambering
out a window. As he ran from the house, he glanced behind him and
saw his father being ordered at gunpoint to leave his car. Because
his father owned a photocopy store whose customers were known to
favor independence, DaCosta feared that his father was killed by
the gangs. The rest of the family also fled, and DaCosta did not
know their fate.
</P>
<P>
   DaCosta remembered the week of East Timor's referendum as a
swirl of ugly images. In the aftermath of the ballot on Aug. 30, in
which the people voted overwhelmingly for independence from
Indonesia, DaCosta said, the anti-independence militias became
enraged. After initially aiming their attacks at pro-independence
people, they began killing and burning indiscriminately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter: old, young, boys, girls _ they killed them
all,'' he said. ``You can't believe how mean they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other refugees interviewed here, DaCosta claimed he would
have preferred East Timor to have elected to remain part of
Indonesia. But he seemed baffled by the anger and destruction that
the vote unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the militias lost in the referendum,'' he said,
``they feel they can win if they get to run East Timor by
themselves. If East Timor has to build a new country, they believe
it should be from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees expressed similar shock at the sudden eruption of
anger. Several said they believed the fury was magnified because
the anti-independence factions did not expect to lose the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should face the fact that we lost,'' said a 42-year-old man
who fled Dili with his family on a ship three days ago. As the man
offered his thoughts, an older man shouted at him. The younger man
later said he could be beaten or even killed by gangs for speaking
to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government estimates that 93,000 people have fled
East Timor since the violence erupted last week. Most have been
forced by troops to board trucks into West Timor, where 55,000 have
ended up in a sprawling camp at Atambua, near the border. Another
22,000 have come to Kupang, a seaside town on the western tip of
Timor, surrounded by scrub brush and desolate hills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government said 20,000 are trapped on the East
Timorese side of the border, unable to cross or fearful of doing
so. And these numbers do not take into account people who have fled
and are hiding in the hills around Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Several international aid agencies are concerned that the
conditions in the refugee camps could deteriorate rapidly. Some are
in remote areas, barely accessible by trucks. The agencies estimate
that the government's food rations will last only five weeks,
according to an internal report.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report said that anti-independence militia groups in East
Timor ``are heavily involved in interrogating'' refugees in hotels,
houses, the harbor, and other transportation hubs. ``This situation
has created trauma and fear,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that fear is aimed at foreigners who, in the eyes of
anti-independence militias and even some of the refugees, are
responsible for setting in motion the events that led to the
destruction of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The Australians, in particular, are being singled out for
suspicion, in part because Australia has repeatedly offered to take
a leading role in mobilizing a peacekeeping force for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very volatile, so we have to be careful,''
said one aid worker. He said his agency had sent only Indonesian
staff into the camps, after stripping off their armbands.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, militia groups patrolling a large refugee camp
just outside Kupang have attacked visitors from the U.N. Human
Rights Commission, aid groups from Australia and Hong Kong, and a
reporter from the Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Local religious leaders have demanded that the provincial
governor instruct the police and the army to confiscate weapons
from militia members. One leader, Dr. B. Fobia, warned that if the
governor did not act, it would cause a ``small conflict that will
lead to fatal consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   In the camps, the refugees survive by keeping to themselves.
Some try to ward off trouble by advertising their allegiance to a
unified Indonesia. One elderly man wore a T-shirt emblazoned with
the phrase ``Otonomi, Yo,'' which means ``Autonomy, Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's referendum was structured as a vote for or against
autonomy. By voting down the option of autonomy within Indonesia,
the East Timorese declared that they wanted to break off
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the refugees are simply exhausted and scared.
With their homes destroyed, many of their relatives dead, and the
life of their new country seemingly snuffed out before it had
begun, few seemed to care much about the political issues behind
this calamity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody talks about politics here,'' said one man, as he smoked
a cigarette and peered furtively around the corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
