<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MERCEDES-AD-COLUMN-NY     09-12 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCEDES-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: MERCEDES-BENZ DOES NOT SHIFT MANY GEARS IN 2000
CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever notice the resemblance between the Mercedes-Benz logo and
the peace symbol? The first campaign for Mercedes-Benz USA from its
new agency resembles recent campaigns from its previous agency even
more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there is anything wrong with that. Still, the
considerable publicity generated by an abrupt switch between the
two New York agencies last winter, plus the acrimony _ as evidenced
by a lawsuit seeking $25 million in damages _ led to some
predictions that the campaign promoting the Mercedes-Benz lineup
for the 2000 model year would differ from what went before.
</P>
<P>
   But the television and print campaign by the new agency, Merkley
Newman Harty, echoes the work of its dismissed predecessor, Lowe &AMP;
Partners/SMS, in content, style and attitude. The warmly emotional
tone is back, intended to present the brand as less austere and
more approachable. Returning, too, are elements like the one-word
titles that appear in the lower right corner of the screen during
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Another constant is the wry, cheeky sense of humor that imbued
past ads. Telly Savalas, for example, is shown playing the
lollipop-loving detective Theo Kojak with a full head of hair.
Rhett Butler tells Scarlett O'Hara, ``Frankly my dear, I don't give
a hoot.'' And Mercedes-Benz employees are portrayed as sufficiently
dedicated to their jobs to replace the dummies in crash tests.
</P>
<P>
   Those significant similarities between the campaigns are just
what executives at Mercedes-Benz USA, a division of DaimlerChrysler
AG, say they wanted. The new effort begins Monday and continues
through the fourth quarter with a budget of $50 million to $60
million _ the brand's largest model-year introductory spending
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a continuation, building on what came
before,'' said Mike Jackson, president and chief executive at
Mercedes-Benz in Montvale, N.J. ``What makes it strong is
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had wonderful success in this glorious economy, which
has been satisfying,'' he added, referring to record sales that
have almost doubled in the last three years. ``But the strategies
Mercedes-Benz has been pursuing since the early '90s are what has
driven our success.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson discussed the campaign last week at a meeting at the
Merkley Newman office in New York City, where he was joined by
colleagues and agency executives.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim W. Eberhardt, vice president for marketing at
Mercedes-Benz USA, said: ``We had always been satisfied with the
ultimate creative product from the former agency. That was never a
bone of contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, company executives have attributed the dismissal of
Lowe, part of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Cos.,
to what they described as increasing difficulties in achieving what
they wanted from the agency during the creative process. The
dismissal also came after the retirement of Marvin Sloves, former
co-chairman at Lowe, who had worked closely with Jackson and
Eberhardt on Mercedes-Benz advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic is suing Sloves for $25 million, accusing him of
influencing Mercedes-Benz to leave his former agency and breach of
fiduciary duty. Sloves has denied the allegations and is fighting
Interpublic in New York State Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was widespread industry speculation that
Mercedes-Benz USA had wanted Sloves to join the agency that
replaced Lowe, that has not happened. Other senior executives who
worked at Lowe on the account, with total billings estimated at
$125 million, did leave for Merkley Newman, which is a unit of
Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a combination of continuity and new people who added
some new strategic insight, some new creative strength,'' said Alex
Gellert, partner and group account director at Merkley Newman, who
had been executive vice president and group account director on
Mercedes-Benz at Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the partners and executive creative directors at
Merkley Newman responsible for the 2000 campaign _ Andy Hirsch,
Marty Orzio and Randy Saitta _ had been group creative heads on
Mercedes-Benz at Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   What is new is a theme, ``The Mercedes experience,'' that
celebrates the factory and dealer employees behind the scenes as
much as the brand's logo, heritage, products and driving
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to ``create advocates for the brand'' among car
buyers, Jackson said, because ``there's still nothing as powerful
as the word-of-mouth referral from those enthusiastic about your
product.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is ``not `Mercedes-Benz is the best car,''' he added,
``but `Mercedes-Benz is the best car for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   The initial commercial, and a related print ad, present humorous
mistakes like the hairy Kojak, the misspoken Butler and the Mona
Lisa with a toothy smile. ``Change one thing and it's just not the
same,'' they assert. ``But if every part is exactly right ...
magic. Welcome to the Mercedes experience.''
</P>
<P>
   One commercial is evocative of perhaps the best spot created by
Lowe in the six years that agency handled the account. The spot
used production techniques to make it seem as if people driving and
building Mercedes-Benzes decades ago were joining Marlene Dietrich
in singing ``Falling in Love Again.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, special effects and recreated footage are combined
with contemporary actors dressed in period costumes to offer an
unusual retrospective of Mercedes-Benz safety tests since the
1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Ten TV commercials will appear on local and national broadcast
and cable stations and networks. Fourteen print ads will run in
newspapers and magazines. There will also be Internet ads,
brochures and materials for dealer showrooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
