<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BUTTERFLY-OPERA-REVIE     09-12 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTTERFLY-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: RESOUNDING WITH NOVEL IDEAS, NOT NOVEL ACOUSTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Madama Butterfly'' opened the New York City Opera's fall
season last Saturday night. Familiar and beloved repertory has been
given a fresh look. Singing was always competent and sometimes
more. Workability and sincerity added up to an affecting evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Lamos production, which emanates from the Glimmerglass
Opera company, has the good idea of eliminating Cio-Cio-San's house
altogether, demonstrating in the process what a stage-cluttering
presence it usually is. We are left with a broad set of steps,
sliding screens and our own powers of imagination. The infrequent
crowd scenes are given room to maneuver, and they do so nicely. A
background of blue skies, alternately revealed or denied by the
movable and transparent screens, renders the idea of indoors and
outdoors by simple means.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini's ever-lovely music is less a study of orientalism than
an Italian's daydream of faraway places, one unencumbered by the
niceties of geographic accuracy. The pentatonic gestures,
ingeniously wed to homegrown melody, are, of course, more Chinese
than Japanese. Here the composer's modest advances on traditional
harmony are also convenient buzzwords for the exotic East. We hear
``Madama Butterfly'' too much; but if we must, let it be in
productions like this, where new ideas exist not just for the sake
of newness.
</P>
<P>
   As Lieutenant Pinkerton, Rafael Rojas labors honorably. The
quality of his tenor voice, and the taste and style with which he
uses it, have their limits, and there was indeed more labor than
beauty in this performance. This is also a particularly cloddish
Pinkerton, crude perhaps to excess given the discreet portrayals
going on around him onstage. The supporting characters are
uniformly good: James Maddalena's Sharpless filled with character,
Goro deftly done by John Daniecki, and Kathryn Honan-Carter an
ardent Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
   The center of attention was also the object of our admiration.
Oksana Krovytska sang beautifully as Cio-Cio-San. The voice works;
its sincerity grips the ear, and it is tempered by a judicious
musicality.
</P>
<P>
   It also carries easily in this ungainly theater, which brings us
to the subtheme of last Saturday's performance: a recently
installed ``acoustical enhancement system,'' to use the description
of the City Opera's general and artistic director Paul Kellogg.
With it, reverberation patterns are altered, but we are told that
music will not necessarily be louder. Among lovers of the human
voice, antennas are sure to rise and alarm bells made to sound, for
use whatever words you will, electric current is being used to help
along what God, and singing teachers, gave the human body to begin
with.
</P>
<P>
   So art, too, contributes to the turmoils over genetically
engineered beef, artificially juiced-up corn, duplicating sheep and
other present scientific forays into natural processes. As a
general principle, we should be alarmed. Broadway offers the
grossest example of what might be in store for plugged-in opera.
There, music is bloated and distorted, and even more injurious,
ears have been made lazy. Opera will not survive the indolent
listener.
</P>
<P>
   The City Opera, on the other hand, has a particular, not a
general problem. I have witnessed two acoustical makeovers at the
New York State Theater in the last 20 years; and even though those
grotesque dead spots onstage are gone and music brought a little
nearer, this is a terminally dead space for opera, and one more
makeover is not going to justify the money it would cost for a
little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   I think Kellogg and his company would dearly love to get out of
their current home altogether. But until they can gather the money
and the nerve (it is funny how the first inspires the second), such
tactics as ``acoustical enhancement'' may be the best that can be
done.
</P>
<P>
   If acoustical monkey business was going on at last Saturday's
performance, I freely admit that I didn't hear it. As usual,
mediocre voices did not carry; good ones (Ms. Krovytska's in
particular) did.
</P>
<P>
   Singing from the back of the stage was barely audible, and so
was it ever. The orchestra, conducted by Joseph Rescigno, did sound
particularly loud. Start asking why, and the dubiousness of most
acoustical debate becomes clearer. A very good or a very bad hall
will make its presence known, but halls are small components in the
amalgam of sound that reaches our ears as music. What is being
played? How is it orchestrated? What is the quality of the voices?
What kind of balances can the conductor manage?
</P>
<P>
   Remember that we go to theaters to hear operas not acoustics.
The more we think like engineers, the less we think like music
lovers. Perhaps the judgments over the City Opera's modest
adventure should be left to the singers. This is a company centered
on young voices, and the State Theater has made them strain
uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   The measure of ``acoustical enhancement'' will be in ease of
delivery and health of technique, not in the contemplation of
analog processors, directional microphones, channels and surging
Con Edison bills.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MADAMA BUTTERFLY
</P>
<P>
   Opera in three acts by Puccini, libretto by Giuseppe Giacosa and
Luigi Illica, based on the story by John L. Long and the play by
David Belasco; conductor, Joseph Rescigno; production by Mark
Lamos; sets by Michael Yeargan; costumes by Constance Hoffman. At
the New York City Opera.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Oksana Krovytska (Cio-Cio-San), Kathryn Honan-Carter
(Suzuki), Rafael Rojas (Pinkerton), James Maddalena (Sharpless),
John Daniecki (Goro), Kenneth Floyd (Yamadori), George Cordes
(Bonze), Gregory Hostetler (Yakuside), William Ledbetter
(Commissioner), Louis Perry (Registrar) and Leah Creek (Kate
Pinkerton).
</P>
</TEXT>
