<SLUG> BC-JOURNEY-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: AT THE EARTH'S CORE, NATIVES IN BIKINIS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the bowels of the earth, at the far side of a subterranean
sea, an intrepid band of explorers, slogging through a four-hour
miniseries, comes upon a jungle village and a crowd of dancing,
chanting natives. ``Amazing!'' one traveler says. ``Caucasian
primitives!''
</P>
<P>
   They are indeed palefaces. Maybe the pigmentation has something
to do with the wan light below the earth's crust, a result of
electromagnetic charges in the atmosphere. Or so we're told in
``Journey to the Center of the Earth,'' a shamelessly loose
adaptation of the Jules Verne novel being shown in two parts on the
USA Network Tuesday and Wednesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   But what's even more amazing than the racial makeup of the
aborigines is, well, their makeup. Could that curvaceous huntress
in the animal-hide bikini be wearing lip gloss? It seems so.
</P>
<P>
   But then these young, buff, sexually restless natives appear to
be less from a fantastic nether world than from the hipper sections
of Los Angeles, by way of central casting's costume department. If
not clad in cleavage-baring skins, they wear standard-issue grass
skirts, paint their faces in the usual way and carry regulation
spears.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to pick on the extras. The marquee stars _ Treat
Williams, Bryan Brown, Jeremy London (of ``Party of Five'') and
Tushka Bergen (of the Whit Stillman film ``Barcelona'') _ aren't
entirely convincing, either. But this goofy, old-hat, early ``Star
Trek'' rendering of primitive types underscores how stale so much
of the production is.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pity because it's not as if the executive producers
(Robert Halmi Jr. and David V. Picker) had weak source material.
Verne's 1864 fantasy, thrusting staid Victorians into mystery and
adventure, is rich with cinematic possibility (and far better
realized in the spirited 1959 film with James Mason). But the
makers of this version flub the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Even some not-bad digital effects (including an eerie
underground ocean vista) and postcard shots of New Zealand can't
overcome a barrage of ponderous dialogue (``You should love this
man; he would give up his life for you'') and simply bland acting.
</P>
<P>
   As for plot, Verne wouldn't recognize it much. Here a
free-thinking scientist, Theodore Lytton ( Williams), traces not
the rediscovered trail of a 16th-century Icelandic explorer, as
Verne had it, but that of Casper Hastings, the wayward husband of a
rich, beautiful Bostonian, Alice Hastings (Ms. Bergen). Casper, it
seems, had disappeared on a volcano expedition in New Zealand seven
years before. Now his wife wants to find him, and to lead the
search she hires Lytton, who could use the money; he moonlights as
a prizefighter to help finance his research.
</P>
<P>
   Lytton, drawn by a Maori legend, presently finds the hole that
will take him far below Down Under. Along for the trip is a
diffident nephew ( London), a Falstaffian guide (played with gusto
by Hugh Keays-Byrne) and the lovely Mrs. Hastings, who shows up
uninvited, apparently to supply romantic possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Once underground, the party encounters a flock of hungry
pterodactyls, a race of intelligent but surly reptilian creatures
and, finally, Casper Hastings himself (Brown), who has turned into
a power-mad lord of the jungle, not unlike Kurtz in ``Heart of
Darkness.'' Brown, at least, seems to be enjoying himself, playing
the villain with some abandon. But then, finding himself cast as a
Joseph Conrad character in a supposed Jules Verne tale, he might
have just thrown up his hands and said, Oh, what the hell.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `JOURNEY TO THE CENTER OF THE EARTH'
</P>
<P>
   USA, Tuesday and Wednesday nights at 8 p.m., ET
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Tom Baum based on the novel by Jules Verne. Robert
Halmi Jr. and David V. Picker, executive producers. George Miller,
producer and director. Connie Collins, producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Treat Williams (Theodore Lytton), Jeremy London (Jonas
Lytton), Tushka Bergen (Alice Hastings), Hugh Keays-Byrne (McNiff),
Petra Yared (Ralna) and Bryan Brown (Casper Hastings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
