<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-HEALTHCARE-POLITICS-2     09-12 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-POLITICS-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN TARGETED IN DEBATE OVER HEALTHCARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Md.) (ART ADV: Graphic of is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is not an accident that Flo, a feisty
sixty-something woman, is the star of the pharmaceutical industry's
latest advertising campaign in the battle over adding prescription
drug coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a coincidence that the White House held an event not
long ago to focus on Medicare as a women's issue. Or that the
Democratic women of the Senate formed a working group last year to
examine what the various proposals to restructure Social Security
would mean to women. Or that the Older Women's League, an advocacy
group, issued a report on Mother's Day this year titled, ``The Face
of Medicare is a Woman You Know.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this reflects a basic demographic and political reality
that increasingly colors the debate over restructuring Medicare and
Social Security: old age is largely a country of women.
</P>
<P>
   Women not only tend to live longer; they also are more
economically insecure, have more chronic health conditions and as a
result, eventually, become more dependent on those basic safety-net
programs, health policy analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, that means they are becoming a prime audience,
target and symbol in the great struggles over entitlements. For the
defenders of generous health benefits, highlighting this vulnerable
group is a powerful marketing approach with broad political appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women perceive it as a two-fold issue: One, they're more
likely to have all the problems of old age because they're likely
to live longer,'' said Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster. ``And
second, whatever caregiving responsibilities exist, women expect to
fall squarely on their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill McInturff, a Republican pollster who also works for the
pharmaceutical industry, said, ``When you do focus groups, women
say, `Look, I'm going to live longer. I could outlive my income.'
Women just presume there's a higher chance they'll need a
government safety net more than men.''
</P>
<P>
   The demographics are clear: At birth, American women's life
expectancy is 79.1, six years longer than men's. Women account for
54 percent of the Medicare beneficiaries between the ages of 65 and
74, and 61 percent of the Medicare population between the ages of
75 and 84. They account for 71 percent of the 85-and-over medicare
population. Reflecting this skew, women make up more than
two-thirds of the nursing home population and two-thirds of the
users of home health care services.
</P>
<P>
   Older women also have higher poverty rates than their male
counterparts: 17 percent of the women on Medicare have incomes
below the federal poverty level ($7,740 in 1996) compared with 11
percent of the men on Medicare, according to a report by the Older
Women's League, released by the Clinton administration. Nearly 7 in
10 of the Medicare beneficiaries living below the poverty line are
women, that report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we live longer than men, and the bad news is
that we live longer than men,'' said Judith L. Lichtman, president
of the National Partnership for Women and Families, an advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Ann F. Lewis, a presidential counselor, said, ``When you start
talking about the fact that women live longer, are paid less, are
far less likely to have pensions with their work, and far more
likely to carry the responsibility for caregiving in our families,
every woman in the audience starts to nod.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lichtman and other advocates say women's groups have long
recognized that ``aging is a women's issue,'' because of women's
work patterns, caregiving responsibilities, economic status and
longevity. But in the last few years, as Social Security and
Medicare appeared to be headed for overhauls, advocates say these
groups have tried to organize to ensure that women's interests are
protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason you're hearing more about this now is the programs
that women and men, but especially women, rely on for old age,
Social Security and Medicare, are under new strains,'' said Joan
Entmacher of the National Women's Law Center, an advocacy group
that focuses on women's legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara A. Mikulski, D-Md., said the Democratic women in
the Senate began meeting on the issue a year ago when Social
Security restructuring appeared imminent and the debate over
privatizing the program was taking off. Any major restructuring is
now considered unlikely until after the 2000 election. A few months
ago, the Democratic women produced a checklist of necessary
ingredients for any Social Security overhaul, including preserving
the program as a guaranteed benefit with protection against
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others wanted to talk about macroeconomics,'' Ms. Mikulski
said. ``We wanted to talk about it at the macaroni-and-cheese
level.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a clear political rationale for presenting Social
Security and Medicare as women's issues, just as liberal advocates
a decade ago tried to cast welfare and poverty as children's
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving and improving expensive entitlement programs for
frail and economically vulnerable widows is much more appealing
than doing so for affluent retirees. ``It puts a human face on
it,'' Ms. Mikulski said of the focus on women. ``And I believe a
far more realistic face. We're not talking about the gilded golf
cart here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats and their sympathetic advocacy groups have been
hitting this issue particularly hard, the focus on women is
bipartisan. Rep. Nancy L. Johnson, R-Conn., and a senior woman on
the House Ways and Means Committee, argues that Republicans have
``been the lead party'' in trying to protect older women's economic
security through such measures as tax credits for caregivers and
the purchase of long-term care insurance. ``I think part of my job
is to educate them about what we're doing and why we're doing it,''
Mrs. Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, these demographic undercurrents are powerful
in the struggle over whether to add prescription drug coverage to
Medicare, as was proposed by the Clinton administration this year.
The administration and the Older Women's League argue that this
coverage gap is a particular hardship for older women, who spend a
greater share of their income on health care than men, 22 percent
compared with 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, for their part, argue that they will target
assistance for prescription drugs to the needy.
</P>
<P>
   The drug industry, which fears that a major new government
benefit will lead to price controls, is sounding alarms in the
person of Flo, who warns that ``the White House plan puts
bureaucrats in charge of our medicines.'' The campaign presents Flo
_ ``an actress but her story and concerns are real,'' according to
campaign literature _ as one of the two-thirds of the Medicare
population that has private drug coverage, and plays to worries
among this group that their insurance will be replaced by a
less-generous and more-intrusive government plan.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements say they are produced by ``Citizens for
Better Medicare,'' a coalition of business, drug industry and some
patients groups, but a spokesman for the group said they were
primarily paid for by the pharmaceutical industry. The
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of American have taken
the lead in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates who support new prescription drug benefits have
reacted angrily to the Flo advertisements. ``The Flo campaign is
really outrageous,'' said Rep. Rosa L. DeLauro, D-Conn. Deborah
Briceland-Betts, executive director of the Older Women's League,
said her organization had mounted an anti-Flo campaign: ``The
message is Flo is a fake, and she doesn't represent the majority of
older women in America who are trying to figure out how to cover
the costs of drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over Flo is a symbol of what is to come, advocates
on both sides agree. ``We're all talking to women on these
issues,'' said Ms. Lichtman, of the National Partnership. ``They
are, we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
