<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURE OF SNAILS PALES WITH A FRIENDLY PAIL OF STEAMED MUSSELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife Alice recalls that as a child she always thought she
would one day marry a farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Oh, during my life I have cultivated some interesting
green molds in forgotten containers at the back of the
refrigerator. But I invariably harvested my ``crops'' down the
garbage disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other forms of farming sounded too risky, too complicated and
involved an intolerable amount of sweating. Of course if I had
known about snail farming, Alice might have gotten her wish.
</P>
<P>
   After being served a few of the critters during a recent trip to
France, I conducted a bit of research and discovered that snails
were once plucked off vines to preserve the grapes. They also
represented a culinary bonus to vineyard workers. But pesticide use
decimated the population of wild snails.
</P>
<P>
   Today, not more than 30 or 40 snail farmers produce the escargot
served in European restaurants and those that arrive on our grocery
shelves in cans or jars.
</P>
<P>
   A snail farm, I learned, consists of row upon row of rough
wooden planks, each about a foot long, tilted over strips of grass
and irrigation tubes. The snails grow in tight clusters beneath
these planks. At the age of 6 months the snails are ready to be
taken indoors and starved for one month, to rid them of any
impurities. They are then cooked in a vegetable-wine broth and
ready to be stuffed into cans, jars or returned to their snail
shells with copious amounts of garlic butter to produce the classic
appetizer ``escargot a la bourguignonne.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago I ordered this delicacy in a Paris brasserie. A snooty
waiter delivered the snails, along with a pair of forceps to grip
the shells.
</P>
<P>
   I loaded one shell into the forceps, but as I approached the
snail with a fork, the teeth of the snail gripper slipped on
spilled butter and the infernal contraption fired the shell across
the room on four bounces. The waiter was not impressed or amused.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact I was accompanied by my wife, the waiter seemed
to sense that she was not married to a snail farmer.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather eat Penn Cove mussels or littleneck clams anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers' Mussels
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds mussels
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup diced, peeled red pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tomato sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh tomato (or two Romas) diced
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup dry, white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons basil
</P>
<P>
   Clean and wash the mussels if needed.
</P>
<P>
   In a large pot heat the olive oil and saute the onion, pepper
and garlic for 2 minutes. Add the tomato sauce, chopped fresh
tomato, the wine and herbs. Lower heat and simmer 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to eat, toss the mussels into the pot, cover and turn
up the heat. When the mussels are all open, dish up into three
bowls and serve with crusty French or Italian bread.
</P>
<P>
   Dijon Mussels
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds cleaned mussels
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large pot. Add the garlic, stir-cook 30
seconds, then add the wine and mustard. Mix, then toss in the
mussels. Cover the pot and steam the little buggers until they
open. Serves two as a main dish or four in appetizer portions.
</P>
<P>
   Hood Canal Clams
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   72 hard-shell clams (or 5 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces canned tomatoes, put through blender
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried basil
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in the clam pot. Saute the garlic 30 seconds then add
the remaining ingredients, cover and boil until all the clams are
open.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat, let sit 5 minutes and serve in soup plates
with chewy Italian bread.
</P>
<P>
   This serves four but do not furnish your guests with clam
grippers or they are liable to break your dining room window.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
