</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAXWELL-POP-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LEERING OR SIMPERING FOR THIS ROMEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Maxwell came back for his encore on Friday
night at the Theater at Madison Square Garden, the stage was set
with about a dozen lava lamps that glowed orange when he returned.
The lamps functioned the way his songs do; they set up a warm,
undulating, potentially hypnotic backdrop for romance. ``I admit
it,'' he said with a smile between songs. ``I made the records for
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell has emerged as the nice guy among rhythm-and-blues
Romeos, harking back to Marvin Gaye and Smokey Robinson while he
keeps his distance from hip-hop's roughneck machismo. He continues
to burnish a sincere persona that has garnered him two
million-selling albums, ``Maxwell's Urban Hang Suite'' and
``Embrya'' (both on Columbia), and he sold out three nights to
audiences dominated by squealing women. His opening act, the
comedian Melanie Comarcho, drew laughs and hoots of solidarity with
a female perspective on hip-hop's raunchy, materialistic carnality.
</P>
<P>
   In his songs Maxwell is assured but never pushy, lusty but
always respectful, and he insists he is seeking true love more than
a one-night stand. Taking his virility for granted instead of
touting it with hyperbole, he promises devotion with a boyish grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to get to know you,'' he insists. ``I can feel your
pain.'' He tells his intended that he will watch black-and-white
movies with her, take time for conversation, comb her hair and
serve her Cap'n Crunch, presumably for breakfast the next morning.
He dressed in good-guy white through his set, then switched to
tough-guy black for the encore.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's music is patient and suave, a promise of leisurely
sensuality. Languid vamps are paced by equable bass lines and
stitched together by wah-wah rhythm guitar, while his voice sinks
into the texture as a smooth but modest tenor. When he lets himself
grow most enamored, his voice rises to a supple, gorgeously
controlled falsetto, as if he were so close to his lover that his
voice had merged with hers.
</P>
<P>
   Where most current love songs either simper or leer, Maxwell
presents love as a force of nature, so intense that it can be
shattering. At the center of his set were ``Know These Things:
Shouldn't You'' and ``Gravity: Pushing to Pull,'' two pensive songs
from ``Embrya'' about love's trusting and terrifying intimacy. The
slowly tolling guitars in ``Know These Things'' summoned old scars
and the potential for violence; the bolero undercurrent in
``Gravity'' signaled an uncontrollable obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage the music suffered from a bottom-heavy mix; drums and
bass sometimes became a bludgeon rather than a heartbeat. Maxwell
showed off some limber dance moves and occasionally knelt in
supplication, and as he crooned about a desire so strong it could
break him down, he basked in affection. Women kept bringing
bouquets to the stage, and near the end of the concert one fan
rushed forward to hand him a box of Cap'n Crunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
