<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Monday, Sept. 13. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dili, Indonesia) _ Conceding that Indonesian forces
have been unable to control the violence in East Timor, President
B.J. Habibie capitulates to international pressure and invites the
United Nations to send a peacekeeping force to the troubled
territory. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-REFUGEES (Kupang, Indonesia) _ As the refugees huddle in
makeshift camps here, militia men roam the grounds menacingly. They
harass aid workers and journalists who try to visit the camps. And
they search for refugees who they believe voted for independence
for East Timor in the recent referendum. The situation in Kupang,
the capital of West Timor, is not as desperate as in East Timor,
where anti-independence gangs have killed thousands and destroyed
the capital, Dili. But the fear here is pervasive and paralyzing.
In visits to two large refugee camps on Sunday, it appeared that
the army and police are unwilling or unable to control the gangs,
which effectively run the camps. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-TURKEY (Athens) _ Greek-Turkish relations had been
improving slowly for several months, but it took earthquakes in
both countries to push them toward friendship. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-VOTE (Berlin) _ From wires: German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's Social Democrats continued their string of state
election defeats by losing Thuringia to opposition conservatives on
Sunday; but the far right failed to gain entry to the state
parliament, according to first exit polls. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Health care for the aged is
increasingly seen -- and marketed politically -- as a women's
issue. Three quarters of those over 80 are women, and they are more
likely to be poorer and more dependent on government support. How
this translates into political terms. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN-POLITICS (Washington) _ The conservative candidate
leans even more heavily toward bolting the GOP and joining Jesse
Ventura's Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN (New York) _ U.S. Open men's final: Agassi vs.
Martin. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ New England at Jets,
1 p.m. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   The following story, eliminated earlier today, is now restored:
</P>
<P>
   POWER-FAILURES (Chicago) _ Over and over again this summer, the
lights went out in this muscular, make-it-work city. Cities around
the country have faced similar frustrations during this sweltering
summer. In New York City, on one of the hottest days of the year, a
power cable short-circuited, leaving 200,000 homes in the
Washington Heights area powerless for 18 hours, the worst blackout
to hit the City in 22 years. Although the reasons behind the power
failures vary from place to place, they hint at deep-seated
problems at the nation's largest electric power companies.
Utilities that are now the lifeblood of the electronic age are
grappling with deregulation, an aging and long-neglected
infrastructure, new and sometimes confusing transmission systems,
and unprecedented demands for the electricity needed to power a
booming U.S. economy. By Pam Belluck and David Barboza.
</P>
</TEXT>
