<HEADER>
A9312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CATASTROPHIST-BOOK-RE     09-12 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATASTROPHIST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE CATASTROPHIST': LOVE AMID CONGO TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(ms) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Gillespie, the protagonist and seeing-I of Ronan Bennett's
marvelous new novel, ``The Catastrophist,'' is himself a writer,
the author of three novels, now working on a fourth. As he puts it,
he is a ``watcher,'' completely ``l'homme-plume.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is the writer's preference, for the margins, for
the avoidance of agglomerations and ranks.'' In a crisis he finds
himself thinking of Ruskin and ``his injunction: Does a man die at
your feet, your business is not to help him, but to note the color
of his lips.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is that James has fallen in love with one Ines
Sabiani, a young Italian whom he meets in London through his
publisher and whom he describes as ``vital, subversive, impatient
and always a part of others' lives.'' Ines is a correspondent for
L'Unita, which she calls ``the Communist paper of Italy,'' and her
commitment to her work draws James out of the margins, first to
Ireland, giving him a chance to visit his mother in Belfast, and
then to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the ``The Catastrophist'' it is November 1959.
James is flying to join Ines in Leopoldville, capital of the
Belgian Congo, where she has found her latest cause in the person
of Patrice Lumumba, leader of the pro-independence party, the
Mouvement National Congolais, whom she insists she was the first to
recognize ``for the hopes he inspired and embodied.''
</P>
<P>
   At first you think that James' attraction to Ines is merely a
device to draw him into the heart of the Congo. And in fact Bennett
_ who like his protagonist is from Belfast, and who now makes his
home in England _ does an effortless job of sketching the
complicated political situation there. Through Ines, James meets
cynical journalists, Belgian settlers opposed to the independence
movement and assorted other memorable natives and colonials.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among these are Mark Stipe, a beefy, authoritative
American who says he works ``at the consulate,'' and Auguste
Kilundu, Stipe's driver, who treats James with amused deference.
Stipe charms James, becomes his drinking partner, lends a
sympathetic ear to his most intimate troubles, even introduces him
to Lumumba and suggests that he start writing articles using inside
information that Stipe will be happy to feed him.
</P>
<P>
   What is Stipe really about? He's with the Central Intelligence
Agency, of course, insisting, ``I'd be happy with an independent
Congo as long as it were stable and well run.'' He tips James off
to the day that independence will come, enabling him to foresee a
picture, frightening to settlers, that is realized when thousands
of blacks march through Leopoldville.
</P>
<P>
   As James' narrative describes the scene: ``They walk at a
deliberate step, their eyes straight and implacably ahead,
expressions set with a confidence I have not seen before on black
faces: it is mixed with ostentation, borders on hostility. They
whip the air with palm fronds to make the violent hiss I first
heard in the apartment. The sound sends shivers down my spine.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the love story of James and Ines keeps tugging at the
reader's sleeve, so arrestingly told that you have the unfair
thought that it must be based on an incident in the author's life.
Ines is driven, passionate and unself-consciously sexy. (After
seeing ``Love in the Afternoon,'' she remarks that Audrey Hepburn
``looks like me. ... Yes, ... she is very like me.'')
</P>
<P>
   James reports: ``I fell in love with Ines in bed. I fell in love
with her in the street, and in bars, and in the company of others,
watching the expressions on her face as she talked and argued,
listening to the little grunts and sighs and sharp inhalations of
breath. Most of all, I believe, I fell in love because she was
promising me a way out of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Congo brings out everything that is flawed in their
affair. She wants him to become politically engaged. He disdains
her inability to be objective. He thinks of her as a fuzzy
romantic. She calls him ``in Italian it would be catastrofista _ a
catastrophist'' and says, ``Is there this word?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only ever heard it used in a geological sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual! English is always so poor. The meaning of this word
is much bigger. If you are catastrofista no problem is small.
Nothing can be fixed; it is always the end.''
</P>
<P>
   James becomes close to Stipe, whom Ines dislikes and mistrusts.
She then takes up with Auguste, Stipe's driver, who evolves from
servitude to defiance of Stipe and James. In the background the
Congo tragedy plays itself out _ Lumumba's drift from American to
Soviet support; America's consequent shift to backing the eventual
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, the subsequent death of Lumumba and his
companions _ yet never once do large events become detached from
the intimate foreground.
</P>
<P>
   In that foreground James is eventually trapped into a commitment
that perfectly reflects the conflict between his mind and his
heart, which, despite the tortured choice he makes, he never can
reconcile.
</P>
<P>
   The result is irresistible: as melodrama, as psychological
portrait and as a story of moral conflict. Previously James has
reported how early in his career his publisher ``reminded me that
Stendhal had once said that politics in a work of art is like a
pistol shot going off at a concert.'' Yet in ``The Catastrophist''
Bennett has written a political novel with many shots going off but
with every sound in tune.
</P>
<P>
   THE CATASTROPHIST
</P>
<P>
   By Ronan Bennett
</P>
<P>
   332 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
