<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-PORTUGAL _LISBON, Portugal _ Although Portugal is too poor
and powerless to protect the people of its former colony, East
Timor, news reports of widespread murders by pro-Indonesian
militiamen have stimulated an outpouring of pro-Timorese sentiment
among the Portugese people. (Nesmith, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GHB _ It is labeled as a solvent and sold by the shot in some
bars. Some people get it at vitamin and health food stores. You
don't have to be 21 to buy it, but it packs a wallop that leaves as
many as 10 people a week comatose in Atlanta emergency rooms. The
Food and Drug Administration banned uncontrolled sales of the drug
gamma hydroxybutyrate, called GHB, in 1990. But for the last
decade, sellers have found ways around the law, selling the
ingredients to make the easily formulated drug or selling slightly
altered chemical compounds, called GBL, BD or 2(3H)-Furanone
di-hydro, as solvents. When an suburban Atlanta teen-ager overdosed
recently, it sparked an investigation into the drug's availability
that is still continuing. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLOYD _ Soon to be a Category 4 storm, Floyd continues to rumble
toward the east Florida coast. Residents beginning to load up on
bottled water; plywood shortages reported at area stores. 35.
(Browning, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PLANE-TROUBLE _ Engine explodes on a Continental Airlines 737
taking off from Palm Beach International Airport. Bird strike is
blamed. Engine parts shower over a West Palm Beach neighborhood
causing damage on the ground. Plane was able to make safe return
landing. 30. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   ELKINS _ A Florida man killed himself Friday after New York
police interviewed him about a body found in an oil drum stored for
decades in a house he once owned. The unraveling of Howard Elkins,
of the Crescent Lakes gated community, started late this summer
when Ronald Cohen sold his split-level home in Jericho, N.Y., for
$455,000. Elkins had owned the home 27 years before. All that
separated Cohen from his money was the disposal of a rusting,
345-pound oil drum that had been rotting in an attic crawl space
for more than 25 years. Cohen opened the barrel Sept. 2 and found
the mummified body of a pregnant woman.(Lambert, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
