<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9323 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-POWER-FAILURES-2TAKES     09-12 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-FAILURES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BLACKOUTS HINT AT POWER INDUSTRY'S PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., La., Ind., Wis., New England, Pa., Md., Fla.)  (lb) 
 By PAM BELLUCK and DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Over and over again this summer, the lights went out
in this muscular, make-it-work city.
</P>
<P>
   There was the blistering midsummer weekend when temperatures
topped 100 degrees and up to 100,000 homes in the Chicago area lost
power _ a weekend in which officials recorded more than 50
heat-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   There was the day the power company, faced with trouble in two
transformers, plunged Chicago's downtown Loop into darkness in the
middle of the afternoon, leaving 2,300 businesses in the dark,
trapping people in elevators, short-circuiting federal court
proceedings and even silencing the cacophony at the Chicago Board
of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the Sunday when power failures prevented the
city's Field Museum of Natural History from opening its doors on
what was supposed to be one of the summer's busiest weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Seething with anger, Mayor Richard M. Daley denounced
Commonwealth Edison, the giant utility whose power system was at
fault because, among other things, it had failed to replace
insulators made of plastic that were so old and faulty that most
utilities got rid of similar ones decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sick and tired of them,'' the mayor said of the power
company, ``and they had better change.''
</P>
<P>
   Cities around the United States have faced similar frustrations.
In New York, on one of the hottest days of the year, a power cable
short-circuited, leaving 200,000 homes in the Washington Heights
section of Manhattan powerless for 18 hours, the worst blackout to
hit the city in 22 years. In New Orleans, power-plant failures led
to blackouts that disrupted service for more than half a million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the power failures vary, but they all hint at
deep-seated problems at the nation's largest electric-power
companies. Utilities that are now the lifeblood of the electronic
age are grappling with deregulation, aging and long-neglected
equipment, new and sometimes confusing transmission networks and
unprecedented demands for electricity to power the technology
behind a booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Utility experts are warning that the industry's emergency power
reserves are getting dangerously low, largely as a result of a
decade-long reluctance by utilities to build new power plants,
because of the costs and uncertainty of power demands.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been a significant number of blackouts in the
last few years, the high temperatures this summer thrust the
utilities' problems into a particularly harsh spotlight, raising
questions about whether they are adequately prepared to cope with
the nation's soaring energy needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been several high-profile outages that have caused
people to get excited about reliability issues,'' said Eugene
Gorzelnik, a spokesman for the North American Electric Reliability
Council, an industry trade group in Princeton, N.J. ``It's not that
the system is falling apart. But as you look at the next 10 years,
you don't want to wait for things to fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has announced an investigation
of the power failures. Some elected officials have filed suit
against power companies over failures or taken steps to lure
competing utilities in the hopes of creating alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   And regulators in several states are considering forcing
utilities to pay a penalty for periods when they fail to provide
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've heard as much complaining about electric
utilities and shortages and outages in a long time,'' said Robert
Burns, a senior researcher at the National Regulatory Research
Institute, which does studies for state public utility commissions.
``It's been decades since there have been this many problems.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the nation's utilities are redoubling their efforts
to make sure this summer's experience is not repeated. Some are
scrutinizing maintenance practices or, like Commonwealth Edison in
Chicago, firing top-level executives. Others are trying to
accelerate the pace at which they are building new plants, with
their earlier reluctance overcome by the need for more power.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, executives at the nation's biggest utilities say
the high-profile power failures are not representative of the
industry. Yet many of them acknowledge that the utility industry is
struggling through a period of major change. The advent of
deregulation of the industry that began with the federal government
meant new competition, new challenges and new sources of power.
</P>
<P>
   Many utilities now have to open their transmission lines to
competitors, which has spawned the buying and selling of power
across regions. Florida utilities now sell to the Southeast,
Wisconsin utilities sell to the East, and New England power
companies sell to the Middle Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have utilities that are running power from region to
region, so you have a lot of traffic,'' said Patrice Hagmann, a
spokeswoman at the Edison Electric Institute, a trade group in
Washington for shareholder-owned electric companies. ``You may need
a traffic cop to control things.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government previously regulated transmission lines
that crossed state boundaries. States have the power to control
utilities within their borders, and many still do, while other
states have freed the companies of controls in the hope that
competition will bring less expensive electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, where a series of power failures inflamed a city and
its outspoken mayor this summer, the problem was faulty
transformers and wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outages revealed a number of weaknesses and shortcomings
in our system,'' said David Helwig, interim senior vice president
of transmission and distribution at Commonwealth Edison. ``Quite
frankly, many of the problems can be traced to maintenance that
wasn't done.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has suffered through power failures before, including a
serious power failure in a heat wave in 1995 in which there were
more than 400 heat-related deaths over a monthlong period.
</P>
<P>
   Although industry experts say that Commonwealth Edison, which is
owned by Unicom Inc., has improved the operation of its five
nuclear plants in recent years, its substations, cables and the
distribution networks that serve the greater Chicago area have long
been neglected.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Commonwealth Edison crews still use an old
plastic, Bakelite, as the insulator in its cables. ``That stuff was
starting to be replaced years and years ago,'' said Burns at the
National Regulatory Research Institute. ``Talking about Bakelite is
kind of like talking about having a rotary phone. There shouldn't
be as much of that stuff out there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that outdated and inadequate plants could continue to
short-circuit the city's power and eventually turn into a political
liability, Daley insisted that Commonwealth Edison institute
round-the-clock inspections of its equipment. In recent months,
Commonwealth Edison has acknowledged major technical and public
relations blunders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This level of service under these conditions is a disgrace to
us,'' John Rowe, the chief executive, said at a news conference
after the latest power failure. ``It's a personal disgrace to me. I
will not tolerate it, and you will not have to.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth Edison has tried to make amends by holding public
forums, offering cash refunds to some customers and promising swift
changes at the top. Rowe fired two high-level executives and
promised to spend $1.4 billion over the next three years to upgrade
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few weeks ago, Chicago began courting a subsidiary of
Wisconsin Energy Corp. with the promise of donating land to help
the utility build a new power plant, opening the door to an
alternative source of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, there are similar concerns about an aging
power system and soaring demand. Indeed, the administration of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has already filed suit against Consolidated
Edison, charging the utility with ``gross negligence'' in the
Washington Heights blackout.
</P>
<P>
   But Con Edison officials say they are operating one of the most
reliable utilities in the nation, yet one that is at times
vulnerable to extreme weather and extreme demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the underground equivalent of an earthquake with all
the heat and humidity,'' said Mary McCartney, a spokeswoman. ``If
we didn't take the network off-line it was basically going to
destroy itself.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day the power failed, energy consumption hit a record
11,850 megawatts in the New York City region, Ms. McCartney said.
The utility's capacity is 12,000 megawatts, with an 18 percent
buffer, clearly straining the system and raising questions about
whether Con Edison has enough power to meet demands and extreme
weather conditions. The utility admits that, this summer, demand
was 10 percent higher than it had projected.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison buys the bulk of its power from other utility
companies, in places like Pennsylvania and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities have been equally burdened this summer, but for
differing reasons. In Louisiana, the big utility, Entergy Corp.,
said that unusually high demand for power in the four states it
serves created an extensive power failure; four or five power
plants malfunctioned at about the time the Tennessee Valley
Authority decided to stop shipping power to the utility, because of
heavy demand in other regions. Crippled by these events, Entergy
decided to shut down power to hundreds of thousands of its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was extraordinarily high demand and we just didn't have
enough power to cover it,'' said Carol Clawson, a spokeswoman at
Entergy, which is based in New Orleans. ``One of the dilemmas
utilities have is: How do you prepare for this kind of thing? Do
you go out and build extra power plants to prepare for a
once-in-a-decade event? And do you charge customers for that? Do
you build additional generation because you think one day in July
it will be really, really hot?''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns about periodic power failures,
Richardson, the energy secretary, announced in July an initiative
to help prevent major power failures, including the creation of a
team of experts to investigate blackouts, pushing for new standards
to reduce energy consumption, and trying to determine whether there
is a shortage of power plants and transmission facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers should not have to wonder whether the lights will go
out when the thermometer hits 90 degrees,'' Richardson said.
``While the causes of recent power outages are still being
reviewed, the fact is that some systems are being stretched to the
limit. Clearly there is cause for concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts, however, point out that the nation's utilities
are not in crisis mode; service is generally reliable. But power
companies need to move swiftly if they are going to meet growing
customer demands.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent figures available show that the nation's
consumption of electric power rose to 3,367 billion kilowatt hours
in 1998, up from 2,578 billion kilowatt hours in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say the power plants now being built may not
keep up with growing consumption. In 1990, there was a 22 percent
cushion of extra power available for emergency use in the United
States. That figure fell to 16 percent in 1997, and it is expected
to drop to 10 percent by 2007 if consumption continues to grow at
the current pace, according to the Edison Electric Institute.
</P>
<P>
   While the utilities say they are working aggressively to meet
the challenges, Robert K. Johnson, the executive director of the
Electric Consumers' Alliance in Indianapolis, said regulators need
to keep a watchful eye on the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that the outages, while they may individually be
explainable in different ways, collectively could be symptoms of
transitional problems in the industry that need to be addressed,''
Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
