<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9326 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-12 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER PROMISING A REVOLUTION, TWO COMPANIES SHOW PROGRESS IN GROUP
BUYING  
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet is ground zero for outsized declarations from
companies that promise to revolutionize, reinvent or obliterate
parts of the retail industry with business plans unimaginable in
pre-Web days.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, two companies with similar business models,
Mercata and Accompany, were started amid such fanfare, promising to
revolutionize e-commerce by attracting groups of buyers interested
in a certain product and extracting wholesale prices from
manufacturers and distributors. As middlemen, the companies would
exact a fee on each sale. In a win-win-win strategy, manufacturers
would sell items in bulk, customers would get lower prices, and
Mercata and Accompany would join the pantheon of e-commerce stars.
</P>
<P>
   But several months later, the revolution seems far off, with
neither site having spent enough money on marketing to attract
large numbers of users. There are some promising signs, however:
More manufacturers are showing interest, giving the sites access to
more brands, and the number of buyers seems to be increasing on
both sites. And with more marketing money on the way, analysts say,
the companies could start realizing their goals.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the group-buying method, combining the aspects of an
online auction and a low-risk opportunity to find inexpensive
goods, seems well suited to the Internet. Typically, the sites
offer goods for limited amounts of time and mark down the price as
more people make offers.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, for example, Mercata offered a Ryobi drill at a
starting price of $40. As more visitors bid, the price dropped.
When the so-called power buy was finished four days later, 500
people had bought the drill for $34 _ well below the suggested
retail price of $89. Even those who had bid higher got the $34
price, while those who had made lower offers clicked away
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Accompany, which sells more high-technology goods, uses a
similar bidding method. Earlier this month, Accompany listed a Palm
V organizer for $350, a price comparable with those of lower-price
online retailers. Once Accompany had more than 20 bids at that
amount, the price dropped to $325, where it stayed until the
bidding was closed two days later, with 75 buyers. Accompany
negotiates with the manufacturers beforehand to determine a scale
of prices based on the number of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The risk for early buyers, of course, is that they will jump in
at the higher price and risk having to pay it if no one else joins
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is a cross between the prisoner's dilemma and the
bystander effect,'' said Greg Kahn, chief executive of Webehavior,
a research firm. ``If they all cooperate, they will reap a greater
benefit, but cooperation puts them at risk _ as in the prisoner's
dilemma. That leads everyone to wait for someone else to jump in
first _ which is the bystander effect.''
</P>
<P>
   These group dynamics, he said, ``can really only be eliminated
by setting the initial price at or below the market price.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies seem poised to do that. Accompany can offer lower
prices in part because it does not ship products; the manufacturers
ship directly to buyers. Accompany charges suppliers between 2
percent and 8 percent of the sale for each bulk purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata, which sells a wider range of goods, employs a hybrid
approach. Some of its suppliers ship directly to customers, others
through distributors. When necessary, Mercata accepts inventory
from the manufacturer and ships through Hanover Direct, a
subsidiary of Keystone Fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   Mercata and Accompany declined to disclose traffic or revenue
figures, but executives from both companies said they remained
optimistic. ``So far, we've exceeded all expectations,'' said Tom
Van Horn, Mercata's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The most promising statistic, he said, is the popularity of
power buys, as their time-limited group offerings are known.
``We've held power buys where our participants exceeded 1,000
people,'' he said. ``When you go after a specific product in a
limited window of time, that's a number that's very valuable to a
manufacturer.'' He predicted between 10,000 and 20,000 buyers for
some sales by year's end, based in part on his plans to spend $20
million to $30 million on marketing in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marc Johnson, an e-commerce analyst with Jupiter Communications,
sees such marketing as imperative because ``this is a situation
where critical mass is absolutely crucial, so marketing and traffic
is like oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing is getting more difficult and expensive, Johnson said,
given the growing demand for prime advertising spots on portal
sites like America Online and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   But the group-buying sites have something other online retailers
lack: stickiness. As with auction sites, customers return to the
Mercata and Accompany sites frequently to check on their purchases.
Because portals need return customers to bolster their advertising
revenue, they have been willing to view group-buying sites as
partners rather than as tenants. Both companies have negotiated
partnerships in which the bidding will occur on a portal site _
Mercata on Microsoft's MSN, Accompany on Excite _ and they say more
such deals are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Another key to success is the participation of major brand-name
manufacturers. Both companies report some hesitation by companies
reluctant to do business over the Internet using a new retail
approach. But executives from both companies said they had made
significant progress in signing up suppliers. ``In manufacturing
circles, people discuss things,'' said Van Horn, of Mercata. ``So
signing Toshiba, RCA, Harman Kardon and Sharp helped us add
Panasonic, Canon and Philips.''
</P>
<P>
   Salim Teja, Accompany's co-founder and vice president for
strategic development, also said ``things are getting better'' with
manufacturers _ particularly those, like 3Com, that have
significantly increased production on certain items and now want to
avoid having excess inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on everyone's radar screen now, which is what we wanted
to do,'' Teja said. ``Now that we have some momentum and customers,
people are willing to take a step back and re-evaluate us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
