<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, September 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Powerful Hurricane Floyd, which will be a threat to Eastern
Seaboard later in the week, will begin to affect the central and
southern Bahamas Monday with bands of rain and increasing winds.
The center of storm, where winds will exceed 120 mph, will stay
over the ocean Monday as it moves to the west-northwest along the
southern flank of a sprawling high pressure area over the central
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather with plenty of sunshine will linger near most of the
East Coast. After a cool dawn, afternoon temperatures will average
at or slightly above seasonal values from New England to the Middle
Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front accompanied by a narrow band of thundershowers will
affect the eastern parts of the Great Lakes, Ohio Valley and
Tennessee Valley. Monday night, the front will begin to slow down
as high-level steering winds shift and begin to blow nearly
parallel to the front over the Eastern States. These high-level
winds from the south are expected to draw Hurricane Floyd north
near the Southeast coast Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the cold front, windy and very cool weather will
spread from the northern Plains to the western Great Lakes. Clouds
and scattered showers will occur in the chilly air from the eastern
Dakotas to the northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, offshore winds will bring unseasonable heat to the
Northwest coast. Most of the Southwest will be very warm with ample
sun, however, clouds and afternoon thundershowers will be scattered
from eastern Arizona to western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Past Peak &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd strengthened north of the Antilles during the
weekend as the historical peak of the Atlantic hurricane season
passed. In about 90 percent of the years since 1886, at least one
tropical storm or hurricane has raged in the Atlantic on Sept. 10
and 11. No other dates have had more storms. Atlantic water
temperatures peak in early September, providing optimum conditions
for tropical storms which draw energy from the warmth of the ocean.
At the same time, the strong high-level winds associated with the
jet stream which are capable of tearing a storm apart are typically
still far to the north. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Thursday _ Wind and rain associated with Hurricane
Floyd will affect parts of the Southeast coast on Wednesday. Damp
weather and increasing wind is expected to reach the Middle
Atlantic and Northeast coasts during Thursday. Meanwhile, high
pressure will promote dry and cool weather in the Middle West and
much of the Southeast. Most of the West will be warm and dry. Some
thunder will occur over the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Saturday _ Rain will end in the Northeast as gusty winds
from the northwest develop. Very cool air and a few afternoon
showers will cover the Great Lakes and interior Northeast. The
Southeast will stay mainly sunny with comfortable humidity.
Meanwhile, the Plains will be dry and warmer although clouds will
increase in the north. The Northwest will turn cooler while the
Southwest stays very warm with afternoon mountain thunder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
