<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN LOOKING AT LAUNCHING REFORM PARTY BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lagging badly in his quest for the Republican
presidential nomination, Patrick Buchanan said Sunday that he was
strongly leaning toward switching to a run for the Reform Party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door really is wide open,'' said Buchanan, a proven
electoral spoiler. ``We are very close to making that decision,''
he said on NBC-TV complaining that the Republican contest was
``closed and rigged'' with the big-money candidacies of Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas and Steve Forbes, the self-financed millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The initial reaction from Reform Party officials was mixed but
far from forbidding at the possibility of Buchanan creating a
three-way contest of the presidential campaign. His presence on a
Reform ballot might be expected to drain conservative support from
Bush, the front-runner for the Republican nomination whose early
dominance has left Buchanan and the rest of the GOP field
struggling for attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he starts meeting people in the party, I think people
will be willing to go and work their hearts out for him,'' said Pat
Choate, who was the vice presidential nominee of the Reform Party
in 1996 and remains a popular figure in the party. He said that he
had talked with Bay Buchanan, Buchanan's sister and chief
strategist, nearly every day for the last six weeks, and that he
believed Buchanan would announce his defection within the next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, the party's biggest success
story, has been wary of Buchanan as a ``retread'' and prefers to
press the search for a more centrist presidential candidate. ``He
has social issues that he puts very strongly on the front burner,
and we in the Reform Party tend to leave social issues aside,''
Ventura said last summer in trying to discourage speculation of a
Buchanan crossover.
</P>
<P>
   Dean M. Barkley, who was chairman of Ventura's campaign and
remains a close adviser, said Sunday in an interview that
Buchanan's stances on abortion and other social issues would pose
``a huge hurdle for Buchanan to sell himself to the Reform Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley conceded Buchanan's proven popularity could make him
a serious contender for the nomination next year under the party's
complex open petition system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a huge recruiting battle between those who
support Buchanan and those who hopefully will unite behind a
centrist candidate,'' Barkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he would decide on a possible Reform bid by
mid-October. ``We're leaning in that direction right now _
strongly,'' he said on ``Meet the Press,'' emphasizing that he
would like to speak with Ventura and with Ross Perot, the
millionaire who created the Reform Party as his 1992 presidential
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we have is a one-party system in Washington,
D.C., that is masquerading as a two-party system, and I think what
we need is a real opposition party,'' he said, describing the GOP
as a ``Xerox copy'' of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had no immediate reaction to Buchanan's threat to defect.
The Bush campaign office noted that Bush previously had expressed
his hope to Buchanan directly that he stay in the party as a proven
conservative leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan, a tireless, fiery campaigner who won the 1996 New
Hampshire Republican primary, clearly was using his appearance on
national television Sunday to try to reclaim some of the political
spotlight that lately has been scarce in his campaign rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time maybe to take a bye in the regionals and go straight
to the finals,'' said Buchanan, using a sports allusion in his
threat to drop from the GOP primary route and focus instead on the
Reform nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Russell J. Verney, the Reform Party chairman and a longtime aide
to Perot, said Bay Buchanan called him within the past two weeks
and sought a detailed briefing about the requirements for seeking
the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform rules require a prospective nominee to make a
good-faith effort to qualify for the ballot in the 29 states, plus
the District of Columbia, where the party does not have an
automatic slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained the scope of the task, which I'm sure is an
eye-opener to anyone who hasn't been through it,'' Verney said.
``It ranges from states where just a fee or a few hundred
signatures are required, to states where you have to get 30,000 or
40,000 signatures within very strict time limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney said that on July 1, party officials would determine
which candidates had made a sufficient effort to be placed on the
ballot for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in late July, ballots are to be sent to people who
signed a petition, or are on the rosters of state Reform Party
organizations, or request one. Voting will be by telephone, mail or
Internet. The result will be announced at the Reform Party
convention next August in Long Beach, Calif. Delegates can overturn
the result with a two-thirds vote, but Verney said that was simply
a safety valve in case only a fringe candidate qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Verney said Perot had not changed his position that he would
support whoever is nominated by the party. ``He's made no
indication that he has any interest in it,'' Verney said. On Jan.
1, Verney is to be succeeded as chairman by John J. Gargan of
Florida, who had been endorsed by Ventura of Minnesota and was
elected at the party's national convention in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
