<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REDGRAVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDGRAVE DELIVERS A FEAST TO ARTS-STARVED KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ First NATO arrived in Kosovo with tanks
and guns for security, then the United Nations with money and
shelter, and now Vanessa Redgrave has come to minister to the
Kosovars' spirits.
</P>
<P>
   In her role as the U.N. Children's Fund special representative
for the performing arts, Ms. Redgrave, the British actress,
organized a three-day festival of dance, music and theater this
weekend, persuading some illustrious names to come to war-ravaged
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, to perform along with Albanian
artists for a culture-starved population.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few days she has been a familiar sight around
Pristina, wearing an air of slight eccentricity amid the bustle of
last-minute organizing. She is a distinctive figure, whether
pushing her troupe of helpers through the border controls or
standing on the steps of Kosovo's National Theater, bending her
tall, slim frame and peering through rose-tinted glasses to talk to
her Albanian colleagues, all of whom seem smaller than she.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening event in the theater, the director and playwright
Enver Petrovci, a Pristina native, likened her to Mother Teresa,
who inspired a network of medical clinics all over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mother Teresa did here for medicine, Vanessa Redgrave did
for cultural humanism,'' he said. ``So I will introduce her as
Mother Vanessa.''
</P>
<P>
   The praise may have been rather elaborate, but there were some
powerful emotions running through the performances that made for an
exceptional, if somewhat jumbled, occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers of the Martha Graham company flew in from New York to
perform two pieces, ``Lamentation'' and ``Errand Into the Maze,''
which Ms. Redgrave had specifically requested for their examination
of pain and suffering. The dancers performed without their sets,
which arrived in Pristina as the performance was already under way.
The pianist Katharina Wolpe played a Schubert Impromptu, hobbling
onto the stage after a crashing fall in the pitch-black wings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Redgrave was to have performed a monologue from ``The
Cursed,'' a 10-year-old play by Petrovci that was never performed
here. With her voice weakening, and too rushed to learn her words,
Ms. Redgrave passed that one by, but spoke at length to introduce
her colleagues and explain her whole mission, severely testing her
translator in the process.
</P>
<P>
   For the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo, there was no doubt that the
festival, titled ``The Return,'' was a symbol of their new-won
freedom, the end of the war and their return to their homes and
cultural life from the refugee camps in Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time something big is happening here in 10
years,'' said Alberta Troni, 23, a music professor at Pristina
University.
</P>
<P>
   With the growing isolation of Yugoslavia during 10 years of wars
and sanctions, Kosovars had had virtually no contact with the
outside world, let alone such guest appearances as these. The
ethnic Albanians had no access to the theaters and concert halls or
the university in Pristina, which became the domain of Serbs only.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 10 years the Serbs never allowed us to play here,'' Ms.
Troni said. ``The concerts we held were in private houses or a
small hall.'' This was the first time she had even attended a
performance in the theater, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to set up their own faculty of arts after being expelled
from the university, the ethnic Albanians had only one piano for
teaching, practicing and performing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the majority of the Serbs living in Kosovo have fled
following NATO's arrival, the Albanians have now taken over the
theaters, concert halls and university. They have plenty of pianos
now, although not a single trained piano tuner in the city.
</P>
<P>
   As for the artists, despite qualms about danger, precarious
stages and other installations, and an arduous journey into Kosovo,
they said the unusual circumstances made it worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sets did not arrive, but in a sense it was very
appropriate to be in that rough sense, stripped of that comfort,''
said Terese Capucilli, principal dancer and associate artistic
director of the Martha Graham Company, who performed ``Errand Into
the Maze'' with Martin Lofsnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rare for an artist to have the opportunity to share what
we do and love what is our life in a situation like this,'' she
said. ``The response was very, very warm. One young actor said to
me, `If your intention was to touch our souls, you have done
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wolpe, a Holocaust survivor, found herself reading the music
she was to perform on the bus ride into Kosovo. ``It's your worst
nightmare, going on stage doing a piece you do not know,'' she
said. ``But I found it a great honor to play for these people, who
have not heard anything but gunshots for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   The greater aims of the whole event, that of peace and
tolerance, lay more mute. Dennis McNamara of Unicef touched on it
in a speech. ```The Return' signifies the return of artistic
life,'' he said. ``But for Kosovo it is much wider, the return to a
free, liberated Kosovo, a free society and free communities. In the
broader sense it means tolerance, living together and living in a
normal society.''
</P>
<P>
   His words came amid the background of a still violent Kosovo,
where the Albanians are now safely home, but their return has been
marred by revenge attacks on the other minorities in Kosovo, namely
the Serbs and the Gypsies.
</P>
<P>
   As the festival continued Sunday with more music and a gala
evening, the nobler aims appeared rather remote. The French rock
star Patricia Kaas was expected to arrive on a French military jet
and play along with the British stars Lulu, Big Country and half a
dozen other bands. For the young audience, the boys and girls of
Pristina, the festival was just simple good fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
