<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SERRANO-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      09-12 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERRANO-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO AN ISSUE OF THE HEART FOR A CLINTON LOYALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During the late unpleasantness here _ something
about the president and an intern _ no member of Congress was more
loyal to the man in the White House than Jose E. Serrano of the
South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the president was impeached, Serrano strode to the
well of the House and let loose. ``The Republican right wing in
this country doesn't like it when we say coup d'etat, so I'll make
it easier for them: golpe de estado _ that's Spanish for
overthrowing a government.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``From Day 1, they wanted to get rid of Bill
Clinton. They're blinded by hate today. This place is full of hate,
because of what they tried to do to our president.''
</P>
<P>
   He closed with a little street talk for the president's enemies,
straight from his Bronx boyhood: ``Bullies get theirs, and you're
going to get yours, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So it might have seemed strange when Serrano kicked over Hillary
Clinton's apple cart last week. After she came out against her
husband's conditional offer of clemency to 16 imprisoned members of
a radical Puerto Rican nationalist group, Serrano said he was
``rescinding my encouragement of her candidacy'' for the Senate in
New York. He suggested that ``it's time to go out and find out who
else is interested'' and warned that the stance of hundreds of
thousands of Hispanic people toward Mrs. Clinton might now be
``abrazos cruzado'' _ folded arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months ago, 99.9 percent of people in the Bronx didn't
have a problem with Hillary Clinton,'' he said. ``Now it's
divided.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Serrano may be off the White House Christmas-party list.
But in politics there is passion as well as loyalty, and Serrano is
a passionate man.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who loved Frank Sinatra so much (the first English
he heard as a toddler in Puerto Rico was on a Sinatra 78, and he
owns every recording the man ever made) that he personally saw to
it that Ol' Blue Eyes received the Congressional Medal of Honor in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who loved performing so much that when he gave up
his dreams of being a singer, an actor or a comedian, he did the
next best thing: He became a politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I traded my dream for one microphone for another,'' he said.
``A lot of what I do I do with a poet's heart, with the heart that
poets have to look at the world, where they show anger and they
speak about love.''
</P>
<P>
   He also loves Puerto Rico and hates what he sees as its colonial
status. ``There isn't a day that this island doesn't run through my
brain and my heart,'' he said. ``I see the United States as my
father and Puerto Rico as my mother, and I'm tired of seeing my
father mistreat my mother. Either legitimize the relationship or
let her go.''
</P>
<P>
   Serrano was brought to the Bronx from Mayaguez as a child by his
factory-working father and his mother, who worked as a seamstress
in a sweatshop and fostered his love of performing. After
graduating from a vocational high school in 1961, he served in the
Army medical corps during the Vietnam War and won election to the
state assembly in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the '70s and '80s that the Puerto Rican nationalists
carried out 130 bombings in the United States, including a
lunch-hour attack on Fraunces Tavern in lower Manhattan, which
killed four people. The 16 offered clemency were not linked
directly to the deaths and maiming in those attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano (pronounced sa-RAH-no, with a rolled R), who after
nearly 10 years in the House is the ranking Puerto Rican member of
Congress, decided last Monday that he was taking a stand against
the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a call, while watching a baseball game, from the White
House, telling me that Mrs. Clinton is going to come out for
rescinding the clemency,'' he said. ``My initial reaction was of
outrage, anger, pain, sadness, disappointment. And if you hurt me,
it lingers.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hillary Rodham Clinton ran headlong into Jose Serrano's
heart. It might have been politic for Mrs. Clinton's campaign to
consult Serrano, who wins 95 percent of the vote in his district, a
margin rarely seen anywhere, and is the longest-serving Puerto
Rican politician in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   She conceded last Friday that ``the consultation process was not
what it should have been.'' He remains miffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the same arrogance and inability to understand issues and
people that allowed them to advise her to make that blunder, they
now are beginning to downplay my role in a senatorial election,''
he said of Mrs. Clinton's campaign. ``I'm not one who says, `I'm
very powerful, I control votes,' but you shouldn't try to test
that, because you might be shocked at what you find.''
</P>
<P>
   After the clemency was denounced by an overwhelming vote in the
House last Thursday, Serrano, speaking of the Fraunces Tavern
bombing, said: ``You have to be an animal or inhuman not to feel
that that was wrong, not to feel the pain of people who lost a limb
or lost a life. But this is an issue of reconciliation. How can the
greatest democracy on earth hold a colony in 1999 in the
Caribbean?''
</P>
<P>
   Some have even accused Serrano, who places himself ``to the left
of the left'' on the political spectrum, of supporting terrorism
against the United States. Nonsense, he replies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the country where I grew up,'' he said. ``This is the
country where my five children were born. This is the country where
my wife was born. This is the country where I buried my parents,
and this is where I will be buried someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
