<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE RADIO TRIES THE ALL-TALK FORMAT 
E-GAMBLING SOFTWARE GIVES PLAYERS AN EDGE
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Va., Ga., Calif.)  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An entrepreneur who made his name in rock radio almost 30 years
ago is now trying his luck at Internet radio.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Meyrowitz, 56, whose DIR Broadcasting in the early 1970s
created the syndicated radio series ``King Biscuit Flower Hour,''
plans to start a radio network on the Internet this week.
Recognizing that, so far, so-called streaming, or continuous, audio
is not always of the highest fidelity on the Net, Meyrowitz plans
an all-talk network, which he calls Eyada.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Herman, who was host of the morning show on the New York
rock station WNEW-FM for 26 years, is Eyada.com's program director.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Eyada.com will offer one channel of programming about
the entertainment industry, with 15 hours of programming each
weekday and four hours each on Saturday and Sunday evenings. The
lineup of hosts for the entertainment channel, which begins
officially transmitting on Wednesday, includes Lionel, host of
Court TV's ``Snap Judgment''; Richard Johnson, editor of Page Six,
the gossip page of the New York Post; George Rush and Joanna
Molloy, the New York Daily News husband-and-wife gossip columnists;
and Bob Berkowitz, the former host of Real Personal, a discontinued
sex advice program on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Eyada.com plans to introduce an all-talk channel for
sports, and it expects to add channels on teen-agers, women and
business by the end of 2000, Meyrowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyrowitz, who said he had raised just under $10 million from
private investors for the start-up, hopes to reach 20,000 listeners
a day, ranging in age from 20 to 40. The network intends to sell
both banner ads and audio commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Allen, a senior analyst for Forrester Research in
Cambridge, Mass., criticized Eyada.com's planned programming, which
she said ``is not uniquely suited to the new medium.''
</P>
<P>
   She also predicted listeners would ignore the advertising. ``If
there's one thing that's clear, it's that Internet users do not
like ads and avoid them,'' Ms. Allen said. ``There's no reason to
think they'll listen to radio ads online.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Mooradian, a senior analyst for Jupiter Communications
in New York, said that if the network could establish its brand, it
might be able to create a niche for itself before the likes of Don
Imus and Howard Stern hit cyberspace. ``They're not online yet, but
I promise you they will be in a year,'' Mooradian said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE L. LEVERE
</P>
<P>
   E-GAMBLING SOFTWARE GIVES PLAYERS AN EDGE
</P>
<P>
   In the world of Internet gambling, participants routinely risk
large amounts of cash with Web site operators of uncertain scruples
who may run afoul of local anti-gambling laws. Now, Reliable
Software Technologies of Dulles, Va., has identified a new peril
associated with gambling online: badly engineered software.
</P>
<P>
   The company has found a flaw in one implementation of a game
known as Texas Hold 'em Poker that could enable a player to quickly
determine the exact ordering of every card in a shuffled deck while
a game was in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given this information, even the weakest of poker players
should know when to hold 'em and when to fold 'em,'' Gary McGraw,
vice president for corporate technology, wrote to a security
mailing list.
</P>
<P>
   The distributors of the affected version of Texas Hold 'em Poker
_ ASF Software Inc. in Duluth, Ga. _ quickly corrected the flaw
when it was brought to their attention, but McGraw said similar
problems might still exist in this and other types of Internet
gambling software. At least three online casinos, planetpoker.com,
purepoker.com and deltacasino.com, appear to be using the
vulnerable version of the software, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ASF vulnerability lies in a faulty implementation of what is
known as a random- number generator to produce a shuffled deck of
cards before each round of play. The order of each shuffled deck is
completely determined by one number, known as the seed. In this
case, the program chose a seed based on the time, measured in
milliseconds since midnight. By synchronizing their program with
the system clock on the server generating the seed, McGraw and his
associates were able to narrow the number of possible decks to
about 200,000 possibilities. Then, given the cards dealt and the
community cards in the center, they could quickly compute which
deck was being used.
</P>
<P>
   This type of vulnerability has been well-known to security
experts ever since a similar problem was identified three years ago
in Netscape's implementation of Secure Socket Layer, a program that
enables secure connections with e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We published an exhortation on this back in 1996, so it's sad
_ but not entirely surprising _ to see more people falling prey to
this trap,'' said David Wagner, a computer security researcher at
the University of California at Berkeley who, along with his
colleague Ian Goldberg, identified the Netscape bug.
</P>
<P>
   Gamblers will spend an estimated $1.2 billion online this year,
according to Christiansen Capital Advisors, a research firm based
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   _ SARA ROBINSON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
