<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUM     09-12 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESENDING TO CORRECT SLUG LINE  
 CON ARTISTS INCREASINGLY TARGETING BUSINESSES, ESPECIALLY SMALL
ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consumers aren't the only people who get ripped off by con
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses _ especially smaller ones _ are growing targets of
increasingly clever schemes to rip them off.
</P>
<P>
   Every year businesses lose hundreds of millions of dollars to
con artists selling listings in fake directories,
too-good-to-be-true office supply deals, bogus loans and
non-existent charities.
</P>
<P>
   They get away with it because many businesses don't have
adequate procedures for approving bills before they get paid.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has reached such proportions that a group of
agencies plans to meet next week in Washington, D.C., to brainstorm
strategies companies can use to reduce their vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   The round table includes the U.S. Postal Inspection Service, the
Yellow Pages Publishing Association, the Federal Trade Commission,
the Small Business Administration, the Council of Better Business
Bureaus, the American Chamber of Commerce Association, the
Department of Justice, the National Association of Attorneys
General and the National Consumers League.
</P>
<P>
   Poor communication within companies is one of the main reasons
businesses get taken, said Robyn Frankel, a St. Louis consultant
who has chaired the business scam round table since it began three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by the Yellow Pages Publishers Association and
the Council of Better Business Bureaus, for example, showed that 90
percent of individuals who pay bills in companies have other major
responsibilities besides handling accounts payable. In addition, 40
percent of companies don't require a second approval before bills
are paid.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it easier for bogus bills to get paid
unintentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Although the schemers target companies large and small, it's the
smaller ones with fewer checks and balances that get taken most
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a numbers game,'' Frankel said. ``It's who's not
paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   When businesses let their ``fingers do the walking,'' for
example, the fingers often walk off with the money.
</P>
<P>
   Since the ``walking fingers'' logo was never trademarked, phony
Yellow Pages billing schemes cost companies about $550 million a
year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Pages is the most widely targeted medium for con
artists, making Yellow Pages advertisers especially susceptible to
phony solicitations, Frankel said. Sometimes a crook will simply
clip a company's legitimate Yellow Pages ad and send it to the
business with a ``renewal'' notice and bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scams never go away,'' she said. ``There's always a new
twist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also a fertile new medium for scam artists.
Billings for Internet directories, for example, are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Another frequent tactic is sending a mailing to ``confirm your
address.'' Although the mailing may say ``This is not a bill'' on
the front, there may be fine print on the back stating that
confirming the address results in a billing and automatic renewal
for every directory issued thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Or people may get phony refund checks that, once cashed, trigger
all kinds of unwanted billings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going out of business'' sales with rock-bottom prices on
office supplies are another hook so-called ``paper pirates'' use to
scam businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Shady ``service reps'' sometimes show up at company doors with
work orders, then walk out the door with expensive office equipment
that needs to be ``repaired.'' Neither the rep nor the equipment is
seen again.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses don't bother to report rip-offs, which allows
the schemes to proliferate. One of the goals of the round table
meeting is to increase business awareness about the scams and
encourage more reporting, Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   There are some steps companies can take to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Look at all bills carefully, and doublecheck them against your
files for pending contracts to make sure the mailing relates to
legitimate advertising or merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   If something seems questionable, contact the local Better
Business Bureau to see whether there is information on the company
originating the invoice.
</P>
<P>
   If you suspect a scam, alert the state Attorney General's
Office, the local postal inspector or the Council of Better
Business Bureaus. Agencies receiving complaints now feed them to a
central database maintained by the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   Warn others in the company if suspect billings are making the
rounds. Don't make commitments to unknown people over the phone.
Get contracts in writing. When dealing with publications, get
verifiable circulation figures, publication dates and sample copies
before signing up.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Yellow Pages Publishers Assoc.
at 1-800-841-0639cq ; the Consumer Response Center at the FTC
(1-877-FTC-HELP)cq, or the U.S. Postal Service Mail Fraud Complaint
Center at 1-800-372-8347cq.
</P>
<P>
   You can also file complaints online at www.ftc.gov, or
www.yppa.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
