<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS13-COX     09-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers believe in Maracle
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. _ He was the only goalie on the roster to
show up in training camp with a freshly painted mask, a
menacing-looking bird with eyes on the top of the mask and a beak
down near his chin.
</P>
<P>
   For added karma, Norm Maracle had his artist paint dream
catchers in either side of his chin. It's all part of the package.
The mask fits in well with the tattoo of a Native American on his
right shoulder and the blur of animal caricatures on his left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, see I consider my glove hand my strength, so I've got a
bunch of crazy stuff over here,'' the Thrashers goalie said,
rolling up a T-shirt to expose his left shoulder. ``See, I've got a
black panther breaking through the skin, here's a skeleton, here's
a face that looks this way. One face looks behind the net. He can
tell me where the puck is. I have about 10 faces here.''
</P>
<P>
   There probably is room for only two goalie faces on the
Thrashers' final roster. Presumably, the NHL will count Maracle as
only one.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old was the most impressive goalie in the first week
of training camp for the Thrashers, which bodes well for the
franchise's future. How so? General manager Don Waddell, who spent
a year as Detroit's assistant GM, zeroed in on Maracle early as the
Red Wings' donation in the June expansion draft. Though Maracle
will enter this season as Damian Rhodes' backup, he is considered
the goalie of the future and performances in scrimmages have some
team officials wondering if the future isn't far off.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Maracle, hardly an imposing athletic specimen
at a 5 feet 9, 175 pounds, has made a nice emotional recovery from
three months ago, when he was so upset about leaving the Red Wings'
organization that he cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little sad about it,'' he said. ``I had been with the
same organization for five years. But now I'm excited about it
because I may get a chance to play more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maracle, who had a 2.27 goals-against average and .918 saves
percentage in 16 games with Detroit, brings with him undeniable
talent but questions about his dedication. A drunken driving arrest
last season, which Maracle has publicly apologized for several
times, and questionable conditioning were two things that raised a
red flag with Andy Moog, the Thrashers' former goaltending
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Maracle was one of five goalies Moog recommended to Waddell
before the expansion draft, but the current Vancouver
consultant/assistant coach said, ``He has a lot to prove. He's
carrying a little baggage with him. In talking to some people in
Detroit, I felt like he didn't understand how much work it took.
Some felt he was a little immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Maracle was neither thrilled nor surprised by Moog's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the comments about my dedication a little bit,'' he
said. ``But you can't say I'm not dedicated because I want to play
every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Maracle admits his conditioning is lacking at times, and he
wants to hire a fitness coach, saying, ``I need somebody with me.''
As to the DUI, he said, ``It was a mistake and it will never happen
again. That's not the type of guy I am at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said of Maracle, ``I know this kid. I know he's focused
to be a No. 1 goalie. If this had happened to somebody I didn't
know, we would've had a lot more conversation about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
