<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA AND TRINIDAD EVENLY MATCHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; This time it seems almost impossible to answer such a question:
Who's going to win the Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad fight on
Saturday night in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   Ask 10 people and you'll get 10 scenarios, split five and five
as to the projected winner. All 10 will be perfectly plausible.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason the long-awaited welterweight
title-unification bout is so intriguing: If ever there was a
tossup, this is it.
</P>
<P>
   They're both undefeated: De La Hoya 31-0 with 25 knockouts,
Trinidad 35-0 with 30 KOs. Each is 26 and in his prime. De La Hoya
is 5-foot-11, Trinidad 5-10. They're both hard punchers with solid
boxing skills. And they're both winners.
</P>
<P>
   In Las Vegas, the odds are essentially ``pick 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   So who will have his hand raised when it's over?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, of course.
</P>
<P>
   How did we come to that conclusion? Another good question.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters' capabilities are so similar that it's incredibly
difficult to differentiate between them. They both box well, punch
well, are vicious, get up from a knockdown, have guts, train hard
and have that certain something that makes superstars. So we'll
concentrate on the one most significant advantage each one appears
to have.
</P>
<P>
   For Trinidad, that might be hunger.
</P>
<P>
   The idol of Puerto Rico has made good money but nothing like De
La Hoya's head-shaking haul, which doesn't sit well with Trinidad
because he's been the IBF champion since 1993 _ four years longer
than De La Hoya has held the WBC 147-pound title _ and is convinced
he's better than the Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad also hasn't fought much recently _ five times in three
years _ because of problems with his promoter, Don King. Earlier in
his championship run, King failed to get him big fights. Later his
career, he was put on hold when he tried unsuccessfully to break
his contract with the promoter.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, the frustration simmered inside him. Now he's
bursting to show the world what he can do and it might be that De
La Hoya has the misfortune of standing in his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what worries me,'' said one executive involved in the
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, De La Hoya admits he has found it difficult to
maintain his motivation amid all his success.
</P>
<P>
   Between personal appearances, endorsement and commercial
obligations, problems inside his camp and his young family, boxing
has became a smaller and smaller part of his life. Emanuel Steward,
his former trainer, predicted De La Hoya would lose in part because
of the distractions, and he might be right.
</P>
<P>
   If he's wrong, it might be because of De La Hoya's distinct
advantage: experience.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, who is less than a month older than De La Hoya, has
four more fights than his rival. However, his level of competition
has been far inferior to that of De La Hoya. Who has he fought? His
most significant opponent was Oba Carr (whom De La Hoya also
defeated) in 1994. Since then, he has faced not a single opponent
worth mentioning, unless a 35-year-old Pernell Whitaker, just out
of drug rehab in February, is to be taken seriously _ and he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Trinidad has never been in the ring with the likes of
De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, De La Hoya, once criticized for his lack of
competition, has faced several meaningful tests. Most
significantly, he outpointed a younger (33), determined Whitaker in
1997 and did the same to Ike Quartey in an unforgettable bout in
February, in which De La Hoya outslugged the immensely strong
Ghanian in the 12th and final round to clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya also has had considerable big-fight experience. His
bouts with Rafael Ruelas, Whitaker, Julio Cesar Chavez and Quartey
have taken place under the glare of tremendously bright lights,
which a fighter must endure to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, such experience _ in terms of both the level of
opposition and magnitude of promotion _ cannot be underestimated.
In the end, it will be the difference in the fight: De La Hoya will
win because he's been there several times and Trinidad hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   What about the hunger issue?
</P>
<P>
   Great fighters get up for big fights and De La Hoya is a great
fighter. He knows that this is a pivotal moment in his career _
perhaps !ital!the pivotal moment. The guess here is that he'll be
able to put everything else aside when he steps into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: De La Hoya by decision.
</P>
<P>
   __ Calling it quits: Pat Goossen and his son P.J. Gosssen are
finished with boxing, the elder Goossen said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Goossen has fought, trained, managed and promoted for the
past 30 years. P.J. Goossen, who lost a one-sided decision to
Hector Camacho in his most recent fight, is the last of three
brothers to step into the ring. He finished with a record of 19-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in my family will fight again,'' said Pat Goossen, the
brother of promoter Dan Goossen and trainer Joe Goossen. ``Boxing
is a losing proposition, a dead-end street.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . That's it for P.J. He did hurt his ribs (against
Camacho), but everyone will remember how he looked. He had his
chance and it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Goossen said he plans to continue to train martial artists.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Roy Jones Jr. will defend his undisputed
light heavyweight title against Germany's Graciano Rocchigiani on
Nov. 6 in Mississippi. Rocchigiani is being trained by Emanuel
Steward in Detroit. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Seattle promoter Bob Jarvis is trying to get an unprecedented
man-versus-woman bout approved by Washington's athletic commission.
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed a lightweight bout between Margaret McGregor and
Mexican Hector Morales for Oct. 9 in Seattle. McGregor, a
36-year-old former kickboxer, is 3-0 as a professional; Morales
would be making his pro debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to several people who said they don't like it, but
they plan to buy tickets to go watch it,'' Bob Olesen, a matchmaker
from Portland, Ore., told The Sun of Bremerton, Wash. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mia St. John of Canoga Park, who will fight Kelly Downey on the
De La Hoya-Trinidad undercard, is scheduled to appear in a two-page
layout in Playboy next month. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Jose Navarro of Los Angeles is part of a 12-man American team
that will compete against Cuba on Sept. 27 in Venice, Fla. Navarro
won the silver medal at 112 pounds in the Pan American Games. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Tapia, who lost his WBA bantamweight title to Paulie
Ayala in June, has pulled out of a fight with Jorge Eliecer Julio
because he wants some time away from boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a tough year,'' he said. ``Everything hit me all at
once. I'm taking some time off to see what happens, get my head
clear.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Laila Ali, the 21-year-old daughter of Muhammad Ali, is
scheduled to make her boxing debut against a yet-to-be-determined
opponent on Oct. 8 in Verona, N.Y. Laila Ali's publicist, NormaLynn
Cutler, said the fighter's famous father has given her tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won't tell anyone, including me, what they are,'' Cutler
told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   She quoted Laila Ali as saying: ``When I have the greatest boxer
of all time as my mentor, why would I want to share the secrets
he's given me?'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad will be on-line for a live chat on excite.com at 6 p.m.
Tuesday. Search for ``oscarfelix.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Bob Arum is scheduled for a chat at 6 p.m. on Thursday
and Don King at 5 p.m. on Friday. . . . Undefeated Luis Perez and
once-beaten Arturo Reyes will meet in the semifinal of the Forum's
junior welterweight tournament tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Julio, the fighter scheduled to face Tapia, will take on
Miguel Martinez in a 10-round non-title bout. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Lopez is scheduled to move up in weight to challenge IBF
junior flyweight champ Will Grigsy on Oct. 2 in Las Vegas. Lopez is
the longtime WBA/WBC strawweight titleholder.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the card, 37-year-old Julio Cesar Chavez will face
capable Willie Wise in a 10-round super lightweight bout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
