<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-JIANG-ASSESS-     09-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JIANG-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: JIANG EMBRACES A NEW `OLD FRIEND'
</HEADLINE>
   (With CHINA-JIANG) 
(rk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Last year, in the aura of Bill Clinton's buoyant
visit, the Chinese called the American president a great statesman
and the United States a strategic partner.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly this spring, as ``U.S.-led NATO'' bombed
Yugoslavia and then hit the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Clinton
was described as a fiend, and the United States as an evil empire.
</P>
<P>
   With their meeting in New Zealand on Saturday, President Jiang
Zemin is once again dancing with ``my old friend'' Clinton, as he
put it a few days ago. Beijing newspapers Sunday morning featured
pictures of the two smiling leaders shaking hands and did not even
mention the Belgrade Embassy disaster, which killed three Chinese
and prompted days of angry demonstrations outside the American
Embassy in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Warier and perhaps wiser than before, China and the United
States are starting to restore normal relations. They seem
determined to seal the bond by finally, after years of tortured
negotiations, agreeing on terms for China's entry into the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   These wild gyrations in Chinese-American relations are a
reminder of the subterranean passions that have always buffeted
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   But China's rapid return to smiles also reflects a more basic
truth, Chinese foreign policy experts and Western diplomats say.
For economic and strategic reasons, they say, China's leaders see
no good alternative to cooperative relations with the United States
in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Recent events, including the American pursuit of the war in
Kosovo and Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui's pugnacious assertions
of virtual independence, have sharpened the sense in some quarters
here, especially the military, that a showdown with the United
States over Taiwan may occur at some point.
</P>
<P>
   But for the immediate future, China's leaders hope their hand
will not be forced on Taiwan, because they are far more anxious to
concentrate on overhauling the economy and building up national
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large consensus here that the relationship with the
United States is the cornerstone of our global strategy,'' said Jin
Canrong, an expert on international politics at the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences. To speed China's modernization and avoid a
costly arms race in Asia, he said, most officials believe that ``we
have to deal with the United States in a steady way.''
</P>
<P>
   China's renewed push to join the World Trade Organization shows
how deeply its foreign policy has become intertwined with domestic
goals. Entry into the trade body, the leaders feel, will aid their
drive to shake out state enterprises and create a market-driven
economy _ their only path to prosperity at home and greatness
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, with unemployment growing and sporadic
reports of social unrest, the pruning of state enterprises slowed,
and powerful industries lobbied against making deep concessions to
the West on trade. Rumors spread this summer that Prime Minister
Zhu Rongji, the main torch-bearer for economic reform, had
threatened to resign.
</P>
<P>
   But by summer's end it appeared that the leaders had
unequivocally decided to plunge ahead with ambitious economic
reforms regardless of the short-term risks, and in so doing to
resume trade talks with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Jiang has staked his own prestige on the state
enterprise overhaul, blitzing the country to deliver speeches with
titles like ``Fortify Confidence, Deepen Reform, and Create a New
Situation for State Enterprise Development.'' Proposals to speed
along change _ consolidating and saving key state firms while
letting others go private or bankrupt _ will be the centerpiece of
a Communist Party meeting this month.
</P>
<P>
   Entry into the WTO, officials here have concluded, is essential
to that task.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Zhu have been heard invoking an old saying: ``Let the
water flow to wash the sand away.'' In this case, the water is the
stiff competition that will result from trade organization
membership, washing away the inefficiencies of hidebound
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rhetoric about entering the WTO on relaxed,
developing-country rules, the Chinese have already agreed to make
sharp cuts in farm and industrial tariffs and to begin opening
industries like automobiles, telecommunications and banking to
outside competition.
</P>
<P>
   Membership, if it is achieved, will of course bring some direct
economic benefits. A study by the China International Capital
Corp., an investment bank in Beijing that is a joint venture by the
government and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, concluded that the
resulting freer trade would increase the gross domestic product by
between 0.5 percent and 1 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But that same report pointed to some of the hazards: millions
more farmers would become redundant, for example, with no obvious
new opportunities opening up soon. And China's fledgling social
security systems are not ready for a new surge in industrial
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the United States and China have cautioned that a
trade agreement has not been clinched.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Taiwan remains the most dangerous and convoluted
issue in Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued bluster in the official press, Chinese
officials have assured the Americans that they are not planning any
military action unless Taiwan takes further steps toward formal
independence. And for now, China appreciates Clinton's restatement
of American support for ``one China'' and counts on Washington to
restrain Taiwan from precipitous moves.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Chinese also resent American arms sales to Taiwan and
they know that if they ever do attack Taiwan, the United States is
likely to join the battle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
