<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICAN NATIONALISTS RETURN HOME FROM PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: INSERTS number of released nationalists in 2nd graf.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ As a group of Puerto Rican nationalists
returned home to the cheers of supporters and relatives, the
political firestorm surrounding their release from prison continued
unabated here.
</P>
<P>
   While it appeared that most Puerto Ricans supported their
release, only a minority of islanders share the radical
pro-independence politics of the 11 nationalists, who were released
on Friday under a conditional clemency offer extended by President
Clinton last month.
</P>
<P>
   If supporters of independence welcomed them as heroes, some
supporters of statehood derided them as terrorists. Still, many
islanders said they felt the nationalists had more than paid for
their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   They had served almost 20 years each on sentences ranging from
35 to 90 years. All of them had been imprisoned on sedition and
weapons convictions stemming from their involvement in the Armed
Forces of National Liberation, a pro-independence group blamed for
130 bombings in the United States that killed six people and
wounded dozens of others from 1974 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing they are released, because it was too harsh
a sentence. They should have been released years ago,'' said Asha
Cintron, 26, a bartender in Old San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fighting for a cause,'' said Iris Vega, 32, an
artist. ``They haven't killed anyone. They haven't raped anyone.
Why should they be in prison more than 20 years?''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Cortes, 44, was the first of the former prisoners to
arrive in San Juan, late Friday. Elizam Escobar, Adolfo Matos,
Dylcia Noemi Pagan, Alicia Rodriguez, Ida Luz Rodriguez and Carmen
Valentin arrived on Saturday. Ricardo Jimenez and Luis Rosa had not
yet arrived by late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, Alberto Rodriguez and Alejandrina Torres, decided to
stay in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On arriving in San Juan, all the prisoners thanked their
supporters, while lamenting the fact that other Puerto Rican
nationalists remained imprisoned. Despite their standard parole
conditions, which bar them from meeting with one another or with
other convicted felons, they said they would continue to struggle
for Puerto Rican independence.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the celebrations at the airport, members of the
pro-statehood New Progressive Party, meeting at the weekend for
their annual convention, worried about the effect the issue of
clemency for the radicals could have on relations between the
United States and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The party's secretary-general, Jorge Davila, a former tourism
director, said the controversy involving the release of the
nationalists and the backlash on the mainland against Clinton's
clemency offer could hurt tourism, one of Puerto Rico's main
sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the controversy could shape the outcome of the
struggle over the off-shore island of Vieques. The Puerto Rican
government wants the U.S. Navy to stop military maneuvers on the
island and return the land the Navy controls there.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Vieques issue has brought about a rare consensus of the
island's pro-statehood, pro-commonwealth and pro-independence
factions. Clinton has appointed a panel to investigate whether
there are feasible alternatives for Vieques. The panel will release
its recommendations this month.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expressing concern over the nationalists' release
was Carlos Romero Barcelo, the former governor of Puerto Rico who
is now the island's sole representative to the U.S. Congress.
Romero Barcelo, who has called the prisoners terrorists, told
reporters he was worried that the controversy might harm the
statehood movement's main goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we ask for equality for Puerto Rico if in Puerto Rico
people defend those who have declared war on the United States?''
Romero Barcelo said.
</P>
<P>
   While Puerto Ricans revel in their national pride, there is
little outright support for independence, which garnered less than
3 percent of the vote in a 1998 referendum. The statehood movement,
which has been growing, pulled down 46 percent of that vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REDSKINS-     09-12 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REDSKINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LANDOVER, Md. _ Dallas coach Chan Gailey couldn't breathe. Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman couldn't see. And others with neither
problem simply couldn't stand to watch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But unlike in the first quarter, when the same ball slipped
through Raghib Ismail's hands, this 76-yard bomb was caught, and
Rocket launched himself into the end zone, thus completing one of
the biggest comebacks in Dallas Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite trailing by 21 points with less than 11 minutes to play,
the Cowboys plugged away to defeat the Washington Redskins 41-35 in
overtime Sunday in a season opener played before a record crowd of
79,237 at Redskins Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it suspended in air or anything,'' Gailey said.
``But when he caught it, I think I breathed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was third-and-two at the Cowboys' 24, and Gailey suspected
the Redskins were probably thinking run. He hoped Emmitt Smith was
as good an actor as he had been a rusher all day. Smith simulated a
run off a perfect Aikman play fake, the safeties bit, and the
Cowboys matched the best comeback in their history. They last
overcame a 21-point deficit against New Orleans in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance to (throw to) Rocket there in the first
quarter with it, and the safeties bit up then, and we didn't come
down with it,'' Aikman said. ``I thought it was a great call when
the call was made. I thought it had a chance to work. I won't get a
chance to really appreciate how Rocket sold the route until I watch
it on film, but I thought it was a great call, and it was executed
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally on that play, you make the play, and you have your
back to the line of scrimmage, and you look for the safeties to see
whether they bit. But the way that game was going, I came out of
the fake, and I couldn't see anybody. The whole time the ball was
in the air, I thought a safety was going to come out of left field
and intercept it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Redskins' safeties _ and the whole Washington defense,
for that matter _ had quit making plays at the end of the third
quarter after shutting out the Cowboys since their first two
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed the Cowboys to score four touchdowns in the fourth
quarter and beyond, one on a one-yard run by Smith and three on
passes by Aikman. Aikman connected with Michael Irvin on touchdowns
of 37 and 12 yards, the second tying the game (with Richie
Cunningham's bounce-through extra point off the left upright) at
35. Aikman then threw the 76-yarder to Ismail for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a great quarterback,'' Redskins rookie cornerback Champ
Bailey said. ``He knew exactly what he was doing at the end and
just picked us apart. He was strong and composed and wasn't broken
by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since the Redskins continued to give Dallas chances.
With the game tied, the Redskins got possession at their 20 with
1:46 to play. They never moved a yard, punting after three failed
pass attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys then got the ball with 1:22 remaining, but two plays
later, Darryl Pounds intercepted Aikman, and momentum again shifted
to the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great momentum on our side at that time,'' Aikman said.
``The interception at that point was devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas corner Kevin Mathis, playing for the injured Kevin Smith,
made what could have been a fatal mistake, getting flagged for pass
interference on a ball intended for Michael Westbrook. It was a
24-yard penalty, advancing the Redskins to the Dallas 23 with 12
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But in what had become a comedy of errors, the snap on the
field-goal attempt was bobbled, forcing holder Mark Turk to
scramble for the end zone. Turk then fumbled as the clock ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is probably the wildest football game I've ever
been a part of,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   The difference seemed to be veteran leadership. Despite having
trailed by 21, the Cowboys insisted they never felt out of it, and
the results proved they never let down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any big Knute Rockne speech on the sideline
before we took the field (for overtime),'' Gailey said. ``But we'd
been moving the ball. I think there was a lot of confidence when we
walked out there. It didn't matter if it was the minus-five or the
50, I think our guys had confidence they were going to take it down
there and stick it in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow that confidence didn't waver when the Cowboys had six
consecutive drives in the second and third quarters end in four
punts and two interceptions. The Cowboys ran only 24 plays in those
drives, amassing a mere 58 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awfully big show of character by our football team,
and I was really impressed,'' Gailey said. ``There were some
executions that were not good on both sides of the ball. There were
times when it looked like we were getting pushed around on the
field. There were times that it was three downs and out, and our
character never faded on the sidelines, and that's what wins.''
</P>
<P>
   That and an offense featuring Aikman, who completed 28 of 49
passes for 362 yards and five touchdowns. He completed passes to
nine players, including tight end David LaFleur, who scored the
Cowboys' first two touchdowns on receptions of 15 and 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And in an offense that now features the speedy Ismail to pull
defenders off Irvin, the two proved to be a formidable combination.
Ismail caught eight balls for 149 yards, Irvin five for 122.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Cowboys struggled, largely because of the
absence of corners Deion Sanders and Kevin Smith. The
unavailability of Sanders, still recovering from toe surgery, was a
game-time decision, and he could play as soon as next week against
Atlanta. Smith, who has a bad back, is out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys allowed the Redskins to score 32 unanswered points
to go from a 14-3 deficit to a 35-14 lead. New Washington
quarterback Brad Johnson threw for 382 yards and two touchdowns.
Stephen Davis ran for 109 yards and another pair of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have some games like this,'' Dallas safety
George Teague said. ``But the message to get out of this is that we
can overcome it. And we're not going to give up 35 points very
often.''
</P>
<P>
   They passed the test this time, but it's not one they want to
take again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys on this team have never been put to that kind of
test,'' said Emmitt Smith, who finished with 109 yards rushing on
23 carries. ``At this level here, it's easy to crawl under the
bench and suck on your wounds and feel sorry for yourself. I'm glad
to see we have a group of guys who just won't quit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
