u a BC-NY-CARDINAL-RETURNS-N     09-12 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CARDINAL-RETURNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VIGOROUS CARDINAL O'CONNOR RETURNS TO PULPIT AFTER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW      
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his first public appearance since doctors removed
a small tumor from his brain, Cardinal John O'Connor on Sunday
nimbly climbed six steep steps to the pulpit of St. Patrick's
Cathedral, where he delivered a 20-minute homily that blended a
serious message about helping those ``who have the least'' with
gracious humor about his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a truly marvelous funeral,'' he said, relishing
the warm applause from about 2,500 people who filled the Cathedral
for the cardinal's annual Mass in honor of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 79, did not offer details about the type of tumor
discovered on his brain, but he described the operation to remove
it as ``extraordinarily successful.'' The doctors have told him, he
said, that he should recover after radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal was released from Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center on Sept. 4 after a 10-day stay.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Sunday's Mass, the cardinal showed no sign of ill
health. As always, he sprinkled his remarks with effortless wit and
a deft political touch. ``I look down and see Mayor Ed Koch and
think it must be Midnight Mass at Christmas,'' he said at the
outset of his homily, as Koch laughed along from his seat up front.
</P>
<P>
   On a more serious level, the cardinal announced an initiative to
protect immigrants from what he described as the ``cruel
underside'' of immigrant life.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York City Central Labor Council, he said, the
archdiocese is forming the Commission on the Dignity of Immigrants.
Staffed by Labor Council volunteers and immigration specialists
from Catholic Charities, the commission will set up a telephone
line that immigrants can call with concerns about wage and hour
violations, housing discrimination or naturalization problems.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will also make policy recommendations to
government agencies on immigration issues.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal, who has forged close ties with organized labor in
New York, reminded congregants that he is the son of a union man.
In fact, he quipped, when his prognosis was unclear, ``I insisted
that my casket have a union label.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal deflected speculation that he may retire in
January, when he turns 80. He confided that he had received ``a
beautiful letter'' from Pope John Paul II, presumably wishing him a
speedy recovery. The cardinal said he is going to send the pope all
the newspaper stories listing who might succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't yet told me I'll be succeeded, if or when,''
O'Connor said. ``But I'll pass on to him these names.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9395 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS-NYT     09-12 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE LOST FOR SEASON IN JETS' 30-28 LOSS TO PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The game was not yet 23 minutes old, the
Jets' season of a Super Bowl dream had not even reached its first
halftime when Vinny Testaverde went down Sunday, on his knees,
hunched into a human ball. Howling. With his left Achilles' tendon
ruptured, with a pain in his head and in his heart that told him it
was over for him for the year, right then, right there, on a Jets'
fumble that bounced around and with Testaverde spinning, twisting,
trying to pounce on it. Snap. It was over.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field he went, in a cart, with all Jets eyes following
him, with the 78,227 fans in Giants Stadium watching in a deep
trance. The New England Patriots were mesmerized, too. How can such
a thing happen? In the first game? With your starting quarterback?
With an All-Pro quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Snap.
</P>
<P>
   And thus, the Jets spent the rest of the game wondering one
thing: How are we going to recover from this? They asked themselves
that daunting question for this game and for the season. For the
game, they could not, losing 30-28 on an Adam Vinatieri 23-yard
field goal with three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   For the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose your quarterback, everybody is going to have to
adjust,'' said Jets' Coach Bill Parcells. Parcells knows Testaverde
_ who a few hours after the game was scheduled for surgery _ faces
a grueling recovery that will last at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not putting the white flag up,'' Parcells said. ``We
will have to adjust and make the most of it and see what we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not exactly what safety Steve Atwater expected when in
the offseason he arrived from the two-time Super Bowl champion
Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to be difficult to win the Super Bowl either way,
with Vinny or without him,'' Atwater said. ``We've got great guys
here and we'll want to pull together and get the job done. We have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Bryan Cox said: ``Vinny is a big part of what we do.
It's tough, man. They ain't going to cancel the schedule. You guys
were talking, `Super Bowl, Super Bowl, Super Bowl.' Now you'll be
saying, `We're dead, we're dead, we're dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was some of the Jets who nearly said that. They
were emotional, of course, after the Testaverde loss, after this
crushing season-opening defeat at home to a nasty divisional rival.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them was receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in a million years did I think I was going to lose my
starting quarterback,'' Johnson said. He was relatively composed
during his post-game news conference, with cameras rolling and
lights flashing and writers penning his every word, and then
Johnson actually said what a lot of the Jets privately felt. His
comments were full of expletives and he said: ``There's nothing you
can do. You can't do anything. There's nothing ... ''
</P>
<P>
   And he pounded his fist on the lectern and, full of dejection,
left the interview room.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had pounded his fist nearly a dozen times on the turf
when injured.
</P>
<P>
   He went down with 7:12 left in the second quarter with the Jets
trailing by 10-7. It was an unusual injury, one where he was not
hit, on a first-and-10 play at the New England 18-yard line. He
made a handoff to back Curtis Martin, Martin was stripped behind
the line of scrimmage by Willie McGinest and the ball bounced near
the Patriots' 25. As Martin dived for the ball, Testaverde spun and
tried diving for it. Martin got it. Testaverde wound up writhing in
pain. Snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew,'' Parcells said when asked just how the injury
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that Testaverde's left foot had been caught in the
Astro-Turf. It twisted and the Achilles' tendon snapped.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment on, the game would undertake a surreal,
hangover-like complexion.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde had been off to a great start _ completing 10 of 15
passes for 96 yards with a touchdown and an interception. Tom Tupa
(6 of 10 for 165 yards with two touchdown passes) entered, and on
his first play threw a 25-yard scoring strike to Johnson. The Jets
were ahead, 14-10, despite the shock of the Testaverde loss. And
then the Jets gained a safety to end the half and left the field
ahead by 16-10.
</P>
<P>
   But at halftime the reality of what had happened to the Jets
must have sunk in, both to the Jets and to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets played the third quarter in a funk. The Patriots began
blitzing Tupa relentlessly. Tupa had been inserted because the Jets
could not have used quarterback Rick Mirer without losing Tupa for
the reast of the game, according to league rules concerning a
team's three quarterbacks. That rule is waived at the beginning of
the fourth quarter. Thus, Mirer, Parcells' choice for the backup
quarterback, had to wait and then played all of the fourth quarter.
Tupa played all of the third.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Jets were blitzed by 17-0 before
answering. McGinest recovered a Tupa fumble in the end zone, Terry
Allen dashed 22 yards for a touchdown on a third-and-2 run and
Vinatieri booted a 21-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That blow to Vinny shocked us for a while,'' said Jets
linebacker Roman Phifer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were kind of wobbly right there,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   And then Cox helped lead a resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   With 3:53 left in the third quarter, Tupa tossed a 7-yard
touchdown pass to tight end Fred Baxter on third-and-goal. Patriots
27, Jets 22 entering the fourth quarter. Fewer than five minutes
into it, Cox intercepted a pass from Drew Bledsoe and returned 27
yards for a touchdown. Jets 28, Patriots 27.
</P>
<P>
   On their last two scores, the Jets tried two-point conversion
passes that failed. On their first possession of the fourth
quarter, at the Patriots' 14, rather than attempt a 24-yard field
goal, the Jets ran a fake field-goal attempt and Tupa ran for the
first down, missing it by less than a foot. The Jets called for
instant replay, questioning the official's spot, but the call was
not overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking the extra points and the field goals in those situations
might have given the Jets 5 more points and maybe the victory. Then
again, nothing was certain on this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some things there we thought would work and they
didn't, but if they had, who knows?'' Parcells said. ``God's
playing sometimes. That's life in the big city. This can be a very
humbling game. It can turn very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows there is little sympathy for his team from his
opponents. ``Nobody cares,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots offered respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to seize the game and it started to turn but we
didn't do it,'' said Patriots Coach Pete Carroll. ``They were too
gallant, they stayed with it, they wouldn't go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Jets did.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Chris Slade intercepted a tipped Mirer pass at the
Jets 49 with 3:30 left. New England behind Bledsoe (21 of 30, 340
yards, 1 touchdown, 1 interception) moved methodically to the Jets
3. New England converted the field goal, allowing the Jets time for
one more play, Mirer's frantic toss that was batted down near the
Patriots' 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots three-game losing streak to the Jets was snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in after the game and heard something by coach in the
locker room but I don't remember,'' Martin said. ``I heard it but I
didn't hear it. I was in my own little world. I feel bad for Vinny.
Vinny is the leader of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   So many Jets in their ``own little world.'' Dazed. The shock.
The dream. Now the Jets must snap out of it. There are, for
certain, 15 games left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Vinny went out of the game it lifted the black clouds
over our heads,'' said Patriots receiver Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   And, for now, placed them squarely over the Jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
