u s BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-12 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE TURF THAT KILLED THE JETS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Stretched out face down, Vinny
Testaverde, was pounding the artificial turf with his right fist in
frustration. Or maybe in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody had to tell the New York Jets quarterback that the
Achilles' tendon in his left heel was ruptured. He knew. In the
second quarter of the Jets' opener Sunday, he also knew he now was
out for the season in which he was supposed to lead the Jets to
Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   And without Testaverde, the Jets may well be out of contention
for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Even more frustrating, Testaverde knew he hadn't been hit,
hadn't even been touched. When he saw Curtis Martin fumble, he
tried to pursue the loose ball, but he suddenly collapsed with one
of sports' most painful injuries apparently caused by one of
sports' most treacherous dangers _ artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Coach Bill Parcells would say later when asked
if the turf had caused Testaverde's injury. ``I'd hate to say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But just about everybody else on the Jets was talking about the
turf as if it were a killer at large. According to a Jets' official
in the locker room when Testaverde arrived there, the quarterback
``didn't say anything, but that's two guys we've lost getting their
foot stuck.'' Three really.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days earlier, wide receiver Wayne Chrebet broke his left
foot when he simply tried to cut on the new artificial turf that
had been installed that week at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time in Sunday's 30-28 loss to the New England
Patriots that Chrebet was accompanying Testaverde to Lenox Hill
Hospital in Manhattan for surgery Sunday night, running back Leon
Johnson damaged ligaments in his left knee. He will undergo surgery
and also is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to cut,'' Johnson said. ``My foot got stuck in
the turf. I couldn't pick it up. My knee felt like a cookie
crumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   For this summer's early pro football exhibition games, Giants
Stadium had a grass field to accommodate the MetroStars' soccer
season. But the night after Chrebet got hurt, the MetroStars' best
player, Sasa Curcic, injured his right knee the same way Chrebet
and Testaverde did _ with nobody around him.
</P>
<P>
   That should be enough evidence to tear up the new artificial
turf at Giants Stadium and install grass permanently. God's grass.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority
that operates Giants Stadium, the Giants have supported grass.
Parcells has wondered if grass would still provide a smooth field
late in the season after some 25 pro, college and high-school
games, especially if a rainstorm turned the grass to mud.
</P>
<P>
   In citing Testaverde's injury as ``non-contact,'' Parcells
added, ``God's playing sometimes; that's life in the big city.''
Especially in the National Football League, where injuries often
determine the winner of the Super Bowl each year. But if God's
playing sometimes, He may prefer to be playing on His grass.
</P>
<P>
   And having lost Testaverde, Chrebet and Johnson to this new
artificial turf, Parcells might decide that mud is better than
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   When Testaverde went down, he had completed 10 of 15 passes for
96 yards and the Jets, although losing 10-7, were on the Patriots'
25.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the rest of the Jets' season, Parcells talked about
how, ``We've got 15 games to go. We're going to have to figure out
how to approach those games and get going.'' Most of the Jets'
players spoke bravely, too. So did Keyshawn Johnson for awhile,
until he was overcome by the frustration of losing their
quarterback and offensive captain.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson described Testaverde as ``irreplaceable, but when you
lose somebody like that, you've got to dig deep.'' He soon reverted
to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' he asked, standing at the microphone in the
Jets' interview area. ``There's nothing you can do. You can't do
anything. There's nothing. We couldn't throw. We're throwing
interceptions . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson banged the podium with both hands, threw a towel in the
air and stalked out, his eyes flashing in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Although Testaverde and Johnson are considered out for the
season, that means the playoffs and the Super Bowl as well. Jumbo
Elliott knows all about a ruptured Achilles' tendon. He needed
surgery for one late in the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long process,'' said Elliott, meaning the rehab. ``You
can't put any weight on it. You've got to work on the scar tissue,
but our guys,'' meaning the Jets' medical staff, ``are the best in
the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet is expected to be playing in another five weeks, but the
medical staff can't put Testaverde and Johnson together again until
it's time for training camp next year, if then.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde will be 36 on Nov. 13 and coming off such a serious
injury, he might not be as agile and as effective as before unless
he can completely trust his left heel.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, Parcells now will turn to Rick Mirer, the
quarterback he obtained from the Green Bay Packers during training
camp, for next Sunday night's game in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells inserted Tom Tupa Sunday, and Tupa completed 6 of 10
passes for 165 yards and 2 touchdowns, but Mirer, who was 4 of 11
for 28 yards, was the ``emergency'' quarterback who couldn't be
used until the fourth quarter without the Jets losing Tupa as both
a quarterback, punter and holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick had a couple of chances,'' Parcells said, ``but the ball
got tipped at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Tipped by cornerback Ty Law to linebacker Chris Slade. Then the
Patriots won on Adam Vinatieri's 23-yard field goal with 3 seconds
remaining. By then Testaverde, and Chrebet were in an ambulance on
the way to the hospital, and Johnson's left knee was being fitted
for a cast.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyor Milloy, the Patriots' strong safety, understood how the
Jets' offense had been decimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artificial turf was new and stiff,'' Milloy would say
later. ``I changed shoes after our first defensive series. I
recognized the feeling I had in college at the University of
Washington when I broke two bones in my foot on artificial turf.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Giants play the Washington Redskins next Sunday at
Giants Stadium, who will be the artificial turf's next victim? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CLINTON-JIANG-1STLD-W     09-12 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JIANG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS U.S. TROOPS WILL HAVE LIMITED ROLE IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
 
(UPDATES grafs 3-4 with Clinton saying there would be an American
presence on the ground in East Timor, but no ground troops; DELETES
6th graf with original quote from Clinton; ADDS 8 grafs at end with
details on East Timor talks.) (rk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ President Clinton said Monday that
American troops would have a ``limited but important function'' in
the peacekeeping force that Indonesia is reluctantly permitting
into East Timor, although Asian officials insisted the United
States will inevitably be drawn into a central role if troops are
to be inserted quickly enough to bring a halt to the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at his hotel here Monday morning, Clinton
described an array of tasks for American forces, from airlifting
troops from several nations into East Timor to supplying them with
intelligence capabilities and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of that would require some presence on the ground in East
Timor,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said that the United States did not anticipate
providing ground troops. ``The Australians are willing to take the
lion's share of the role,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that many of the forces had not trained together
as NATO forces did before their insertion in Kosovo earlier this
year, Clinton added: ``We might be asked to provide some command
and control.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, a small team of American military officials from
the Pacific Command in Hawaii have been in Australia to develop a
plan for moving the peacekeepers into place, perhaps beginning as
early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say that they believe the U.S. participation
can be held to about 600 troops, though Australian officials and
Asian diplomats who have been briefed on the plans say they expect
the figure to be much higher. ``The assets offered by the Americans
are very pleasing to the Australian defense community,'' John
Howard, the Australian prime minister, said here, where he has
frequently been meeting Clinton on the sidelines of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
   The back-room negotiations over the composition and timing of an
East Timor peacekeeping force dominated much of the first day and a
half of a summit meeting that is supposed to focus on restarting a
series of trade and economic initiatives in the wake of the
recovery from the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was clearly far more engaged on a host of security
issues. On Sunday he held an unusual trilateral meeting with Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan and President Kim Dae-jung of South
Korea, jointly committing to penalizing North Korea if it conducts
a long-threatened missile launch, and dangling a resumption of aid
and economic cooperation if it publicly declares it is freezing
such tests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also met for the first time with the new Russian prime
minister, Vladimir Putin, and in an unusually direct acknowledgment
of Russian corruption that the White House has often downplayed in
the past, the president told him that corruption could ``eat the
heart out of Russian society.'' Critics of the administration's
Russia policy say those warnings should have been delivered far
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But East Timor has dominated much of the conversation among the
leaders of 21 ``economies'' represented here _ the phrase is used
to allow the participation of Taiwan and Hong Kong _ and Clinton
was awakened at 1 a.m. Monday morning to be told that Indonesia's
president, B.J. Habibie, had finally agreed to allow in the
peacekeeping force he had resisted for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Monday morning praised several nations that had
pressured Jakarta to change its mind. He added, ``It's important to
get the details worked out and get the force in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from his list was America's closest ally in
the Pacific, Japan, which is Indonesia's largest supplier of
foreign aid. Tokyo had declined to join Clinton in threatening a
cut off of aid and other economic ties if Indonesia failed to stop
the violence or let in the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held open the possibility of lifting the sanctions
threats as soon as Habibie carried through on the commitments he
made Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens,'' he said, ``we can resume our work with the
people of Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials and diplomats say they expect the force to
reach about 7,000 personnel, though it could take weeks to reach
that level. About 4,500 would likely come from Australia, with New
Zealand, Canada, Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, Sweden,
France, Britain and Portugal all supplying far more modest numbers
of troops.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would provide the aircraft and ships to
transport armored vehicles and other equipment to East Timor, and
Clinton suggested Monday morning that process could start within
days.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, congressional leaders expressed support as long
as the commitment remained limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously what's been happening there is shocking and
appalling,'' said Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican majority leader
from Mississippi. Speaking on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' he endorsed
American logistical help but said ``if it involved troops on the
ground, I think then a lot more questions are going to be asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists were concerned about the response from
the militias responsible for the death and destruction. ``This is
the period of maximum danger,`` said Sydney Jones, executive
director of Asia for Human Rights Watch. ``A lot depends on how
soon troops can get there. The U.N. and other world leaders have to
make clear that they are going to hold Indonesia responsible for
any further terror that takes place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
