<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICROSOFT AND U.S. REFINE ARGUMENTS IN ANTITRUST CASE
</P>
<P>
   In court filings on Friday, Microsoft and the government made
their last written submissions of evidence before final oral
arguments in the software giant's federal antitrust case begin on
Sept. 21. The documents gave each side a chance to refine its own
points while taking jabs at the arguments offered by the other.
</P>
<P>
   But more revealing may be a series of e-mail messages that the
government subpoenaed from Microsoft. Those discussions involved
the public-relations campaign that the company devised when
Netscape, cast as a victim of Microsoft's monopoly, was being
acquired by America Online. The spin was that the purchase of
Netscape rendered the government's antitrust suit irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   DEVICE PROMISES LONG BATTERY LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Analog Devices plans to announce a new product on Monday that it
says will reduce the cost of the radio portion of cellular
telephones while increasing battery life. The product, a tiny
assembly of components, allows for 1,000 hours of standby time. The
phones would have to be charged more often, depending on the
frequency and length of conversations.
</P>
<P>
   CARTOONIST CRITICIZED IN INDIANAPOLIS
</P>
<P>
   After Gary Varvel, the cartoonist for The Indianapolis Star,
illustrated invitations to a $250-a-head birthday party that was a
political fund-raiser, reporters at the newspaper, in a letter to
their editors, questioned Varvel's involvement. The publisher and
Varvel's boss, the editorial-page editor, agreed that it was
inappropriate. Varvel called it ``a stupid mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   BARNES &AMP; NOBLE TO DROP TIMES LIST
</P>
<P>
   While online booksellers wage a fierce price war over New York
Times best sellers, Barnes &AMP; Noble is preparing to phase out its
use of the newspaper's weekly list at its superstores. In place of
the Times list of books, for which Barnes &AMP; Noble typically offers
discounts, the bookseller intends to offer bargains based on the
chain's own sales rankings.
</P>
<P>
   PROMISED REVOLUTION SLOW IN COMING
</P>
<P>
   Two companies, Mercata and Accompany, promised to revolutionize
e-commerce by attracting groups of buyers interested in a certain
product and extracting wholesale prices from manufacturers and
distributors. Several months later, neither site has attracted
large numbers of users. But more manufacturers are showing
interest, and the number of buyers seems to be increasing. And with
more marketing money on the way, analysts say, the companies could
start realizing their goals.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE TAX POSES POLITICAL PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   Politics and business appear headed for a clash when technology
and government leaders appointed by Congress to draft sales-tax
policies for the Internet meet this week.
</P>
<P>
   $299 PC IS TOO GOOD TO BE TRUE
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Richard Latman's Microworkz announced that it
was selling a personal computer, the Webzter Jr., for $299,
including a year of Internet service and bundled software. Many
analysts and competitors said the Microworkz offer sounded too good
to be true. And in hindsight, it was. Since announcing the Webzter
Jr., the company has been accused of bad management, shabby service
and failure to deliver machines that had been paid for. Microworkz
eventually killed the Webzter Jr., and Latman announced last month
that he was stepping down as president.
</P>
<P>
   FREE WEEKLY ANGERS PUBLISHERS
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese-language publishers in California's Silicon Valley
are angry with The San Jose Mercury News for creating a free
Vietnamese weekly that the publishers say unfairly undermines their
businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
