<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HO-HUM ABOUT A SO-SO GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one looked very upset, really, as the Cal State
Northridge football players made their way to the team buses that
took them away from one of the school's worst losses.
</P>
<P>
   Not a great sign, considering this program was on the ropes this
summer and the only way to drum up support in the San Fernando
Valley is by either: (a) winning the games the Matadors are
supposed to win, or (b) not getting embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happened Saturday night as CSUN took a 71-14
beating at the hands of host Kansas. Sure, the Jayhawks are a
Division I program and a member of the Big 12 Conference, one of
the strongest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But KU has been PU for most of its history, and if CSUN can't
score more than two touchdowns against a defense more fit to stop a
wishbone offense than the run-and-shoot, there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   If the Matadors' skill-position defenders, who pride themselves
on their speed and coverage ability, get burned repeatedly by
Kansas receivers who don't have much experience, that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse is CSUN's apparent willingness to accept the
56-point loss. Where was the anger?
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Jaumal Bradley, who represents CSUN's soul,
called the game ``a learning experience.'' Defensive lineman
Shawnbay Jones, another senior, said the Matadors ``now know what
it takes'' to compete against teams of a higher caliber, and
``physically, it was harder than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, but 71-14?
</P>
<P>
   Kansas suited up 30 more players than Division I-AA CSUN; the
Jayhawks had better depth. But those aren't a bunch of former high
school All-Americans on the Kansas roster.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN appeared to give more effort in making excuses after giving
up the most points in a single game in school history.
</P>
<P>
   One player said the officials, who are from the Big 12, made ``a
few bad calls.'' But the Jayhawks committed 14 penalties, almost
twice as many as the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore quarterback Marcus Brady, who didn't play particularly
well in his first game on regional TV, said: ``We beat ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady was at least warming to the idea that even though the
Matadors had nothing to lose, playing the patsy to Kansas in the
Jayhawks' home opener, CSUN didn't play well.
</P>
<P>
   One college football publication picked the Matadors to finish
second in the Big Sky Conference, and the coaches and players have
basically shrugged off the conference's coaches' poll that picked
CSUN to finish next-to-last.
</P>
<P>
   But the players, especially those who have two or more years of
eligibility, must realize that a loss such as Saturday's doesn't
help when students are deciding whether to vote yes in October for
a proposed fee referendum that would raise money to build a new
football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys out there,'' Bradley said, referring to the
Jayhawks after the game, ``know that we didn't roll over.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Matadors didn't quit. But they didn't play the way they
are capable of playing, and they know that. They needed to show it
a little more. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CSUN STATUS REPORT &QL; 
__ Game: &UR; !off! &LR;  2 &QL; 
__ Result: &UR; !off! &LR;  Kansas 71, CSUN 14 &QL; 
__ Record: &UR; !off! &LR;  1-1 &QL; 
__ This week's GPA: &UR; !off! &LR;  1.9 &QL; 
__ Cumulative GPA: &UR; !off! &LR;  2.5 &QL; 
QUARTERBACK  &QL; 
Statistically speaking, Marcus Brady had the second-worst game of
his 13-game CSUN career. Brady had just 17 completions and 180
yards and threw two interceptions. Backup Josh Fiske came in and
immediately threw an interception. Yuck. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS  &QL; 
With 203 yards in two games, Jaumal Bradley is on pace to pass his
1998 rushing total in CSUN's next game. Bradley had runs of 28, 27,
18 and 17 yards Saturday and his game total of 109 is a
career-best. Rest of the team had 9 yards. &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
RECEIVERS  &QL; 
Preseason All-American Aaron Arnold had a reception on CSUN's first
offensive play and then disappeared; he had only three the rest of
the game. There were a few dropped passes. Drew Amerson (6 catches,
113 yards, 1 TD) is developing as a complement to Arnold. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE  &QL; 
Matched Kansas' defensive line in size but allowed Jayhawks to
streak inside and knock down two passes. Brady was only sacked
twice and he had decent protection most of the time. Opened good
holes for Bradley. &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE  &QL; 
Put pressure on Kansas QBs but didn't have a sack. Blown off the
line by Jayhawks' offensive line; KU had 353 yards and five TDs on
the ground, and junior David Winbush, honorable mention All-Big 12
last year, had 134 yards. &QL; 
Grade: D &QL; 
LINEBACKERS  &QL; 
Highlight: Jack Heaslet, an undersized (5-10, 218) senior who had
six tackles, including one that was unassisted in the open field.
Lowlight: Cos Abercrombie, who had 17 tackles in first two games
last year, had only two against KU. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS  &QL; 
Yes, this unit is missing two starters, but the Jayhawks looked
like Florida Saturday, completing 19 of 25 passes, three for TDs.
No INTs and too many missed tackles. &QL; 
Grade: D &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS  &QL; 
Great start on Terrence Jones' 32-yard return of Kansas' first
kickoff. Nightmarish after that. A penalty wiped out excellent fake
punt. Gave up an average of 32{ yards on punt returns and kickoffs.
KU had a 72-yard punt return for a touchdown. &QL; 
Grade: D &QL; 
COACHING  &QL; 
Kearin accepts blame for 56-point loss, second-worst in school
history. Players were prepared for Jayhawks, who were simply better
in all phases. But for the second game in a row, CSUN came out
listless and committed too many penalties. &QL; 
Grade: C &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
