<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S RIGHT NOMINATES PRAGMATIC CANDIDATE FOR PRESIDENT 
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Vicente Fox Quesada, the lanky former Coca-Cola
executive known for his high-shine cowboy boots and down-home
style, was chosen Sunday as the National Action Party's
presidential candidate in a nationwide primary. The outcome makes
him the man for the governing party to beat in the election next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's nomination in the vote within the party _ the pro-business
opposition group known as the PAN _ was a foregone conclusion,
since he was the only candidate. But the balloting by registered
members of the party was still a novelty, because for decades it
picked its presidential nominees in closed conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 56, broke the mold of Mexican politics by starting his
presidential run in 1997, three years before the election and long
before any other politicians had begun to focus on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show that he is the most popular challenger to the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which has not
lost a presidential election since its founding 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A national poll on Aug. 30 by the newspaper Reforma showed Fox
tied at 39 percent with Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the choice of
most PRI leaders, including President Ernesto Zedillo. In a matchup
against another PRI politician who has surged in public opinion,
Roberto Madrazo Pintado, the poll showed Fox trailing by one point,
with 38 percent to Madrazo's 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fox's solid appeal among voters who dislike the
governing party, up to now he has been forced to mount an
outsider's campaign, with little enthusiastic support from the
best-known leaders of his party and critical cash shortages.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three weeks, while the PRI dominated news coverage
by holding the first televised debate ever among the men who hope
to be its candidate, Fox's campaign disappeared from the media. PAN
officials said he had run out of money. To dramatize his
predicament, Fox created a ruckus at the sober congressional
session on Sept. 1, when Zedillo made his annual state of the union
address.
</P>
<P>
   First a jovial Fox marched out onto the floor of the Congress,
shaking hands and clapping backs of other PAN members, breaking
protocol rules that restrict the floor to elected lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Then he walked out halfway through Zedillo's speech, saying he
had ``more important things to do'' and telling reporters that his
antic was the only way he could think of to get on television.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Fox's campaign said they hoped that after his
official nomination Sunday, party leaders would rally round him,
eliminating doubts among PAN supporters about his legitimacy and
opening the spigots of contributions from the business community.
</P>
<P>
   Fox comes from a pragmatic wing of the party and has avoided its
traditional Catholic, conservative fundamentalism. He says he will
adopt free-market policies to create jobs and shape public
education to train Mexicans for the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   He steers clear of issues like opposition to abortion, a deeply
held conviction among many party members that is not popular with a
majority of Mexican women.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox has shown that he knows how to harness the power of
television, which in this campaign may be a decisive factor for the
first time. At a rally in his home state of Guanajuato on Friday,
his two children sent him off by handing him a huge satin banner
showing the Virgin of Guadalupe, Mexico's much-revered patroness.
The television cameras lapped it up.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's government fired back with a statement saying Fox was
breaking laws establishing the separation of church and state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
