<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-POLITICS-925(     09-12 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-POLITICS-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPOINTED DEMOCRATS OFFER CHANCE FOR BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, Mo., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are a lot of things in Bill Bradley's
biography that Joan Lydic likes, from his Rhodes Scholarship to his
Hall of Fame career with the New York Knicks to his three terms as
a senator from New Jersey. And oh yeah, he is a down-to-earth guy.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Lydic, 55, a family therapist from St. Louis who
attended a rally last week for Bradley in Keokuk, Iowa, has another
reason for supporting him over Vice President Gore, his sole rival
for the Democratic presidential nomination: He was never part of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm uncomfortable, being a mother, with what went on there,''
Mrs. Lydic said. ``It sickened me. I know Al Gore is different. But
if Al Gore were principled, he should have wanted to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lydic and other disenchanted Democrats represent both the
central opportunity and the major challenge for Bradley as he gears
up his insurgent rivalry with Gore, the party's presumptive
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in a campaign swing through Missouri and Iowa last
week, it was clear that many of Bradley's supporters are fueled, at
least in part, by a deep disillusionment with Clinton _ and, by
extension, with Gore. And while few blamed Gore for the
administration's ethical problems, many said they believed the vice
president had been badly tarnished by his close association with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Bradley, from a moral point of view,'' said Merel
Young, 68, a retired teacher from Keokuk. ``I think that makes him
more electable than Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But building a base among anti-Clinton Democrats is not likely
to be enough for Bradley to wrest the nomination from Gore, whose
support in the Democratic establishment runs deep. To win, Bradley
would have to assemble a broader coalition that picked off Gore's
supporters on the party's right and left, analysts say. And while
the election is still a long way away, Bradley will have to hustle
to widen his appeal by the early primaries this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, two-thirds of Bradley's appeal is soft,'' said Fred
Siegel, a professor of history at the Cooper Union for the
Advancement of Science and Art in New York. ``People like him
because he's an adult, he seems like a fully formed human being
with a backbone, who is not going to be tossed by the winds. And
he's not caught up in the Clinton scandals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To vault to the next level, he has to go further,'' Siegel
added. ``He has to lay out specifics for what a Bradley presidency
would look like.''
</P>
<P>
   So far Bradley has been unwilling to do that, avoiding major
policy pronouncements on the issues he says will define the coming
election: the economy, health care, race relations and foreign
policy. Those will come in the fall, when voters are more focused
on the race, his campaign says.
</P>
<P>
   But in his recent speeches, Bradley has provided clear
indications of how he plans to establish himself as the anti-Gore
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of every speech is a liberal critique of the
Clinton administration's economic policies: that the nation's
roaring prosperity has not trickled down to struggling
working-class and poor Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult argument to make, because the strong economy
is probably Gore's greatest political asset. But with a New
Deal-like pitch to traditional liberalism, Bradley evokes the
spirit of his father, a small-town banker, who he says refused to
foreclose on a single home during the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stock market is skyrocketing and family farms are going
bankrupt,'' Bradley told 18 people at a diner in Newton, Iowa,
``you shouldn't feel good about where the economy is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has also placed race relations front and center in his
campaign, saying, ``The only thing deserving of hate is hate
itself.'' Polls indicate that blacks _ who represent 30 percent or
more of the Democratic primary vote in some Southern states _
remain loyal to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of Bradley's desire to grab black votes from
Gore's left, he appeared before a Harlem organization run by the
Rev. Al Sharpton last month _ even though his visit angered
centrist white voters and Jews who view Sharpton as divisive.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley is doing more than trying to outflank Gore in the
party's liberal wing. He is a staunch advocate of sweeping gun
restrictions and changes to the campaign-finance system. Both are
issues of concern not just for liberals but also for middle-class
reformers and centrist suburban voters.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have extensive proposals on both issues, but
Bradley's go significantly further. He has called for the licensing
of all gun owners, registration of all guns and a ban on so-called
Saturday night special handguns, as well as for public financing of
congressional campaigns and free television time for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   To broaden the appeal of his economic message beyond the very
poor, Bradley advocates making it easier for workers to form
unions, expanding access to health care and bolstering pensions.
</P>
<P>
   And for independent voters, Bradley offers a populist,
Perot-like critique of Clinton and Gore's leadership styles,
asserting that politics today is ``obsessed with the mechanics of
winning, which is polling, fund raising and spinning.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, by focusing on the importance of character and virtue
in politics, Bradley seems to be directly addressing the
small-town, moderate Democrats who tend to vote in the Iowa
caucuses and New Hampshire primary, where he must perform well next
year to survive.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It helps Bradley that most of this does not seem forced. He can
fairly claim that he has been concerned about race relations since
he was a boy and that the civil rights movement inspired him to
enter politics.
</P>
<P>
   And he was talking about the importance of character in politics
long before Monica Lewinsky became a household name.
</P>
<P>
   He also seems to benefit from his unhurried, easy manner. In
Keokuk he shook hands and signed basketballs until the last
supporter had drifted off, leaving him alone in the fading
afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of a good old country doctor,'' Katie Wood, 48,
of Hannibal, Mo., said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley can be maddeningly short on specifics, and even some
supporters say his gauzy appeals to human goodness may begin to
lose voters if they do not soon include hard details.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the campaign just two weeks, and people are
already asking me where he stands on things,'' said Nancy Parrott,
a Bradley organizer in southeastern Iowa. ``Right now, we are just
giving them resumes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bradley often dodges questions on broad policy matters, he
can be quite specific on issues that concern Iowa voters.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottumwa, he told farmers that he supported Justice Department
oversight of agricultural mergers that threaten small farmers. In
Des Moines, he told peace activists that he opposed sending U.S.
troops to East Timor. And in Grinnell, he told college students
that although he opposed legalizing gay marriages, he supported
giving homosexual partners legal rights and protections comparable
to those of married couples.
</P>
<P>
   By nature cautious and methodical, Bradley admits to fearing
that candor will cause him problems as the campaign heats up.
</P>
<P>
   When a woman in Newton asked him about his position on public
financing of private schools, Bradley acknowledged that he had
voted for a pilot voucher program while in the Senate, a position
strongly opposed by the powerful teachers unions. But he added that
he did not consider vouchers ``the answer to the problems of public
education.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to be as candid with you as possible,'' Bradley
told the woman. ``That leads to the maximum possibility of
distortion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9412 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      09-12 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS AND YANKEES LOSING THEIR GRIP AS RED SOX SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens had a baseball and the evolving pennant
race resting in his sweaty fingers Sunday. What Clemens could
accomplish with that ball in those fingers would help determine
whether this surprising tussle with the Boston Red Sox would become
even more serious for the Yankees and more serious than anyone ever
dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens pitched commendably for most of the afternoon, but he
sputtered in a critical juncture in the eighth inning, and that was
enough to doom the Yankees in a disheartening 4-1 loss at Yankee
Stadium. Forget serious. Suddenly, this skirmish with the calm Red
Sox has become extremely serious for the nervous Yankees after they
were swept during this three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks the Yankees' once-cozy bulge of eight and
one-half games in the American League East has shrunk to three and
one-half with 20 games to play, and so many players were vowing not
to panic that it seemed as if they were panicking. Jeff Nelson even
mentioned how the Yankees have the wild-card spot as their security
blanket. That is true, but it is a revealing statement from the
defending World Series champions, who have not seen the Red Sox
this close to them since July 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston's resiliency should serve as a very loud wake-up call
for us,'' said David Cone, whose face was flushed and whose voice
was loud enough for teammates to hear him. ``Whether we needed it
or not, we certainly got one this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   That was obvious. From Joe Torre asking reporters to stop
comparing the stumbling 1999 Yankees to the memorable 1998 Yankees
to Derek Jeter saying he was shocked that the Red Sox had swept the
Yankees in the Bronx for the first time since June 1986 to Clemens
curiously claiming that Sunday's start was no more pivotal than any
others, it was a stunned and confused clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, winning all those games, I still wasn't confident
until the champagne popped,'' Torre said. ``This game has taught
you that anything can happen. History shows that.''
</P>
<P>
   History will show that Clemens, who was feisty enough to shout
at Jose Offerman after a strikeout and who surrendered only two
hits in seven innings, allowed three more hits on his first six
pitches in the eighth to enable the Red Sox to snatch a 2-1 lead.
Trot Nixon ripped a liner that forced Clemens to duck, and Offerman
slashed a hit-and-run single past third baseman Scott Brosius, who
had crept in about 25 feet anticipating a bunt and missed snaring
the ball by inches.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and third, no outs and the score tied, the
Yankees needed Clemens to be overpowering and record a strikeout or
a pop out. Clemens got the pop fly as Darren Lewis hit a bloop to
shallow center field, but Bernie Williams got a late jump on the
ball and it dropped a few feet in front of him after he rushed
forward. A 200-foot single began Williams's inning of adventures,
conquered Clemens and gave the Red Sox a lead they never
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   After Clemens walked Reggie Jefferson to load the bases, Torre
replaced him with Nelson. Nomar Garciaparra followed with a
sacrifice fly to center to deliver the third run and O'Leary's
bloop single in front of Williams off Mike Stanton made the score
4-1. The Red Sox were celebrating at the Stadium again while
Clemens bolted to the exercise room after losing for the fifth time
in his last seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They held us down and got it done,'' said Clemens, whose
fastball had reached 96 mph. ``They had some bloop singles, but
sometimes you need those in close ball games to get you through.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, it is the Red Sox who are more likely to collapse in
September. Normally, it is the Yankees who are more apt to play
like they own the stadium. But those roles were not fulfilled on
this lost weekend in which Boston excelled and made the Yankees
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Bret Saberhagen was so relaxed starting his first game
in 26 days that he told a clubhouse attendant: ``It'll be a fast
game today. I promise.'' Saberhagen was serious. Other than Chuck
Knoblauch's seventh leadoff homer of the season, Saberhagen did not
allow a run over five innings, and four relievers stifled the
Yankees on two hits over the last four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had first and second and no outs in the sixth, but
Paul O'Neill slapped into a double play and Williams struck out.
Chili Davis actually swung at a 3-0 pitch while leading off the
seventh with the score still 1-1 and grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were listless while the Red Sox were aggressive and
rammed into catcher Joe Girardi on two plays at the plate (they
scored once).
</P>
<P>
   ``Why panic?'' Torre said. ``It doesn't do any good. If you
panic, nothing good can happen, other than scaring other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Yankees need to be scared. They have lost five of
their last six games and eight of 12. The Yankees started the
weekend needing one measly victory to remain relatively relaxed,
and they ended it with Clemens losing to his old team and with his
new team losing its secure grip on first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in firm control of the division and now we're not,''
Cone said. ``We still have a four-game lead in the loss column, but
we're a lot worse off than we were three days ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
