<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: FEEL THE POWER FROM AFAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wanna know how a typical Los Angeles male aged 18 to 34 spent
the opening Sunday of the '99 NFL season?
</P>
<P>
   Read it and weep:
</P>
<P>
   ++ Crack of dawn: Watched NFL pregame shows from clubhouse TV at
local golf course, waiting for starter to call name. Name was never
called. Woulda shot 114 and walked off after nine holes anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Morning-ish: Watched more NFL pregame shows from gym TV while
straddling idle cybex. Tried to strike up conversation with
Jennifer Esposito-looking female on next machine. Discussion began
on nuances of instant replay. She challenged his explanation. Buff
guy on Stairmaster ruled in her favor. He not only lost a timeout
but was banished to Blinkie's Donut Emporium.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Brunchtime: Watched early NFL games from bar TV at the
Cheesecake Factory, an excuse to flip through the menu and check
out the ads. ``Loser, Party of 1'' was never called.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Early afternoon: Watched end of Dallas-Washington NFL game
from bank of TV monitors at local Good Guys store while sucking
down McFlurry. Screamed and pumped fist at Troy Aikman's overtime
TD pass. Got sour look from haggard clerk who was awakened in
small-appliances department. Left McFlurry cup to drip on stack of
overpriced toaster ovens.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Later afternoon: Watched 49ers-Jags on portable TV held by
guy at front of line of other applicants for job as key grip in new
Pamela Anderson movie. Asked person during interview if she's back
together with Tommy Lee Jones. Received a blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Kinda later afternoon: Tried to watch ``NFL Prime Time'' game
from home TV hooked up to illegal cable box left behind by previous
renter. Audio in Mandarin Chinese. Chris Berman finally
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Early evening: Watched Cleveland-Pittsburgh game on TV from
limo in Shrine Auditorium parking lot, waiting for clients to
return from Emmy Awards. Was supposed to pick up Camryn Manheim's
family but told by dispatcher to wait for a call to get Sarah
Jessica Parker's twin sister instead. Call never came. 'Cause twin
doesn't exist. Guys back at office had a great laugh. Took home one
of the guys who plays an anchor on ``Sports Night,'' but he knows
nothing about the day's games, let alone football.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Night: Watched NFL highlights on all local and cable news
shows. Again. And again. And again. And still couldn't figure out
why the Chargers' score never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   __ And what do we learn from this little dramatization?
</P>
<P>
   L.A. still loves the NFL. It fits in our day just fine. On TV.
We just aren't controlled by it.
</P>
<P>
   Public funding? Here, Tags, take these pennies, a 25-cents-off
coupon from Arby's and a crusty Tic-Tac out of our pockets as you
reconvene the owners today and bang that Wednesday-deadline drum
again.
</P>
<P>
   We hear it. We just won't jump.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, you have the problem.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bill Cosby has been mentioned as a possible sucker to buy
part of the Balti-less Ravens, which Art Modell is trying to dump
in part to pay off debt. Slimy owners do the darndest things. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Dem 'Boys in Dallas, at $663 million, are the most valuable
NFL franchise today according to a Forbes magazine list based on
revenue and operating income. Last year, they were only worth $413
mil. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The greatness of the Raiders? They're next to last at $299 mil.
Maybe discounted more on the way home from GBay. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The Denver Post found out that the Broncs wanted to keep John
Elway on the active list so his $5 million salary would create
space under the cap for next season. But then he went and did those
Coors spots _ active NFL players aren't allowed to endorse alcohol
_ so the Broncos' hand was forced.
</P>
<P>
   Drink up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
