<HEADER>
A9434 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     09-12 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNEES WILL HELP BUT PROBABLY NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The worst loss of Bob Toledo's tenure came four
years ago on a crisp fall day in Ann Arbor, Mich., when Michigan
manhandled the Bruins 38-9. UCLA was confused and ineffective on
offense and helpless on defense as the Wolverines rushed for 300
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 22-point loss at Ohio State, although decisive, was
not demoralizing or humiliating as was last year's loss at Miami.
The Bruins took a 10-0 lead and were within 21-17 throughout the
third quarter. They comported themselves as well as could be
expected without 11 suspended players and with 13 freshmen and
sophomores in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Their performance should improve when the suspensions end today.
Seven starters will return, including five on defense. Not all are
assured of regaining their starting jobs, but their presence in any
capacity will add experience and depth.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there are problems, and some have little to do
with the suspensions. For the Bruins to compete with USC and the
Arizona schools _ the Pac-10's early-season favorites _ they must
resolve the problems before a critical Oct. 2 date at Arizona
State.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback, of course, is the primary concern. While Cade
McNown reportedly obtained an improper parking permit, he's not
returning this week. Instead, the Bruins have two choices: Drew
Bennett and Cory Paus, and one week to decide. (Toledo plans to
pick a starter before the Pac-10 opener against Stanford on Sept.
25.)
</P>
<P>
   Paus, a freshman, probably will make more mistakes because of
unfamiliarity with the offense. But he has two years on Bennett, a
junior, and thus more potential. Given that UCLA's best days are
ahead, maybe Paus is the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if Toledo and offensive coordinator Al Borges
believe Bennett's athleticism and experience are worth two or three
victories this year and possibly next, maybe he's the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Toledo and Borges will earn their pay.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacks' performance is directly related to the
offensive line, and the offensive line's performance is somewhat
related to the suspensions. Sure, having Oscar Cabrera at left
guard and Jim Ghezzi to relieve the tackles will help. But their
presence won't solve the rudimentary problems of communication and
timing.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Cabrera back, the Bruins will have two redshirt
freshmen (guard Mike Saffer and tackle Blake Worley) and a
sophomore (center Troy Danoff) in the lineup. They need game
experience and they also must get used to playing with Cabrera and
tackle Brian Polak.
</P>
<P>
   Is the line any better this season than it was in 1996, when
Andy Meyers, Shawn Stuart and Kris Farris replaced Jonathan Ogden,
Matt Soenksen and Mike Flanagan? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   The other problem is the defensive backfield. Cornerback Marques
Anderson has been suspended for the fall quarter, leaving starter
Ryan Roques and reserve Eric Whitfield as the only players
returning this week.
</P>
<P>
   Are they enough? Don't count on it. One cornerback, Joe Hunter,
is a redshirt freshman with decent potential. The other is a
senior, Jason Bell, who has moxie but little athleticism and a bad
heel.
</P>
<P>
   With Jason Stephens, Julius Williams and Audie Attar, strong
safety is such a mess that holder Joey Strycula has gone unnoticed
as the starting free safety. The best player in the group might be
freshman Ricky Manning, who graduated from high school a few months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   And that pretty much says it all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UCLA STATUS REPORT  &QL; 
__ Game: 2 &QL; 
__ Result: Ohio State 42, UCLA 20 &QL; 
__ Record: 1-1 &QL; 
__ This week's GPA: 1.96 &QL; 
__ Cumulative GPA: 2.5 &QL; 
__ Next week: Fresno State  &QL; 
__ Quarterbacks:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how bad it would have been if Drew Bennett's miracle
touchdown to Matt Stanley had been intercepted _ as it should have.
The QB search continues.  &QL; 
Grade: D  &QL; 
__ Running backs:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most effective runners were a receiver (Freddie Mitchell)
and a quarterback (Bennett). Fifty-one yards from DeShaun Foster
won't cut it. Line gets part of the blame.  &QL; 
Grade: C+  &QL; 
__ Receivers:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten players caught passes; only three were wideouts. Trouble
begins up the chain, with blocking, running and passing.  &QL; 
Grade: B  &QL; 
__ Offensive line:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suspended guard Oscar Cabrera's return this week should help,
but only experience will correct the primary problems: timing and
communication.  &QL; 
Grade: C-  &QL; 
__ Defensive line:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Held its own until fatigue surfaced. No pass rush without the
blitz, and that's killing the DBs. Ken Kocher is most improved
lineman.  &QL; 
Grade: C  &QL; 
__ Linebackers:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starters return this week, but don't expect freshman Marcus
Reese (nine tackles) to go away quietly. The other fill-ins are
just that.  &QL; 
Grade: C-  &QL; 
__ Secondary:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make frosh Ricky Manning a starter this week. Suspended starter
Ryan Roques was supposed to play the weakest position. Can he be in
three places at once?  &QL; 
Grade: D  &QL; 
__ Special teams:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coverage is solid but return game lacking. Nate Fikse's punts
could be worse (or blocked). Kicker Chris Griffith, with field
goals of 35 and 33 yards, was player of the game.  &QL; 
Grade: C  &QL; 
__ Coaching:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First quarter showed dynamic offense at its best. The game plan
was solid; players simply too young to execute. Toledo will earn
his money with quarterback decision this week or next.  &QL; 
Grade: B &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-DJUJIC--NYT &LR;      09-12 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DJUJIC--NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMCILO DJUJIC, SERBIAN PRIEST AND WARRIOR, DIES AT 92
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID BINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Momcilo Djujic, a Serbian warrior-priest who fought as a Chetnik
commander in epic World War II battles in Yugoslavia, died Saturday
at a hospice in San Diego. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Djujic, who lived in San Marcos, Calif., was in the view of some
Serbs the last great ``Vojvoda,'' the designation in Serbia for a
military commander distinguished by bravery, devotion to the
Orthodox Church and loyalty to the now-exiled monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The title of ``Vojvoda'' was conferred on Djujic in June 1942,
by Gen. Dragoljub ``Draza'' Mihailovic, the commander of the
royalist Chetniks, after Djujic had already been fighting Nazi
Germans, Croatian Fascists and Communist Partisans for a year in
the mountains and valleys of his native region on the border
between Croatia and northwestern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   So fierce was the fighting in Yugoslavia in World War II that
Djujic, a tall, bearded commander in traditional black lambs wool
cap with a skull and crossbones insignia, never met Mihailovic
during the war because they were in different combat zones.
</P>
<P>
   They had begun fighting Axis forces almost simultaneously in the
months after Hitler's invasion of Yugoslavia in April 1941, an
invasion that unleashed brutal ethnic, religious and political
rivalries between the countries Serbs, Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks into the war, Croatian nationalist forces surrounded
the home of Djujic, a priest. He grabbed a rifle, escaped across
the mountains with his family and found refuge in the hills above
the Croatian coast. By July 1941 he had organized a Chetnik
uprising in northwestern Bosnia, seizing the city of Drvar from the
Ustashe, as the Croatian fascists were known. The revolt soon
spread to neighboring Croatia's coastal region, Dalmatia.
</P>
<P>
   How was it to strip off his priest's cassock and become a
warrior? ``That decision didn't come easily,'' he said in 1990,
``but the forests were full of refugees and I could see the Ustashe
in front of my nose in my parish. The people were crying, they
needed deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   In March 1942, Chetnik officers brought Djujic a radio
transmitter. He battled on, and for a short time boasted of holding
all of Dalmatia. A 1942 letter from Mihailovic praised and thanked
him for his ``gigantic efforts,'' recognized by the later award of
high royal decorations.
</P>
<P>
   His acts of wartime bravery included the rescue of six American
airmen shot down over Yugoslavia. But he also encountered charges
that he collaborated with Communists and the Ustashe on occasion _
both sworn enemies of the royalist Serbian Chetniks _ and in 1946
Tito's Communist government branded him a war criminal on charges
of being responsible for the death of 1,500 people during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Djujic said later, ``I never made a compromise, never an
agreement, either with the Communists or the Ustashe.''
</P>
<P>
   Djujic was born Feb. 27, 1907 in the village of Kovacic, in the
region known as Tromedja, or junction, where Croatia meets
northwestern Bosnia and their mixed populations of Serbs and Croats
converged.
</P>
<P>
   He attended high school in the Croatian coastal city of Sibenik
but at 22 went to the Orthodox theological seminary in Sremski
Karlovci, graduating in 1931. Consecrated a priest, he was assigned
to a parish near his birthplace. There his passionate sermons soon
won him the the nickname, Pop Vatra _ ``Father Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Djujic's first and only encounter with Mihailovic came when the
body of King Alexsander, who was assassinated in Marseilles in
1934, passed through the priest's native region. Djujic was chosen
to stand by the coffin as the funeral train proceeded.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating future ethnic conflict, Djujic met after the king's
death with a Serbian paramilitary leader and the president of the
Chetnik movement, Kosta Pecanac. With their assistance, even before
war erupted, he organized and began to arm 11 Chetnik bands in his
region. ``I knew that the country would not survive,'' he said
later, ``because nobody can put Serbs and Croats in the same bag.''
</P>
<P>
   His toughest moment in battle, he said, was on Dec. 3, 1944,
battling Communist Partisans in Dalmatia. His men were outnumbered
five to one. Losses were heavy on both sides. ``It was also a big
victory,'' Djujic recalled, ``because Tito gave his general an
order to take me alive. Later the Partisan general wrote: `Though
we had the strongest forces, Djujic slipped away from us like a
fish through our hands.'''
</P>
<P>
   As the war ended, Djujic hoped to combine with other anti-Tito
forces to build a kind of redoubt in northern Yugoslavia. Instead,
he was ordered by Allied forces to surrender. His division was
taken to southern Italy, from there to Germany and then dispersed
to European countries, the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Djujic was in Paris from 1947 to 1949, then moved to the United
States, where he became active in Serbian emigre circles and the
Orthodox Church, although not serving as a priest.
</P>
<P>
   He enraged some emigre Serbs when he endorsed a church patriarch
in Belgrade authorized by the Communists, but remained strongly
inimical to Tito. Finally he retired to San Marcos, writing poems
and jokes published in America and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 he pronounced Vojislav Seselj, then an anti-Communist
dissident, a Serbian ``Vojvoda.'' Seselj is now head of the Radical
Party and a government coalition partner of President Slobodan
Milosevic. ``I was naive when I nominated Seselj Vojvoda,'' Djujic
said in 1998. ``I ask my people to forgive me. The greatest
gravedigger of Serbdom is Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his sons, Sinisa, of Redondo Beach, and
Radivoje, of Santa Monica; a daughter, Radojka Kinach, of San
Marcos; two granddaughters and four great-grandchildren; a brother,
Bosko, of Torrance, Calif., and a sister, Ika Djuric, of Escondido,
Calif. His wife, Zorka, died in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
