<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-TIMOR-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      09-12 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
INDONESIA AGREES TO ACCEPT INTERNATIONAL PEACEKEEPING FORCE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Bowing to international pressure,
Indonesia agreed Sunday to allow a foreign security force into East
Timor to halt the slaughter of civilians by pro-Jakarta militias.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other Pacific Rim nations gathered here
for the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum continued to press
Indonesia President B.J. Habibie to allow a rapid deployment and to
step up its lackluster efforts to halt the continuing violence.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie, dropping his nation's defiant stance, announced he
would acquiesce to worldwide demands for a peacekeeping force.
However, he set no time frame nor did he offer any details on what
type of force would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people have lost their lives since the beginning of
the unrest, lost their homes and security. We can wait no longer.
We have to stop the suffering and the mourning immediately,''
Habibie said during a news conference in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who had earlier accused the Indonesian
military of ``aiding and abetting'' the militias, said he welcomed
Habibie's words but wanted to see action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is for President Habibie to make good
on his statement, get the details worked out, get the force in in a
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters prior to a morning APEC session that
Jakarta should have no say about who is in the security force or
how it is structured. He said U.S. participation would be limited
to a supporting role and may ``require some presence on the ground
in East Timor, but no one has asked for any combat troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Dire conditions continued in East Timor amid reports that the
capital, Dili, had been sacked and thousands had fled into hiding.
Rampaging pro-Indonesian gangs began mounting attacks against
civilians following an Aug. 30 vote in which East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony and heavily Roman Catholic, voted overwhelmingly
for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia, whose population is largely Muslim, invaded East
Timor in 1975 and annexed it the following year. Two decades of
conflict have claimed the lives of an estimated 200,000 East
Timorese.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, Clinton's national security adviser,
said Habibie's announcement ``represents a stepping back from the
brink on the part of Indonesia from what could be a quite
disastrous situation, not only for the people of East Timor, but
for Indonesia and for the region as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie was surrounded by military officers, including army
chief Gen. Wiranto, who like many Indonesians uses only one name,
in a scene that lent some credence to the president's statements.
Wiranto and others had offered conflicting statements about the
acceptance of foreign troops.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie informed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan of his
decision and immediately sent Foreign Minister Ali Alata to the
United Nations to work out the details. He is expected to arrive in
New York today.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Prime Minister John Howard, who took the lead in
assembling troop commitments, called the decision a ``great step
forward for the people of East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their welfare, their future, their safety, their freedom
that this has been all about,'' Howard said. The Australian prime
minister used the APEC gathering to personally lobby members to
pressure Indonesia and to contribute to the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The East Timor crisis dominated the APEC conference which wraps
up late today.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia objected to the force being led by Australia, which
has committed 2,000 troops, but a number of Asian nations pledged
to provide infantry. Malaysia, Singapore, Thailand and the
Philippines offered contributions. New Zealand, Britain, Canada,
Portugal and Fiji also will provide some of the 5,000 to 7,000
troops expected as an initial deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States may provide troops for logistical support but
Clinton said there had been no request for combat soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of what our role would be in East Timor, we have had
extensive discussions with the Australians through out defense
channels and we've been asked to provide a limited, but important
function related to airlift, transportation, communications,
intelligence and perhaps in engineering work,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly what the details would be have yet to be worked out
and require more extensive consultations with Congress,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Congress
probably would support a limited U.S. role. ``If it's
communications, logistics, transportation, I think there would be
support for that,'' he said Sunday on CBS' Face the Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it involves troops on the ground, I think then a lot more
questions are going to be asked, and of course there's always the
question of what the cost is going to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   International pressure on Indonesian had been growing for days.
The United States and Britain halted military sales and broached
the possibility of economic sanctions. Governments from Asia to
Europe had condemned the Indonesian military's inaction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, hoping to keep the heat on Habibie, said the United
States would not resume normal relations with Indonesia until the
security force is in place. Later today, the president will meet
with Jose Ramos-Horta, an East Timorese independence leader and
Nobel Peace Prize winner.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. Security Council team that visited Dili on Sunday
described it as a ``living hell'' after gangs looted and burned
much of the city. An estimated 600 to 7,000 civilians have been
murdered. Thousands fled to Indonesia's West Timor, which shares
the island. Another 100,000 refugees are thought hiding in the
forests outside Dili where food is scarce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle wire services contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
