<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-BUCS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE COMPENSATES FOR LACKLUSTER OFFENSE IN GIANTS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ A year ago when the New York Giants played in
Tampa, their offensive performance was so inept that quarterback
Danny Kanell apologized to his defensive teammates afterward. It
was a courtly gesture but the beginning of the end for Kanell and
the dawn of a downward Giants spiral that ruined a season of
promise.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants returned to Tampa on Sunday wary of the bad karma the
place held for them. And like last year's offense, this year's
Giants offense played crudely. But after Sunday's season-opening
game against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, Giants quarterback Kent
Graham did not offer apologies. He did, wisely, give thanks to his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Five turnovers forced by the Giants' defense turned a clumsy yet
tense game into a 17-13 victory at Raymond James Stadium. And there
was no discord between the Giants' offense and the defense on the
sideline or in the locker room as there was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That was because the Giants' offense did not turn the ball over
and the defensive players magnanimously accepted that their
offensive brethren were having an off day. They happily rescued the
offense, scoring two touchdowns and setting up a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants may have look hopelessly awkward on offense _ they
had just four first downs _ but the Giants left Tampa gleeful, as
if they had romped, because coaches and players alike had
identified this game as the schedule's most daunting assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be games like this,'' Giants coach Jim
Fassel said. ``But you've got to figure out a way to win these
games. No, I'm not happy with our offense, but we didn't make
mistakes that cost us the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a mental maturing process on this team. As the game
evolved, we had a sense that we had to do whatever we had to win.
That's an important thing to learn. I feel as good about our team
as I have since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that belonged in the Giants' 1997 season, when the
defense won games and the offense tried not to lose them.
</P>
<P>
   On Tampa Bay's first offensive series, Giants linebacker Jessie
Armstead blitzed, sacking Trent Dilfer the Buccaneers' beleaguered
quarterback, and forcing a fumble. Defensive tackle Christian Peter
grabbed the fumble and dashed 38 yards into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Although the teams would play for another three hours, Peter's
touchdown set a tone for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave us belief that things could be different for us,''
Armstead said. ``We got the old fire in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Buccaneers came back to take a 10-7 lead, four
second-half interceptions chased Dilfer from the game. The most
damaging came when Dilfer threw from his end zone in the third
quarter. The rookie cornerback Andre Weathers caught the ball _ it
was thrown right to him _ and returned it 8 yards for a touchdown
and a 14-10 Giants lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants never lost that lead as Dilfer was twice picked off
by free safety Percy Ellsworth in the fourth quarter. Dilfer's
backup, Eric Zeier, then came on and was intercepted by Phillippi
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a look in our eyes today that I've never seen in the
guys before,'' defensive end Michael Strahan said. ``This team is
our nemesis and for us to score first, take the ball away from them
and hold on was a huge first step for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a game of field position. As the Giants took the
lead and realized they could not move the ball against Tampa Bay's
strong defense, the punting of Brad Maynard became pivotal. He
punted 12 times, averaging 43.8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Maynard punted so often because the Giants were going nowhere
offensively. Except when taking over after a Tampa Bay turnover,
the Giants never crossed midfielde. They had just 107 yards
offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called new-look Giants offense averaged just 2.2 yards
per passing play and 1.1 yards on 24 rushing attempts. Graham
finished with 91 passing yards while completing 12 of 23 yards. The
rookie Sean Bennett was the leading Giants rusher with 24 yards on
13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all the Giants' defensive dominance, the Buccaneers
were still in the game in the final two minutes. That's when the
Giants caught a break from the officiating crew. A 28-yard pass
from Zeier to Karl Williams was nullified by the game officials
after watching replays of the play.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the officials ruled that Williams had caught the
ball after it passed through the hands of safety Shaun Williams,
but after consulting replays decided the ball hit the ground before
Williams pulled it in.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast television replays seemed to show Williams catching
the ball. An incompletion certainly did not appear conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later, Sparks intercepted a Zeier pass that was
deflected, assuring the Giants' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the first of two Ellsworth interceptions set up a
36-yard field goal by Brad Daluiso that proved to be the winning
score. Ellsworth took advantage twice of Dilfer's wild scrambling
and ill-advised decisions to hoist passes downfield into ample
Giants coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants made a number of mistakes, including nine penalties.
They committed three penalties on punt plays, and the last one
helped cost them the lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes of the first half, Maynard pinned the
Buccaneers at their 15-yard line with a 53-yard punt. But the
Giants' Corey Widmer was called for holding, necessitating a
rekick. This time, kicking out of his end zone, Maynard's punt
carried just 37 yards and Tampa Bay took over at its 46-yard line _
a field position gain of 31 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 90 seconds later, Tampa Bay had a 10-7 lead, scoring
on Dilfer's 1-yard pass to Dave Moore.
</P>
<P>
   It was without question the low point in the game for the
Giants, but the defense had other comebacks planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a sense we wouldn't be denied,'' Strahan said. ``We
knew we had to do ourselves if we had to. But that's OK Today was
an unusual game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
