<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-GIANTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss stops Maddux's streak at 8
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Braves got a double whammy on Sunday
afternooon as they bid good riddance to 3Com Park, losing Greg
Maddux's eight-game winning streak and falling 8-4 to the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves lost four of six games here this season, the last one
before the Giants move to Pacific Bell Ballpark and finished 4-5
against the Giants overall this year, their first season series
loss to the Giants since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate this place,'' said Brian Jordan, who didn't get too
many arguments from his teammates. ``Playing here, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's first loss to the Giants since 1996 was decided when he
surrendered six consecutive singles in a four-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just started to get his change-up up,'' manager Bobby Cox
said. ``I don't know if it was the wind. He got it in the same spot
every pitch, right there belt high.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since his spring struggles had Maddux given up hits with
less of a fight. Barry Bonds started it with a rip to right center
and eighth hitter Doug Mirabelli finished it with a two-run single
up the middle for a 6-1 Giants lead.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones gunned down Bonds at second base with a great throw
from right center and that would be the only out the Braves would
see until pitcher Joe Nathan laid down a sacrifice six batters
later. Maddux got out of the inning only after Ramon Martinez, the
ninth batter in the inning, sent Jordan to the warning track in the
right field corner.
</P>
<P>
   The six runs were the most Maddux allowed since the Cardinals
scored eight on him May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when I leave (my change-up) up, I can feel it when I
throw it,'' said Maddux, now 18-7. ``It just wasn't sinking. I felt
like I was throwing it pretty good, but it just, I don't know. It
was more me than the conditions. I'll see if I can't fix it by the
next time out. I didn't really make pitches when I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, 19-11 against the Giants in his career but only 8-8 at
3Com Park, wasn't blaming the windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be 99 percent my fault and 1 percent I can blame on
the conditions,'' Maddux said. ``I should be able to make the
adjustment. It's not like it's the first time I've pitched here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tried to rally for him, scoring three runs in the
sixth inning on a two-run Bret Boone homer and Chipper Jones' 40th
home run of the season. But the offense went flat after that and
the bullpen made it worse by serving up home runs to Rich Aurilia
and Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
