<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-BISHOP-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMORESE BISHOP IS CALLING FOR WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TIMOR-RDP, TIMOR-REFUGEES) 
(lb) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bishop Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo of East Timor,
who fled his homeland last week after anti-independence forces
riddled his house with bullets and then burned it down, called on
Sunday for the creation of a war crimes tribunal to bring charges
of genocide against Indonesian military commanders and militia
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Belo, the Roman Catholic religious leader of most of the 800,000
people of East Timor and the co-winner of the 1996 Nobel Peace
Prize, also said in an interview that he feared that the
military-backed militias would begin a new wave of massacres unless
international peacekeepers are deployed to East Timor this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is necessary to put peacekeepers there immediately _ within
24, 48 hours _ to defend the people and to protect the refugees who
are still in the forest,'' he said, speaking by phone from Lisbon,
Portugal, where he was invited by his religious order. ``It is
necessary to save the people of East Timor.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a scheduled audience with Pope John Paul II at the
pope's Italian summer residence at Castel Gandolfo, the bishop said
he had heard reports from East Timor that the death toll was now
measured in the thousands _ ``I was told more than 10,000'' _ and
that the killings continued Sunday in both East Timor and West
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of East Timorese have fled or been forced to
go to the western half of the island, which is also a province of
Indonesia. ``The militias are still going around, and they are
killing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to see the creation of a war crimes tribunal
for East Timor, like those created by the United Nations to deal
with human rights abuses in the Balkans and Rwanda, to prosecute
crimes against humanity carried out by Indonesian military
commanders and the militias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, some actions must be taken,'' he said. ``There must be an
international court to judge these actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Belo said he was convinced that Indonesian soldiers in civilian
clothes had tried to kill or harm him by firing into his home last
week, and that Indonesia's military commander, Gen. Wiranto, had
been directing the violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He planned this _ he blessed this,'' the bishop said. ``The
military, absolutely, they are responsible for the violence. I
think this is a kind of revenge for the military because they
failed to keep East Timor as a province. They saw that East Timor
was now free, and they wanted revenge.'' In a referendum last
month, East Timorese voted overwhelmingly for independence from
Indonesia, though the action still needs official ratification by
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now Timor is almost completely destroyed,'' the bishop
said, adding in reference to the capital, ``Dili is a ghost city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that four or five priests have already been killed,''
he said, adding that Roman Catholic priests and nuns were being
selected as targets because ``they have been the moral strength for
the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Religious differences are considered one element of the turmoil
in East Timor. Most East Timorese are Roman Catholics, while the
vast majority of Indonesians are Muslim; Indonesia is the world's
largest Muslim nation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Belo said of Wiranto, ``He's responsible, and he should be
dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not harsh in his assessment, however, of President B.J.
Habibie, who appeared to have been muscled aside by the military
during the crisis in East Timor but who made the announcement
Sunday inviting the United Nations to send peacekeeping troops to
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the man who agreed to an international election to
decide independence for East Timor, so we hope that he will
continue as president,'' the bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Belo fled East Timor last Tuesday, traveling first by an
Australian military plane to the northern Australian city of
Darwin, and then on to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The day before leaving his homeland, the bishop was trapped in
his house in Dili as armed men began firing on the compound. ``When
they attacked my house, the bullets were flying over my head,'' he
said. ``I know that they were military.'' Asked how he could be so
sure they were soldiers, he replied: ``I saw them. I know they were
military.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was too early to establish a time line for East
Timorese independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force is needed ``to give tranquillity to the
population, and then little by little, our leaders can decide how
to bring East Timor to independence,'' he said. ``There should be a
period of transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is scheduled to spend several days in Italy and then
return to Portugal, the bishop said he was ready to return to East
Timor this week if the peacekeeping force is in place. ``Yes, if
the peacekeeping force is already there, I will go,'' he said.
``Today, tomorrow, the day after tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
