<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-FINAL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agassi grand in final
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andre Agassi affirmed his new No. 1 ranking Sunday
with a 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-2 victory over the best of
Todd Martin in a 3-hour, 23-minute classic of a men's final at the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   It was Agassi's fifth major title, his second this year, and his
first at the U.S. Open since 1994, the year he finished his first
great comeback by winning as an unseeded player against Michael
Stich.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win two Slams, which is something nobody else did this
year, makes me feel like I've accomplished the most,'' said Agassi,
who overtook Pete Sampras at the top of the ATP Tour rankings
today.
</P>
<P>
   At 29, this Agassi may be older, but he's fitter and simply
better. Against one of the game's top service returners who was
playing the match of his life, Agassi didn't surrender a single
service break, holding all 25 times while saving eight break
points. Agassi was broken only six times in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the seventh seed, was in his first major final since
Sampras beat him at the 1994 Australian Open, and he played well
enough to have won his first.
</P>
<P>
   The opening set was decided essentially by a single point.
Leading the first game 30-love, Martin had the open court on a
short ball and drove a backhand into the corner, but Agassi guessed
right and intercepted it, guiding it into the open court for a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi then got the only break of the set with three sraight
backhand winners, one a return, another a passing shot.
</P>
<P>
   The second set went to a tiebreaker without a service break, and
Martin took control of it serving at 3-4. He hit consecutive
first-volley winners, one off each side, then got a mini-break on
Agassi with an inside-out forehand winner crosscourt. After Agassi
pulled to within 5-6 with a service winner, Martin won the set by
forcing a volley that Agassi couldn't handle from his backhand
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Martin won the third-set tiebreaker with ease. Agassi opened it
with a double-fault, and Martin got two other mini-breaks with
strong up-the-line returns that Agassi found difficult to match.
Martin was serving flawlessly as he knocked off two first volleys
for winners and had a service winner.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Agassi got the first service break since the
match's opening game when at deuce Martin double-faulted, then
floated a first volley long. Martin had led 40-15.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to unravel for Martin at 0-1 in the fifth as Agassi
hit a backhand return winner and Martin followed with a
double-fault and a long backhand for love-40. Agassi then ripped
Martin's wide first serve down the line for a backhand winner to
lead 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, sprinting to the chair during changeovers while the
fatigued Martin waddled back, then held at love, giving him nine
straight points won and a 3-0 lead. At that point, the match was
essentially over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly couldn't call this disappointing; I lost to a
better player,'' Martin said. ``He beat me when I played a very
good match.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi is the first American to win the French and U.S. titles
in the same year since Tony Trabert in 1955. The only great
achievement he's never attained is the year-end No. 1 rankings, and
now he's leading coming down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest times of my life, and I'll never forget
New York right here,'' said Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
