r l BC-CYBERTIMES-MIGRANTS-S     09-12 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-MIGRANTS-STUDY-ON-INTERNET-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN OF MIGRANT WORKERS KEEP UP STUDIES ON THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PAMELA MENDELS  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
<P>
   GOSHEN, N.Y. -- While other teen-agers were enjoying the
dwindling vacation days of late summer, Mario Rangel was sitting in
front of a laptop computer, trying to memorize the capitals of
Europe for an on-line geography class.
</P>
<P>
   Mario's father is a migrant farm worker, one of many who travel
each year from southern Texas to Orange County, N.Y., areas rich in
black-dirt fields of onions, lettuce and other crops. For youths
like Mario and his siblings, the stay up north, about an hour and a
half from Manhattan, is an exciting time to renew summer
friendships cultivated over the years.
</P>
<P>
   But the migrant life can take a heavy toll on their educations.
</P>
<P>
   Students like Mario almost inevitably lose time in the classroom
when they shuttle between states with different school calendars.
Those who leave Texas for New York in late May, for example, may
find it little use to sign up for the last few days or weeks of New
York's school year, especially since much of that time is given
over to test taking.
</P>
<P>
   And since curriculums and course schedules also vary widely
among states, migrant children who take classes out of state
frequently find themselves several steps behind their classmates
when they return home in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Mario, who dreams of becoming an electrical
engineer, is participating in a program that gives the teen-age
children of migrant farm workers laptop computers to use in taking
classes on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can get the class over with on line, I can do something
else in school instead of feeling like I have to catch up,'' said
Mario, who is studying world geography.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old project, known as Estrella (``star'' in
Spanish), is paid for with a $400,000 grant from the United States
Department of Education. It seeks to use technology to alleviate a
pressing problem among a group of high school students whose
dropout rate is about 50 percent: lack of continuity in schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to get kids graduated,'' said Robert E. Lynch,
coordinator of the program in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, the program seeks to give children
from poor homes a familiarity with computers that middle-class
children with personal computers in their bedrooms take for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 50 teen-agers from Texas who migrate to New York,
Illinois and Montana are taking part. They and their families are
given lessons in how to use the equipment before they leave Texas.
They also sign a contract pledging to devote at least seven hours a
week to their classes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the teen-agers in Montana and Illinois, and a smaller
number in New York, work in the fields during the day and carve out
time at night to do their studies, usually in school buildings with
the phone lines necessary for computer modems.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, meanwhile, many of the students do their lessons
from their homes -- often crowded, ramshackle housing that the
program equips with telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obstacles, most of the 35 students who participated
in the program's first year completed the classes, which are
offered in subjects ranging from algebra to world history,
according to Brenda R. Pessin, who oversees Estrella as part of her
job as director of migrant education services for the nonprofit
Illinois Migrant Council.
</P>
<P>
   For three failing middle-school students, she added, taking and
passing the on-line course meant they could advance to the next
grade when they returned to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If Mario, 15, successfully completes the course and its
follow-up tests, he receives credit at his school in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The courses are offered through NovaNET, an on-line education
company that sells its services to school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Students are given bite-size chunks of lessons, sometimes
accompanied by video clips, charts and other multimedia graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons include drills, quizzes and instructional games. Mario's
geography course, for example, included a crossword puzzle about
rivers of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Each unit of study generally ends in an on-line test that must
be passed before the student can go to the next unit.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella students decide what courses to take after consulting
with guidance counselors at their schools in Texas and, in some
cases, New York.
</P>
<P>
   While they are logged on, students are generally on their own --
there are usually no teachers to join them on line to answer
questions or discuss their work. But there is some oversight. From
her computer, Nancy Fernandez, a staff worker in a migrant
education outreach program for the mid-Hudson area, can determine
how much time students have devoted to their studies.
</P>
<P>
   She also meets in person with each student each week to chat,
discuss problems and act as a gentle prod if any of them begin to
slow down in their school work.
</P>
<P>
   Students can also turn to the project's Texas-based Web master,
who manages the project's technical aspects, for technical help.
</P>
<P>
   The service does not come cheaply. At close to $8,000 per
student, the program causes some educators to wonder whether the
money would not be better used to match students with
flesh-and-blood teachers. ``Maybe it's the best we can do, but I
think it's sad that we don't see the need for getting teachers more
closely involved with these kids,'' said Lowell W. Monke, an
assistant professor of education at Grinnell College and the
co-author of a book, to be published next year, that examines
classroom Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas M. Sloan, a professor at Columbia University's Teachers
College, said the program risked being a Band-Aid for a serious
social ill. ``It promises to solve a problem without addressing the
real nature of the problem involved -- an exploitative labor
system,'' Professor Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Estrella's organizers respond that the program exists to give
the participants a means to escape migrant life. ``We are providing
the migrant youth with education and skills so they can make a
choice,'' Mr. Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers also say it would not be possible to hire all the
specialty teachers needed for the many subject areas taught in high
school. And, they say, they try to build human contact into the
program.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a ``cyber-mentor'' E-mail correspondence program
pairs the teen-agers with college students.
</P>
<P>
   To Gary Chapman, a social policy researcher at the University of
Texas who has criticized some computer-based education as little
more than technological glitz, Estrella makes sense. ``This is one
example where you get the thing that technology is good for --
shifting time and space -- where it might actually help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some students find that on-line instruction is not enough. Mr.
Lynch and Ms. Fernandez are considering finding a tutor to help one
Estrella student who did well with an on-line English course last
year but is struggling this summer with algebra.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mario, a lean, soft-spoken young man with a trace
of a mustache, says the project has its ups and downs. ``If you
don't understand something, you can't ask teacher,'' he noted. But
he added that he liked working at his own pace, adding, ``You can
concentrate more and take your time, as much as you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Related Sites
</P>
<P>
   Project Estrella: http://www.estrella.org
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Education's Office of Migrant Education:
http://www.ed.gov/offices/OESE/MEP/
</P>
<P>
   Grinnell College: http://www.grinnell.edu
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University's Teachers College:
http://www.tc.columbia.edu
</P>
<P>
   Chapman is director of the 21st Century Project at the
University of Texas: http://www.utexas.edu/lbj/21cp/
</P>
<P>
   NovaNET: http://www.novanet.com
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Mendels at mendels(AT)nytimes.com welcomes your comments
and suggestions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-HABIBIE-BOS &LR;      09-12 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-HABIBIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABIBIE BOWS, WILL ALLOW FOREIGN TROOPS IN EAST TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Declaring that ``too many people have lost
their lives,'' President B.J. Habibie ceded to mounting outside
pressure and threats of diplomatic sanctions Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, and
consented to the deployment of UN-sanctioned troops in the
violence-wracked territory of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The international community welcomed the about-face, with
Australia volunteering to deploy forces within days and the United
States offering support troops. But Indonesian officials put
conditions on the deployment that could delay the arrival of a
force for weeks, and that could leave the door open for further
killings, destruction and a humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters Monday morning in New Zealand, President
Clinton said, ``The most important thing is for President Habibie
to make good on this statement, get the details worked out and get
the force in in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Major General Sudrajat, an
Indonesian armed forces spokesman, said that Indonesia was ``not in
a rush'' to receive troops, and that it expected UN approval and
deployment to take at least two weeks. He underscored that Jakarta,
which faces nationalist sentiment against foreign troops, ``has the
prerogative to select which one will coordinate . . . and which
countries we would like to join a peacekeeping force.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in contrast, said Indonesia should have no say over the
composition of a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps'' the Indonesian military ``should have some parallel
presence even, but they should not be able to say who is in or not
in the force and what the structure . . . will be, otherwise it
will raise all kinds of questions about whether there will be
integrity in the force and it will also delay the implementation,''
Clinton said in Auckland, where he is attending the annual
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, or APEC, summit. The East Timor
crisis has dominated the agenda at APEC.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds, if not thousands, of East Timorese civilians,
including some nuns and priests, have been slaughtered by
pro-Indonesia forces in the week since the announcement of a
landslide vote for independence in the disputed territory.
Indonesia declared martial law in East Timor on Sept. 7, but the
soldiers who are supposed to enforce peace are accused of
participating in the rampages.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the White House cut off arms sales and military
aid, and over the weekend threatened economic and commercial
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In a live televised address Sunday night after a three-hour
Cabinet meeting, Habibie told his nation that outside forces were
needed because ``too many people have lost their lives . . . lost
their homes and security. We cannot wait any longer. We have to
stop the suffering and mourning immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the UN secretary general to inform him about our
readiness to accept international peacekeeping forces through the
UN from friendly nations to restore peace and security in East
Timor,'' Habibie said in the presidential palace, as his Cabinet
and generals stood by.
</P>
<P>
   Australia has offered to deploy 4,500 troops and lead forces
from ``willing nations'' until a UN force is ready to deploy this
year. Clinton said Australia would carry the ``lion's share'' of
the peacekeeping burden, while the United States would, with the
approval of Congress, provide logistical support such as transport,
communications and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   US troops are already involved in operations in Kosovo, Bosnia,
Haiti and the Sinai Desert.
</P>
<P>
   But Sudrajat said that it would be ``very difficult'' to accept
Australian forces, because of their ``political meddling. They
intervene in our policy too much. Asian forces might be more
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore and Cambodia have
offered to contribute to an international force, as have Britain,
Portugal and others.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, the one nation ready to lead a force, is just 400
miles south of East Timor and home to a significant East Timorese
exile community. Sudrajat said flag-burnings and protests at the
Indonesian Embassy and threats against Indonesian students in
Australia have tainted opinion against Sydney, and would make it
impossible to guarantee safety of Australians if militias in East
Timor ``get angry with them.''
</P>
<P>
   An American UN civilian police officer who was shot in East
Timor last week said he had been targeted because militias and
soldiers thought he was Australian.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta invaded East Timor, a former Portuguese colony on the
southeastern end of the Indonesian island chain, in 1975, sparking
a guerrilla war and military crackdown that claimed 200,000 lives
from fighting, starvation and disease by 1980. The international
community, ironically with the exception of Australia, has never
recognized Indonesian rule there.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Habibie offered the province independence if it
rejected a plan for autonomy under continued Indonesian rule.
Nearly 79 percent of voters opted for separation on Aug. 30,
provoking a savage campaign of revenge by pro-Indonesia militiamen
aided and armed by elements of the military.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, 50 UN ambassadors condemned Indonesia for allowing
the violence in East Timor and for refusing outside help.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie treaded a fine line Sunday night to ease pressure to
accept foreign troops and nationalist sentiment against them. The
Indonesian and English texts of his address were different, with
the Indonesian ``inviting international peacekeeping forces to
assist us in restoring order with the Indonesian military in a
cooperative manner.'' The English version expressed ``readiness to
accept international peacekeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign troops have not been allowed into Indonesia since it won
independence from the Dutch over 50 years ago, and Habibie, who
hopes to be renamed president by his National Assembly this fall,
is aware that inviting outside forces will be unpopular at home.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said he appreciated that
Habibie's announcement ``was a very difficult decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats in Jakarta called Habibie's announcement a slap in the
face for the Indonesian military, an admission that they were
unable to control rampaging civilian militias or their own rogue
forces who aided them.
</P>
<P>
   Sudrajat denied that it was ``an offense'' to the military,
insisting, ``We have carried out our duty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we were unable to control the situation, but we
have to wait for the right time. If we wanted to stop it within two
days, we'd have to kill the people'' suspected of mob violence, he
said. ``We cannot just open machine guns against them. . . . These
people have become family.''
</P>
<P>
   After 24 years of arming and allying with pro-Indonesia civilian
militias against separatist guerrillas, troops in East Timor have
``to change our paradigm, and acknowledge'' the separatist
guerrillas ``who used to be our enemy as our friend. . . . It's
very difficult to keep neutral,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said members of two batallions of East Timorese soldiers
aided friends in militias or guerrillas in the last week. He said
the approximately 900 East Timorese soldiers were transferred to
West Timor to ``keep them neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat in Jakarta said Sunday that he was ``fairly
skeptical'' of Habibie's offer. ``His announcement was clear this
would be in cooperation with the Indonesian armed forces, and not a
replacement for them. . . . They are going to want to save face and
not to take a back seat to forces coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   The 15-nation UN Security Council must approve any UN force, and
can do so only after a five-ambassador delegation that visited
Jakarta and Dili last week returns to New York. Indonesian Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas departs for New York Monday to negotiate the
details of a force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
