<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-CYBERTIMES-MESSY-ONLI     09-12 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-MESSY-ONLINE-RETURNS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SALES CAN BE MESSY, ESPECIALLY THOSE PESKY RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BOB TEDESCHI &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
<P>
   Life was much easier for E-commerce companies when their primary
focus was on acquiring customers. They could simply take the
company public, spend huge sums on advertising then wait for the
customers to show up.
</P>
<P>
   Things became messy when shoppers actually arrived. Suddenly,
E-commerce executives realized that managing online sales could be
as difficult as managing offline merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   Merchandise returns, in particular, have been nettlesome for
Internet stores, especially those without previous experience in
catalog or traditional retailing. Analysts and executives say
E-commerce sites have not done enough to give customers the same
confidence in their return policies as offline merchants do and
have been slow to devise effective systems for refunds and
exchanges. In short, they say, if Internet retailers want to
attract more return customers, they are going to have to deal
better with returns by customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handling returns is a complicated process that can't be
standardized the same way as outbound shipments,'' said James
Vogtle, an E-commerce research director with Boston Consulting
Group. ``And it's a process that's not getting the attention it
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   For every $100 in goods an E-commerce company ships, $5 worth is
returned, according to a recent study by Boston Consulting in
conjunction with Shop.org, an Internet retailing trade group. That
5 percent rate compares favorably with that of direct marketing
companies, which have return rates of 5 percent to 7 percent, as
well as traditional retailers, whose returns total 6 percent of
sales, according to the National Retail Federation. But the
comparison is also somewhat misleading because a large percentage
of Internet commerce is made up of items like books and CDs, which
have low return rates.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is not the number of returns, but how those
returns are being handled. Analysts and executives say customers
are often subjected to poor customer service when trying to make
returns, resulting in delayed exchanges or mishandled refunds.
Because most sites require customers to pay for shipping items back
to the retailer, the process can be costly, as well.
</P>
<P>
   These problems are reflected in two surveys conducted among more
than 2,000 Internet users by Jupiter Communications, an Internet
research firm. In one survey in which Internet shoppers ranked
their top 12 sources of dissatisfaction with E-commerce sites the
fifth-greatest concern was returning merchandise. In the other
study, also conducted by Jupiter, 40 percent of those surveyed
indicated they would buy more on line if they could return items
easily.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have retailers been frequently caught off guard by the
volume of orders received, but, says Ken Cassar, a Jupiter analyst,
E-commerce sites often cede control of fulfilling orders -- as well
as handling returns -- to outside companies. ``When things do go
wrong, a vast majority of the time it's because there's a gap in
the seams between various parties,'' Cassar said. ``The fewer times
the baton is passed, the greater the chances are for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Morris, executive vice president of Bluefly, an online
retailer of clothing and housewares, says the company sees a return
rate for clothing ``in the low 20 percent range'' -- nearly 10
points below the catalog rate for apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly, which uses a third-party to handle orders and returns,
manages the return process in several steps. After a customer calls
and indicates a problem, the item is shipped back at the company's
expense, using a United Parcel Service packing slip included with
each item delivered. The item is inspected when it arrives, and the
customer's account is credited ``within a week of them sending
it,'' Morris said. The fulfillment center repackages and restocks
items that are in perfect condition; imperfect items are either
repaired or discarded.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that no orders are mishandled, Bluefly ``is all over
the fulfillment house,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We manage them really closely,'' he said, ``and treat them
like they're virtual employees.'' Of returns in general, he added,
``This is definitely the less-sexy side of the business, but it's
as important -- if not more important -- than any other aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Brooks, chief executive of Furniture.com, an
Internet-only retailer, said that because the cost of returned
furniture -- and dissatisfied customers -- was so high, the company
designed its Web site to insure that customers made the right
choice. ``The best way is to make the customer as educated as
possible about what they're getting,'' Brooks said, adding that
Furniture.com's return rate is materially lower than that of
catalog companies, though he would not disclose a specific rate.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com's Web site enables customers to view photos of an
item from a number of angles, use a room-design option to see how
it would fit with their current furniture and e-mail or speak to
design consultants and have fabric swatches sent to them free. Once
the furniture is shipped, customers can hold the furniture for a
week before returning it -- at no cost. The only catch: customers
get a store credit, not a cash reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing companies like Lands' End and Levi Strauss are also
improving their sites with modeling technology that allows
customers to indicate their physical dimensions and receive
guidance on what size to order.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to accepting returns, perhaps the best option
is one that remains unreachable for companies that operate only on
line -- namely, physical stores. The Gap and Federated's Macy's,
for instance, accept returns of merchandise at their stores even
when items are purchased on line -- a policy that is not shared by
many Internet retailers who have physical outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Kapp, vice president for special markets and new media at
Estee Lauder, which includes the Clinique Web site, agreed there
was a benefit in allowing customers to return items to a physical
store. She said Estee Lauder customers could do so as long as the
department store in which the company's products were sold allowed
it.
</P>
<P>
   But that option has limits, Ms. Kapp said. ``What if you live 20
miles away, or you don't feel like going to the mall?'' she asked.
``Isn't that the reason why they got on line in the first place?''
</P>
<P>
   Related Sites
</P>
<P>
   Boston Consulting Group/Shop.org study on returns:
http://www.bcg.com/features/shop/fs_shop.html
</P>
<P>
   Shop.org: http://www.shop.org
</P>
<P>
   National Retail Federation: http://www.nrf.com
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications: http://www.jup.com
</P>
<P>
   Bluefly: http://www.bluefly.com
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com: http://www.furniture.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Tedeschi at tedeschi(AT)nytimes.com welcomes your comments
and suggestions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
