</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCON-ANALYSIS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons left `warming up' while Vikings take win
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Vikings won against the Falcons on Sunday because
they dominated the middle of the field, got three turnovers to
none, and the worst penalties of the game went against Atlanta at
terrible times.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings turned the tables and played Falcons-style football,
winning the time of possession battle by more than six minutes
against a team that last year led the league in that category.
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first quarter, wide receiver Ronnie Harris
fumbled after a 20-yard gain early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Buchanan was penalized 52 yards for pass interference while
defending Randy Moss, and beaten a couple plays later on a hard
inside slant by Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I battled (a sprained left) the knee,'' Buchanan said.
``Sometimes, that's the way the game goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dwight fumbled the kickoff, hurling himself into a left
wedge after taking a kickoff four yards deep on the right side of
the end zone. Minnesota punter/kicker Mitch Berger recovered at the
Atlanta 21. Soon a Gary Anderson 36-yard field goal made it 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't make those kind of mistakes (last year),'' coach
Dan Reeves said. ``Those things are correctable, but we have to
keep working. (The mistakes) are the same things that we did in the
preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Morten Anderson missed a 35-yarder to start Minnesota's final
scoring drive, and a 24-yard pass interference penalty against
Atlanta strong safety Marty Carter helped too. Leroy Hoard's 1-yard
run with 1:48 left in the first half made it 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta raced downfield after that, and drew to within 17-7 on a
23-yard pass from Chandler to wide receiver Chris Calloway with 43
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway beat second-year Vikings cornerback Ramos McDonald with
an inside move on a post route.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, the Falcons didn't challenge McDonald much,
especially deep, even though Minnesota's safeties were guarding the
middle of the field more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta had hoped to get Dwight in space, but he strained a
hamstring in pre-game warm-ups and barely played on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were re-routing us (bumping Falcon wide receivers),''
Reeves said. ``We always seemed to be going sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the Falcons never got a running game going, rushing
for 81 yards on 23 carries (21 yards coming on Chandler scrambles).
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Bob Christian scored on a 1-yard dive over guard in the
fourth quarter, but Falcon running backs were stuffed up the middle
most of the day. Leading rusher Jamal Anderson had just 50 yards on
16 attempts, a 3.1-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings did it with multiple run-blitzes, and by often
playing outside linebackers a half-yard closer than usual to the
middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Minnesota challenged Atlanta to run wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons couldn't, and their game plan never caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get behind, you can't do certain things with your
running game,'' said right guard Gene Williams. ``We got going, but
it took us too long to get warmed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian's 1-yard run came with 13:18 left, but the Falcons had
a hard time getting the ball back, as the Vikings held the ball
33:14 to Atlanta's 26:46.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to believe the Vikings when they said they were
going to be more methodical offensively, but they were Sunday.
Quarterback Randall Cunningham didn't throw for big yardage (184
yards), but he completed 22-of-33 passes, and Minnesota converted
9-of-17 third downs into first downs.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves complained afterward about the lack of a pass rush.
Atlanta didn't sack Cunningham, even though Minnesota had horrible
problems in the preseason protecting the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons defensive tackle Shane Dronett said that the Vikings'
plan to have wide receivers, tight ends and running backs stay in
to block, sometimes coming in motion to do so, worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were pulling a lot of people back inside,'' he said. ``A
lot of times, they were running one- and two-man routes. They've
got the people to play pitch-and-catch with that kind of routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's chance to tie with 3:38 was wide left, as Andersen
tried to compensate for his earlier hook by aiming outside. The
ball stayed outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I hit it pretty good,'' said Andersen, who made 23
of 28 field goals last year. ``I certainly don't know, from a
technical standpoint, what I did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
