<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9480 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS13     09-12 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler injured as Falcons' comeback falls short
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spotted through binoculars, the sight of Dan Reeves on
Sunday evening might have been alarming. The Falcons coach had
every right to be steamed.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was Morten Andersen's 39-yard field goal try sailing
wide left with 3:38 left in the game that triggered his barking, a
laundry list of foibles made Reeves a time bomb waiting to go off.
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough that his team lost 17-14 to the Vikings while making
virtually all the mistakes it had avoided on the way to the Super
Bowl last season. Add the status of quarterback Chris Chandler,
whose right hamstring could keep him out of the next game, a Monday
night affair at Dallas, and it was the worst day at the office
since Nov. 9, 1997, when Tampa Bay prevailed 31-10 in the Georgia
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts any time you lose, but particularly the way we
lost,'' said Reeves, after seeing the end of streaks of 11
regular-season victories and 11 in a row at home. ``I don't know
how bad Chris's hamstring is, but he couldn't have come back in if
we got the ball back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons did get the ball back after Andersen's miss, but
only for the final play. A 32-yard screen play from Tony Graziani
to Jamal Anderson left a sellout crowd of 69,555 groaning.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Falcons led the NFL in turnover ratio. Sunday,
they had three fumbles and forced no Minnesota turnovers. Atlanta
helped the Vikings to at least 10 of their points after first-half
fumbles by Chandler and kick returner Tim Dwight left Minnesota 58
and 21 yards from the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties gave the Vikings 55 of the 58 yards on the first
score, including a questionable 52-yard interference call against
cornerback Ray Buchanan, who was defending Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they called me on that one,'' Buchanan
said. ``Here I am 5-10, and Moss is 6-10 (actually 6-4), and they
say they're not going to call that (incidental contact) this year,
and they call it on the poodle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings led 17-0 at the half. Atlanta tried to recover, but
unlike the 1998 NFC Championship Game, the Falcons' Andersen missed
after the Vikings' Gary Anderson left the door open with a late
miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never brought a cape,'' said Andersen, who also missed a
35-yarder in the first half. ``I'm not Superman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
