<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-2TAKES-NYT     09-12 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S AGASSI IN (WHAT ELSE?) A COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By   ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man has shed so many skins and cycled through so
many lifetimes he seems to have a feline gene lurking somewhere,
but for 29-year-old Andre Agassi, who won the U.S. Open the hard
way Sunday, with a foray into five-set territory, the ninth and
last tennis life is his best life. He guarantees it.
</P>
<P>
   Reincarnated again, this time with a body chiseled, whittled and
polished to resemble granite and a frill-free game plan that
resembles no one else's, the balding, bold Agassi captured his
second Grand Slam title of the year, and installed himself as the
No. 1 player in the world, with a 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-7 (2-7), 6-3,
6-2 demolition of another 29-year-old American in the midst of a
career renaissance, seventh-seeded Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you ask for anything more than two Americans in the
finals of the U.S. Open?'' said Agassi, for whom this tournament
has always been his favorite Grand Slam event. ``Win or lose, it
was a privilege to be out here; this is the greatest time in my
life,'' said Agassi, who reached three consecutive Grand Slam
finals this year and made history at the French Open when he became
only the fifth player to collect all four Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's match, his ninth career Grand Slam final and his fourth
at the Open, which he won in 1994, featured few bells and whistles
from Agassi. The trick shots, the histrionics, the celebrity
entourage are gone with the frosted hair and acid-washed denim. The
attitude was businesslike. According to him, it had to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played so well I felt like I was hanging on by a thread for
most of the match; he gave me a lot to worry about,'' said Agassi,
who hung on and around so successfully that he never lost a service
game and committed just 23 unforced errors, 37 fewer than Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember any five-setter I ever played where I didn't
lose my serve,'' Agassi said after checking the statistics and
confirming that he had fended off all eight break points held by
Martin, like Agassi considered one of the most dangerous return
artists in the men's game.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-hour-23-minute friendly confrontation, the fifth
all-American final in Open history, began in the sun-dappled and
finally humidity-free Arthur Ashe Stadium beneath a humane blue sky
and concluded under the spotlights. A pair of Americans last
reached the final in 1996, when Pete Sampras thwarted Michael Chang
for the title.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as Agassi's semifinal victim, second-ranked Yevgeny
Kafelnikov remarked with equal parts respect and resignation, is
Agassi's year. ``Without a doubt, 1999, this year belongs to him,''
Kafelnikov said.
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi had to earn it. Two years ago, overweight and
under-achieving, Agassi sent himself back to the minor leagues of
tennis, the challenger circuit, to school himself on how to win
again after his ranking nose-dived to 141st. Last year he
re-established his work ethic, but despite finishing the year
ranked sixth, his Grand Slam results were desultory.
</P>
<P>
   Correcting that was his goal for 1999, and he achieved it by
mounting a comeback from a two-sets-to-none deficit to capture his
crown at Roland Garros, pushing Pete Sampras to heroic heights in
their Wimbledon final, and achieving his ultimate goal, this title
and the top ranking that came with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Open is what I want,'' he declared before taking his
9-5 record against Martin into the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Agassi pranced right out and snatched an instant service break
in the opening game, where a backhand return put Martin in trouble
at 30-40 and a crosscourt backhand pass eluded Martin completely.
Agassi then sneaked away from a 0-40 deficit in the fourth game,
and, apparently in control from the backcourt, claimed the set when
Martin elbowed a backhand return into the net. But Agassi's
momentum was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who wound up wearing a hospital gown as he received
intravenous treatment after his torturous fourth-round comeback
against Greg Rusedski but made a flawless transition back to tennis
whites for the next two rounds, was not about to let anything as
mundane as one lost set deter him.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two hours, and throughout two tiebreakers that
improved Martin's 1999 tiebreaker record to 25-13, Agassi could not
pry another service break away from Martin, who compensated for his
less-than-fleet lateral footwork by rushing the net and keeping the
points compact and vertical.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set's tiebreaker, Martin's first serve and
dagger-like volleys turned a 3-4 deficit to a 5-4 lead. He reached
set point with a crosscourt forehand bullet and converted his
second set point with a serve-and-volley charge that hurried Agassi
into a backhand error.
</P>
<P>
   Martin nearly skinned his nose on the net as he ducked to avoid
a decapitating overhead from Agassi to trail 0-15 in the eighth
game of the third set, then double-faulted to trail 0-30, but
Agassi again failed to use his momentum to do any lasting damage.
</P>
<P>
   They trundled into another tiebreaker, but this one was owned by
Martin from the start, where Agassi spouted a double fault, to the
finish, where Agassi, down 6-2 but seemingly indifferent to his
proximity to a two-sets-to-one deficit, swatted a careless backhand
out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   And that was his wakeup call. In the fourth set, Agassi zeroed
in with his returns like a homing pigeon: he earned himself a set
point with a blistering forehand return that traced the sideline
like a guided missile, and he broke Martin for the set with a
net-clipping return that Martin blocked long.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's eyes were saucer-sized by the fifth set, and that's how
he was seeing the tennis ball, too. Larger than life. This time
Agassi was a little stingier about keeping the momentum on his
side. He broke Martin, who had 23 aces but exited the match with a
leaden arm, at love for a 2-0 lead, and by the time Agassi had held
himself together for a 4-1 lead, he was high-stepping toward his
changeover chair like a Lippizaner. From there, it was academic:
the kinetics were all Agassi's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more than a tad short,'' Martin said of his waning
efforts in the final set, where he crumbled in the face of
something he called Agassi's ``relentless pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can't think of a better way to go out,'' Martin said,
``than to play a great match against a great champion.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
