<SLUG> BC-EGOVERNMENT-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PAPERWORK FLIES OUT THE WINDOW AS LOCAL GOVERNMENTS GO ONLINE
 &HT;     By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco   Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Every October, some 75,000 San Francisco
business owners have to renew their city business licenses.
Traditionally, that has involved filling out a paper form and
mailing it off with a check.
</P>
<P>
   This year, if all goes well, they'll have the option of doing it
all over the Web _ including paying by credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot project, supervised by City Treasurer Susan Leal and
her staff, is an example of the latest e-trend: e-government. If it
lives up to its promise, it will eventually enable individual
citizens and businesses to deal with official forms, permits and
payments of all sorts _ from parking tickets to marriage licenses _
right from their computer screens, 24 hours a day and seven days a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it won't necessarily eliminate red tape _ it'll just
convert it to digital form. But at least you won't have to wait in
line for your chance to wrestle with government bureaucracy, or
worry about mail getting delayed, lost or misfiled. And, on the
government side, doing business electronically should someday
generate substantial savings and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Computers in government, of course, are nothing new: City, state
and federal bureaucracies have been using them internally for
decades. And when the Web emerged in the mid '90s, San Francisco
and most other municipalities were quick to set up sites any surfer
could peruse.
</P>
<P>
   But those sites consisted, for the most part, of static
information: agendas, minutes, phone lists, regulations and the
like.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, e-government refers to interactive services _
mechanisms for citizens and companies not just to obtain
information, but also to transact business with public agencies.
It's the public-sector equivalent of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for San Francisco's pilot project aren't yet firm, in part
because the city and its partner in the program, consulting giant
KPMG, haven't yet signed a contract. It's possible, officials warn,
that there won't be time to implement their plan for online
business license renewals before the November 1 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But Leal's team has a smaller-scale fallback plan: If they can't
offer license renewals, they'll at least make it possible to order
and pay for copies of birth and death certificates on the Web this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The next step would be to expand to online payment of water
bills and business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities and counties in the San Francisco Bay Area and
around California are also adding interactive services to their
sites:
</P>
<P>
   San Carlos already has an online ``Citizen Complaint Form,''
where residents can report potholes, burned-out lights, recurrent
traffic-law violations and anything else that's bothering them.
</P>
<P>
   Next month the city will add a page where contractors and
homeowners can file and pay for permits for simple construction
work, such as reroofing and water-heater installation. (Online
processing of permit filings complex enough to require blueprints
will come later.) And, by the end of the year, residents should be
able to sign up and pay online for Park and Recreation Department
courses and programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale and Mountain View also plan to offer online filing and
payment for permits in October. Their joint effort, backed by
$100,000 in consulting services donated by Microsoft and partners,
is an offshoot of Smart Permit, a project of Joint Venture: Silicon
Valley, the South Bay public-private consortium.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland plans to add software to its Web site that combines
police data with maps of the city, making it easier for citizens
groups as well as officials to track and analyze crime problems.
</P>
<P>
   The city is holding off on online permits for now, on the
grounds that its current file-by-fax system meets the need, but
like San Francisco, it's hoping to put its business-license renewal
forms on the Web later this year.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego County has allowed residents to pay property taxes
over the Web since March.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura County Superior Court this summer began installing
ATM-inspired kiosks it calls ``Automated Court Clerks'' in malls
and public facilities. Residents can use the kiosks, which have
touch screens and receipt printers, to pay their parking tickets,
among other chores.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica, which has sponsored a free, text-only electronic
network since 1989, began offering city services such as
business-license renewal, recreation-program registration and
service-request forms on the network in the early '90s, even before
the Web arose, according to Jory Wolf, the city's manager of
information systems.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens now also have the option of carrying out these and
other transactions via the Web, and the city is in the process of
rolling out its own kiosk program.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its focus on high technology, California has no
monopoly _ and perhaps not even a lead _ in the e-government area.
</P>
<P>
   While California's Department of Motor Vehicles, for example,
has only recently begun to investigate ways the Web could keep
Californians out of its legendary lines, the equivalent agencies in
several other states already have made some services available in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has provided online (and phone-in) registration renewal
since 1997, through a program developed and run by IBM. Michigan
has a similar program, using software developed by SDR Technologies
of Westlake Village, Calif., a company that got its start
developing campaign-contribution reporting software for San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the widest range of online services, including payment
for dog licenses, excise taxes and parking tickets, is available in
Boston. That city also seems to have invested more than any other
municipality in laying a heavy-duty technical foundation for future
development of additional services: Its Web site,
www.cityofboston.com, runs on a Hitachi server powered by eight
Intel Xeon microprocessors _ the most powerful type of
PC-compatible computer in existence today.
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians who don't have computers of their own will be able to
tap into services from kiosks, connected via high-speed digital
subscriber lines, that will be installed by year end, not only in
the downtown area, but also in residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who tied the knot in Las Vegas in such a rush they
forgot the paperwork, Clark County, Nev., recently began selling
copies of marriage licenses over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the e-government movement lags far behind the boom in
private e-commerce. ``The public sector in general tends to be
about 18 months behind private business in this kind of thing,''
said Payton Smith, an analyst at Federal Sources Inc., a market
research company in McLean, Va., that focuses on government
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's absolutely a trend all over the country toward
putting more services online,'' he added, ``and it's only going to
pick up speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there aren't obstacles. One is a matter of attitudes:
``Local governments are often a little conservative,'' said Terry
Bursztynsky, director of online services at the Association of Bay
Area Governments in Oakland. ``They have the citizenry looking over
their shoulders, and no one wants to be accused of wasting the
taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when public agencies decide to bring service to the Web,
they rarely operate at the fast pace known proverbially as
``Internet time.'' Joint Venture: Silicon Valley's Smart Permit
project was launched almost five years ago. And the pilot project
San Francisco expects to launch this fall is a successor to an
larger online initiative that was launched in 1997 but ``never
panned out,'' according to City Treasurer Leal.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, no doubt, is political and bureaucratic
infighting, but governments, especially at the local level, often
lack the financial and technical resources needed to build a
sophisticated e-commerce infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of EGOV13 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``These registration-and-payment applications may seem simple,
but they actually involve integrating a lot of different
components,'' said Brian Moura, assistant city manager of San
Carlos, Calif., and a longtime technology guru. ``It's been a lot
harder than we would have thought.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, though, almost everyone agrees that
e-government will be increasingly important in the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be a little ahead of the curve right now,'' said Jay
Banfield, special assistant to Leal and point man for the city's
e-government initiative, ``but our constituents are demanding and
getting this kind of service from the private sector, and they're
going to expect it from us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, adding new government services should get cheaper and
easier over time. ``The hard part is now, when we have to create
the whole infrastructure,'' Banfield said. ``As we get that done,
we start to benefit from experience and economies of scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his 20 years as Santa Monica's information-systems
manager, Wolf summed up his view of e-government: ``There's no
question, no opposition _ this is the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
