<SLUG> BC-EGOVSIDEBAR-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
THE ECONOMICS OF E-GOVERNMENT &HT;    By HENRY NORR
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco   Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Over the long haul, doing business online should
produce significant savings for government.
</P>
<P>
   But the economics of e-government still can be complex. One big
issue is how to handle credit card fees.
</P>
<P>
   Just like merchants, governments have to pay for credit card
processing services. The fees vary _ they're negotiated between
city and bank _ but typically they're several percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   That might not sound like much, but it adds up to a big problem
for delicately balanced municipal budgets. And it's one that's
likely to grow as services involving larger payments move online
and more citizens and businesses take advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with that problem, some government bodies add
``convenience fees'' for users paying fees online. But most
officials say they're reluctant to add such surcharges, for fear
that they'll deter usage of online services and breed resentment,
especially because the vast majority of private businesses absorb
credit card fees instead of passing them on to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of business on Arizona's online registration-renewal
site tripled ``overnight'' when the original $6.95 convenience fee
was eliminated last October, according to Jack Alderson of IBM's
government services group, which operates the program.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of EGOV13SI (50748 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Exactly how San Francisco will handle this problem remains to be
determined, said City Treasurer Susan Leal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long haul, the savings generated by doing business
electronically should make it easy for governments to justify
absorbing credit card fees.
</P>
<P>
   But these savings typically don't show up at the outset. In the
early stages of an e-government initiative, development costs are
high, online transaction volume is relatively low and the staff
assigned to handling in-person or snail-mail transactions can't yet
be redeployed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the private sector, governments can't exactly turn to
angel investors or venture capitalists to help them get their
programs off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   For many government entities, though, public-private
partnerships play a similar role. Microsoft and some of its
partners contributed $100,000 for a permit project in Mountain View
and Sunnyvale, Calif. IBM did all the development work for
Arizona's vehicle-registration program, and now operates it on its
own servers, in exchange for $1 per transaction and 2 percent of
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Kimball, CEO of government-software developer SDR
Technologies, called such partnerships ``the only real solution''
for e-government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new model,'' he said, ``is that we develop the necessary
software, run it on our own servers and take care of all the
maintenance and upgrade hassles, all at no charge to the agency.
Our compensation is entirely transaction-based.'' The company now
runs the Federal Election Commission's campaign-finance reporting
site on that basis.
</P>
<P>
   The details of San Francisco's arrangement with consulting firm
KPMG, its partner in planning the city's upcoming e-government
pilot project, aren't yet available, but it's clear that the
company will play a central role.
</P>
<P>
   Some municipal officials, on the other hand, question such
arrangements. Frank Kliewer, manager of internetworking at
Oakland's Office of Information Technology, said ``I'd much rather
pay $12 an hour to interns from Laney College (in Oakland, Calif.)
to get what we need than create dependence on some outside
company.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 3 of EGOV13SI (50748 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
