u a BC-BUSING-RECOLLECT-760(     09-12 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSING-RECOLLECT-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONDERING THE END OF BUSING IN THE CITY WHERE IT BEGAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By   The New York Times   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As Dr. Venton Bell, the principal of West
Charlotte High School, sat in the stands at the American Legion
Memorial Stadium here on Friday, most of his attention was focused
on whether his school's football team would beat the state
champions from Winston-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell, 54, also had another matter on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that day, a federal judge had ordered the
Charlotte-Mecklenburg school system to end busing and stop
assigning students to schools based on race. The ruling said the
schools had eliminated ``all vestiges of past discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Charlotte became the birthplace of busing three decades
ago, West Charlotte High School has often been cited by the
Charlotte-Mecklenburg school district as a place where integration
was working. An all-black high school before busing began, it is
now about 75 percent black, said Bell, who graduated from West
Charlotte in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's court ruling brought up memories of the old
separate-but-unequal school system. Bell remembered when his school
made do with cast-off books and supplies from white schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``See those yellow and gold uniforms that our football players
and cheerleaders are wearing?'' he said, pointing to the brightly
clad students on the field. ``Those are our school colors today
because we used to have to take the hand-me-down old uniforms from
Harding, a white school, whose colors are yellow and gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte became the first city in the country to implement
school busing after Judge James McMillan of U.S. District Court
here ruled in 1969 that the Charlotte-Mecklenburg schools had been
intentionally operating a racially segregated system.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan ruled that busing students to schools outside their
neighborhoods was an appropriate method for achieving racial
balance. The Charlotte plan was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court in
1971, clearing the way for school systems nationwide to implement
busing.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's ruling came in a lawsuit by white parents who claimed
Charlotte's educational policies discriminated against whites. In
his ruling, Judge Robert D. Potter of U.S. District Court here, who
had campaigned against busing as a private citizen in 1969, said
the schools had fulfilled their obligation under the original court
order.
</P>
<P>
   School officials had argued that they needed to use race in
school assignments for at least five more years because the system
had not done all it could to eliminate disparities between the
facilities at schools in black and white neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said the reactions he had seen to the ruling varied with
the generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids don't know what's the big deal,'' he said. ``The
people who are uptight about this are the parents. I'm sure some of
the kids were not aware what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebony Davis, 16, was one of those who did not know why there had
been a swarm of television reporters at the school on Friday when
she got on her bus to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the first half of the football game, Ms. Davis
finally heard what all the commotion was about, and she was
outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I going to get to school?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Davis, who is black, and her friends, both black and
white, had heard that Charlotte was the first city in the United
States to implement school busing, they were unclear about the
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't busing started because some parents didn't have a way
to get their kids to school?'' Ms. Davis asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richey, 52, a white investment banker, understood all too
well the implications of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling my daughter about the court decision,'' said
Richey, whose son and daughter attend West Charlotte High School.
``I told her that busing is going to be illegal next year. And her
reaction was, `OK, just so I don't have to leave West Charlotte.'
She loves it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Richey, a Charlotte native, was at the game to watch his son,
who is on the football team, and his daughter, who is a junior
varsity cheerleader. Until each child was in seventh grade, Richey
had sent them to a virtually all-white private school near their
suburban home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air tends to be rarefied at private schools,'' he said.
``I didn't want our kids to grow up thinking that everyone lives in
a world where their biggest decisions are whether to go to Bermuda
or Cancun for Easter break.''
</P>
<P>
   Richey said he and his family worried that doing away with
busing would deprive both blacks and whites of an important
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids have seen both sides,'' he said. ``How do you buy an
education like that?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Richey acknowledged that many white parents in
Charlotte were happy about the court ruling because they want to
keep their children in schools closer to home, and away from
inner-city children.
</P>
<P>
   And while many black parents worried that the ruling would
return Charlotte to a segregated school system, others had mixed
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Hinton, 36, a detention officer in the sheriff's
department, was at the football game with his son, a second-grader.
Busing began here when Hinton was a little older than his son is
now. He was bused to a previously all-white school at the time, and
recalled it as the first time he had been around white people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did think it was a good thing back then,'' Hinton said. ``I
thought that predominantly white schools were better and were
getting better books. But now I really think that neighborhood
schools are best. I don't think busing works when you try to shove
integration down people's throats.''
</P>
<P>
   As the game ended and West Charlotte won, Ebony Davis learned
that the busing ruling might mean that some of her white friends
would not return to West Charlotte next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race is not really a factor for me,'' she said. ``I went to
the beach with a white friend for a week this summer. Having all
races there makes the school more diverse, and that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell was mindful of the concerns voiced by opponents of the
ruling, but he said he was trying to remain hopeful about how
things would play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think busing at the time was a good thing, because there was
no other way to change things,'' he said. ``But the days of Jim
Crow and apartheid are gone. I don't think this judge's decision is
going to have a big effect _ as long as we have equal facilities at
all of our schools.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
