<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN REFORM'S MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 13:
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important election events of the current season
takes place this week, not in Iowa or New Hampshire or any other
primary state, but on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the House of Representatives votes on the
Shays-Meehan campaign finance reform bill to ban unregulated ``soft
money'' donations to political parties, regulate phony ``issue
ads'' on television and impose new fund-raising disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would curb abuses and practices at the heart of
the 1996 fund-raising scandals, appears likely to pass. But the
more votes it gets, the better the chances will be for Senate
approval of what would become the most sweeping electoral reforms
in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the political establishment have begun feeling the
pressure from voters and even donors. The Committee for Economic
Development is rounding up business leaders opposed to soft-money
donations. Gov. George W. Bush last week announced that his
campaign would list donors on its Web site, a positive step but
nothing like real reform.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and
Martin Meehan of Massachusetts passed last year by a vote of 252 to
179, including 61 Republicans who broke with their party leadership
to back the bill. If supporters stand firm, the majority ought to
be just as big this year.
</P>
<P>
   But in a repetition of their junkyard tactics of 1998, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert and Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, are
offering amendments and substitutes that would gut the bill's main
provisions or split the delicate coalition backing reform.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats and Republicans may be tempted to waver.
Anti-abortion groups are pressuring their allies to support
amendments that would gut the legislation's regulation of
television campaign ads sponsored by independent groups.
Republicans and Democrats who favor campaign reform have urged
anti-abortion forces not to oppose the Shays-Meehan bill, but
without success. On Tuesday they need to vote for reform, in
defiance of the misguided wishes of people with whom they might
agree on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger to reform comes in the form of ``poison pill''
amendments. One would throw out the whole bill if any one part of
it was declared unconstitutional. Others would increase ceilings on
donations to candidates, a premature step. Another would weaken the
ability of unions to raise money. If passed, it would drive
Democrats from the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A poison pill administered by DeLay would deregulate campaign
activities as long as they were conducted on the Internet. Still
another measure would require that a candidate raise at least 50
percent of his contributions in his home state, a measure that if
passed would force blacks and other urban minorities to oppose the
underlying bill.
</P>
<P>
   The gravest danger to reform is posed by three seemingly
attractive ``substitute'' amendments pushed by Republicans that, if
passed, would supplant the Shays-Meehan bill altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The one sponsored by John Doolittle of California would repeal
all campaign limits and merely require disclosure, an obvious step
backward. Another pushed by Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas would allow
``soft money'' for state parties, a loophole that would simply
rechannel the flow of corrupt money. A third pushed by Bill Thomas
of California sounds harmless enough. It would strengthen filing
requirements and take other constructive steps. But because it is a
substitute, its passage would defeat Shays-Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   Without a campaign overhaul, the parties are sure to spend $500
million to $750 million in soft money this year, twice as much as
in the last presidential election. A ``yes'' vote on Shays-Meehan
can head off more corrupt fund raising and more scandals in the
coming election cycle. On Tuesday the House faces a test of its
members' sincerity and of whether it is listening to the public
instead of special-interest donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
