<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Sept. 13. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEMANDING (undated) _ Ranks of `demanding' elders grows. One woman
called 911 and demanded that someone come make her coffee when her
family didn't show up fast enough. Others call their adult children
40 or 50 times a day, asking for everything from a back rub to help
changing a light bulb. In nursing homes, they hit the call button
every five minutes. Call them difficult, crotchety or just plain
cranky _ they are the highly vocal minority of elderly people
formally described as ``high maintenance.'' In the past, they rode
the porch rocker and yelled at passing kids, or tormented
long-suffering daughters-in-law in the privacy of the family home.
Today, social-service workers say, difficult older people are
growing in number, living longer and are increasingly separated
from their families. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LIGHTRAIL (Phoenix) _ While backers ready more details for a
Phoenix-area light-rail train, other folks are leaning hard on the
brake, arguing for alternative forms of rapid transit. To them,
monorails, or Jetson-like travel pods suspEnded from a guide-rail,
or even buses that run on rubber tires but operate like a train,
are better than launching an electric train on a 17-mile track from
central Phoenix to downtown Mesa. To these dreamers, the rail plan
is nothing but an ``electric street car,'' a 19th-century rail
holdover, a rapid-transit plan that will not be rapid and won't
attract riders. But local city planners say they looked at
everything from monorails to subways and concluded that an electric
train, running at street level, is the best way to start building
rapid-transit in the Valley. They hope a train could be running by
2005. By MARY JO PITZL. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new
books. By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
