r a BC-MO-VETOES-2NDTAKE-KAN     09-12 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-VETOES-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JEFFERSON CITY, THE PUSH TO OVERRIDE VETOES IS GAINING
MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ... of a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But the section that led to the veto would allow a judge to
require defendants who are put on probation to pay a fee into a
county law-enforcement fund. The fund would be controlled by the
county sheriff, the presiding commissioner and one other elected
county official.
</P>
<P>
   In his veto message, Carnahan objected to the money being spent
outside the normal budget process. He complained that the bill set
no maximum fee and set no restrictions on how the money could be
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Those provisions, Carnahan wrote, create the impression that
defendants could buy probation by paying into the fund _ and that
poor defendants without the money to pay would be sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Caskey argued that the public is demanding that offenders bear a
greater portion of the cost of the criminal justice system. Such
funds have been used for years, he said, but judges had asked for
specific statutory authority for such fees.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers considered the potential for abuse and required the
funds to be phased out by 2002 unless reauthorized by the
legislature, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter urging an override, Caskey wrote that the bill ``is
tougher on crime while being smarter on costs associated with
wholesale incarceration for non-violent offenders.''
</P>
<P>
   Caskey last week predicted that he had the 23 votes necessary in
the Senate to override the governor's veto. He said he was
optimistic about gaining the required two-thirds support in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat, said the bill's
breadth was its chief asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several provisions were very popular in the House,'' Gaw said.
``The telemarketing-fraud section was important to the AARP.
Registration of sexual predators has wide appeal. And the
sentencing provisions helped with prison overcrowding. There is a
feeling among many members that a lot of the objections to this
bill were dealt with in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Don Lograsso of Blue Springs, however, said he
would support the veto. He called the bill ``a piece of junk'' that
would soften the penalties for some crimes. The most egregious
part, he said, was imposing fines as part of probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are nothing but slush funds,'' Lograsso said. ``They've
had those in southeastern Missouri where they were using the money
for computers and office equipment, not law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate President pro tem Ed Quick, a Liberty Democrat, said the
crime and abortion bills were the only issues he saw gaining much
support. Lawmakers, he said, had shown scant interest in
overturning vetoes of bills that would allow adults to ride
motorcycles without helmets or legalize arcade games that give out
prizes worth up to $250.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Walt Mueller of St. Louis County is drumming up
support to override the veto of a $100,000 pilot program to
subsidize the cost of traveling to visit prison inmates. Mueller
said the program would reduce recidivism by keeping inmates in
touch with their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, however, called the spending a questionable use of
state funds and said the amount was inadequate to fund a statewide
project.
</P>
<P>
   Gaw said Mueller's effort did not seem to have gained widespread
support. But the bill had attracted an unusual following of House
members on the far right and far left.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Sen. Harry Wiggins of Kansas City said he might call
for veto overrides on two bills that would create, among several
specialty license plates, one for ``Respect Life.'' The bills also
would create a state Respect Life Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan vetoed both bills, saying the legislation violated the
state Constitution, which requires bills to pertain to only one
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of a license-plate bill to create a lobbying
organization is inappropriate,'' the governor wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Wiggins said he planned to meet Tuesday with the House sponsor,
Democrat Patrick O'Connor of St. Louis County, to discuss whether
to mount an override bid. In this veto session, even motor vehicles
can't escape the abortion divide.
</P>
</TEXT>
