<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-MO-VETOES-TWOTAKES-KA     09-12 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-VETOES-TWOTAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JEFFERSON CITY, THE PUSH TO OVERRIDE VETOES IS GAINING
MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _As the war of words over abortion escalates
heading into the Missouri General Assembly's annual veto session
this week, several lawmakers are quietly pushing to override vetoes
dealing with crime, prison inmates and even specialty license
plates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the efforts are considered longshots. But several
lawmakers said the momentum generated by the campaign to override
the abortion-bill veto has scratched the veneer of invincibility
around Gov. Mel Carnahan, who has never had a veto tossed aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a fever,'' said Democratic Sen. Harold Caskey of
Butler. ``Once you get one override, you may get a steamroller
effect. It depends on the psychological mix at the time, whether
people are worked up and what the governor's reaction is.''
</P>
<P>
   The veto session, which begins Wednesday, will be convened to
consider only the nine measures Carnahan vetoed last legislative
session.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers recognize that overrides are almost unheard of in
Missouri. The legislature has overridden only two vetoes this
century and only six in state history. And with the exception of
1833, no Missouri legislature has ever rejected more than one veto
in a year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both chambers are controlled by a slim majority of
Democrats, who are loath to override a governor of their own party.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sifford, Carnahan's chief of staff, said he was confident
that the legislature would back the governor on eight of the nine
bills he vetoed and on all of the individual items struck from
appropriations bills. The ninth bill, which would ban the late-term
procedure often referred to as ``partial birth'' abortion, is too
close to call, Sifford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've obviously got a full-court press on, but we have no feel
for which way it's going,'' he said. ``A lot of people are
undecided, but we're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a veto session dominated by the emotionally charged
abortion debate, no issue can avoid being caught in the whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that appears to have the next-best chance of an
override is a crime bill that Caskey championed. Several lawmakers
said abortion opponents are trying to ease anxiety about overriding
the governor on the abortion bill by suggesting lawmakers split the
difference: Override on abortion and sustain on the crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he heard that argument in the Senate. But the
House, where he said he was doing most of his lobbying, was less
inclined to link the two measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``House sponsors of the crime bill have indicated to me that
they are not into vote-swapping on the abortion bill,'' Carnahan
said. ``The best lobbying against a bill is to talk about its
problems. That's what I'm doing, and people are listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Ronnie DePasco, a Kansas City Democrat,
said it would be nearly impossible to override two vetoes. But
lawmakers are in a feisty mood. If the override attempt on the
abortion bill fails, an override on the crime bill becomes more
likely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crime measure, Senate Bill 335, is the combination of
several bills dealing with a wide range of criminal issues. The
bill originally was aimed at easing prison crowding by reducing
sentences for nonviolent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the legislative process, the bill had sections
that would regulate telephone marketing; let judges, police and
prosecutors carry concealed guns; require sexual predators to be
listed on the Internet; stop the sale of bootleg cigarettes; and
make it a crime to leave the scene of a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
