A9501 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-DEMOCRAT-POLLS-KAN &LR;      09-12 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRAT-POLLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY PRESIDENTIAL POLLS INDICATE DEMOCRATS FACE TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a 1995 White House reception, Ohio Democratic
Party Chairman David Leland guaranteed President Clinton that his
state's 21 electoral votes would be in his column again the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   This at a time when Ohio appeared to be soured on Clinton and up
for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you sober at the time?'' Leland's friends joked later.
</P>
<P>
   But Leland was not just talking the party line. Clinton won
Ohio, as well as a host of other battleground states. All had been
in doubt for the Democrats as they headed into 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now the political map looms just as large, as Ohio again
presents a challenge for the Democrats. The same holds for
Missouri, Michigan, Wisconsin, Illinois and Pennsylvania, to say
nothing of Iowa, Kentucky, Arkansas and Louisiana. These 10 swing
states could decide the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore ticket won them all in 1996 and 1992. But based
on current polling, they are all leaning toward Republican Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls also show that if the election were held today, the
Democratic presidential candidate _ whether Vice President Al Gore
or Bill Bradley _ could have trouble even in friendly territory
like California, New York and New Jersey, although Bradley, a
former senator from New Jersey, does well there. Without that trove
of electoral votes _ 102 in all _ a Democrat would be hard-pressed
to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   How seriously should these polls be taken?
</P>
<P>
   ``I use these early polls as a political weather vane to tell
you the shifting winds,'' said Neil Newhouse, a Republican
pollster. ``It's kind of a reflection of the national mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Barone, an author of /{The Almanac of American
Politics,/} divides the country into distinct political regions,
based on political trends: Democrats seem most solid in the
northeast corridor and the Pacific rim; Republicans hold sway in
much of the South, the Great Plains, the Rocky Mountains and the
desert states.
</P>
<P>
   Carved up like that, the map shows the two parties close to
parity in electoral votes. If the 2000 election holds to form, each
party would draw about 200 electoral votes from their strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   With 270 electoral votes needed to win, victory lies in the
middle _ in chunks of the Rust Belt, the heartland and the South,
in possibly 10 states that control 136 votes.
</P>
<P>
   And despite polls that give Bush widespread support, Barone
said: ``The more fertile way to look at it is we've got a real even
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Newhouse put it: ``Everybody realizes that this election
is not going to be as one-sided as the polls are right now. Nobody
is taking these numbers with more than a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   Anxious Democrats _ and there are many _ might also take comfort
in recalling that at this time four years ago, the political
geography appeared nearly as daunting. Then, as now, Republicans
had more states leaning their way as they handicapped their White
House chances.
</P>
<P>
   So what must Democrats do to replay history? And can they?
</P>
<P>
   Past is not necessarily prologue in presidential politics, but
history does provide cautionary guidance. ``The person who led at
this point in the race is usually the person who lost,'' said
Democratic pollster Mark Mellman, who works for the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Early polls showed President Bush beating Clinton in the 1992
campaign, Michael Dukakis beating Bush in 1988, Walter Mondale
beating President Reagan in 1984 and President Carter beating
Reagan in 1980, Mellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are familiar with the roster of failed front-runners
and insist that they are not overconfident. But they also do not
believe that Democrats can count on a repeat of the big public mood
swing that occurred between 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, a Bush political adviser and former executive
director of the Christian Coalition, said Republicans allowed
themselves to be blamed for the two government shutdowns that
angered the public. The Republican nominee, former Sen. Bob Dole,
paid the price.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a similar budget blowup occurs this year, Reed said,
``it will be lot more difficult to tie Governor Bush to that. In
the voter's mind, there's not really a connection. He's not doing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that shift in mood toward Clinton, bolstered by an
extensive advertising effort against Dole when he had little money
to respond, that boosted the Democratic ticket in the battleground
states in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That Gore, the current Democratic front-runner, is struggling _
even as the economy continues to soar and the president continues
to remain popular _ is a source of frustration to supporters. Early
polls show that Bush is even beating him in an unshakable
Democratic bastion such as Massachusetts, the only state George
McGovern carried in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Moore, Gore's campaign press secretary, said that the poll
numbers were misleading and that his numbers would turn around as
the campaign progressed and voters understood better what he would
do as president.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, and even some worried Democrats, say the vice
president is a victim of ``Clinton fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy the way it is, this should be a walk for the
vice president,'' said Ron Kaufman, White House political director
in the 1992 campaign for President Bush, the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman knows something about the vagaries of presidential
politics and public opinion, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 14 to 15 months away from the election,'' he said. ``We
don't even have nominees. My guess is, lots can happen. Being the
person who took President Bush from 91 points in the polls to 37
points in the polls, I can say that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
