<SLUG> BC-NIC-EFED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL WOULD GIVE OVERLAND PARK COMPANY FOOTHOLD IN GOVERNMENT
PURCHASING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ The company that helped put the state of
Kansas on the Internet is planning to revolutionize the way
government agencies do their purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   National Information Consortium, with headquarters in Overland
Park, plans to purchase a Reston, Va., Internet software company
for about $30 million. The company, eFed, has developed a
purchasing system that claims to cut the administrative costs of
government purchasing by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the agreement are expected to be announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   National Information Consortium has developed Web sites for nine
states, including Kansas. The company specializes in helping
government agencies develop Internet sites that allow businesses
and consumers to do business with the state online.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, for example, the company developed the Information
Network of Kansas, which allows businesses, professionals and
consumers to do everything from look up court records to purchase
hunting licenses online.
</P>
<P>
   NIC plans to use eFed to expand the services it offers
government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, eFed works with purchasing agents in nine federal
agencies, and has been working to develop contracts with some state
agencies. The company, which is expected to have profits of $5
million in 1999, is growing at a rate of more than 100 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
   It currently costs taxpayers an average of more than $100 in
administrative costs alone each time a federal purchasing agent
places an order, according to eFed statistics. The company contends
it can reduce the time and cost by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a purchasing agent interested in buying 10 new
personal computers for an agency currently might page through a
catalog or surf the Web sites of three or four computer
manufacturers. The eFed software creates a catalog of more than 1
million products and updates the prices each time a buyer accesses
the software.
</P>
<P>
   It also allows the purchasing agent to buy online with a federal
purchase card, cutting several steps out of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Reston-based Electric Press, a privately held Internet
publishing company, currently owns eFed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of NIC and eFed declined to comment on the deal.
Sources close to the negotiations said the agreement calls for NIC
to pay Electric Press $15 million and 600,000 shares of the
Overland Park company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   NIC stock closed Friday at $24.12 a share, up $3.81 for the day.
That makes the deal worth about $29.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   NIC was formed about nine years ago and went public on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The company sold 13 million shares at $12 a share, raising about
$156 million. The company stock since has doubled, and the
company's stock on Friday was valued at $1.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NIC is expected to have revenues of about $53 million during the
current fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
