<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ClINTON FAULTS MALAYSIA ON REPORTER'S JAILING 
 (ms) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after a Canadian journalist began serving a six-week
sentence in Malaysia for slandering the country's court system,
President Clinton criticized the Malaysian government Monday
morning for jailing a reporter for the act of reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting a journalist in jail for doing his job undermines the
press freedoms that play such a critical role in building a
democratic society,'' the president said in a statement released in
New Zealand, where he is attending the Asian economic summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The journalist, Murray Hiebert, the Malaysia bureau chief of The
Far Eastern Economic Review, began serving a six-week sentence on
Saturday, after a panel of judges rejected his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that press supporters say is a heavy blow to
Malaysia's shaky press freedom, the three-member appeals court
ruled that Hiebert had slandered the judiciary by writing an
article that discussed a lawsuit by the wife of an appeals court
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tofel, a spokesman for Dow Jones &AMP; Co., which owns the
magazine for which Hiebert works, said the company was disappointed
by the ruling. ``As Hiebert has maintained in court and throughout
this case, neither he nor The Far Eastern Economic Review had any
intention to attack either the courts of Malaysia or the litigants
in any particular case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hiebert's conviction in 1997, the Malaysian authorities
have held his passport. Hiebert, 50, said he had decided to
retrieve his passport by serving out his sentence, rather than
pursuing further appeals, because he was eager to join his family
in the United States and to visit his parents in Canada. His
lawyers, however, said they would continue to seek vindication for
him.
</P>
<P>
   The article in the case was published in January 1997 in The Far
Eastern Economic Review. It discussed the growing litigiousness
among Malaysians and, as an example, recounted a widely publicized
case in which the wife of an appeals court judge sued her son's
school, claiming it had unfairly dropped him from its debate team.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit raced through Malaysia's legal system in seven
months. In the article, Hiebert quoted lawyers who questioned
whether the plaintiff's relationship to a powerful judge helped
speed the process.
</P>
<P>
   The judge who presided at Hiebert's trial, Low Hop Bing, said at
the time that the conviction was meant to send a message to the
media that disrespect for the court system would not be tolerated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
