<SLUG> BC-BARNES-NYTIMES-BOOKS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNES &AMP; NOBLE TO PHASE OUT USE OF TIMES BOOK LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While online booksellers wage a fierce price war over New York
Times best sellers, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. is preparing to phase out
its use of the newspaper's weekly list at its superstores.
</P>
<P>
   In place of the Times list of books, for which Barnes &AMP; Noble
typically offers discounts, the bookseller intends to offer
bargains based on the chain's own sales rankings. Executives at
Barnes &AMP; Noble, the United States' leading bookstore chain, said
they would begin shifting to the system in the coming weeks. They
said they were making the change because their own sales rankings
did not always match the Times best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Barnesandnoble.com, the Web company that the chain spun off in a
public stock offering in May, plans for now to continuing offering
discounts based on the New York Times best-seller lists, the Web
company's spokesman, Gus Carlson, said. ``We're looking at what
they've done and we're looking at our own situation,'' Carlson
said. ``The best thing to say is that we're reviewing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since May, top online booksellers _ including
Barnesandnoble.com, Borders.com _ which is part of Borders Group _
and Amazon.com _ have been engaged in a fierce competition to
attract customers through 50 percent discounts on books from the
Times best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   And Amazon.com, after a legal dispute with The Times, struck an
agreement with the newspaper that allowed the bookseller to
continue posting the lists online. The Times had demanded that
Amazon.com stop publishing the list on its site without a licensing
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Back on terra firma, though, Barnes &AMP; Noble has decided that it
does not need the list for its bricks-and-mortar superstores.
``Frequently there were titles that we went after _ for whatever
reason _ that were selling like crazy, but were not on the New York
Times best-seller lists,'' said Alan Kahn, chief operating officer
for Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that our list that we cut every weekend reflects
more accurately what goes on in our stores,'' Kahn said. ``Any
retailer wants to sell more of what they're selling.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Barnes &AMP; Noble's top competitors said that they would
continue to use the newspaper's lists as the basis for offering
discounts. Bill Curry, a spokesman for Amazon.com, said, ``We think
it's a valuable way for customers to know the savings on
best-selling books, because it's such a well-known list.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that Barnes &AMP; Noble's use of a different list would
make it more difficult to compare prices against the promotions of
other competitors. But Barnes &AMP; Noble executives note that many of
the discounted books would probably appear on both lists. The chain
will offer 30 percent discounts on its best-selling hardcover
titles and 20 percent reductions off its trade paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Borders, the second-largest bookstore chain, said it planned for
now to continue using the New York Times lists, although one
executive indicated that his company was reviewing its options.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At The Times, Nancy Nielsen, a spokeswoman for the newspaper,
issued a brief statement about Barnes &AMP; Noble's action. The chain
``has made a commercial decision, which is what it is in business
to do,'' she said, adding that it is the newspaper's role to
``review books and also report the most comprehensive and impartial
sales data of all such lists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our list includes more than just one chain store,'' Ms.
Nielsen said. ``It includes several chain stores and independent
booksellers and thus is a broader audience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
