<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9507 &Cx1f; kan-z
r s BC-POSNANSKI-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-12 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSNANSKI-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL DAY FOR CHIEFS COACH ENDS IN AGONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOE POSNANSKI  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Elvis Grbac threw, and the ball floated a long way
down the field, and no receiver was going to catch up, and Gunther
Cunningham's heart exploded. That's how it felt. His heart
exploded, and his mind trembled, and he felt as if he were sinking
into the ground. Thirty years, he had waited to be the head
football coach. Thirty long years.
</P>
<P>
   The ball floated away. The game floated away.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Chiefs were going to lose to the Chicago Bears,
20-17.
</P>
<P>
   ``You die,'' Cunningham says. ``You absolutely die. I don't
think anybody can understand it. You die. There's no feeling like
that in the world. There's no pain so great. You work your heart
out, and then you see that pass going too far, and you die.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham died so many times on Sunday during his first game as
head coach. He died two dozen deaths in the first half alone, when
Chicago unleashed its loony new offense, and the Chiefs defense ran
around bewildered, bumping into each other, leaving receivers
uncovered, letting runners slide by. The Bears scored on every
possession in the half, took a 20-3 lead, and Cunningham went into
the locker room feeling every emotion on earth except joy, feeling
every kind of inner pain a man can feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slept well Saturday night,'' he said. ``You know why? I
believed. I knew this team was ready. Then, that first half, we
played defense like that. But in the second half, we shut them out.
We played the kind of defense we can play. And I said, `That's my
team.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the second half, Cunningham danced up and down the
sideline, he pumped his fist, he bounced around, everything
changed. The defense stiffened. Grbac connected on an 86-yard
touchdown pass to Derrick Alexander. Chicago fumbled the next
kickoff. Moments later, the ball slipped out of Bears quarterback
Shane Matthews' hand, and Donnie Edwards raced 79 yards for a
touchdown. Chicago was trying to give away the game. Cunningham was
flying. He wore the headphones. He dumped the headphones. He
slapped helmets. He screamed at an official. He grimaced. He kicked
at a loose ball. The Chiefs were going to come back and win the
game. He could feel it in his gut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any doubt in my mind,'' he said. When Pete
Stoyanovich missed a 38-yard field goal, Cunningham still believed.
When the Chiefs had a drive stall at the Chicago 41, he still
believed. When the Chiefs got the ball back and faced fourth-and-10
with less than three minutes remaining, Cunningham believed so
deeply that he decided to go for it, when the safer and more
dependable play would have been to punt and let the defense get the
ball back. Grbac threw long, Alexander went short, and that was
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for it,'' Cunningham said. ``And I will go for it
again. And I will go for it again after that. That's me. That's my
team. We're swashbucklers. We're not falling back on our heels.
We're not playing it safe. I went for it because I believed, deep
down, we were going to make it. We should have made it. And I will
go for it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Chiefs got their last chance, 94 yards from the end
zone, two minutes and 10 seconds left, and a run went for short
yardage, one pass was incomplete, then another, and finally it was
fourth down, and Grbac threw the ball long, Alexander could not
catch up. The game was lost. Cameras closed in on Cunningham as
that last ball floated away. His face remained blank. His insides
simmered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so frustrating,'' he said. ``Our defense kept giving
our offense chances. We've got to make those plays. We've got to
find ways to make plays. It killed me to watch us in those last
minutes on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   He went into the locker room, spoke softly to his team about how
games and chances don't ever come back. He answered a few media
questions. His face was red; his eyes bloodshot. Then, Gunther
Cunningham went into the coach's room to regroup, to slow his
heartbeat a bit, to calm his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun,'' Chiefs president//general manager Carl Peterson told
him, ``it's just one game. There will be others.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said similar things. Cunningham nodded. He knew this
agony was part of the bargain, part of the lifelong dream to be a
head football coach in the National Football League. Didn't make it
sting any less, though. Cunningham showered and put on his tie and
jacket and stared at the wall for a while. He wandered into the
training room to talk to Grbac: ``I told him, `Elvis, you haven't
changed in my eyes. You're my guy. You're going to be a great
quarterback in this league. And don't you ever forget it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's going to take some hits back in Kansas City over
this loss,'' Cunningham said. ``I will too. We're adults. That's
the way it goes. We'll take our hits, you bet, but then we will
come back next week and play our hearts out. That's pro football.
That's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham began to wander to the bus. He knew what would happen
next. He knew the routine as if it was his vaudeville act. First,
he would ride the bus, then get on the plane, then get in the car,
and he would feel worse and worse as the night went along. He would
manage to fall asleep for an hour or two when suddenly he would
jolt awake, as if stabbed by a knife. And, with that, sleep would
be done, and he would spend the rest of the night working, think up
strategies, staring out the window, into the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to coach more,'' he said. ``That's clear. I've been
spread so thin. But that's going to change. Nobody knows this team
better than I do. So, I will get in there and coach more for this
Denver game coming up. I will be everywhere next week. This team is
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost smiled then as he headed for the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what?'' he said. ``I'm already excited about Denver.
I really am. I've just got to get all this darkness out of my
mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
