<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSQUITO SPRAYERS BLITZ THROUGH NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By   JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The white pickup trucks outfitted with canisters and
spray hoses were gone as quickly as they arrived, leaving only a
foul odor and an ominous-looking white cloud of insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   The ground war against the outbreak of St. Louis encephalitis, a
mosquito-borne viral disease, was in full swing over the weekend,
backed up by aerial support from insecticide-spraying helicopters.
But it was a lightning blitz so fast that many residents barely
noticed the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were coming,'' Crystal McKenny, 22, said at 2:50
a.m. Sunday, about 15 minutes after a convoy of trucks passed a
building where she was sitting on the steps with a friend in
northwest Harlem. ``I just forgot we were first. I was going to be
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   By 6 a.m. Sunday, all of northern Manhattan had been treated
with malathion, the insecticide that city officials are using to
fight the mosquitoes that carry the virus, which so far has been
responsible for three deaths in the city.
</P>
<P>
   City workers have been spraying Staten Island, Central Park and
much of northern Manhattan. Midtown and lower Manhattan are
expected to be completed by Tuesday. The Mayor's Office of
Emergency Management is using 11 trucks, five helicopters and an
airplane in the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Sunday the number of possible cases
of St. Louis encephalitis, an occasionally fatal disease that can
cause extreme swelling of the brain, was about 80. The number of
confirmed cases remained at nine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night and Sunday morning, as truck drivers sprayed
northern Manhattan and Brooklyn Heights, several new possible cases
were reported to city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that test results returned by the Federal Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention had discounted 16 possible
cases, but that four cases needed more testing because the results
were inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   One of those four cases involved a 79-year-old woman from
Whitestone, Queens, who died in mid-August, before the outbreak had
become public, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly, small children and people with weakened immune
systems are particularly vulnerable to the disease, while most
healthy people recover on their own. The symptoms can range from a
slight headache or fever to a high fever and convulsions.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evening, the convoys trolled back and forth on
crosstown streets, just north of Central Park and Morningside
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the smell quickly disappeared after the trucks
went by, and people were often able to return to the streets. The
stench, although powerful, was sometimes so short lived that some,
including a group of Columbia University students, did not even
realize that the spray truck had passed through their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, Virginia Heath, 52, a mental health worker, and her
husband, Jose Nina, 46, a former outfielder for the Los Angeles
Dodgers were momentarily distracted from their view of the Hudson
River and the New Jersey skyline as one of the trucks roared by.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question is how come they want to spray everywhere but
midtown on a Saturday night?'' Ms. Heath said as her husband held
his nose. ``It must be some chemical that is hazardous to your
health, that they don't want to give to rich folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials have said that the spraying of malathion
poses almost no risk to humans, although people with respiratory
problems like asthma could have an attack if exposed to the spray.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
