r a BC-COLUMBINE-CROSSES-KAN     09-12 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-CROSSES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS GATHER AT CROSSES SYMBOLIZING VICTIMS OF COLUMBINE HIGH
SCHOOL MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ Thirteen crosses on the crest of the hill
symbolized the innocent victims of last spring's Columbine High
School massacre and offered inspiration to hundreds who gathered in
a Johnson County field Sunday evening to affirm their faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   The original wooden crosses erected after the Littleton, Colo.,
shooting, which are now traveling the country, still bear messages
scrawled by loved ones and the tattered remains of ribbons and
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleep, baby sleep,'' was written in black marker on several of
the crosses. ``We loved you, coach,'' was written on the one for
teacher William David Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The poignancy of the sad reminders was eclipsed by a message of
hope brought by Darrell Scott, whose daughter Rachel was killed
April 20 outside the school and whose son Craig survived by playing
dead in the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I believed for a second that God was asleep on April 20 I
wouldn't be here,'' Darrell Scott told the crowd of several hundred
in lawn chairs and on blankets. ``I would be very, very angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott read from his daughter's diaries to reveal how deeply she
believed that God had a mission for her in life and in death. In a
diary addressed to God, Rachel wrote, ``I want you to use me to
reach the unreached.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you something,'' her father added, ``her prayer
was answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's televised funeral was viewed by millions and the
17-year-old's death has inspired countless people to turn their
lives around, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Her last diary, which was in her backpack the day she was shot
and which bears a bullet hole, contained a drawing Rachel made of a
pair of eyes crying tears over a rose that, her father said, is
growing out of a columbine plant.
</P>
<P>
   Scott spoke at an evening service on the grounds of the future
First Family Church at 143rd Street and Metcalf Avenue. A morning
service at the site was moved to Rockhurst High School because of
Sunday morning's rain.
</P>
<P>
   At the morning service, Craig Scott related his experience
during the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Local youths were selected to carry each of the crosses down the
hill and through the audience to the front of a portable stage
below. Scott spoke of each of the victims as the crosses were
brought down, noting the absence of crosses for the two killers,
who committed suicide after the shooting. Scott asked for prayers
for those boys' families.
</P>
<P>
   The crosses, built of unvarnished wood by carpenter Greg Zanis
of Aurora, Ill., have traveled to visit congregations across the
country. First Family pastor Jerry Johnston invited Scott to bring
the crosses here.
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City woman who is in the process of becoming a member
of the First Family Church brought her dog with her to the outdoor
service. She stooped to read the messages on the crosses in the
setting sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my faith is that God uses experiences like this,''
said the woman, who identified herself only as Aileen. ``Even
though it's really sad, it might bring a person closer to God. If
these families believe in God after something like this, that's
pretty powerful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
