<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBC-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTHUSIASM AND DAYNE'S PATIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating to add art note0 ON COLLEGE FOOTBALL: ARRINGTON'S(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is what we know as the college football season begins to
find its legs.
</P>
<P>
   First, Florida State's Peter Warrick is a worthy front-runner
for the Heisman Trophy and Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton should vault
to second place after the two took turns trampling each other's end
zones late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Penn State's LaVar Arrington lost what little chance he
had for the award but probably insured that he would become the top
pick in the National Football League draft by playing well and
acting badly in a 20-17 victory over Pittsburgh. The linebacker
blocked the game-tying field-goal attempt, snatched an interception
and, most impressively, pounded and bullied a punter. A punter!
</P>
<P>
   Third, Wisconsin's Ron Dayne needs tougher opposition if he
wants to separate Warrick and Hamilton from the Heisman. And
finally, the sense of time of the Swiss might better serve Notre
Dame than the luck of the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play one more second of that game,'' said
Coach Bobby Bowden after Florida State, top-ranked in the
Associated Press poll, outlasted Georgia Tech, 41-35, in
Tallahassee. ``I never thought I would see the day that an offense
would score that many points on us. I think Tech had a chance to
win up to the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Florida State's Travis Minor smothered an onside-kick
attempt with 1 minute 35 seconds left, Georgia Tech did have a
chance in a high-wire game that showed Warrick belonged alongside
Johnny Rodgers, Desmond Howard and Tim Brown _ the only true
receivers to win the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable sequence, Florida State (2-0) and Georgia Tech
(1-1) rang up touchdowns on seven consecutive series, combining for
five of them in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick caught a 26-yard touchdown pass, lined up at quarterback
in the shotgun and ricocheted 17 yards for a touchdown run, and
finished with 167 yards on 8 catches.
</P>
<P>
   And the 5-foot-10-inch Hamilton, the South's version of Doug
Flutie, fired right back. He was 22 of 25 for 387 yards and 4
touchdowns. He ran for another score and completed his final 14
passes of the game, touchdown throws of 11 and 22 yards among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit, and they hit back,'' said Hamilton, who was knocked
out of the game the last two times the teams met. ``They made plays
and we made plays back. They just made more plays than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, Penn State, which was ranked second going into
the weekend, was considered to be the big-play team of the new
season after crushing victories over Arizona and Akron. But the
Nittany Lions looked Victorian in surviving over the 34-point
underdog Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, a 6-foot-3-inch, 242-pound all-American, slapped
around Pitt's 6-0, 189-pound punter Greg DeBolt in the early going.
But he finished by getting a hand on a 52-yard field-goal attempt
by Nick Lotz with four seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, the emotional Arrington blindsided DeBolt
after his punt and jumped on him as a penalty flag flew. He then
leaped to his feet, ignored the referee and shoved DeBolt again.
Another flag flew, and Arrington was penalized 30 yards for two
personal fouls.
</P>
<P>
   The outburst did not seem to bother the college game's arbiter
of taste and sportsmanship, Joe Paterno. He spoke calmly to
Arrington on the sideline and the linebacker remained in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to nitpick all of the time,'' Paterno said
afterward. ``He should have walked away, but it was a good lesson
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Feel sorry for the Badgers' Dayne. But don't feel sorry for that
dawdling bunch from South Bend, Ind. Dayne, the Wisconsin man
mountain, rolled for 158 yards in a 50-10 thrashing of Ball State.
He only played three quarters _ one more than he did the previous
week in Wisconsin's rout of Murray State.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne is not only in search of the Heisman, but also the career
rushing record set last year by Ricky Williams of Texas. With
Cincinnati next for the Badgers, both will be part-time pursuits.
He needs the Big Ten schedule to get there in a hurry before he
loses any more ground to Warrick and a Hamilton in the Heisman
race.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame again proved it cannot do anything in a hurry. For
the second week in a row, the Irish ran out of clock _ this time
after driving to Purdue's (2-0) 1-yard line in a 28-23 loss. The
Irish (1-2) had already turned the two-minute drill into
slow-motion chaos. It caught up to them when they called a timeout
with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Davie called two plays intended to move them three
feet for the score. Unfortunately, the first one allowed
quarterback Jarious Jackson to call an audible, if necessary, for
an option play. He had not.
</P>
<P>
   But fullback Joey Goodspeed thought he had. He relayed it to
tailback Tony Fisher. They went right. Jackson went left as
planned, but instead of finding Fisher ready for a handoff, he was
hit by linebacker Mike Rose. The play lost 9 yards. End of game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a coaching staff, we had a couple of mistakes,'' said
Davie, who last week heard the gun sound as his team was trying to
win the game from Michigan's 12.
</P>
<P>
   The season is still young, but there are some truths on the
college landscape. Look for the Heisman Trophy winner to streak out
of the South. The Great Dayne will rumble toward them out of
Wisconsin when he gets a chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-12-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
