<DOCNO> NYT19990912.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-TUPA-NYT &LR;      09-12 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TUPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIRER'S CHANCE TO REPLACE TESTAVERDE COMES TOO SOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As Keyshawn Johnson stormed out of the
interview room _ unleashing all of the frustration from the injury
to Vinny Testaverde in the Jets' opening-day 30-28 loss Sunday to
the New England Patriots and the realization that maybe the Super
Bowl dreams were fading _ Rick Mirer was ushered in through a door
on the other side of the room, a disconcerting welcome to his first
postgame news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Before Johnson left the room, he had described Testaverde as
irreplaceable. Mirer is left to prove him wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty rough situation for everybody right now,'' Mirer
said as he walked through the corridors under Giants Stadium.
``They've had high expectations and Vinny was a big part of that. I
don't even know all these guys yet. I haven't done much here yet.
You have to earn all that stuff on the field on game day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Mirer, that chance came much sooner than he believed it
would when he was acquired in a trade with the Green Bay Packers on
Aug. 20, shortly after playing against the Jets in an exhibition
game. In his brief time with the team, he earned the backup
quarterback job behind Testaverde. Now, after less than a month
with the organization he finds himself saddled with the
responsibility of salvaging the team's title hopes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On this day, he did not even get his chance until the fourth
quarter as  &UR; c &LR; oach Bill Parcells placed him as the emergency
quarterback, presuming that Testaverde would be healthy and that
Tom Tupa, who serves as the punter as well as holder on kicks,
would never be called into action in his listing as the
second-string quarterback.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tupa entered the game when Testaverde went down with the
ruptured Achilles' tendon midway through the second period because
if Parcells had inserted Mirer before the fourth quarter, Tupa
would not have been allowed into the game even to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa responded with a 25-yard touchdown pass to Johnson on his
first play, the first pass he had attempted since Nov. 17, 1996, on
a fake punt while he was a member of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa, a quarterback at Ohio State, had thrown his previous
touchdown pass in 1992, and his performance amazed even Patriots
quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is an amazing athlete,'' Bledsoe said. ``He had no
reps in the preseason. He has had very little work with the first
team. But he did get his dream shot this week because he got to be
me on the scout team.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, it would be Mirer under the microscope, and he
was only third best on his own team. Testaverde was 10 of 15 before
the injury and Tupa was 6 of 10 with two touchdowns, in addition to
punting and even running on a fake field goal, ending up just short
of a first down.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer was 4 of 11 for 28 yards with two interceptions, the most
costly one coming with only 3 minutes 30 seconds to play in the
game and the Jets trying to run down the clock while protecting a
28-27 lead. After a late read brought him to Johnson, his attempt
to force the ball in bounced off Johnson and into the hands of New
England linebacker Chris Slade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mirer, who was the second player selected in the National
Football League draft, behind Parcells' selection with New England
of Bledsoe, has worn his way through four teams now in seven years.
He did not play a down last season with Green Bay, but will now be
counted on because Parcells said that he would not reach out for a
veteran quarterback, instead going with Mirer, Tupa and Ray Lucas,
who was inactive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For Mirer, inspiration for what can happen came from what
Testaverde achieved last season after enduring years of struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been done, so I've seen it happen and feel good about my
chances,'' Mirer said. ``I have a little less time than he did and
a little less time than I want. But it's possible and I feel good
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not always be pretty, but I'm going to try to get the
job done my way and execute his plays. We're going to need help
from other guys, but we have that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would happen this way,'' Mirer said. ``It
did and it's time to play and I've got to be ready to go. There's a
lot of work to be done and not a lot of time to do it. You hate to
see anybody get hurt, especially the guy that controls the offense.
It accelerates my learning process. Right now there's a lot of
things I'm going to have to get comfortable with real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirer should get the majority of practice snaps as the team
prepares for next week's meeting with Buffalo on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to be playing,'' Mirer said. ``Today I felt
like this morning waking up, it's a new season and I'm not playing,
but I'm one play away. Sure enough, that happens early. It's not
really the way you'd like to see it happen. It's a good opportunity
for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to slow this team down because there are things I
need to get comfortable with to be successful. Hopefully, I can
pick up where Vinny left off and get this team where they deserve
to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
