<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
CELLEGY PINS ITS HOPES ON HEMORRHOID GEL &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Mike Forrest of Cellegy Pharmaceuticals doesn't take it
personally when people steer clear of him at cocktail parties.
</P>
<P>
   His South San Francisco, Calif., firm is in the final stages of
testing the first new treatment for hemorrhoids and anal fissures
in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly the most popular topic of conversation,'' he
admits.
</P>
<P>
   But by Christmas, Forrest hopes to have analyzed the results of
Phase III clinical trials involving 300 patients, who are now using
an experimental gel to relax the swollen blood vessels and cramped
muscles that cause hemorrhoids and fissures.
</P>
<P>
   The gel's active ingredient is nitroglycerin, the same chemical
angina patients use to ease blood flow around the heart. New York
surgeon Steve Gorfine realized several years ago that nitroglycerin
could probably have the same calming effect on inflamed anal
tissue, and in 1997 he patented the idea of using nitro relaxants
for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Cellegy acquired these patent rights and quickly won Food and
Drug Administration approval to skip early-stage safety tests _
saving years of trials _ and jump right into Phase III studies of
whether the nitro gel works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nitroglycerin has been used for so long in humans, the FDA was
convinced it was safe,'' Forrest says, explaining the expedited
trials.
</P>
<P>
   Cellegy hopes the trial data will prove its nitro cream a more
effective pain reliever than current prescription steroid drugs or
over-the-counter remedies, both of which have been around for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   If the Phase III data are positive, Cellegy will seek FDA
approval next year to sell a drug with a U.S. market potential in
excess of $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cellegy's shares have more than doubled since the spring, when
the company announced its Phase III trials. The stock closed
unchanged Friday (Sept. 11) at $8.13.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 30-person Cellegy recently completed Phase II safety
studies of a gel rub that would give aging men a testosterone
boost. (It's not what you think: Patients rub the gel into an arm
or thigh muscle.) ``In the U.S., 5 million men have clinically low
testosterone levels,'' Forrest says.
</P>
<P>
   The medical term for testosterone deficiency is hypogonadalism.
The condition generally occurs after age 40, causing mood swings,
loss of muscle mass, a decrease in libido and problems in
concentrating.
</P>
<P>
   Three forms of testosterone replacement therapy are on the
market, but Forrest says all have drawbacks. Oral tablets can cause
liver damage. Injections can safely deliver testosterone boosts,
but the effect wears off soon.
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, the FDA approved testosterone skin
patches, which deliver steady doses of hormone. But Forrest says
the patches, which must be applied daily, cause skin irritation and
leave unsightly red blotches.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, thousands of American men shell out $1,000 a year for a
year's supply of testosterone skin patches. If his experimental gel
can deliver its hormonal kick without the skin irritation, Forrest
thinks Cellegy could have another Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Cellegy has only tested its gel on a handful of men.
The FDA will doubtless scrutinize whether the testosterone rub
outperforms the placebo.
</P>
<P>
   So touting this prospect is premature. Then again, if you were
Mike Forrest, which gel would you rather talk about at cocktail
parties?
</P>
<P>
   RUMOR DEPARTMENT: Over the past month, shares of Chiron Corp.
have soared on rumors that it might be acquired by Novartis, the
Swiss drug firm that already owns a 45 percent stake in Chiron.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors began shortly after Roche, another Swiss drug firm,
acquired Genentech Inc., then turned right around and spun off part
of Genentech in a hugely successful public offering. Roche had
owned two-thirds of Genentech before this maneuver, and market
speculation held that Novartis might do a similar dance with
Chiron.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company has commented on the rumors. Analysts who follow
Chiron have largely declined to speculate on possible merger talks.
And Novartis, which is traded on the Zurich exchange, isn't well
understood in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   But the market gossip provides a good excuse to learn about
Novartis, one of the world's top three drug vendors. With $22
billion in revenues, Novartis ranks 159 on Fortune magazine's
Global 500 list.
</P>
<P>
   Based down the street from Roche in the Swiss city of Basel,
Novartis has three main businesses. Prescription drugs is the
largest division, accounting for 55 percent of sales. Another 18
percent comes from consumer health products, which include such
popular items as Ex-Lax and Maalox, as well as Gerber baby food.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis derives the last 27 percent of its revenues from the
sale of pesticides, herbicides, genetically modified seeds and
agri-chemicals. European financial reports say Novartis' ag
business is in trouble, owing partly to weak crop prices, which
have crimped purchases of seeds and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over genetically modified foods has also bruised
its reputation. Novartis sells a strain of corn altered so that its
stalk contains an insecticide meant to kill corn pests.
</P>
<P>
   Poor performance in the agri-division, combined with lackluster
results in the pharmaceutical and consumer categories, has driven
Novartis shares down more than 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis has tried to reverse the slide by dedicating about a
third of its $7.8 billion cash reserve to a stock buyback program.
The company is also gearing up to launch several new prescription
drugs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Euro-press has noted, but not dwelt, on the prospect that
Novartis might acquire Chiron now, rather than later, effectively
renegotiating a contract that currently prevents Novartis from
doing a buyout until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But the more active rumor on the other side of the Atlantic is
that Novartis might spin off its troubled agri-unit, tightening its
focus on prescription and OTC drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Novartis digests Chiron now, or deals with its
agri-problems first and its biotech opportunities later, the Swiss
drug giant is destined to play a determining role in Chiron's
future. Since Genentech is already majority-owned by Roche, this
means the San Francisco Bay Area's two leading biotech firms will
both one day take their lead from Basel.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's an ill rumor that blows no good. Chiron shares
had been stalled in the low 20s for nigh on to three years, defying
CEO Sean Lance's efforts to excite investors. But now the hint that
Chiron may be in play has made its stock unstoppable in recent
weeks. Its shares gained 3 cents Friday (Sept. 11) to close at
$34.78.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
