<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   SOFTWARE MARKET REBOUNDS &HT;    By TOM STEIN
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Software stocks, which have taken a beating for
much of the year, are starting to bounce back, as investors
anticipate a rebound in sales once companies get over their Y2K
worries and start buying business software again.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks of leading software companies such as PeopleSoft,
Oracle, Intuit, Siebel and SAP hit the skids this year as customers
put off buying commercial software and turned their attention
toward making sure their existing software was ready for the
potential Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   But now many companies think they have the Y2K problem under
control, and they are once again shopping for new software to
modernize their operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an increasing awareness on the part of companies that
there will be life beyond Y2K and that they'd better be prepared
with new business information systems,'' said Jim Shepherd, an
analyst with AMR Research in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in leading business-software companies have risen 30 to
50 percent in the past month. The sector could get another boost
Tuesday (Sept. 14), when Oracle of Redwood City, Calif. announces
earnings for the first quarter of fiscal 2000. Chuck Phillips, a
analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said he expects Oracle's
business software revenues to rise 17 percent from the year earlier
period. In recent quarters, sales growth has been mostly flat for
business-software companies. Oracle stock closed at $46.38 Friday
(Sept. 11), up 29 percent in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel Systems in San Mateo, Calif., is perhaps positioned the
best. The company sits smack in the middle of the red-hot market
for sales force automation software, which helps companies manage
their sales leads, call centers and marketing operations. Analysts
say customers get the most immediate return on investment from this
type of software.
</P>
<P>
   AMR Research predicts the market for sales software alone will
grow from about $2 billion last year to $11 billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Siebel's stock closed at $75.78 Friday (Sept. 11) _ up 50
percent from $50.38 a month ago _ and is hovering just below its
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft and SAP _ which make software that help companies run
their finance, distribution, sales and manufacturing operations _
have also seen their stocks climb back from frightening lows
recently.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, PeopleSoft's stock has soared 37 percent. It
finished on Friday (Sept. 11) at $18.13, compared with $13.19 a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Pleasanton, Calif., company also seems to have settled many
of its management troubles. Investors, and customers, were scared
off after the company's founder and chief executive Dave Duffield
said this spring he would step back from day-to-day operations. At
the same time, many longtime executives departed the company. But
according to analysts, Wall Street now feels more comfortable with
PeopleSoft's new management team, lead by President Craig Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Even Intuit, a Mountain View, Calif., maker of financial
software for consumers and small businesses, has seen a sharp rise
in its stock price. Intuit shares closed Friday (Sept. 11) at $103,
up 44 percent from $71.44 a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing some large deals coming back into the pipeline
for the business software vendors,'' said Bill Lanzon, an analyst
with Dain Rauscher Wessels. That's a vast improvement over a few
months ago, when the customer pipeline had all but dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Babcock, chief technology officer at Pacific Coast Feathers
in Seattle, is one SAP customer who is looking to buy more
applications in the New Year. Her company, which makes down pillows
and comforters, would like to buy an executive information system
that gives management immediate feedback on critical information
such as product sales by region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think companies are still focused on Y2K, but I think that
focus is starting to shift toward new technology projects.''
</P>
<P>
   While business-software stocks have rebounded nicely of late,
most are still below their 52-week highs. Analysts think it's
unlikely prices will recover fully this year. ``Companies like
PeopleSoft have come back lately, but they still have a long way to
go,'' said Shepherd of AMR Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
