<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9517 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RENTAL-SOFTWARE-SFCHR     09-12 1529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENTAL-SOFTWARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   RENT OUT YOUR CHOICE OF SOFTWARE &HT;    By TOM STEIN
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Desktop software has always been a pain.
</P>
<P>
   For most consumers, loading new software on a personal computer
can be a frustrating, mind-bending experience. And the more
software you install on your PC, the more technical troubles you're
likely to have.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those infinite software upgrades to worry about,
not to mention all the uninstalling and reinstalling you have to do
when when you replace your old machine with a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, these software issues are a real deterrent to PC
use,'' said Jeff Tarter, publisher of Softletter, an industry
newsletter in Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be a better way. A few high-tech giants, as well
as a host of small startups, are playing with the idea of renting
software over the Internet. Instead of trudging off to a local
retailer and plunking down $40 or more for the latest software
title, consumers could simply log on to the Internet and access the
software package of their choice _ sometimes for free, sometimes
for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: The software resides on a remote server in
cyberspace and is never loaded onto the individual's computer
desktop. Users would access the software on an as-needed basis and
pay either a per usage fee, a monthly subscription fee or,
sometimes, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Users also can pay to have their files stored remotely or can
transfer the files to their own computer hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, for instance, being able to rent, for a nominal charge,
a tax-preparation application. When you are finished, your tax
return is filed on your hard drive _ or possibly zapped directly to
the IRS _ while the application that created it disappears into the
cyber-clouds.
</P>
<P>
   While the idea of renting software over the Internet is new to
the consumer market, it has already taken hold in the business
world. That's because corporations spent much of the past decade
trying to install complex software applications to run their
businesses. Some of these software projects took years to complete
and cost millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   To alleviate the problem, some companies are now renting access
to financial, manufacturing and sales software over the Internet.
As a result, a winemaker, for instance, can focus on growing grapes
instead of worrying about installing and maintaining complicated
software applications.
</P>
<P>
   Companies as varied as Robert Mondavi Winery and Samsung
Semiconductor spent a total of $150 million on software rentals
last year. That figure is expected to grow to $2 billion by 2003,
according to International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors are eager to tap into this market. Oracle Corp., for
one, has set up a separate business unit, called Oracle Business
Online, dedicated to software rental. Other companies in the market
include Corio and USinterworking, which rent out software from the
likes of PeopleSoft and SAP.
</P>
<P>
   And while the action to date has been on the business software
side, some industry experts believe the real potential of the
rental market is on the consumer side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't want to fret with technology in the home,''
said Clare Gillan, an analyst with International Data Corp. ``I
think you will see some big vendors make a play (in the software
rental market) because that is a way to own the consumer and have
control of the home.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems lent huge credibility to the notion of software
rental late last month when it acquired a company called Star
Office and said it would begin offering word processing and
spreadsheet applications for free over the Internet. The service is
aimed at both consumers and businesses. By giving away the
software, Sun is hoping to increase sales of its computer servers,
which host the software.
</P>
<P>
   Sun also said it would unveil a new Web site later this year
called StarPortal, where consumers can access applications similar
to those in Microsoft Office, the leading ``business productivity''
package.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the threat from Sun, Microsoft said it's working
on its own Web-based office productivity services. At first, these
rental services will take shape around Microsoft's Windows 2000
software and will be targeted at small businesses, not consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts believe it's crucial that Microsoft quickly address
the consumer market. ``The big question is whether Microsoft is
willing to change its revenue model and accept a near-term loss,''
said Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga Information Group.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that there are 100 million Office customers, who each
pay about $400 for the software in retail outlets. ``If Microsoft
wants to hold on to its market share, it has to provide a
compelling solution in the software rental space that is priced
right.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sun will offer its software for free over the Web, it is
still unclear what consumers can expect to pay for Microsoft
applications under a rental model.
</P>
<P>
   It's also crucial to note that, for several reasons, consumer
software rental is not yet ready for prime time. The first problem
is slow and spotty Internet access. Critics argue that most people
just won't tolerate waiting minute after frustrating minute to
access, say, an Internet-based spreadsheet document to crunch
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the rental concept to work, you have to give consumers
bulletproof applications,'' said Yogen Dalal, a partner at venture
capital firm Mayfield Fund in Menlo Park, Calif. ``If I'm a college
student using a Web-based word-processing application to write my
term paper, I won't be happy if my Internet connection crashes and
I lose all my data.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dalal and others believe software rental is inevitable,
they say it won't be a reality for another three to five years. By
that time, it's expected that most people will have high-speed
access to the Internet and that network connections will be more
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Another critical issue is privacy. How secure will consumers
feel if their private word-processing or financial documents are
stored remotely on an Internet server?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the idea of my personal files sitting on someone
else's server,'' said Rebecca Susser, a 30-year-old San Francisco
resident who has given the issue some thought. ``Also, if I'm on
the road and can't log on to the Internet, does that mean I won't
be able to do my work?''
</P>
<P>
   But Susser sees plenty of upside as well. ``Overall, the whole
rental aspect is very appealing,'' she said. ``I like the fact that
my software will always be automatically updated and that there
would be a plethora of programs I could use.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she is interested in high-end design software but that
she wouldn't use it often enough to justify forking out hundreds of
dollars. ``It would be really cool if could pay (a small fee) for
the software only when I needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, millions of people are accessing software _ albeit
small-scale applications _ over the Internet. Online giants like
Yahoo, American Online and Microsoft, as well as fledging startups
like Visto, offer e-mail and calendaring programs over the Web that
are hugely popular with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers speculate that the next logical step would be
for these companies to increase the number of Internet-based
applications in their portfolios and start charging a subscription
fee. Just as cable television operators offer consumers the choice
of basic, premium and pay-per-view services, a similar model could
be applied to software rental.
</P>
<P>
   Two startups that are clearly forging ahead in this direction
are Desktop.com in San Francisco and Arepa.com in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop.com, which will formally launch its service on September
20, wants to become, quite literally, the desktop of the Internet.
Today, computer users go to a single, centralized spot to access
all their software _ namely the PC desktop. The concept behind
Desktop.com is to give users that same convenience on the Internet,
whether they are trying to access games, finance or personal
productivity software.
</P>
<P>
   The company is building its own Internet-based applications, but
is also encouraging third-party developers to create software for
its platform. Desktop.com chief executive Katie Burke said the
site, at first, will cater to niche applications targeted at a
focused market, such as software that will allow long-distance
runners to log the number of miles they cover each week. The
service will initially be free to users.
</P>
<P>
   Arepa.com, for its part, is targeting the nearly 2 million U.S.
households that already have high-speed, or broadband, access to
the Internet. Subscribers to the service, which is now being tested
in select locations across the country, get instant access to
popular software titles, including educational, gaming and personal
productivity applications.
</P>
<P>
   The company is still experimenting with pricing, but subscribers
can expect to pay a few dollars to rent a particular application
for a day or two, or they can access a unlimited number of software
titles in a particular category for about $10 a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
