<HEADER>
A9539 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-HNS &LR;      09-12 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUCHANAN POISED FOR REFORM PARTY BID
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By CRAGG HINES &QL; 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pat Buchanan, whose aggressively conservative bids
for the Republican presidential nomination have weakened the
party's eventual standard-bearer in the last two national
campaigns, said Sunday he was almost prepared to seek the Reform
Party nomination _ an even more harrowing prospect for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door really is wide open,'' Buchanan said on NBC's Meet
the Press. ``We are very close to making that decision ... We are
taking a hard look at leaving the Republican nomination run and
running for the Reform Party nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The comment was the clearest indication yet by the conservative
commentator, who was an aide to Republican Presidents Nixon and
Reagan, that he is prepared to abandon his current lackluster GOP
presidential bid and seek the nomination of the party founded by
Dallas billionaire Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's time maybe to take a bye on the regionals and
go straight to the finals,'' Buchanan said of the prospect that he
could leave the Republican primary race and seek a place on the
November 2000 presidential ballot as the Reform nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan indicated he would make a decision by Oct. 15. The
Reform Party is expected to nominate a presidential candidate at a
convention next summer. But in some states, including Texas, where
the party does not have a guaranteed ballot position, individual
candidates face deadlines _ as well as costly petition drives _
before summer 2000 for getting on ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's latest Republican campaign has been faring poorly,
mired in single digits in national polls _ all of which are led by
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sort of made up my mind, that I cannot endorse the
Republican nominee as of now,'' Buchanan said, referring to Bush.
``I cannot make that commitment, because my party at the national
level has become a Xerox copy, basically, of the Democratic
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan criticized the party's support for several
international commercial pacts, including the North American Free
Trade Agreement, and U.S. intervention in Bosnia and Kosovo, which
have been supported by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning Sunday in Iowa, recalled that he had
encouraged Buchanan to stay in the Republican Party, but said:
``Some things in politics are beyond your control.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the principal worries of the Bush campaign has been that
the Reform Party would spring back to life enough to deny the
Republican nominee victory. That concern would be magnified were
Buchanan to be the Reform candidate.
</P>
<P>
   A mid-August national poll, by Schroth and Associates,
traditionally aligned with Democratic candidates, found the
following result in a three-way presidential contest: Bush 39
percent; Vice President Al Gore 35 percent; Buchanan, as the Reform
nominee, 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine, in its new edition, said a private poll conducted
by Frank Luntz, a Republican consultant, found Buchanan would win 6
percent of the vote in a three-way contest with Bush and Gore _
with two-thirds of the Buchanan vote coming from Bush supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only bad news'' for Republicans, George C. Edwards III,
director of the Center for Presidential Studies at Texas A&AMP;M
University, said of Buchanan's prospective jump to the Reform
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible Reform nominees did not pose a similar threat to
Bush, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a certain (GOP) constituency that will never
be satisfied with George Bush but would not necessarily be
attracted to (Minnesota Gov.) Jesse Ventura,'' the newest Reform
Party star.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who shares some of Buchanan's conservative economic
positions but not his hard-right social positions such as
opposition to abortion, has been cool to Buchanan as a prospective
Reform presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, in an interview last week in the Capitol Hill newspaper
The Hill, belittled the possibility that ``a retread from another
campaign or another party'' would pick up the Reform banner.
</P>
<P>
   But Russell Verney of Dallas, chairman of the Reform Party and
political adviser to Perot, signaled a welcome to Buchanan. He also
said that Pat Choate, the Washington economist who was Perot's vice
presidential running mate in 1996, had been urging Buchanan to make
the switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the idea that (Buchanan) has recognized that
the Republican presidential nomination contest is content-free,''
Verney said in a telephone interview. ``He has a lot of issues he
is passionate about that aren't going to get discussed in the
Republican primary process. Through the reform party he can give
the voters an opportunity to express their views and build a new
political party.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gargan, who represents the Ventura wing of the Reform Party
and will take over as party chairman in January, could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe Perot's first presidential run, in 1992,
cost President Bush a second term. Exit polls indicated, however,
that Perot took evenly from both Bush and Democratic nominee Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan seemed unimpressed by the argument that as the Reform
candidate he could cost Bush the election and allow Democrat Gore
to be elected. Buchanan said he could win with a campaign in which
he espoused ``an American foreign policy that puts our own country
first a trade policy that puts our workers ahead of the global
economy ... an immigration policy that says we need a time out.''
On those issues, he contended, Bush and Gore have few differences.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan acknowledged the Reform Party did not share some of his
conservative social views, including his opposition to abortion,
but said: ``If I am going to run for the Reform Party nomination,
I'm not going to start trimming on my convictions. Clearly, on
life, there are many members of the Reform Party who disagree with
me. But I will tell them honestly, if I get into the race, I'm
pro-life.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney said that the party has not taken positions, ``so they
are neither a qualifier or disqualifier.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney said Buchanan ``would be expected to endorse our party's
platform, which is about government reform and economic reform
issues. As he presents himself to (Reform Party) voters _ and I
certainly would expect him to remain passionate about his position
on abortion _ he will win or lose support based on his personal
position on social issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
