   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-REFUGEES (Kupang, Indonesia) _ As the refugees huddle in
makeshift camps here, militia men roam the grounds menacingly. They
harass aid workers and journalists who try to visit the camps. And
they search for refugees who they believe voted for independence
for East Timor in the recent referendum. The situation in Kupang,
the capital of West Timor, is not as desperate as in East Timor,
where anti-independence gangs have killed thousands and destroyed
the capital, Dili. But the fear here is pervasive and paralyzing.
In visits to two large refugee camps on Sunday, it appeared that
the army and police are unwilling or unable to control the gangs,
which effectively run the camps. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-TURKEY (Athens) _ Greek-Turkish relations had been
improving slowly for several months, but it took earthquakes in
both countries to push them toward friendship. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
