<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CRUSH DODGERS, 10-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If only the Three Stooges had an opportunity to
work with this material.
</P>
<P>
   Tossing aside the refined pitching and clutch hitting that had
defined the first three games of this series, the New York Mets
defeated the Los Angeles Dodgers, 10-3, in a game that started out
like normal baseball with two good pitchers and devolved into a
parade of such ridiculous plays that a laugh track should have been
playing on the loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   If this was no thing of beauty, then the results nonetheless
looked pretty good for the Mets. They are just two games behind the
Atlanta Braves in the National League East Division while remaining
two and a half games ahead of the Cincinnati Reds in the wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets led, 5-3, after the sixth inning and broke open the
game when the Dodgers' meltdown began. With the Dodgers' Eric
Gagne, who was making his second major league start, gone, reliever
Mike Judd was in to contribute to the comic chain of events. He
started by walking Roger Cedeno and Edgardo Alfonzo. John Olerud
singled to left, advancing the runners. But Cedeno ran past third,
and, a third of the way down the basepath to home, he turned to go
back. But Alfonzo was halfway to third himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, running like a kid who knew he was going to get yelled
at when he got home but figured he should go anyway, headed back to
third, catcher Paul LoDuca in pursuit. Cedeno and Alfonzo arrived
at third almost simultaneously, staring at each other briefly.
Alfonzo broke back for second, leaving the base for Cedeno and
taunting LoDuca to follow him. LoDuca did, and Alfonzo was tagged
out. But Cedeno remained safe on third.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza then hit a shot past third base that scored Cedeno
and Olerud. Judd walked Robin Ventura, and Shawon Dunston singled
in Piazza. Then the Dodgers put in reliever Robinson Checo. His
start fit in perfectly with this blooper reel: his first pitch was
sailed to the backstop and scored Ventura. The score was 9-3 and
mercifully, the inning ended that way.
</P>
<P>
   This series has largely hinged on pitching matchups, with subtle
swings and tiny mistakes determining the outcomes of the first
three games.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday night's game, the Mets had a clear advantage. They
were starting Kenny Rogers, who had gone 4-0 since joining the Mets
in late July. The Mets had won all but one of his eight starts, and
Rogers was coming off a four-hit shutout of the Giants. The
Dodgers, on the other hand, had Gagne _ who was named the Texas
League pitcher of the year for the Dodgers' Class AA team in San
Antonio, and he got in trouble immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who was batting leadoff because Rickey Henderson had the
night off, hit a ground-rule double that bounced over the
center-field fence. Edgardo Alfonzo was up next. Since he went 6
for 6 with three home runs against Houston on Aug. 30, Alfonzo has
been in a slump, going 6 for 37. But on Sunday night, Alfonzo timed
his swing perfectly and blasted a home run to left field to give
the Mets an early 2-0 lead. That gave Alfonzo 100 runs batted in,
the first time three Mets _ Piazza and Ventura are the others _
have driven in at least 100 runs in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers began well, retiring the side in the first and second
innings. But he had tweaked his left hamstring while running
Saturday, and he appeared to tire in the third. Facing the bottom
of the Dodgers' order, he walked Adrian Beltre to open the inning.
LoDuca, batting eighth, hit a roller to Ventura, whose throw to
first bounced in the dirt and rolled toward the camera pit to the
right of the dugout. Beltre went to third and LoDuca to second on
Ventura's error, the first he has committed since July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne grounded out to short, scoring Beltre, and LoDuca scored
on Eric Young's flare to left center. The Dodgers went ahead by 3-2
in the fifth when Gagne singled to right and scored on a double by
Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, though, Gagne was facing the heart of the Mets'
order for the third time. He retired Alfonzo and Olerud but walked
Piazza and yielded a single to Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston, in the lineup because Darryl Hamilton bruised his knee
while hitting the wall as he made a catch on Saturday night, laced
a 1-2 pitch for a double that was barely fair down the third-base
line. It rolled into the corner as left fielder Gary Sheffield went
after it. Piazza scored easily, and the third-base coach Cookie
Rojas waved the slow-running Ventura home, too.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca squatted and braced for impact. If he made the tag, the
inning would be over with the score tied. But Ventura ran to
LoDuca's right, practically lifting LoDuca's shoulder with his body
as he tumbled around him. LoDuca lost his grip on the ball, and
Ventura completed his roll with the aplomp of Olga Korbut, reaching
out to tag home. The Mets led, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was the beneficiary. Despite allowing 10 hits, three
walks and three runs in seven innings, he earned the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
