<HEADER>
A9633 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     09-12 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANSECO SOUNDING UPBEAT ABOUT FUTURE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ He was gone in a blink, like a lightning bolt in
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail's business was done. His presence duly
noted. His impact upon the day's events stunningly established.
</P>
<P>
   And his locker was empty.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket Ismail doesn't do interviews. When asked, he more or less
politely declines. He doesn't offer an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   And thus, by the time that most of the assembled media had
reached the giddy locker room Sunday after the Dallas Cowboys'
41-35 overtime victory, Ismail was long gone, safely harbored on
the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. Millions of words are written about the Cowboys in
any given NFL season. Scan the radio dial, troll the cable TV
channels, and there's a Cowboy being quoted every hour.
</P>
<P>
   But win a desperate season opener, memorably coming from 21
points behind in the fourth quarter, and the Cowboys receiver who
scored the electric, deciding touchdown doesn't utter a peep?
</P>
<P>
   This just in _ ``Rocket wins the first, then takes the fifth.''
Silent film at 11.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, this was Troy Aikman's day. A day when Aikman,
after it was all tallied and done, could stifle the critics and
debunk the myths. And it was also Emmitt Smith's day, and Michael
Irvin's.
</P>
<P>
   And let me suggest that it was a poignant day for owner Jerry
Jones and his head coach. It was Jones, after all, who passed over
higher-profile names to hire the unassuming Chan Gailey. And it was
Gailey whose offense ran aground late in his first season and had
begun to inspire doubts.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to the Washington Redskins, which seemed profoundly
possible as Sunday's fourth quarter began, would have incited the
wolves _ count me in, I'll admit _ who thought Gailey hadn't proven
anything, except that he wasn't Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   But how things can turn. In the first quarter, a play-action
fake to Smith had frozen the Washington defense, and Aikman had
lofted a rainbow to Ismail at the Redskins' 10-yard line. A
would-be 54-yard touchdown pass slipped right through Rocket's
fickle arms.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third period, Gailey's alleged signature
offense had dug the Cowboys a 35-14 hole. Ismail, the team's most
prominent free-agent signing, had ``stretched'' the Washington
defense for only 21 not-so-elastic yards.
</P>
<P>
   As the Redskins' Larry Centers said, ``We had them down. We
should have gone into a feeding frenzy and really finished them
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as Gailey put it later, the Cowboys fell back on their
``character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when it looked like we were getting pushed
around the field,'' the coach said. ``And that's what wins games
like this _ character.''
</P>
<P>
   Well-llll, to be accurate, the Redskins helped. They twice lost
fumbles inside the Cowboys' 10-yard line. They shied away from a
game-turning onside kick. They leaped offside three times on the
visitors' tying touchdown drive. And with the game theirs for the
final taking, in the waning three seconds of regulation time, the
Redskins botched a field-goal snap.
</P>
<P>
   Character? It was more a case of the Redskins acting out a death
wish.
</P>
<P>
   But it took something on the Cowboys' part to answer the
opportunity. Something they didn't often have last season.
</P>
<P>
   Something like the lightning-quick Ismail. And a fit and
confident Emmitt Smith. And Irvin, again playing with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin paid homage to Ismail's presence, noting, ``Having a guy
with that kind of speed, you can't help but respect it. Today I saw
some one-on-one coverage. And that's a blessing from God.''
</P>
<P>
   In the game's final 19 minutes, Ismail caught five passes for
128 yards. Irvin, with elbow room, caught three for 62 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Gailey offense burst to life. Suddenly, Owner
Jones looked like a genius again, for hiring Gailey, and signing
Ismail, and re-signing center Mark Stepnoski, and not giving up on
Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, even for inviting his royal good-luck charm, Prince
Bandar of Saudi Arabia, to rejoin him in the visiting owner's box,
as the Cowboys knocked off Washington for the fourth consecutive
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were trailing there, Prince Bandar leaned in my ear
and told me that General Patton said he always wanted to lead
desperate men into battle,'' Jones related.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from the Super Bowl wins, I think this was the most
exciting thing I've ever been a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet from Owner Jones sat Ismail's silent, empty locker. A
Cowboy who doesn't bask in the spotlight? Who knew?
</P>
<P>
   It was like old times for the new Cowboys. It was like the old
script, rewritten with a new twist.
</P>
<P>
   It could mean everything. It could mean nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't know yet. But if you're going somewhere, I'd say hitching
a Rocket is a good start. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
