<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-12 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9634 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAME-STOR     09-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAME-STORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET LAUNCH IN OVERTIME CAPS WILD COWBOYS COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Ray Buck 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ The Cowboys' 41-35 overtime victory against
Washington in the season opener yesterday at Redskins Stadium
wasn't artistic, but then sweating rarely is.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, their missed tackles, dropped passes and
penalty-ridden drives all were forgotten on one spectacular 76-yard
pass play from Troy Aikman to newcomer Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail,
who was playing in his first game that counted in a Dallas uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in a Redskins uniform has touched Ismail yet.
</P>
<P>
   With that one immaculate reception, as uncluttered a picture of
a game-ending pass play as you will ever see, a crowd of 79,237 sat
in stunned silence. It was the largest crowd in Maryland sports
event, excluding the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   And when Ismail gathered in the ball at the Washington 40 and
made his courtesy dash to the end zone, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
looked like a man who had chased down a speeding bus.
</P>
<P>
   On the other sideline, Redskins coach Norv Turner looked like a
man who had just been run over by the same bus.
</P>
<P>
   The local media already is on job-security watch, wondering how
new Redskins owner Daniel Snyder will react to Turner's letting his
team blow a 35-14 fourth-quarter lead.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, who extended their NFL-best opening-day record
to 30-9-1, this Rocket-fueled comeback tied the club record for the
biggest comeback in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an awfully big show of character by our football
team,'' Gailey said. ``Our execution at times wasn't good on both
sides of the ball, and at times it looked like we were getting
pushed around on the field ... but our character never faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what wins ... character. And I think we can build on
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman called it ``the wildest football game that I've ever been
part of.''
</P>
<P>
   It indeed was a wild ride with plenty of warts. It also was a
victory that allows the Cowboys to begin a season beset by injuries
and a suspension totally committed to Gailey's philosophy of
getting everybody involved.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's idea is to have a different star every game. He rests
his front-liners. He rotates in and out his reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game-stopper came on the 12th play of overtime ...
after Richie Cunningham's extra-point kick caromed off the left
upright and forced overtime with 1 minute, 46 seconds in regulation
... after Washington won the toss and had the ball first in
overtime ... after the Cowboys started from their own 5-yard line
in overtime ... before Daryl Johnston fell on an Emmitt Smith
fumble on the first offensive play to keep the dream alive.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of sweating before this one was over.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ismail dropped that same pass on the same pass play
earlier in the game. But this game was less about pretty and more
about pride and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys jumped out in front, 14-3, one play into the second
quarter as Aikman, with the first five-touchdown game of his
11-year NFL career, hooked up with tight end David LaFleur for
touchdown passes of 15 and 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas went into mistake mode in the middle quarters, compiling
more penalties than big plays, and tumbled behind 35-14 as
Washington quarterback Brad Johnson, under little pass-rush
pressure, picked apart the Cowboys' secondary. Receivers Michael
Westbrook and Albert Connell finished with 159 and 137 yards,
respectively, on a combined nine receptions and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' comeback began with Smith's scoring on a 1-yard
pitch to the left, Toss 39 Bob, in which Smith followed Johnston's
lead block just like the old days. It was Dallas' first points
since the first play of the second quarter, and it came with 10:43
left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a lot of the new stuff,'' Johnston said, ``but
maybe old style. That's the mentality we've had here in the past:
Don't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey ordered up an onside kick, and rookie Dat Nguyen
recovered for the Cowboys. When that didn't lead to any points,
Johnston admitted, ``We had to bring ourselves up again.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Cowboys' defense forced the Redskins to run three
plays and punt, Aikman went to his longtime favorite target,
Michael Irvin, for a 37-yard touchdown pass that Irvin caught in
spite of pass interference. Barely two minutes later, Irvin caught
a 12-yard touchdown pass that Aikman simply drilled into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Irvin had doubled his touchdown total from last
season, and the Cowboys were headed for overtime and a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the way we did, I think is going to help us,'' Irvin
said. ``We have some guys who haven't been to war with us, and we
haven't been to war with them ... a game like this, you start
trusting one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail caught a team-high eight passes for 149 yards; Irvin,
five passes for 122 yards, and went much of the middle two quarters
without even being in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different approach for me,'' Irvin explained. ``But
I've said before, I'll try anything as long as it works. And that
means winning.''
</P>
<P>
   First game into a new season, it definitely worked.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
