<HEADLINE>
AGASSI'S COMEBACK TRAIL ENDS IN TRIUMPH AT U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Andre Agassi's journey to the
mountaintop is complete.
</P>
<P>
   His long, arduous trip from the depths of the tennis world, from
the lows of triple-figure rankings and the ignominy of having to
play challenger events, ended Sunday with both feet firmly planted
at the peak.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi defeated Todd Martin, 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 6-7 (2-7), 6-3,
6-3, to win the U.S. Open men's singles championship, solidifying
his grasp on the No. 1 ranking by winning his second Grand Slam
title of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To accomplish two Slams, which is something no one else did
this year, makes me feel I'm the best,'' Agassi said. ``This is
what you play for. I'm appreciating this time of my life. It feels
good to accomplish it, definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Agassi was ranked No. 141 and his immense talent
appeared squandered
</P>
<P>
   That's when Agassi rededicated himself, and began the journey
that ended Sunday in Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make a choice if I was really going to play the game
or quit,'' Agassi said. ``If I was going to play, I had a lot of
work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The final leg up the mountain was unexpectedly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi was the second seed. Martin was seeded seventh. Agassi
was the heavy favorite. Martin was the foil.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, though, pushed Agassi to excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd deserved to be in the finals,'' Agassi said. ``The way he
played it was disappointing that someone had to lose. He played so
well. I felt like I was hanging on by a thread most of the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi won the first set by the smallest of margins. He broke
Martin in the second game, then battled back from a 0-40 deficit
the next time he served.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't do anything with Martin's serve the next two sets,
though. Martin mixed it up, serving hard shots down the middle and
changeups wide. He followed his first serve to the net and knocked
off volleys. He was solid on his groundstrokes.
</P>
<P>
   Martin couldn't break Agassi either, and the second and third
sets went into tiebreakers. Martin won both, not because of Agassi
mistakes _ he had only 23 unforced errors _ but because he played
great tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The underdog had the lead and the crowd roared, sensing an
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had a chance to win,'' Martin said. ``I knew I needed
to keep playing well on my serve and better on his serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi realized he was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very worried,'' Agassi said. ``He gave me a lot to worry
about. Not only was he serving great but he was volleying
magnificently, and holding his own from the baseline. My goal in
the fourth was to take care of my serve and hang in there until
something good happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi took care of his serve. He wasn't broken all match,
fighting off all eight break points against him.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing happened in the third game of the fourth set,
when Agassi broke when Martin pushed a volley long.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth set wasn't close.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who played an exhausting, five-set match against Greg
Rusedski in the fourth round, began to wear down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem was I lost my legs a little bit,'' Martin
said. ``When that happened, the serve is what goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi broke Martin for a 2-0 lead in the fifth set, and held
for 3-0. To emphasize that he was the fresher player, he sprinted
to his chair on the changeover, while Martin slowly walked off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he dropped off a hair, and I was able to
maintain,'' Agassi said. ``It seemed more physical than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi sprinted to the chair again two games later, when he had
a 4-1 lead. Martin faced the same deficit in the fifth set against
Rusedski, and came back. It wasn't in him Sunday, though.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi held, then broke Martin again to win the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He beat me when I played a very good match,'' Martin said. ``I
feel very good about being at the 1999 Open. I would have loved to
have been the champion, but playing the seven matches I did I feel
very good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as good as the man who sits atop the tennis world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you ever make up for missed opportunities,''
he said. ``The best you can do is not live in regret. What I missed
out on earlier in my career I'll never get back, but it's nice to
get another opportunity at it. Who knows if I could have
accomplished more. But there's still time.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
