<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GONZALEZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA STEALS SHOW AT AMERICA'S SLAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ They call the U.S. Open ``America's
Slam.'' Not this year. This tournament was ``Serena's Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away from Broadway, Serena Williams was the star of
this production. The 17-year-old won the women's singles Saturday
and co-starred with 18-year-old sister Venus on Sunday to win the
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking maybe next year I should try to enter the men's
event and see if I can at least win a round,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was only kidding. Then again, she could probably do it.
</P>
<P>
   There were some great moments in this year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi was a compelling story. He capped a return from
career oblivion by clinching the No. 1 ranking with a victory
against Yevgeny Kafelnikov in the semifinals. Then, Sunday, he came
from behind to beat Todd Martin in five tough sets and win his
second Grand Slam singles title of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road for me and one that I'm proud of,''
Agassi said. ``It means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, the gentleman tennis player, played the tournament of
his life. He survived a tough first-round match against unheralded
Stephane Huet in the first round and came from two sets down to
beat Greg Rusedski in the third round. He played much better than
expected Sunday, turning what was supposed to be a rout into a
nail-biter by pushing Agassi to five sets.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov created a buzz when he predicted only three men, he,
Agassi and Richard Krajicek, could win the Open. Krajicek served a
record 49 aces against Kafelnikov, and still lost.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's side, one-time troubled teen Jennifer Capriati
made it to the fourth round before losing to Monica Seles. In her
subsequent postmatch news conference, she read a prepared statement
that she would field no more questions about her past, then left in
tears when the subject wouldn't go away.
</P>
<P>
   There were great shots, including Cedric Pioline's running
passing shot that prompted Gustavo Kuerten to congratulate him in
the middle of a game, and the stabbed one-handed backhand that
Hingis somehow got into the court against Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament also raised a couple of key questions.
</P>
<P>
   Can Pete Sampras, who was favored to win and break the tie he
holds with Roy Emerson for most Grand Slam titles but missed the
event because of a back injury, return to challenge Agassi for
tennis supremacy?
</P>
<P>
   Can Seles get in shape and challenge the current crop of
teen-agers?
</P>
<P>
   It was a tournament that lost some luster when Sampras couldn't
play and defending champion Patrick Rafter withdrew in the first
round because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was a tournament that overcame that with equal parts
great tennis and great drama.
</P>
<P>
   And squarely on center stage was Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams family commanded the spotlight from Day One, when
papa Richard predicted an all-daughter final.
</P>
<P>
   Few believed him. Venus was in the same bracket as Hingis, the
top-ranked woman who was on top of her game. Serena, the seventh
seed, was in the same bracket as No. 2 seed and defending champion
Lindsay Davenport and the fourth-seeded Seles.
</P>
<P>
   If either sister made it to the final, it was supposed to be
Venus. Serena, in her second full year on tour, had never made it
past the quarterfinals of a major. Venus had experienced big-time,
big-match pressure and seemed ready to win her first Slam.
</P>
<P>
   Serena, though, upstaged her sister. She beat Seles in the
quarterfinals and Davenport in the semis. In the final she met
Hingis, who had shattered Richard Williams' dreams with a victory
over Venus in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Serena destroyed Hingis in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the spotlight, the sisters energized women's tennis.
Attendance at the National Tennis Center hit record highs. TV
ratings were up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to be part of what's happening,'' Venus said.
``Right now, this is what's happening. People are running to be
part of it. Honestly. If you saw something good, wouldn't you want
to be part of it? I would.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters figure to be a part of it for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Open provided a glimpse of the future of tennis, and
it is beaded and brash.
</P>
<P>
   The future of tennis is two teen-agers from Compton, Calif., who
move better than anyone in the women's game, hit the ball harder
than anyone in the women's game, serve faster than anyone in the
women's game and, with the possible exception of Hingis, are more
confident than anyone else in the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   The future belongs to both of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the present, this year's U.S. Open, was Serena's slam. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
