<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN CAN'T KEEP VIKINGS FROM GRUMBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the high-fives and chest thumping filled the
visitors locker room here Sunday, Minnesota Vikings offensive
coordinator Ray Sherman sounded like a man whose team had lost by
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He snapped at a reporter, he refused to answer questions, and he
was defensive when he did answer.
</P>
<P>
   In a rematch of the 1998 NFC Championship Game, the Vikings
might have won a measure of revenge with a 17-14 victory against
the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   But their offense Sunday looked nothing like the juggernaut that
scored a league-record 556 points last season. And so Sherman was
left to defend a unit that scored its fewest points since a 14-13
loss to Detroit on Dec. 14, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the game, didn't we?,'' he barked in the direction of
ESPN reporter Andrea Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman has a point. Problem is, points are suddenly becoming
hard to come by for Sherman-coached offenses. Sherman was the
Vikings' quarterbacks coach in that loss to the Lions nearly two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Sherman replaced Chan Gailey as the offensive
coordinator in Pittsburgh. But the Steelers, who went to the AFC
Championship Game in 1997, didn't even make the playoffs in 1998.
Sherman, whose offense once bored Kordell Stewart to tears, was
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings coach Dennis Green rehired Sherman as an offensive
assistant after the 1998 season, and then promoted Sherman to
offensive coordinator when Chip Myers died of a heart attack Feb.
23.
</P>
<P>
   In Randy Moss, Cris Carter, Randall Cunningham, and Robert
Smith, Sherman inherited a Mercedes, equipped with all the bells
and whistles. Yet, there must be sugar in the gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   In four preseason games, the Vikings' first-team offense scored
27 points. Sunday, the passing game looked unimaginative, with
Cunningham either throwing it deep or dumping it short. (Mostly, he
dumped it short, averaging a measly 5.6 yards per attempt). Moss
didn't have a reception longer than nine yards. Smith, the featured
running back, was held to 2.9 yards per carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very aggressive game plan,'' Cunningham said. ``They
just did some things that made us not look aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The elements _ and a Falcons defense ranked No. 8 last season _
combined to hold the Vikings to less than 300 yards of total
offense. Minnesota failed to score in three of the four quarters.
Two of their scoring drives came with help from the referee; Moss
drew pass interference calls on both of the Vikings' touchdown
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Yo Ray, could Sherman Hemsley have done a better job?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about the comparisons to last year and
what we did today,'' Sherman said. ``We scored 27 points (in the
NFC Championship Game) and we lost, didn't we? Our job was to find
a way to win the game. The Falcons get paid to play too. The point
structure didn't matter. We won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No, surprise, the Vikings' defense won the game. Forced to play
with four new starters because of free agency, the Vikings' defense
bore down on the ``Dirty Birds,'' limiting running back Jamal
Anderson to 50 yards on 16 carries, and sacking quarterback Chris
Chandler twice, knocking him out of the game with a hamstring
injury with 3:58 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserved a lot of criticism for the way we played last
year,'' cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock said. ``We had a lot of marquee
players who didn't step up and do the job. We lost a couple of guys
in free agency, but the core is still here. And that core of guys
got the job done today.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that Ray Sherman, somewhere, is breathing a sigh of
relief, and muttering to himself, ``didn't we win the game?''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
