<SLUG> BC-FBN-BROWNS-STEELERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEELERS CRUSH BROWNS, 43-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In the parking lot outside Cleveland Browns Stadium
there were grown men wearing dog bones on their heads, and they
weren't ashamed. That of course means all is right again in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments in sports that can warm even the hardest
hearts. Football returning to Cleveland is one of those times.
Nothing could dampen the excitement. Not the at-times obnoxious way
every local car dealer, grocery store and bank tried to jump on the
bandwagon. Not the dark clouds and the loud claps of thunder that
threatened rain.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Pittsburgh Steelers could ruin this night. It would
have added to the storybook feel if the Browns had won, but that
was asking for a little too much. Thus Pittsburgh won, 43-0, in
what was largely an unremarkable game.
</P>
<P>
   The game may have been a dud, but the significance of it was
not. In 1995, the owner Art Modell moved his team from Cleveland to
Baltimore. It took almost five years, but the Browns, one of
professional football's most storied franchises, is playing again.
The city of Cleveland could not have been more ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uniqueness of this situation, the game had almost
a Super Bowl feel to it, and the 73,138 fans stayed glued to their
seats, cheering the Browns well into the fourth quarter. They did
so despite the lopsided nature of the contest in which the Browns
gained 1 yard in the third quarter. And they stayed when the rookie
quarterback Tim Couch, the No. 1 pick in the draft, entered the
contest with 10 minutes 47 seconds remaining and threw an
interception on his first pass as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   All week the city of Cleveland had treated the return of the
Browns like it was a spiritual event. When Browns linebacker Chris
Spielman retired it did not matter that he had spent most of his
career with the Detroit Lions _ or that he had never played a down
in the regular season in a Cleveland uniform _ local stations
interrupted their afternoon programming to cover his retirement
news conference live.
</P>
<P>
   Signs welcoming back the team adorned the city on Sunday,
especially downtown. Fans flooded the stadium, inside and out,
wearing orange dresses or orange T-shirts or orange pants. Dog
masks sold for $14 a shot. People chewed on dog bones _ some fake,
some real. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue made an appearance at the
game, expressing how great a day this is for the league.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dawg Pound was back.
</P>
<P>
   A small corner of the $283 million stadium was designated for
the people wearing the dog masks. Almost every television camera
and microphone within a 50-mile radius paid a visit to the pound,
which was as big an attraction as the game itself.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, the night, was one big celebration, and when the
Browns came running onto the field, they seemed to sense that this
evening was indeed special. Some went to the stands and high-fived
fans wearing orange wigs, and this was before the game even began.
</P>
<P>
   Once it started, Browns fans did see some early treats. On the
Steelers' opening offensive possession it was clear that the new
offensive coordinator Kevin Gilbride has put his stamp on the team.
Pittsburgh twice went to five wide receiver sets and picked apart
Cleveland's defense, spicing the razzle-dazzle with the occasional
Jerome Bettis bulldozer-like run or option by quarterback Kordell
Stewart. But on fourth down and one inch at the Cleveland 22-yard
line Stewart's sneak up the middle was stopped by the Cleveland
defenders. That got the fans to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   But, in terms of on-field highlights for the Browns, that was
about it. The team's return to the city is one of the best football
stories this season, maybe this decade, yet it did not take long
for reality to set in. Cleveland is an expansion team and, unlike
expansion cousins Carolina and Jacksonville, there will likely be
no Cinderella playoff run. The Browns have little talent and it did
not take long for the Steelers to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's next two drives ended in scores. The first was
after Browns quarterback Ty Detmer threw an interception that
Pittsburgh converted into a five-play, 39-yard drive that
culminated in a Stewart 1-yard touchdown run. The Steelers followed
that with a 19-yard field goal for a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with about five minutes remaining in the first half,
Stewart connected with running back Richard Huntley after he beat
defensive back Marlon Forbes on a 5-yard crossing pattern. Just
before the half the Steelers added a 28-yard field goal to give
Pittsburgh a 20-0 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   What had been a raucous beginning dimmed to a quiet simmer. Of
course the fans, an ocean of orange in the stands, did not leave.
They did not boo. There was a sort of unspoken understanding. This
was one of those times when a city was just happy to see its team
play, even if it did not play that well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
