<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HILL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL SCORE CONSOLES COWBOYS DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Cornerback Kevin Mathis and the Dallas Cowboys
defense survived two onslaughts at Redskins Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The first one came on the field during the Cowboys' improbable
41-35 overtime victory against the Washington Redskins _ a victory
even though Dallas allowed 504 yards of total offense, including
369 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   The second one came in the postgame locker room, as members of
the defense were unable to enjoy the miraculous 21-point comeback
victory because of repeated questions about their shoddy
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, largely responsible for Redskins receiver Michael
Westbrook's video-game-like output of five catches for 159 yards
and one touchdown, accepted responsibility for his play. But he
refused to be denied the pleasure of celebrating the season-opening
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in my play,'' Mathis said. ``I got a lot of
things to work. But I'm going to stay focused to get better next
week. But we play as a team. We came a way with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat lost in rumble, however, was that part of the reason
the Cowboys came away with a victory was because Mathis and the
defense played better in the fourth quarter and overtime, when they
held the Redskins scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear what the Redskins' offense did in the first three
quarters of the game. Quarterback Brad Johnson targeted Mathis and
nickel cornerback Charlie Williams, who started in place of injured
cornerback Deion Sanders (toe).
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas A&AMP;M receiver Albert Connell benefited along with
Westbrook, catching four balls for 137 yards, including a 50-yard
touchdown reception on which he seemingly ripped the ball out of
the hands of Williams before racing to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys expected the Redskins to take advantage of their
injury-depleted secondary _ which also played without veteran
cornerback Kevin Smith (back injury). But what they didn't expect,
said defensive-line coach Jim Bates, was for Redskins running back
Stephen Davis to conjure up memories of former Washington legend
John Riggins. Davis plowed for 109 yards on 24 carries, mostly
through the middle of the Cowboys' Leon Lett-less defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really did a good job of game-planning us,'' Bates said.
``We wouldn't have thought they could run like that. They ran well
and gashed us several times.''
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened during the Cowboys' own offensive
onslaught in the fourth quarter. The defense joined in the fun with
a few plays themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the whole defense to together at the beginning of the
fourth quarter and told them to keep their heads in it,'' Bates
said. ``We told them we are going to get it together. The offense
scored and changed the momentum, and the defense followed
through.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a 35-14 lead into the fourth quarter, the Redskins
came up empty on five consecutive possessions, including four
punts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' game-winning drive was set up by a sack by
defensive end Greg Ellis, his second of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense didn't play well by no stretch of the
imagination,'' Ellis said. ``And we won't be happy when we see the
film. But you've got to keep in mind we did win.''
</P>
<P>
   IRVIN FUMES THEN SHINES Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin's
back-into-the-limelight day of 122 yards and two touchdowns began
with him catching passes of 34 and 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He followed the second catch with a gyrating dance that riled
the packed house of Redskins fans.
</P>
<P>
   There is some question, however, as to who Irvin was aiming his
``I'm still a bad man'' taunts at, considering that the Cowboys
tried to trade him during the off-season and then administered a
game plan to cut back on his time.
</P>
<P>
   The television shots of a seething Irvin sitting on the sideline
during a third-quarter offensive possession when the Cowboys were
down 28-14 were quite telling.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who sat for a total of 18 plays in the game, accepted
being on the bench in the first and second quarter. But down 28-14
in the third quarter and watching your offense go three-and-out
without you was another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say I was mad,'' Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   He was back in the game in the fourth quarter, and it seemed
like old times. Irvin keyed the Cowboys' comeback with a 37-yard
touchdown catch and 12-yarder on his patented slant route to tie
the game. The two scores doubled his touchdown output for all of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (the two touchdowns) was great,'' Irvin said. ``I didn't
want to go through the spell of one touchdown catch and then it was
here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to duplicate last season is at the root of the
Cowboys' decision to rest Irvin, 31, during games. Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey said the mission is to keep his star receiver fresh
late in the season, but he wondered out loud if the plan was the
reason for Irvin's fourth-quarter outburst Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An elated Irvin wasn't in a disagreeing mood after the game,
saying ``it worked (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll accept anything as long as we win,'' Irvin said. ``But
it's not going to be easy for me. I'm used to playing all the time.
This was different.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE LOCKER ROOM The Redskins were not the only ones
confused by Cowboys coach Chan Gailey's play calling Sunday, as
several Cowboys questioned why he abandoned the running game during
the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins never did get a handle on running back Emmitt
Smith, who rushed 23 times for 109 yards, including six carries in
the first quarter to power two touchdown drives (the second
touchdown came on the first play of the second quarter).
</P>
<P>
   Smith carried the ball just seven times in the middle two
quarters when the Cowboys' offense registered zero points.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gailey's bent to mix it up paid off in the end when
the Cowboys game-winning touchdown pass came against a defense
expecting a run.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Michael Myers entered the season as the
favorite to replace suspended defensive tackle Leon Lett in the
lineup. But a poor preseason cost him a starting job. Now he is at
the bottom of the depth chart at defensive tackle, as he was made
inactive for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Questions that tackle Flozell Adams, who is deaf in one ear,
committed a couple of motion penalties because of his hearing were
quickly shot down by Gailey. He said the Cowboys were going on a
silent count when Adams got the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET GO DEEP If it was the playground, the Cowboys'
game-winning play would simply be called Rocket Go Deep. That's
certainly how it looked.
</P>
<P>
   But things weren't that simple. It couldn't have been, or the
Redskins would have least put somebody in the same zip code of
receiver Raghib Ismail on his catch of Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman's 76-yard overtime pass.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Redskins lose the battle with Ismail's speed,
but they were done in by the formation, the play call and the play
fake.
</P>
<P>
   What's ironic is that the Cowboys ran the same play earlier in
the game, but a wide-open Ismail dropped the ball. Yet, they didn't
know what hit them when the Cowboys lined up in the same formation
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a third-and-two at their own 24-yard line, Chan Gailey
took receiver Michael Irvin out of the game and sent in an extra
tight end. The Redskins looked at the Cowboys' lineup and saw two
tight ends, fullback Daryl Johnston and tailback Emmitt Smith and
thought run.
</P>
<P>
   That belief was buoyed by the fact that Gailey had opted for
running plays on a number of third-and-shorts throughout the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   So when Aikman faked a handoff to Smith, both Redskins safeties
took a couple of steps forward. Then it was too late to catch
Ismail, who sold the play by pretending to block before darting
straight down the middle of the field. Aikman lofted a perfect pass
that Ismail caught in full stride.
</P>
<P>
   Now the dogpile in the end zone, that was straight off the
playground.
</P>
<P>
   GAME BALLS The rule of sports is that the hero is the person who
won the game.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Raghib Ismail's career-best performance _ eight catches
for 149 yards and one touchdown _ certainly qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   Other game-ball superlatives:
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith rushed 24 times for 109 yards, topping
the 100-yard barrier for the 50th time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Michael Irvin's 122-yard effort put him over the
100-yard mark for the 47th time.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman's career-high five touchdown passes tied
the team record shared by Eddie LeBaron, Don Meredith, Craig Morton
and Danny White.
UP NEXT
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will be hard-pressed to top Sunday's season-opening
victory for sheer excitement. However, Game 2, set for next Monday
against the defending NFC champion Atlanta Falcons in the home
opener, could feature a nice caveat _ the return of injured
cornerback Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be a stretch to think that Sanders might time his
return from toe surgery to coincide with a Prime Time affair
against his old team on ``Monday Night Football''.
</P>
<P>
   It could also feature a dance-off between Sanders and his
to-legit-to-quit two-step and Falcons dirty-bird dancing running
back Jamal Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the game is concerned, the Cowboys must be better
against the run than they were Sunday, or Anderson will win by
default.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
