<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S CAN'T BUY A BREAK IN 4-1 LOSS TO ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Ken Griffey Jr. came in from center field.
Infielders Alex Rodriguez and David Bell came out. And the pop fly
by Eugene Kingsale, who was leading off the fifth inning for the
Baltimore Orioles, landed in the center of a Mariner triangle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in no-man's land,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly where the Mariners find themselves this morning
after three games of a maddening four-game series at Oriole Park at
Camden Yards. That little single Sunday touched off a rally that
B.J. Surhoff capped with a two-out, three-run home run, the crucial
blow in a 4-1 Mariners loss.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsale was erased on a fielder's choice, and the next batter
flied out. But after Mike Bordick singled, Surhoff drove a high
fastball from John Halama (11-7) over the wall in right-center
field for his 27th home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 2-0 (in the count), and he's feeling comfortable,''
said Halama, who lasted into the eighth inning. ``I needed to throw
a strike. He's going to be aggressive, and he just beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true, but the Mariners have had One of Those Series _ the
kind where the other side turns the freak double play, gets the
back-to-back infield hits and watches troublesome home runs hook
foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole series they've hit balls we've had to dive to knock
down,'' pitching coach Stan Williams said. ``Everything's been in
the hole, and each and every time we give them an extra out, we end
up paying the price. It's just been one of those series where
everything they're hitting gets under a glove or just over the
infield, and everything we're hitting goes right at them. Sometimes
it works that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the sun shines on one team while blinding the other _
literally.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsale's pop, innocent as it looked, was trouble from the
start. Bell saw it all the way, and thought he could have tried to
catch it. But Rodriguez, who was a good 15 feet away from the ball
when it landed, called for Griffey to catch it. Bell thought
Griffey was camped under it _ when Griffey, in fact, was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flipped my glasses down and had to hope for it to come out
of the sun,'' Griffey said. ``I heard Alex call, `You, you, you!'
and I thought, `I guess he can't see it.' It's just one of those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many. Brian Hunter led off the game with a single
off the leg of Orioles starter Scott Erickson. Bell followed with a
pop-up that Erickson caught with a sprawling dive. Hunter was at
second by then, and was easily doubled up at first.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's 18th home run put the Mariners ahead 1-0 in the fourth,
but Erickson (13-11) was nearly flawless after that.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey hooked a would-be homer a few feet wide of the
right-field foul pole leading off the ninth, then was retired when
shortstop Bordick lunged for a looping liner, catching it on the
second base side of the bag.
</P>
<P>
   That was how it went for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   An inning earlier, Baltimore had gotten its final run on a pair
of infield hits. With one out and Bordick on second, Halama gave
way to Todd Williams. The side-arming right-hander broke Albert
Belle's bat on a ball up the middle, and Rodriguez gloved it, spun
and threw _ just late.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Jeff Conine, hit a grounder that was deflected
by diving third baseman Russ Davis down the line. Davis bare-handed
the ball and threw to first, late again, and Bordick scored to give
the Orioles a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bad breaks? Probably, but Bell wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little break here or there might affect the outcome of the
game, but I will admit that we control most of what happens,'' Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three games, we haven't gotten it done. I don't feel
we've been playing bad, we just haven't done quite what it takes to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Tyler Kepner can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or tylerkepner &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
